a group of moderate baptists gathers tonight for its second annual meeting, wondering if it will retain a place in the fundamentalist-dominated southern baptist convention that sparked its formation
we are southern baptists, but we intend to hold up that flag of religious liberty and we're going to yell ouch every time they step on that principle and we're going to keep on yelling,'' said the rev. jim strickland, a cartersville pastor who is a leader of the southern baptist alliance
strickland said victories by moderates at some state baptist conventions last year indicate the southern baptist convention's annual meeting in san antonio, texas, this summer may be ``a high-water mark ... a shootout at the o.k. corral.''
nevertheless, strickland said, this week's alliance meeting at mercer university is not a strategy session for moderates
the southern baptist alliance is not a political organization. ... we are not going to do that footwork out there,'' although the alliance supports those political efforts, he said
the alliance was formed in february 1987 in reaction to fundamentalist actions as they gained control of the southern baptist convention, the nation's largest protestant denominaton with about 14.5 million members
fundamentalists maintain that the bible is without error in historical and scientific as well as religious areas; moderates hold there is room for interpretation
fundamentalists have removed moderates from leadership positions, including the presidency of southeastern baptist seminary in wake forest, n.c. in another instance, an employee of one of the denomination's agencies says he was fired because he said he believed jews could go to heaven without accepting jesus
the alliance has grown to include 34 churches with more than 20,000 members, plus about 2,500 other member whose churches do not belong to the alliance. strickland said the alliance is not intended to be the nucleus of a new denomination
our hope as members of the southern baptist alliance is that we can articulate baptist philosophy _ not necessarily current southern baptist philosophy _ about religious liberty. we want to call baptists who think religious freedom is important back to that heritage,'' strickland said
strickland is pastor of heritage baptist church, formed less than a year ago, partly because of fundamentalist control of the first baptist church of cartersville, he said
mercer university, supported by the georgia baptist convention, was itself the center of controversy last year when fundamentalists mounted a campaign to gain control of the school, citing its listing as a ``party school'' by playboy magazine and the moderate views of president r. kirby godsey
but the georgia baptist convention last november defeated efforts to remove godsey. the action was seen at the time as one of a series of victories by moderates in various state baptist conventions
most of the veterans and people who have worked for quite a while really keep health conscious. in the last six months we've even begun printing up a newsletter to all the actors and actresses with health tips.'' _ pornographic film star angel kelly, addressing concerns that the adult film industry is threatened by aids following the aids-related death of actor john holmes
the only thing in the last 10 years that hasn't been crooked is both the da's and the u.s. attorney's office.'' _ former philadelphia district attorney edward rendell, commenting on widespread local corruption that has led to convictions or charges against judges, police, defense lawyers and prison guards
i think things are back to normal for a spring break, which is in no way normal.'' _ port aransas, texas, city manager gordon beck, following a weekend that included a beach riot, four stabbings and the deaths of two youths whose car plunged off a dock
