negotiations to reunite south korea's bitterly divided opposition collapsed again today with both sides refusing to compromise over sharing power and party posts
the reunification democratic party announced it had pulled out of talks with the smaller party for peace and democracy and said there was no hope of uniting the two parties. it denounced party for peace and democracy supporters for staging a violent protest that broke up talks
the party concluded it would be meaningless and impossbile to continue merger talks because the positions between the parties are so wide apart,'' said a reunification democratic party spokesman, kim pae-ryong
party for peace and democracy leaders said they wanted to continue unification talks, but they recognized negotiations had stalled. they charged the reunification democratic party wanted to destroy rival opposition groups
the two parties said there was no chance of reuniting before national assembly elections next month. both groups said they would mount separate election campaigns even though it would boost the government's chances of a major victory
the acting party for peace and democracy president, park young-sook, said the party hoped that unification talks could be revived after the election if not sooner. ``we need a strong leadership and a strong opposition,'' she said
about a dozen students staged protests at the two party headquarters today to demand the talks resume and wrote protests with blood after cutting their fingers
some opposition leaders and lawmakers had been pushing for reunification of the two parties to avoid a major defeat in the national assembly elections expected to be held april 26
opposition leader kim dae-jung and his supporters split away from the reunification democratic party to form the party for peace and democracy late last year after he and the larger party's president, kim young-sam, failed to agree on which one of them should run for president
both kims ran in the dec. 16 election and were defeated by government candidate president roh tae-woo after splitting the opposition vote
roh took office feb. 25
a standoff between nashville police and a man who said he accidentally killed his girlfriend ended early today when the gunman fatally shot himself, while an alabama gunman critically wounded himself after killing a man and holding police at bay, authorities say
george e. powell, 45, of nashville died at 1:35 a.m. of a shotgun wound to the head at vanderbilt university medical center, officials said
powell called police at 6:45 p.m. sunday and told them he had accidentally shot his girlfriend, caroline campbell of nashville, during a scuffle, said buddy mitchell, a hostage negotiator for the police
he says they both had been drinking and had a sawed-off shotgun,'' mitchell said. ``he says they got into an argument over the gun and it went off and shot her. he dragged her into the bedroom and covered her up with a blanket and set the telephone on top.''
powell, a sheet metal worker, told police he planned to kill himself, mitchell said. police said they talked on the phone with powell throughout the ordeal
at least 10 patrol cars and the swat team communications van were dispatched to the scene, and police sealed off the area
at 12:45 a.m., powell said goodbye to the negotiators on the phone, hung up and shot himself in the head, police said
in huntsville, ala., a 40-year-old man was listed in critical condition after an eight-hour standoff that began with the gunshot slaying of an acquaintance of the man's ex-wife and ended when the man apparently shot himself, authorities said
madison county sheriff joe patterson said jerry staggs apparently attempted suicide about 7 p.m. sunday after he released his ex-wife, sherry, 29, and the couple's two boys, whom he had taken hostage before noon
staggs was taken by helicopter to huntsville hospital, where he was being treated for a gunshot wound to the head, said spokeswoman june hackworth
the apparent suicide attempt ended a tense standoff that began when staggs shot the acquaintance of his ex-wife as the man sat in his car outside staggs' trailer, police said. about 25 police officers surrounded the trailer and evacuated residents of the dozen other mobile homes in the trailer park north of huntsville
the huntsville news reported today the victim was identified as don pressnell, a former athens police officer
patterson said staggs had been arrested two weeks ago on a kidnapping charge and there had been an attempt to obtain psychiatric treatment for him
the standoff ended when a shot rang out and mrs. staggs ran out the door of the trailer. she told police her ex-husband had shot himself in the head, said capt. robert moder of the huntsville police department
butler said staggs was employed by the city maintenance department. prominent arab attacked, arab houses bulldozed, other details. no pickup.</note>
israeli soldiers shot and killed a palestinian in the gaza strip today, arab reports said, and palestinians staged a widespread general strike in the occupied territories
the strike, which left shops shuttered and public transport idle, came in response to a plo call for ``the most severe confrontation'' to commemorate the 20th anniversary of a palestinian guerrilla clash with israel
also today, attackers fired at a moderate arab's home, the army bulldozed homes of suspected firebombers and a leaflet by arab underground leaders urged more arabs working for the israeli government to quit by saturday
defense minister yitzhak rabin warned sunday night the army may use tougher measures against palestinians after the shooting death of an israeli soldier, the first member of the military to be killed in four months of rioting
in the gaza town of rafah, soldiers today fired tear gas and ammunition at stone-throwing protesters. abdel ahmed jaber al mudalal, 17, of rafah, died after he was shot in the chest, according to arab reports and the palestine press service
al mudalal's body was taken to khan yunis' nasser hospital, the reports said. the army said it was checking the report. if confirmed, the fatality would bring to 104 the number of palestinians killed since the uprising began dec. 8, including four tear gas deaths, according to u.n. figures
rabin told reporters the army was investigating whether the shooting death of sgt. moshe katz indicated palestinians intended to expand the scope of their protests to firearms from the usual stones and gasoline bombs
katz, a reserve soldier, died sunday in bethlehem after he was shot in the head at close range while on guard duty at a government building
if ``extremist palestinian terrorist elements try to combine terrorist acts with civilian protests, we will have to change our operations and take harsher measures to handle both,'' rabin said
attackers fired shots before dawn today at the home and car of jack khazmo, a prominent moderate palestinian newspaper editor, workers at the weekly al bayader assiyasi said. no injuries were reported
wajiha awadallah, khazmo's secretary, said attackers ``fired many shots'' into khazmo's house in the village of ram, just north of jerusalem, at about 2:45 a.m
she said they also ``tried to burn the car, but it was windy and rainy,'' and the effort failed. she said she did not know who attacked the editor, whose newspaper follows a mainstream nationalist palestinian line
the domestic news agency itim reported the army demolished nine arab houses during the night _ three because they belonged to people suspected of firebomb attacks. the agency said it was the first time the army demolished homes of suspected firebombers. new rules for soldiers also allow them to shoot when attacked with firebombs
arab reporters said underground leaders of what palestinians call ``the uprising'' distributed a new leaflet, no. 11, calling for arabs belonging to or working for israeli-appointed municipal councils in the west bank and gaza to quit by saturday
hundreds of arab policemen resigned last week at the request of palestinian underground leaders, who are members of the plo
time and newsweek magazines filed an injunction with the supreme court today in an effort to recover news film israeli authorities confiscated after the shooting of katz. ``demands for the return of the film made repeatedly to israeli authorities has been unavailing, and as a result legal action is being pursued,'' the magazines said in a statement
israeli arabs on sunday decided to hold a general strike on march 30 to mark land day, an annual national event which began a decade ago as a protest against the government's policy of expropriating arab-owned land
fbi agents acting on an anonymous tip peacefully captured one of the agency's 10 most wanted fugitives, a killer sought in three kidnappings since his escape from a louisiana prison 19 months ago, authorities said
danny michael weeks, 34, and a companion, jorene h. florea, 56, were arrested sunday by a 10-member fbi team, said don s. tokunaga, who heads the agency's seattle office
the two apparently were just passing through when agents received an anonymous tip from someone who had recognized weeks as on the most-wanted list, tokunaga said
it was one of those spur-of-the-moment things,'' he said. ``we were fortunate there were no incidents.''
the two were scheduled to appear before a u.s. magistrate today
weeks was wanted for escape, interstate flight, and on warrants alleging kidnapping in houston and kidnapping and robbery in greensboro, n.c. he also has been implicated in a kidnapping in alexandria, la., the day after his aug. 24, 1986, escape from the louisiana state penitentiary
ms. florea was wanted by officials in greensboro on a warrant charging her with kidnapping
when arrested, the pair were unarmed and were looking into the trunk of a car
weeks, originally of roswell, n.m., was serving a life sentence for armed robbery and murder when he and james lee colvin, 33, of shreveport, la., escaped from the prison
the next day, authorities said, colvin and weeks kidnapped a woman at knifepoint in alexandria and forced her to drive to houston, where she was freed unharmed
later that day, authorities said, the two forced another woman at gunpoint into her car in houston. she was forced to drive them to el paso, texas, but was unharmed
colvin, who was captured in 1986 in los angeles, was convicted in august in houston of federal kidnapping charges
tokunaga said the greensboro warrants stemmed from the feb. 23, 1988, kidnapping at gunpoint of guilford county, n.c., sheriff's deputy susan kathleen vincent, 27. she was released unharmed in chicago on feb. 26
ms. vincent said that during her abduction, her captors robbed a bank in davenport, iowa
greensboro police said they were seeking the extradition of weeks and ms. florea in ms. vincent's abduction
weeks was serving a 99-year sentence for armed robbery when he was sentenced in 1985 to life in prison for the christmas 1981 contract slaying of army sgt. major hubert ester. weeks pleaded guilty to second-degree murder
ester's wife, patricia, was convicted of first-degree murder in 1983 for hiring weeks and is serving a life sentence
weeks escaped twice from authorities in ouachita parish, la. he committed the armed robbery in shreveport after his first escape. expert says</head>
most of the psychological tests now in use do a poor job of evaluating black personality and attitudes, according to a black psychologist who says he has developed a test to remedy the problem
it is time we begin to show sensitivity to black american culture and stop trying to make black americans conform to anglo test material and test biases,'' said robert l. williams, a professor of psychology and black studies at washington university in st. louis
williams made the comments saturday to about 150 people at a psychology conference, where participants studied the impact of ethnicity and race on their clients
black lifestyles should be examined and understood in terms of their historical, cultural and social realities and not in terms of a comparison with the experiences of other groups, for example euro-americans,'' said williams
he said he has developed a standardized test for blacks called themes concerning blacks
the test, now being used by a number of schools, corporations and psychologists, consists of 20 charcoal drawings depicting various aspects of black culture and lifestyles in rural and urban areas, he said
culturally specific tests are necessary because people of various ethnic backgrounds may perform badly on tests designed for and by euro-americans, and they may be labeled inaccurately as a result, williams said
mislabeling may have profoundly negative effects on intellectual and personality development,'' williams said
he said he was told by a white counselor in elementary school that he had only borderline intelligence and should take manual training programs in high school. williams later went to college and earned a doctorate from washington university
the conference, which ended saturday, was sponsored by the chicago school of professional psychology
a delta air lines jet made a safe emergency landing after one of its sets of wheels failed to lower. the jet's left wing scraped the runway and ignited but no injuries were reported
flight 314 circled portland international airport for 40 minutes sunday after the boeing 727-200's left landing gear failed to operate
the pilot, 20-year delta veteran tom peace, gently set the plane on its right and front wheels as it rolled 2,000 to 3,000 feet on a rarely used runway, said darrel buttice of the port of portland
port spokeswoman sara roberts said emergency crews immediately put out the small fire on the left wing
inflatable emergency chutes were deployed from the doorways, and the 71 passengers were evacuated without incident, ms. roberts said
the incident was under investigation by the federal aviation administration
the flight originated in atlanta and made a stop in salt lake city before heading to portland, buttice said. styles</head>
models in glen plaid cutaways or sequined jackets over black pants looked like emcees from the folies bergeres as italian enrico coveri threw a winter wear floor show to celebrate his 10th year as a paris designer
as for the skinny sequin dresses with hearts or fringes on bosoms and the crinoline short puffy dresses, they more often looked like toulouse-lautrec's dancers
his longer dance-hall dresses with striped taffeta skirts, moire jackets and bodices laced up with velvet were more wearable
coveri's show sunday featured day looks with military details. reversible short capes in all colors, plaids and houndstooth checks flew open over well-cut suits, either with short, full skirts or pants with gold-buttoned military jackets _ sergeant's stripe details stitched into the sleeves
long pants or minis had the zebra touch, sometimes paired with leather
angelo tarlazzi had a ``spaghetti western'' show with some strong ideas for day clothes
boots and cowboy hats were worn with almost everything, including the full-skirted belted coats _ black for daytime, taffeta for evening
some of the long and swirly-skirted coats in dusty pinks came out with brown beaver collars and full beaver sleeves. some of his greatcoats were worn with gray or navy battle jackets and flounced grey flannel skirts underneath
another suit had a tailored jacket front and puffy sleeves over slim velvet or tweed pants. tarlazzi often topped pants with long split or wrapped pleated skirts
minis appeared in low-waisted royal blue and black or red jersey, sometimes topped with wrapped shawls _ long a tarlazzi trademark
his new soft sweaters either had yoked fronts and black ribbons wound through their hems or ``passementerie'' or tasseled curtain-edging in bi-colored outfits
for evening, it was western saloon garb, with puffy taffeta skirts hitched up over boots, fitted fake fur tops with pointed hems, tiered and ruffled skirts with short tuxedo tops _ over pants
issey miyake, the artistic japanese with a flair for fabrics, has loosened up his complicated looks to smoother styles for easy wear
his triple-layered flowing jersey tent dresses in soft sky or royal or grape blues, plum, gray and black left the body totally unconstricted
menswear styles looked pleasingly shaped or baggy. but feminine notes abounded as well, especially in a short sheer crepe caramel dress pleated all over
miyake finished up with some trouser suits splattered with color
at balenciaga, designer michel goma showed simple sophistication in belted coats with pilgrims' or caped collars, suits with cropped weskit jackets and full-skirted tweed suits with full lacy petticoats showing underneath
at dorothee bis, the unpretentious styles were easy, young and offhand, always colorful, with fuchsias, blues and bright greens
her all-knit starters were slim polo-necked and short, coming out in 14 colors with matching tights. to pep up some of the dresses, she plastered them with triangles flapping from one point
shorts suits and babydoll dresses with yokes put in a cheery appearance. and evenings had glitter dusted on black or cocktail suits with guipure or heavy lace backs and sleeves on blazers over guipure skirts
a motorcycle that may have been laden with explosives blew up in downtown tokyo today, damaging windows of nearby buildings but causing no injuries, police reported
a police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the explosion occurred near hibiya park about 880 yards southeast of the imperial palace. he said the motorcycle appeared to have been rigged with explosives
he said there were reports of explosions in three other parts of the city and that authorities are investigating the incidents
the official said japanese radicals might have been responsible for the motorcycle explosion, but details were not immediately available
members of the florida baptist general convention are in an ``uproar'' over the drug arrest of their executive director
the rev. john taylor, 25, was one of 139 people arrested last week in operation crackdown iii by the broward sheriff's department, deputies said. he was charged with trying to buy crack from an undercover officer, police said
dr. henry j. lyons, a minister and president of the st. petersburg-based group, said taylor has been suspended without pay. that leaves vacant the convention's top administrative post two weeks before the 500,000-member organization convenes its annual meeting
taylor's future will be discussed at that gathering, lyons said
everyone is in an uproar and an outrage. they don't know what to think,'' lyons said. ``we will offer him some sort of rehabilitative help if he wants it or deems it necessary.''
if proven guilty, we will have no alternative but to terminate him from his office,'' lyons said. the convention is an association of 728 baptist churches that considers itself the single largest black organization in the state
lyons said taylor, who lives in st. petersburg, was in fort lauderdale on official convention business. he was arrested northwest of fort lauderdale several hours after he attended a service thursday at mount olive baptist church
lyons said he sent two ministers to fort lauderdale on friday to learn the facts of the case
the convention hired taylor 16 months ago, recruiting him from bishop college in dallas, where he was doing graduate work
he handles the nuts and bolts. he carries the program of the convention across the state,'' lyons said. ``he does his job extremely well. we were quite satisfied with his job performance. i have no reason to think he was using cocaine. it never dawned on me.''
a broward county jail employee said taylor was no longer in custody saturday
an unarmed intruder was shot to death while scaling a gate outside parliament, police said today
police spokesman ravi pawar said the unidentified man was challenged by security guards shortly after midnight sunday. when the man did not heed their calls, the guards opened fire, pawar said
a senior police officer investigating the case said the intruder was not armed. the official spoke on condition of anonymity
security is tight at parliament because it is currently in session and sikh militants agitating for a separate homeland have threatened to kill prime minister rajiv gandhi and members of his cabinet
the officer said a police team was sent to neighboring haryana state to an address in a diary found near the intruder's body
until the team returns, we cannot identify the man,'' he said
m. butterfly,'' which opened sunday night, is a brilliant new play, with layers of ironies, fantasies, sexual and romantic ambiguities and gender reversals by individuals and even the occident and the orient
the play, california-born playwright david henry hwang's broadway debut, stars john lithgow and b.d. wong, both giving striking performances
the story turns on its head puccini's opera ``madame butterfly,'' in which navy lt. pinkerton marries madame butterfly while stationed in japan then sails away while she lovingly believes he'll come back
in ``m. butterfly'' _ meaning monsieur butterfly _ it is the foreign man posted in the orient who deeply loves. lithgow plays rene gallimard, attached to the french embassy in beijing in 1960
the naive, babyfaced gallimard, who narrates the story in flashback from a french prison, sees the woman of his dreams, song liling (b.d. wong), singing ``madama butterfly.'' he calls the singer butterfly ever after
but butterfly is a chinese actor playing a woman, and whether butterfly cares for gallimard is unknown. they have an affair for 20 years in which gallimard never sees butterfly naked or allows himself to realize butterfly is a man
hwang, whose plays have been acclaimed off-broadway, was inspired by real-life reports of a similar situation in an espionage trial in france
in ``m. butterfly,'' butterfly is a communist agent who gives gallimard misinformation to pass on to america about vietnam. eventually butterfly gets him to become a courier and photograph documents
at gallimard's treason trial, butterfly, in a business suit, tells the judge, ``the west has a racial mentality about the east. the west thinks of itself as masculine, the east as delicate, wanting to be submissive.''
the play is talky, as plays of ideas are. but lithgow's character, as written and acted, is a rich one. gallimard had a wife (rose gregorio) and a fling with a young blonde (lindsay frost) whose frank speech he considered masculine. butterfly, asked by the judge (george n. martin) how gallimard could not know he was a man, says: ``men believe what they want to believe.''
the play is ambiguous about whether gallimard wanted to believe in his dream woman or whether he was, without knowing his own secret, homosexual. the two argue about that _ for too long _ after the trial, gallimard insisting, ``i am a man who loved a woman created by a man.''
the play ends like the opera, with gallimard having taken over butterfly's situation and finally her role
director john dexter has seamlessly woven eastern and western stage elements. stagehands wearing black, so they're ``unseen,'' as in oriental theater, move furniture and props. the stage has a red backdrop and a black platform encircled by a sweeping white ramp that reaches high into the wings
in other reviews, the daily news' howard kissel said the play is witty and filled with provocative images, but baffling. ``off-broadway, its assets would be properly appreciated,'' the review said. ``here its slick trappings set expectations it cannot meet.''
reviewer frank rich of the new york times said the ``singular'' play treats a number of universal conflicts _ men versus women and east versus west
though `m. butterfly' presents us with a visionary work that bridges the history and culture of two worlds, the production stops crushingly short of finding the gripping human drama that merges mr. hwang's story with his brilliant play of ideas,'' the critic wrote. honduras</head>
gov. richard celeste wants defense secretary frank carlucci to reconsider holding national guard training exercises in honduras because of recent reports of hostilities with neighboring nicaragua
in a letter to carlucci on saturday, celeste said he was concerned for the safety of ohio guardsmen after president reagan ordered ``combat ready'' members of the 82nd airborne into the central american nation
reagan sent the troops last week after nicaraguan troops reportedly crossed into honduras in pursuit of contra rebel forces battling nicaragua's sandinista government
i urge you to defer this and all national guard training missions at least until the current highly charged situation is behind us,'' celeste said in the letter. ``if not, what assurance can you provide that this is a neccessary and prudent training mission for our guard members at this time?''
the governor also wrote that he believed the presence of u.s. national guard units in honduras could undermine progress on central american peace negotiatons
celeste wrote that he continued to oppose sending ohio engineering units into honduras for exercises scheduled for 1989, but pledged to abide by instructions of the defense department and the national guard bureau
ohio and several other states joined minnesota in a lawsuit challenging the guard bureau's authority to commit state guardsmen to training exercises outside the country over a governor's objection. a federal court in minnesota last summer ruled in favor of the guard bureau, but the decision is being appealed
the governor's press secretary, debra phillips, said the letter was sent saturday by an overnight delivery service to carlucci ``so it will be on his desk when he gets in monday morning.''
copies of the letter also were sent to ohio's u.s. senators _ john glenn and howard metzenbaum _ and to u.s. rep. edward feighan, all democrats
the recent death of child star heather o'rourke has left mgm studio executives in a quandary over how to market her film ``poltergeist iii'' without appearing to exploit the 12-year-old actress
normal adults and obviously fathers like myself might be very offended,'' said barry lorie, mgm's senior vice president for marketing
miss o'rourke died feb. 1 of septic shock caused by a bowel obstruction. she had completed the film, scheduled for release june 10, last spring
she was best known for her lines ``they're heeeeere'' and ``they're baaaaack,'' which helped sell the first two ``poltergeist'' films
in ``poltergeist iii'' miss o'rourke's character, carol anne, still haunted by ghostly beings, is sent to live with relatives in chicago
although lorie said the films generally appeal to teen-age audiences whose members likely wouldn't be disturbed by miss o'rourke's death, he added he could imagine angry letters from adults denouncing an ad campaign that appears to trade on her death
the studio plans to test audience reactions to various ad campaigns shown at screenings before releasing the film june 10
lorie said mgm has also asked the movie's other main stars, tom skerritt and nancy allen, to avoid interviews that would lead to questions about miss o'rourke
lorie said the studio is worried about tabloid exploitation, particularly because one actor on each of the previous movies died shortly after shooting was completed
actress dominique dunne, who appeared in the original 1982 film, was strangled by an ex-boyfriend in 1982. julian beck, of ``poltergeist ii'' died of cancer in 1985
horse thieves cut a hole in a fence and allowed at least 75 beefalo to wander onto the florida turnpike, leading to five minor accidents, an injury to a woman and the deaths of seven animals, police said
five of the beefalo died in the accidents and two other injured animals had to be killed by humane society workers, the florida highway patrol reported
the beefalo, part of a 400-head herd owned by dr. arnie oper, roamed through a hole cut by thieves and ambled onto the turnpike extension north of miami sunday morning, said fhp sgt. alvis chinn
what they're doing apparently is stealing the horses in the early morning hours and they're leaving without fixing the fence,'' chinn said
the accidents caused an estimated $18,000 to $20,000 in damage to the vehicles involved, chinn said. an unidentified woman who was treated for minor injuries and released from palmetto general hospital, he said
motorist shelley d'errico said she slowed down when she spotted part of the herd. when one started toward her car, she took off
my husband told me to gun it,'' she said, adding that her car was unscathed. ``i don't know if my insurance company would believe that a buffalo put a dent in my car.''
the herd was rounded up by animal-control officers, passersby and ranch workers, chinn said. the beefalo, a hybrid of buffalo and cattle, were valued at $1,500 to $1,800 each
a woman who owed a $50 cocaine debt was beaten and locked in a car trunk, then doused with gasoline and set afire by angry drug dealers, police said
the 36-year-old woman, who officers refused to identify, was taken to alta bates hospital in berkeley with second- and third-degree burns on 15 percent of her upper body, police said. a nursing supervisor who asked not to be identified said the woman was in stable condition
this is my first time to find something like this in a coke deal,'' said police sgt. roy williams
authorities said witnesses told investigators a group of men confronted the woman friday seeking payment of the drug debt
they said that when she said she couldn't pay, she was beaten, thrown into the trunk of their car and driven away, then was returned and set afire
residents of one north oakland neighborhood held a rally saturday to urge a battle against drug dealers
after years of slavery, job discrimination, the depression, northern intimidation, lynchings and beatings, none of which broke the spirit of the black race, a little white powder has come along that has done more damage to the black community than any span of history,'' the rev. ray williams told listeners
many homes in the area had boarded up windows and barred doors
what's happened to the neighborhood?'' asked estelle harmon, a resident for 28 years. ``name it. everything. it used to be nice and neat and clean, and now all of these dope people have gotten in here, and i mean we are surrounded.'' strike, mrs. mandela saying no trouble with police. pickup 5th graf ``in soweto...''; subs 12th graf ``at the...'' with one graf to confirm reports students beaten</note>
commuter buses from soweto were deserted today and four buses near durban were firebombed as hundreds of thousands of blacks joined the first nationwide protest strike since major opposition groups were banned last month
in other violence, police fired tear gas at a predominantly indian university and arrested students who tried to force others to join the boycott. the strike was organized in defiance of emergency regulations to commemorate the 28th anniversary of a massacre in the township of sharpeville and to protest the banning of any activity by the united democratic front and 16 other anti-apartheid groups
police estimated 40 percent of the black work force in the johannesburg region stayed away from their jobs, but did not give a figure for the number involved
in sharpeville, residents placed flowers at graves of some of the 69 massacre victims and held memorial services
winnie mandela, wife of jailed african national congress leader nelson mandela, attended one of the services after arriving in the township south of johannesburg in a bus with other activists
there was an unconfirmed report police ordered the bus to leave, but mrs. mandela said her group left voluntarily
in soweto, the black township of 2.5 million people outside johannesburg, virtually no passengers boarded commuter buses, according to cheryl roxmouth of the putco bus company. normal daily ridership is about 75,000
schools and most shops in soweto were closed, and residents said few of the hundreds of mini-bus taxis which carry many sowetans to work were operating
south african transport services said ridership on its trains during morning rush hour was down by up to 20 percent. it dismissed as inaccurate an earlier press report that said ridership was down by about 80 percent
in durban, four putco buses were firebombed, prompting putco to halt service in several townships when drivers refused to work. police reported two unrest-related killings of blacks overnight, one near durban and one in soweto, but gave no indication if they were linked to the protest
at the university of durban-westville, where most students are of indian descent, police used tear gas to disperse protesters and arrested some students who tried to force others to boycott classes. some students attending class were beaten by supporters of the boycott
the strike was widespread in the johannesburg-pretoria area, in durban and around the eastern cape province city of port elizabeth. more than 90 percent of black workers reportedly stayed home around the city of uitenhage, where police killed 21 blacks during a funeral procession on sharpeville day in 1985
there was no explicit call for workers in the cape town area to strike
the united democratic front, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition, had coordinated previous nationwide protests during the 21-month-old state of emergency. emergency regulations outlaw calls for strikes and boycotts, but hundreds of thousands of black workers and students nonetheless observed these protests by staying away from jobs and schools
several affiliates of the front, not affected by the new ban, took out newspaper advertisements announcing today's ``national day of protest.''
police commanders threatened action against organizers of the strike and issued assurances that blacks wishing to work would be protected from intimidators. there were reports of black youths turning back commuters but no reports of physical intimidation
commemorative services were scheduled in several cities and townships to mark the anniversary of the 1960 massacre in sharpeville. sixty-nine blacks were killed and about 180 injured when police fired on thousands of demonstrators protesting the pass laws. those laws, which restricted blacks' freedom of movement, were repealed in 1986
the predominantly white university of cape town and the mostly mixed-race university of the western cape closed in solidarity with the protest. for similar reasons, today's performance of ``district six,'' a musical with an anti-apartheid theme playing to full houses in johannesburg, was canceled
an afternoon protest was planned at johannesburg's university of the witwatersrand, where the president of the student council, rosemary hunter, reportedly was detained by police early today
sharpeville returned to the spotlight last week when it became known that friday had been set as the execution date for the ``sharpeville six'' _ five black men and a woman convicted of complicity in the mob killing of a black town councilor during anti-apartheid riots in 1984
appeals for clemency poured in from around the world, but president p.w. botha said he would not intervene to save the six
on thursday, 15 hours before the hangings were to take place, a supreme court judge granted a one-month stay of execution in order to consider defense attorneys' claims that a key state witness has perjured himself. find</head>
police looking for overdue books with fines totaling about $3,000 found more than 10,000 books from libraries worldwide in lockers rented by the oscar-nominated author whose book became the movie ``full metal jacket.''
police want to question jerry gustav hasford, author of ``the short-timers,'' said campus police detective ray berrett of california polytechnic state university, san luis obispo
a search warrant served by police from the school sought 87 overdue books that had been checked out from the campus library in hasford's name. fines totaled about $3,000
we found a lot more than we bargained for,'' said wayne carmack, another investigator
officers found only seven campus library books, but seized thousands of books marked as belonging to libraries as far away as england and australia, carmack said
university police have been unable to find hasford and question him about the books, but have not sought an arrest warrant from the district attorney's office, berrett said saturday
officers took a weekend break from the mammoth job of cataloging the pile of books, which measures 27 feet long, 5 feet wide and 5 feet tall, police dispatcher suzi goodwin said sunday
hasford, who recently lived in nearby morro bay, doesn't attend the university but got a library card under a program open to state residents, carmack said. but the card was obtained with a false address and social security number, carmack said
there was no comment from hasford; he does not have a listed telephone number in san luis obispo
hasford shares a 1988 academy award nomination for best screenplay adaptation with ``full metal jacket'' director stanley kubrick and michael herr
he didn't appear friday night at the writers guild of america awards ceremony, where he was considered for a similar award but didn't win. confirmed and to update total deaths. picks up graf 7 pvs bgng ``rabin told''</note>
israeli soldiers shot and killed a palestinian in the gaza strip today, arab reports said, and palestinians carried out a widespread general strike in the occupied territories
the strike, which left shops shuttered and public transport idle, came in response to a plo call for ``the most severe confrontation'' to commemorate the 20th anniversary of a palestinian guerrilla clash with israel
also today, attackers fired at a moderate arab's home, the army bulldozed homes of suspected firebombers and a leaflet by arab underground leaders urged more arabs working for the israeli government to quit by saturday
defense minister yitzhak rabin warned sunday night the army may use tougher measures against palestinians after the shooting death of an israeli soldier, the first member of the military to be killed in four months of rioting
in the gaza town of rafah, soldiers today fired tear gas and ammunition at stone-throwing protesters. abdel ahmed jaber al mudalal, 17, of rafah, died after he was shot in the chest, according to the palestine press service and other arab reports
al mudalal's body was taken to khan yunis' nasser hospital, the reports said. the army confirmed the death, but said it could not establish a cause because the youth's family had taken the body from the hospital
u.n. officials, meanwhile, confirmed arab reports that two men died sunday from gunshot wounds suffered earlier
khalid mohammed taher, 25, was shot march 16 during a protest in tulkarim. mohammed mahmoud hamad, 25, was hit by gunfire march 4 in the village of silwad, near ramallah
the fatalities brought to 106 the number of palestinians killed since the uprising begin dec. 8, including four deaths from tear gas inhalation, according to u.n. figures
rabin told reporters the army was investigating whether the shooting death of sgt. moshe katz indicated palestinians intended to expand the scope of their protests to firearms from the usual stones and gasoline bombs
katz, a reserve soldier, died sunday in bethlehem after he was shot in the head at close range while on guard duty at a government building
if ``extremist palestinian terrorist elements try to combine terrorist acts with civilian protests, we will have to change our operations and take harsher measures to handle both,'' rabin said
attackers fired shots before dawn today at the home and car of jack khazmo, a prominent moderate palestinian newspaper editor, workers at the weekly al bayader assiyasi said. no injuries were reported
wajiha awadallah, khazmo's secretary, said attackers ``fired many shots'' into khazmo's house in the village of ram, just north of jerusalem, at about 2:45 a.m
she said they also ``tried to burn the car, but it was windy and rainy,'' and the effort failed. she said she did not know who attacked the editor, whose newspaper follows a mainstream nationalist palestinian line
the domestic news agency itim reported the army demolished nine arab houses during the night _ three because they belonged to people suspected of firebomb attacks. the agency said it was the first time the army demolished homes of suspected firebombers. new rules for soldiers also allow them to shoot when attacked with firebombs
arab reporters said underground leaders of what palestinians call ``the uprising'' distributed a new leaflet, no. 11, calling for arabs belonging to or working for israeli-appointed municipal councils in the west bank and gaza to quit by saturday
hundreds of arab policemen resigned last week at the request of palestinian underground leaders, who are members of the plo
time and newsweek magazines filed an injunction with the supreme court today in an effort to recover news film israeli authorities confiscated after the shooting of katz. ``demands for the return of the film made repeatedly to israeli authorities has been unavailing, and as a result legal action is being pursued,'' the magazines said in a statement
israeli arabs on sunday decided to hold a general strike on march 30 to mark land day, an annual national event which began a decade ago as a protest against the government's policy of expropriating arab-owned land. dakota, since capturing gop caucuses in iowa.</note>
leaning back in his chair at a hotel suite as he waited for his next campaign appearance, sen. bob dole reflected on his reasons for remaining in the race for the republican presidential nomination
while some have begun to speak of concerns about splitting the gop, dole spoke sunday about responsibility and confidence
it's about the best thing that could happen to the party,'' dole said of his decision to stay in the race even though he has won just one primary _ south dakota _ since he captured the gop caucuses in iowa
it's the responsible thing to do. we've had a dozen republicans either look at this or formerly run as candidates. now we're down to two and we can get down to business.''
although some have speculated that a loss in the wisconsin primary april 5 may force him out of the race, dole said he thought his campaign work was only starting
it's the first day of spring, and we still haven't debated the issues,'' he said. ``we've had little press conferences that they called debates. ... but now we have a real chance to debate george bush.''
dole had challenged bush to a debate before the illinois primary, but bush refused. dole said he will try to arrange a debate before the wisconsin primary _ perhaps in wisconsin itself
we'll talk about any subject. he'll pick two and i'll pick two _ no notes, no moderator, just an hour or hour-and-a-half debate.''
dole kicked off a three-day campaign swing through wisconsin just hours after receiving news of a milwaukee journal poll that showed him trailing bush nearly 3-to-1 among wisconsin voters likely to vote in the primary
he said the poll was probably inaccurate but admitted ``i've got a lot of hill to climb.''
it's not surprising, but i don't think its accurate,'' he said. ``it was taken right after illinois with super tuesday still hanging over my head. my view is that you give voters a couple of weeks.''
dole was trounced by bush on super tuesday and then lost again in illinois. he said wisconsin was an important state for his campaign, but a loss april 5 did not necessarily mean he would drop out
we've been hearing the end is near, but people forget george bush stayed in eight weeks after he began losing to ronald reagan. eight weeks was enough for him to lose,'' he said in reference to the 1980 gop race. ``but i think eight weeks would be enough time for me to turn some things around.''
although emphasizing confidence, dole indicated that recent attention to the cuts he made on his paid national staff wore on his patience
he said he picked up a newspaper sunday morning in washington and was pleased to see there was not a single story about politics
it was kind of refreshing to pick up the paper and read about _ maybe not refreshing but different _ to read about panama, honduras, nicaragua and no politics
there are a lot of issues that should be discussed,'' he added. ``we shouldn't be into this game about are you going to run or are you going to drop out and how many staff people you have and all that inside baseball. the voter can care less about that.''
a misunderstanding by officers resulted in police breaking into the house of an elderly couple, where an 84-year-old man was killed in an exchange of gunfire, a prosecutor says
the officers were supposed to knock on the door but thought incorrectly that they were being ordered inside to capture a rape suspect, district attorney andy fuller said in an interview published sunday in the times of gainesville
dillard free was killed in the christmas eve shooting. fuller said free apparently was awakened by the sound of his front door being kicked down and fired two shots at officers
a grand jury on march 10 declined to indict the officer who shot free, but it expressed outrage about the shooting and called for a review of police procedures
a georgia bureau of investigation report on the shooting remains sealed because of indictments against the two people who told police the rape suspect was in the house. they are accused of making false statements
fuller said he decided to discuss the gbi's findings because ``the people of hall county need to know this information.''
fuller said six law officers told the gbi they remembered police detective robert gable directing that they use normal procedure for serving an arrest warrant _ that is, knocking and announcing ``warrant'' _ at the free home
but the officers who took up positions in front of the house, lee west, gary lenderman and kirk williamson, were not present to hear that order, fuller said
he said that when detective russell elrod told the officers by radio to ``go on in,'' lenderman seemed surprised and asked, ``you want us to go?''
the evidence indicates the detectives did not mean for (west and williamson) to break the door down, but the evidence also indicates that the uniformed officers felt they had been given a directive to go into the house,'' fuller said
west kicked down free's front door and he and williamson entered the darkened living room while sgt. benny patrick rushed onto the front porch, fuller said
he said patrick saw a silhouette moving inside and shouted ``police,'' but a shot was fired that narrowly missed his head. he said west then also shouted ``police'' and saw the figure fire again, striking a door frame
west then fired two shots, fatally wounding free in the thigh and neck
free's wife, agnes, 73, was hospitalized for shock and died march 5, three days after suffering a heart attack
the rape suspect the officers were seeking was arrested christmas day in texas. with details of second explosion.</note>
a motorcycle, apparently rigged with explosives, blew up today near the saudi arabian airlines office and a car bomb exploded near the israeli embassy about 15 minutes later, police said
there were no reports of injuries in the attacks. police said radicals may have been responsible
a police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the motorcycle, with apparent explosives on its back seat, burst into flames at about 7:17 p.m. near hibiya park and shattered windows of the saudi arabian airlines tokyo office. the park is about a half-mile yards southeast of the imperial palace
the police official said the second attack occurred near the israel embassy about 15 minutes later when explosives in a parked car's trunk exploded, damaging windows of nearby houses
he said there were no reports of damage at the embassy, about 3{ miles from hibiya park
the official said japanese radicals, who sometimes fire homemade missiles from cars parked in streets, may have been responsible for the explosions. further details were not immediately available
last month, four shuttle buses used to transport passengers to and from airports were burned in tokyo in apparent arson attacks by radicals opposed to the expansion of the new tokyo international airport in narita
local farmers and their supporters, including anti-government radical groups, have been resisting government plans to expropriate farmland to construct a second runway at narita
in may 1986, japanese radicals fired homemade missiles at the state guest house, the u.s. embassy, the imperial palace, the crown prince's residence and police headquarters in osaka before a seven-nation summit meeeting in tokyo
one attack came during japan's welcoming ceremonies for the heads of government of the united states, canada, britain, france, west germany and italy
a garbage truck driver who thought a cat had climbed into his compactor was stunned to find a man nearly buried under loads of trash
driver michael penton said he had taken on two loads of garbage when he got out of the truck to adjust the next garbage bin and heard a noise
at first i thought it was kids playing,'' penton said. ``but then i realized there are no kids there; it's all retirees or professional people.''
then he thought a cat was stuck inside
i just climbed up the ladder on the side of the truck, and there was this guy buried in the trash,'' penton said. ``all i saw was this arm and head.''
pasco county emergency workers disentangled dale berube, who suffered a broken pelvis and other injuries in the thursday accident
berube said he had been trying to retrieve an old rug from the garbage bin for a friend who wanted it to line a doghouse. he never heard the garbage truck coming
nor did he realize what was happening until he felt the truck pick up the metal box, he said in a strained voice saturday from his bed at bayfront medical center in st. petersburg. he was tossed into the truck and the compactor was started
i was very lucky,'' said berube, who has been having nightmares about his brush with death
i thought i was going to die for sure,'' he said. ``it was like squishing my body apart. i saw it coming back the third time and i thought, `please, god, please.'''
one of the country's most militant anti-apartheid newspapers today lost a court appeal seeking protection from government action, clearing the way for authorities to shut it down for three months
home affairs minister stoffel botha had intended to close the new nation in january, but the paper's court challenge delayed the move. his office would not comment today on how soon he would act
the paper was launched in january 1986 by the southern african catholic bishops conference as an alternative newspaper to reflect ``the daily struggles, desires and aspirations of the masses.''
published weekly with a circulation of 50,000 to 60,000, it has a small staff, and gets many of its reports from members of community organizations, trade unions and youth groups in the rural areas where the majority of black south africans live
its editor, zwelakhe sisulu, has been detained without charge for 16 of the 26 months of publication. the government has said he is being held because of his journalistic activities
authorities have banned four of the paper's editions and seized two. police have raided the new nation offices, and it was the first of six publications to be warned by botha that they could be closed or censored for publishing material he found objectionable
the paper does not claim to be objective. it's philosophy was explained in the last issue: ``journalists should not only report on what happens in society, but should also help find solutions to the problems of our country.''
but the paper challenged the government to prove in court that any of its reports were illegal under the law or the emergency regulations
the johannesburg supreme court ruled last week that botha has nearly unlimited powers to deal as he pleases with papers he feels might contribute to unrest. the court specifically ruled that botha did not have to give reasons for his decisions or actions
the court said the paper could appeal. but today, the court turned down the paper's request to keep botha from closing it during the nine months the appeal will take to be heard
the decision left the way open for botha to immediately issue a decree closing the paper
acting editor gabu tugwana said after the court decision, ``we are pretending we don't face any suspension. if the deadline (for the thursday) edition comes and we are printed, good luck to us.''
he noted that government gazettes, in which emergency decrees are published, usually come out on friday ``except in special circumstances. we don't know if we are that special to the government. they don't contact us. they don't have to.''
botha's power allows him to close a paper for up to three months, or establish an in-house censor, but tugwana said that if the paper is closed it would only be allowed to reopen under even more stringent restrictions
i just think the world at large, internally and externally, haven't yet seen this seriously. it is an action against the whole media,'' he said
there are many more axes hanging in the air that will fall on many others,'' he said in reference to warnings issued against several other papers. ``we are the first on the line because we have lesser protection. as far as the government is concerned, we are just a pamphlet.''
actors and announcers who make commercial went on strike nationwide today after contract talks were deadlocked over cable television residuals and cost-of-living adjustments
the screen actors guild and aftra did begin a strike at 12:01 this morning against advertising agencies and producers of commercials,'' said dick moore, a spokesman for the american federation of television and radio artists
he said no new negotiations had been scheduled
the joint sag-aftra membership numbers more than 100,000. the unions negotiate together on the commercial contract
talks on a new three-year pact between the performers and the joint policy committee of the american association of advertising agencies and the association of national advertisers began jan. 11 in new york city and hit an impasse march 7
union negotiators received a 93 percent strike authorization vote from members just before contract talks broke off
meanwhile, no new talks were scheduled between the 9,000-member writers guild of america and producers to end that union's 2-week-old strike. they have been at a stalemate over residuals from foreign distribution, creative control and a management proposal to restructure residuals for one-hour television shows sold into syndication
the commercial contract dispute centers on performers' demands for a share of money made from commercials broadcast on cable television and advertisers' attempts to reduce union cost-of-living adjustments
actors currently receive no residuals from cable television broadcasts of their commercials after they have earned their first $1,000 in payments from regular, prime-time television. virtually all ads shown on cable meet the $1,000 requirement, said guild official ken orsatti
the unions recently sent telegrams to all u.s. presidential candidates offering to grant them production waivers if they agree to interim contracts conceding to the demands
the interim contract offer was given to regular advertisers as well, and as many as 40 have said they will seek them, according to the union
three teen-age girls have been arrested and accused of terrorizing two elderly woman by pushing their way into the women's apartment and demanding money while they tore the place apart, police said
tanya williams, 16, and two 13-year-old females whose names were withheld because of their age were arrested sunday and charged with first-degree robbery and first-degree burglary, said police sgt. diane kubler
the three teen-agers allegedly pushed their way into an apartment occupied by 90-year-old emma otto and her 83-year-old sister, margaret tellesen, on march 16, kubler said
tellesen said she let the girls in wednesday when they asked to use the bathroom. one of the 13-year-olds knew one of the women through her mother, police said
the three scattered papers around the apartment, cut the telephone line and threatened to kill the women if they did not give them money, kubler said. the three left after the women gave them $50, she said
the three returned to the apartment saturday, pushing their way in and again threatening the women, the sergeant said
the three left after taking $300 in cash and two bank books, kubler said
building owner zack kaimakliotis took the women to police after the second robbery and detectives staked out the apartment
the three girls were arrested after they returned a third time early sunday. the girls told police they spent the money on clothes, the newspaper reported. assessment is not locero's, but his paraphrase of company statements.</note>
the government's ``superfund'' program cleaning up toxic waste dumps should go back to its old policy of seeking up-front payment commitments from polluters before beginning work, an environmental protection agency official says
gene a. locero says the program faces inevitable shortfalls as it begins new cleanup projects before the polluting companies agree to pay for the work
locero is head of the waste programs enforcement office at epa, but plans to leave. on april 15, he will become a special assistant to administrator lee m. thomas
his gloomy analysis of superfund's prospects appears in the march-april issue of ``environmental forum,'' a publication of the environmental law institute
locero's boss, winston porter, the assistant administrator whose programs include superfund, had not yet seen the article, his office reported
for the first two years of the program, officials negotiated with companies responsible for pollution at dump sites, trying to win agreements to pay before substantial work was begun
but accusations of political influence on decision-making that rocked the agency in 1983 and led to many resignations also led to a new strategy _ if cleanup agreements aren't reached quickly, the agency will start site investigations and cleanup work anyway and seek reimbursement later
amendments passed in 1986 that authorized an $8.5 billion program over the next five years oblige the agency to start 175 cleanups by october 1989, and another 200 by 1991
locero presented this worst-case analysis:
if it is assumed that the agency will fund all the starts itself, and that the average cost is $30 million for each action, then by october 1989 the agency would need $5.25 billion for these actions alone,'' and $6 billion more for the 200 actions to follow by 1991
epa now assumes each site will cost $21 million for cleanup alone, not counting overhead _ an estimate that has more than tripled in six years
companies will obviously pay for some, but ``the agency's top management officials do not dispute whether there will be a shortfall, but only how much,'' locero wrote
epa now tends to seek ``all or nothing'' agreements from the companies responsible for a site. the agency has little incentive to craft the far more difficult agreements where some companies pay for only some of the cleanup followed by court action against recalcitrants
locero says the court action is ``unlikely to be a priority'' and thus not much of a threat
to many companies that might settle with epa, ``this is equivalent to `shooting the volunteers,''' locero wrote. ``this dynamic, if not changed, reduces the likelihood that the agency can look to (companies) for a greater share of the cleanup outputs it is committed to.''
meeting the commitment means ``confronting the possibility once again that outside observers, especially congress, may criticize the agency by slowing down cleanup by looking to more (company) cleanups, or for entering into partial settlements that are too favorable'' to the companies
the 1986 amendments recognized that remedial action may not be able to achieve full restoration of every site, but ``some in the agency fear that making remedy decisions that are less than full restoration will provoke harsh and damaging criticism of the program,'' locero said
unfortunately this has diverted attention to collecting more and more data to justify decisions, which threatens to add more time to the ever-increasing length'' of site investigations, he added
locero said the the agency must consider beginning cleanup before the investigations are finished, and stop trying to make cleanups that will be final
on sites that involve polluted groundwater, he said epa should consider installing pump-and-treat systems early in the first months of a site investigation to capture the contaminant plume and keep the groundwater resource from being polluted further and save both time and money
in some cases, it might be just as appropriate ... to restrict access as long as the result was adequate protection of human health and the environment,'' locero said
prime minister noboru takeshita told graduating military cadets today that japan's military power should match its economic strength
we cannot cope with a military threat or maintain ties with our allies and gain their trust without defense capabilities commensurate with our national power,'' takeshita told the 410 graduates of the national defense academy in kanagawa prefecture, west of tokyo
takeshita's speech was his first at the nation's only defense college since he became prime minister last november
takeshita said japan would use its military only for defensive purposes and would never threaten other nations
he said japan's defense buildup would be attained within the framework of the japan-u.s. security treaty, while adhering to japan's three non-nuclear policies. japan bans the manufacture, possession and introduction of nuclear arms into japan
the united states has been pressuring japan to increase defense spending and take more responsibility for its defense. but some asian nations, which suffered from japanese aggression during world war ii, have expressed concern about a japanese military build-up
takeshita said japan's security ``will not be guaranteed by its military power alone'' and called for a comprehensive approach to security, including diplomatic efforts and efforts to maintain a continuous supply of natural resources from abroad, academy spokesman nobuo tsuchida quoted takeshita as saying
last year, japan formally scrapped a decade-old ceiling which limited defense spending to 1 percent of its gross national product. during the current 1986-90 defense buildup plan, the government says japan's defense spending will total $119.87 billion. protesters</head>
king hussein of jordan today called on moslem nations to back protesters in the israeli-occupied territories and repeated that the the plo must join any peace talks
the palestinian people have a rightful claim on us to support their uprising both on the national and international level so that the uprising may bear fruit,'' hussein said in opening a conference of foreign ministers from the organization of islamic conference. the group includes 45 moslem nations and the palestinian liberation organization
hussein, a key player in any middle east peace negotiations, said: ``the uprising of the palestinian people is not an end in itself nor is it a transient coincidental event that will soon wither away
it is rather an expression of the will of an entire nation to fight for its freedom and right of self-determination in its own land.''
hussein, in his remarks prepared for delivery to the conference, gave no specifics of what kind of help he wants for the palestinian protesters
the protesters have been fighting israeli occupation forces in the west bank and gaza strip in an outbreak of violence that began nearly four months ago. the united nations reports more than 100 palestinians have died in that time from gunfire, beatings, and tear gas inhalation. the first israeli soldier was killed sunday
israel seized the west bank from jordan and the gaza strip from egypt in the 1967 middle east war
in demanding that the plo be included in peace talks, hussein parted ways with the united states, which subscribes to the israeli view of the group as an illegal, terrorist organization
hussein also called on iran to accept u.n. calls for a cease-fire in its 7{-year-old war with iraq. in the latest escalation, the two nations have been hurling missiles into each other's cities for the past three weeks
hussein told those attending today's conference that the war was a ``wound ... still bleeding and draining our resources and energies.''
iraq has said it will stop shooting if iran does. but tehran has said it will only comply with the u.n. appeal when iraq is branded the aggressor
the supreme court today agreed to consider killing a key provision of a law designed to promote competitive bidding on government contracts, setting the stage for a new ruling on the boundaries between congressional and presidential powers
the court said it will hear reagan administration arguments challenging the comptroller general's role in administering the 1984 competition in contracting act
the case raises issues similar to those in the constitutional fight over the gramm-rudman deficit-cutting law
the case stems from rejection by the u.s. army corps of engineers of a low bid submitted by ameron inc., a new jersey company, to repair sewer lines at the united states military academy at west point, n.y
although ameron submitted a bid of $1.03 million, some $200,000 less than the next lowest bidder, it was rejected by the corps because of a problem with the bond supporting the bid
ameron protested the rejection under provisions of the 1984 competition in contracting act
the law empowers the comptroller general, a congressional watchdog, to suspend the award of contracts and to award bid-preparation costs and attorney's fees to companies that successfully challenge the rejection of their bids
the law was prompted by alleged excess costs of awarding many lucrative government contracts without competitive bidding. the law's supporters said that in fiscal 1983 the government awarded $114 billion in non-competitive contracts out of a total of $168 billion
administration lawyers said the powers given the comptroller general in the 1984 law are unconstitutional under the supreme court's 1986 ruling in the gramm-rudman case
in that decision, the justices struck down the core provision of the deficit-reduction law because it designated the comptroller general as the official with power to set across-the-board budget cuts. the court said such a function impermissibly blurs the line separating the legislative and executive branches
the comptroller general is appointed by the president but can be removed from office only by congress
in the dispute over contract bidding, the 3rd u.s. circuit court of appeals said the comptroller general's powers under the 1984 law are within constitutional bounds
the appeals court said the law ``rather than concentrating power in the legislative branch ... diffuses and divides power, giving final control over procurement decisions to the executive but permitting meaningful oversight by an agent of congress.''
it said the comptroller general legitimately may delay contract awards to assure that federal procurement officials pay attention to his recommendations
the law is aimed at counteracting ``the apparent willingness of procuring agencies to frustrate congressional inquiry by rushing to complete challenged procurement projects,'' the appeals court added
justice department lawyers told the high court that the law gives the comptroller general non-legislative powers to determine ``the timing of a contract between an agency of the executive branch and a private party.''
the law was defended by comptroller general charles a. bowsher and by democratic and republican leaders of congress
the case is army corps of engineers vs. ameron, 87-163. gulf. picks up 4th graf, `iraq, meanwhile ...' edits to tighten. changes byline.</note>
iranian gunboats today attacked a liberian tanker and a spanish refrigerator ship in the persian gulf, setting them afire, and norwegian officials said as many as 54 crewmen were believed killed in a weekend iraqi raid
maritime salvage experts, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the blaze today aboard the 10,168-ton refrigerator ship iberian reefer was ``fierce.''
salvage tugboats were racing to aid the vessel, but there were no immediate word on casualties, the officials said
gulf-based shipping executives said earlier at least one iranian gunboat fired up to 10 rocket-propelled grenades at the 61,762-ton liberian-registered fumi, setting its engine room ablaze and blasting holes in one of its tanks
the japanese-managed tanker, laden with saudi arabian oil, was on its way out of the gulf. the executives said salvage tugboats helped the fumi's crew put out the fire
the iranian attacks today were in apparent retaliation for an iraqi attack on kharg island oil terminal saturday
the norwegian foreign ministry in oslo said as many as 54 crewmen were presumed dead in that attack
most of the crew were iranians or asians, although a swedish officer was among the missing
if the norwegian report is correct, it would be the highest death toll from an iraqi raid on iranian vessels since the so-called ``tanker war'' began in 1984, an offshoot of the 7{-year-old iran-iraq war
about 480 ships have been attacked by one side or the other since the war broke out. until the weekend attacks, more than 200 seamen had been killed
christen puntervold of the norwegian shipping association said four of the 29-man crew of the tanker 253,837-ton sanandaj had been found alive after the attack saturday
the others are missing. about the other ship, we don't know for sure, but we are afraid it could be the same for them,'' he said, referring to the 316,379-ton avaj which also carried a crew of 29
both ships were owned by the national iranian tanker co., but sanandaj's crew was enlisted by viking engineering, which is norwegian owned
bahrain's information minister, tariq al-moayyed, called for foreign naval forces in the region to guarantee the safety of shipping lanes in the gulf, through which 20 percent of the non-communist world's oil supplies pass
the minister, in an interview with nbc-tv urged the foreign forces to ``reach a declaration ... that they will not allow interference with freedom of shipping in the gulf.''
iraq, meanwhile, said it fired a long-range missile into tehran today, the 105th in three weeks, and that iranian gunners pounded its southern port city of basra in an 18-hour artillery and rocket barrage
there was no immediate report from tehran of a missile strike
but the official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, cyprus, reported that the missile was fired at 3:40 p.m. in retaliation for the bombardment of basra
it said there were ``heavy casualties'' in basra, which the iranians were hammering in apparent retaliation for rocket and air attacks on tehran and other cities sunday
iran's official media said at least 33 civilians were killed and 65 wounded in those strikes
both sides have fired nearly 250 missiles into each other's main cities and border towns since feb. 29, reportedly killing hundreds of civilians
the iranian news agency today reported scores of kurdish children, aged between 2 and 10 years old, were being treated in hospitals for injuries suffered in iraqi chemical bomb attacks thursday
the children were among 4,000 iraqi kurds tehran claims were injured in the iraqi raids on towns captured by iranian forces in a new offensive
the iranians have charged that 5,000 kurds in the northeastern towns of khomal, halabja and dojaila were killed in the chemical bombing raids
iran claims it has punched 9{ miles into northeast iraq in an offensive launched a week ago
the iraqis have admitted the loss of several towns in sulaimaniyeh province as iran reported fighting still raging between its revolutionary guards and iraq's 5th corps
the supreme court today refused to let states and local governments regulate the prices most of the nation's cable television operators charge for basic service
the court, without comment, rejected arguments that the deregulation effected in 1986 by congress and the federal communications commission left subscribers vulnerable to illegal monopoly pricing
most of the nation's 7,800 cable operators provide both basic and ``premium'' services. for an extra monthly fee, subscribers receive channels offering exclusive sports and movie programming
basic service includes local broadcast stations and a few cable networks such as cnn, espn and c-span
prior to 1984, the fcc allowed local communities to regulate the rates charged for basic cable service but not for premium service rates
congress in 1984 enacted the cable communications policy act, which lets local authorities regulate basic cable rates only in the absence of ``effective competition.''
defining ``effective competition'' was left up to the fcc, and the commission's definition paved the way for the deregulation of basic-service rates charged by more than 90 percent of all cable operators
the commission's rule says any cable system faces effective competition _ and avoids local regulation of basic-service rates _ if television viewers in the area can watch at least three different channels without a cable hookup
the deregulation took effect dec. 29, 1986
the prices cable operators charged for basic service rose an average of 10.6 percent during the first six months of deregulation, according to a survey released by the national cable television association
the survey indicated that premium-channel rates dropped 2.3 percent during the same period
the u.s. circuit court of appeals here upheld the commission rule and basic-service rate deregulation last july 17
the appeal acted on today was filed by lawyers for connecticut, new york city, the national league of cities and the american civil liberties union
the fcc committed procedural and substantive errors that will ... pre-empt state and local governments of traditional cable rate regulation powers and will expose cable subscribers to monopoly pricing,'' the appeal contended
lawyers for the commission and the cable operators association urged the justices to reject the appeal
the case is connecticut vs. fcc, 87-671
the supreme court today agreed to examine the power of labor unions to fire elected officials for disagreeing with union policies
the court said it will consider killing a lawsuit by a los angeles area union business representative who said he was fired illegally by the sheet metal workers' international association
edward lynn was elected to his position with local 75 of the sheet metal workers union in 1981
he and other members of the local became increasingly critical of how the union was spending its money, and organized a dissident group that successfully defeated proposals to raise the local's dues
the international association in 1982 placed local 75 in trusteeship and under the leadership of a regional official, richard hawkins
hawkins proposed a new dues increase that again was defeated, with lynn speaking out against the hike
hawkins then filed charges against lynn, and the international union removed lynn from office. he also was fined $2,500
lynn sued in federal court in 1983, accusing union leaders of firing him illegally and violating his free-speech rights
a federal judge threw out the suit but the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals reinstated it
the appeals court said that because lynn was elected to his position as business representative he could not be fired for taking a stand against policies proposed by other union leaders
lynn's removal was precipitated by his outspoken opposition to the proposed dues increase, a position which also reflected the view of the majority of the union membership,'' the appeals court said
its decision drew a distinction between an elected union official and one who is appointed
the supreme court in 1982 ruled that appointed union administrators are not protected from dismissal when there is a change in union leadership. the high court ruled then that business agents of a teamsters union local could be fired for supporting a rival of the man elected president of the local
the 9th circuit court said lynn's firing was a different matter because he was elected, and that he cannot be dismissed by the parent union to suppress dissent
just as the international may not impose a trusteeship for illegitimate purposes such as suppressing dissent, so it may not use the powers inherent in a legitimate trusteeship for similarly illegitimate purposes,'' the appeals court said
the case is sheet metal workers vs. lynn, 86-1940. 5th graf, `aurelio barria ...' edits to tighten.</note>
shops and stores remained shuttered today and thousands of soldiers toting m-16 rifles and tear gas canisters patrolled the capital at the outset of a general strike aimed at ousting strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
buses and taxis were operating normally, but many were empty or were carrying fewer passengers than normal. traffic was light
many government offices appeared to be operating with limited personnel, despite a government warning that public employees would be suspended if they joined in the work stoppage
in the city's central business district, where six previous strikes in the past nine months have had little effect, most stores didn't open
businessmen there have never before joined larger, wealthier merchants and industrialists in a strike
we're sending noriega a message,'' said the owner of one small shoe store, who asked not to be identified. ``we hope he's listening.''
helmeted soldiers in battle garb patrolled nearby. no violence was reported early in the day
the government said the troops were deployed to assure transit of buses and taxis and to provide security for businesses and store owners that wanted to open despite the strike call by the national civic crusade
many of the transportation companies are owned by the panamanian defense forces and those that aren't require government licenses to operate
aurelio barria, head of the opposition national civic crusade, said sunday the government may try to use an emergency decree to forcibly open industries and businesses that close during the strike
the indefinite work stoppage was called after noriega, commandr of the defense forces and the force behind the civilian government, rejected a u.s. plan for his removal as ``unacceptable, illogical and anti-panamanian.''
noriega, who has been indicted in the united states on drug trafficking charges, reportedly told william walker, a u.s. deputy assistant secretary of state, he wanted to remain in panama and help from a transitional government
walker and michael kozak, a state department legal officer, were said to have offered noriega freedom from u.s. extradition if he sought asylum in a third country. they met with the general and his high command on friday
secretary of state george p. shultz, appearing sunday on nbc's ``meet the press,'' said noriega ``can't expect to have any say in the transition.''
the panamanian government has responded to recent unrest with a state of emergency allowing it to suspend civil rights and take over private businesses
the next few days are the determinant time,'' said barria. he predicted the strike ``will be very, very successful.'' the civic crusade is an umbrella coalition of groups seeking noriega's downfall
barria also said sunday he heard meetings had been held within panama's defense forces to discuss what to do about noriega, and barria said he expected some action by the military this week
but maj. augusto villalaz, who had been one of noriega's personal pilots before defecting last week, said noriega had loyalists and cuban arms to keep him in power
villalaz told abc's ``this week with david brinkley'' on sunday that he had flown three shipments of arms to panama from cuba and that noriega planned to import 500,000 pounds of weapons
on sunday, many panamanians flocked to supermarkets to stock up on food, flashlights and other essentials to last through the coming strike
barria confirmed sunday he had met with the papal nuncio, msgr. jose laboa, but denied persistent reports that the church official was mediating a solution between noriega and the opposition
barria previously said noriega approached opposition leaders with an idea for a ``panamanian solution'' to the crisis that would allow the general a future role in the military. but the crusade rejected the idea, barria said
we don't have anything to negotiate with him except his departure,'' barria said, ``the day and the flight number.''
in panama city's pacific port area of balboa, dock workers striking because they have not been paid their full salaries vowed to keep the docks shut down today. the union has run out of emergency food bags and its 800 members have not received wages for two weeks
panama's already ailing economy was sent into a tailspin last month after noriega's indictment and the effort of then-president eric arturo delvalle to fire the general, who heads panama's 15,000-member defense forces. noriega allies in parliament on feb. 26 ousted delvalle, who has since been in hiding
the reagan administration retaliated by backing the freezing of panamanian government bank deposits in the united states, creating a critical cash shortage in panama, which uses the dollar as its currency
the supreme court today sought the reagan administration's views of an appeal by hawaii officials seeking to roll back an annual $10.5 million increase in intrastate telephone rates
the court asked justice department lawyers to comment on a lower court ruling that the state lacks authority to block the higher rates
the high court is not expected to decide whether to grant full review to the case until hearing from the government lawyers, which could take months
the hawaii public utilities commission in 1984 granted a $20 million rate increase to hawaii telephone co., $10.5 million less than the company requested
the company then filed a federal lawsuit, charging that the reduction violated an order of the federal communications commission
generally, the fcc regulates interstate phone rates while state public utility officials regulate intrastate rates
but the commission in 1981 adopted a plan to reduce interstate rates for phone users in hawaii, bringing the charges into line with interstate rates for people in the 48 contiguous states
the lower rates were to be phased in over four years in an effort to avoid a dramatic impact on rates for in-state calls
the hawaii telephone co. said the commission plan bars state officials from imposing the $10.5 million reduction
a federal judge agreed with the company, and that ruling was upheld last september by the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals
the appeals court said the commission properly pre-empted the state's authority in this case
no one disputes the authority of a state ... to establish a reasonable rate of return for utilities within its jurisdiction,'' the appeals court said. ``but ... (hawaii's) adjustment here was a fairly transparent and improper attempt to circumvent the fcc mandate.''
the appeals court said the commission has priority in apportioning the cost of equipment and other expenses between in-state and out-of-state service
the case is puc vs. hawaiian telephone co., 87-1152
the supreme court today agreed to decide whether an airline may be forced to reinstate workers when their strike ends, making necessary the layoffs of trainees and employees who crossed the picket lines
the court said it will study an appeal by trans world airlines in a dispute stemming from a 1986 strike by flight attendants
twa and the independent federation of flight attendants had a three-year contract that expired july 31, 1984. when negotiations failed, the union called a strike on march 7, 1986
twa hired more than 1,220 new flight attendants after the strike began. in addition, about 1,280 twa flight attendants crossed picket lines either at the outset of the walkout or as the strike continued for more than two months
twa also placed new flight attendants in training, including 463 who had not completed training when the strike ended may 17, 1986
the union then filed a federal lawsuit charging twa with unlawfully refusing to reinstate more than 2,000 workers who had gone out on strike
the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last may that some striking flight attendants were entitled to their old jobs at the expense of all trainees and some flight attendants who had crossed the picket lines
the appeals court said the strikers should be reinstated if they had more seniority than those, called cross-overs, who had not honored the picket lines
but the appeals court also said the 1,220 flight attendants hired during the strike could not be dislodged by any of those who stayed out during the strike
with regard to the cross-overs, the 8th circuit court said they may not be given preferential treatment over striking workers with more seniority ``because such action impermissibly discriminates among union members based on the degree of their union activity.''
an employer may not divide the workforce into those who engaged in strike activity and those who did not,'' the appeals court said
it said the 463 trainees cannot be considered permanent replacements in the same category as the 1,220 newly hired flight attendants. therefore, the trainees ``were subject to displacement by returning strikers,'' the appeals court said
the distinctions were made under the railway labor act, which governs airlines as well as railroads
twa said it is ``simply incomprehensible'' to force employees choosing not to strike to give up their jobs in favor of ``unsuccessful strikers.''
by a 4-4 vote on march 2, the supreme court ruled in another case growing out of the 1986 twa strike that an airline may be forced to continue collecting union dues from workers after its contract with employees has expired
twa sought to discontinue the dues check-off after the strike ended. but the justices' split vote automatically upheld an 8th circuit court ruling that the airline may not cancel the check-off provision unless it is agreed to in negotiations with the workers
the case is twa vs. independent federation of flight attendants, 87-548. hawkins</head>
the supreme court today turned away a legal dispute sparked by controversy over the health of former sen. paula hawkins, r-fla
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the public has no right of access to pretrial statements and other materials generated by civil lawsuits
lawyers for the miami herald had argued that denying public access to all unfiled pretrial materials in civil cases violates the constitution's first amendment
in a related case, the justices last november let stand a florida supreme court ruling that the public has no right to hear or see pretrial statements, called depositions, given during criminal prosecutions
in the case acted on today, the florida court extended its ruling on pretrial materials in criminal cases to depositions and other pretrial materials in civil cases
hawkins, who lost her senate seat in the 1986 election to democrat bob graham, a former florida governor, injured her back in a 1982 accident at television station wesh in orlando
she sued in early 1986, charging that the accident _ a studio set wall fell on hawkins while she was taping a talk show _ was caused by the station's negligence
the lawsuit alleged that hawkins' injury became a physical handicap that impaired her ability to work
while pretrial proceedings were underway, hawkins continued her work in the senate and actively sought re-election. but as a result of the lawsuit's allegations, her health became a major issue in the campaign coverage
in october 1986, about two weeks before the election, the orlando sentinel sought to intervene in the lawsuit between hawkins and wesh and compel access to pretrial documents, including hospital and medical records
two other newspapers, the miami herald and the florida times union in jacksonville, filed similar requests
hawkins settled her lawsuit out of court in june 1987 but the herald continued its effort to obtain the pretrial documents
under florida law, those documents are not routinely placed in public court files
the supreme court last july 2 ruled against granting access. it relied on its earlier decision denying public access to pretrial depositions in criminal cases
the herald then filed the appeal acted on today
the case is miami herald publishing co. vs. gridley, 87-1193
the supreme court today sent back to a lower court a dispute over a racial-quota integration plan for a public elementary school in chicago
the justices told the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals to study whether a challenge by a group of whites, cubans and american indians to quotas at the walt disney ``magnet'' elementary school has become moot
the court did not explain why it believes the case may have lost its legal relevancy but the chicago board of education contended that the children on whose behalf the original lawsuit was filed now are too old to attend the school
the disney school was opened in 1968 on chicago's north side to promote integration. students were selected by lottery to reflect the racial, ethnic and economic composition of the area
the school is considered a ``magnet'' because it offers special educational opportunities designed to attract a cross-section of the community
many cities in the nation have adopted the magnet concept as a key element in integrating public schools
chicago officials incorporated racial quotas at the disney school as part of the school system's overall integration plan adopted in response to a complaint by the federal government charging segregation. the city signed an agreement in 1980 with federal officials, promising to implement a citywide integration plan
the quotas at disney were challenged in 1981 by parents of cuban, american indian and white children. those children were told they would be admitted to the school but two months later were informed they could not attend because the quotas had been adjusted in the interim
the quotas require that white students comprise 15 to 35 percent of the school's population, and that minorities comprise from 65 to 85 percent
the disney plan was upheld by a three-judge panel of the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals. the panel said that chicago's citywide desegregation plan already had been upheld in previous federal court rulings, precluding any attack on the quotas at the disney school
the students excluded from disney ``are indeed necessarily attacking the desegregation plan as a whole by challenging its effect upon them,'' the panel said
the students' parents then asked for a review of their appeal by all 10 members of the 7th circuit court. by a vote of 6-4, the judges refused to hear the case
judge frank h. easterbrook of the 7th circuit, in voting to hear the case, said, ``chicago has not been found to have engaged in racial discrimination in operating its schools. some such finding ... is essential before children may be shuffled from one school to another on account of their race.''
he added that the children who were barred from attending the disney school were being deprived of educational opportunities they may be unable to receive at any other public school in the city
the case is samayoa vs. chicago board of education, 86-1503. lawyer</note>
the iran-contra independent counsel has evidence that richard secord and albert hakim skimmed nearly $1 million from bank accounts containing money from the arms sales to iran, a newspaper reported today
the money was used by secord and hakim to invest in arms, food and real estate businesses for their personal gain, the chicago tribune reported, citing unidentified sources close to the investigation by independent counsel lawrence walsh
according to the report, secord and hakim transferred the money from swiss bank accounts in three installments from august to november 1986. the two reportedly used $760,000 from the accounts to buy a one-third interest in forway industries, a military supply company in new jersey, and $50,000 on a plan to work with forway to market a laser sight for night weapons firing, the newspaper said
the tribune said walsh obtained some of his information through the help of willard zucker, an attorney and financial adviser who has been granted immunity from prosecution. the geneva-based zucker managed the swiss bank accounts and allegedly set up shell corporations to mask the diversion of $18 million of the money paid by the iranians, the tribune said
a federal grand jury indicted secord and hakim, along with lt. col. oliver north and former national security adviser john poindexter last week on charges of conspiring to siphon the profits from the iranian arms sales and use the money for the benefit of the contras fighting the leftist nicaraguan government. it also accused secord, hakim and north of using some of the money for personal gain
the four have said they would plead innocent at an arraignment thursday
the indictment also charged secord and hakim of conspiring to pay illegal gratuities to north
zucker and a spokesman for walsh declined to comment about the matter, the tribune said
secord was in meetings today and unavailable for immediate comment, said joan corbin, a secretary at washington, d.c.-based american trade consultants
secord's attorney, tom green, was traveling and also unavailable to comment immediately, said julie linwood, a secretary at green's washington, d.c. law firm. governor's suit</head>
the supreme court today refused to revive some allegations previously raised in former massachusetts gov. edward j. king's $3.6 million libel lawsuit against the boston globe
the justices, without comment, let stand rulings that three editorial cartoons, one editorial and two columns king sued over, did not libel him
the high court earlier this month cleared the way for a jury trial on king's claim he was libeled by a nov. 8, 1981, column written by david farrell, who since has left the newspaper
state courts threw out most of the ex-governor's claims in pretrial proceedings, ruling that the sued-over comments and cartoons amounted to constitutionally protected expressions of opinion
king, who served as the state's governor from 1979 through 1983, contended that he was libeled in various cartoons and articles, most of which were published in 1981
cartoons are seldom designed to disclose facts but rather are ordinarily understood by reasonable viewers to be rhetorical, exaggerated means of expressing opinions,'' the massachusetts supreme judicial court said in ruling on king's suit last aug. 17
the state court said the other articles ordered dropped from the suit also fell ``within the ambit of protected opinion.''
the case is king vs. globe newspaper co., 87-1259
the supreme court today refused to reinstate a $150,000 libel award won, and then lost, by a joplin, mo., policeman against his local newspaper
the justices, without comment, let stand rulings that officer don r. speer failed to prove the joplin globe acted with ``actual malice'' when it accused him in an editorial of using excessive force
the controversy stems from an april 23, 1983, demonstration outside a downtown joplin bar
about two dozen protesters picketed the bar that evening because most of its patrons were homosexual
speer was sent to arrest the demonstrators because they had not obtained a parade permit
while making the arrests, speer got into an altercation with max mccoy, a globe reporter who was taking photographs of the demonstration and arrests
mccoy, who sustained injuries and whose camera was broken, told globe editors that speer and other police officers used excessive force
an april 24 article reflected both mccoy's and the police's versions of the incident
an editorial published two days later condemned speer's conduct, stating that while mccoy was ``cuffed and defenseless, the officers continued to strike him, kick him.''
speer sued the paper's publisher, ottaway newspapers inc., in federal court, contending that the editorial had libeled him
a jury awarded him $100,000 in compensatory damages and $50,000 in punitive damages but the trial judge threw out the award. the judge ruled that speer, treated as a public figure for purposes of the lawsuit, had not proved actual malice
public figures who sue for libel must prove that the statement was false and published with knowledge or reckless disregard of its falsity. private individuals who sue for libel have an easier task: they must prove the statement was false and published through negligence
in upholding the trial judge's ruling, the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled last sept. 9 that mccoy had nothing to do with publication of the editorial at issue
a finding of institutional actual malice by the globe may not be based only on mccoy's state of mind,'' the appeals court said
it added that globe editors knew mccoy ``as a trusted employee and believed him to be reliable, honest and good with details.''
in the appeal acted on today, lawyers for speer argued that the appeals court ruling will spur newspapers to ``compartmentalize their fact-finding and writing functions since liability can only be imposed by persons occupying the latter status.''
the appeal added, ``rewarding a newspaper for the calculated deceit of an employee it retains to gather information ... constitutes an unnecessary denigration of the individual's right to the protection of his own good name.''
the case is speer vs. ottaway newspapers, 87-942
civil rights leader joseph lowery has been denied a visa for a trip to south africa, his wife said today
evelyn lowery said the south african embassy in washington gave her husband, who is president of the southern christian leadership conference, no reason for the denial
we ... have our suspicions. you know the situation in south africa, the persecution of black leaders there, and they certainly know we're in sympathy (with south africa's blacks),'' mrs. lowery said
lowery, who was in massachusetts today to lecture at holy cross college, had planned to deliver a sermon at memorial services for martin luther king jr. scheduled for friday through sunday in south africa. he was informed of the visa denial over the weekend, mrs. lowery said
kevin brennan, a spokesman for the south african embassy in washington, confirmed that lowery's visa application had been denied, but would not give a reason
a jury today began its fifth day of deliberation in the murder trial of a young man accused of strangling a teen-age woman in central park, where they walked from a popular watering hole
the jury returned to the courtroom this morning and listened to a reading of testimony from dr. robert c. shaler regarding body fluid stains on the victim's jacket
during deliberations sunday, jurors asked justice howard e. bell to restate the charges against robert chambers and asked if they could take notes
bell allowed that, but admonished the jurors to also listen carefully. it is highly unusual for new york juries to be allowed to take notes
chambers, 21, is charged with second-degree murder in the aug. 26, 1986, strangulation of jennifer levin, an 18-year-old woman he had met in an upper east side bar frequented by affluent young people
the jury could convict chambers of the lesser crimes of first-or second-degree manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide
the prosecution has charged that chambers used miss levin's blouse to strangle her, while his lawyers maintain he accidentally killed her when she hurt him by squeezing his genitals during rough sex. rightists trouncing christian democrats. picks up 5th graf, ``i want ...' edits to tighten.</note>
a resurgent right battered the governing christian democrats in municipal and legislative elections, according to early returns today
the result of sunday's balloting, in which hundreds of thousands participated despite threats of guerrilla violence, sets the stage for a rough final year in office for president jose napoleon duarte, a christian democrat
the leftist guerrillas had called for a boycott of the voting, and the sizeable turnout was hailed by politicians as a triumph for democracy and a demonstration of civic spirit
the rightist republican nationalist alliance, or arena, won the mayor's post in san salvador from the christian democrats, who had held the position for the past 24 years. they also appeared assured of a majority in the 60-seat national assembly, according to projections made by local television stations
the christian democrats currently hold 33 seats. arena has 13
the ``areneros'' apparently benefited from a wave of popular discontent with the christian democrats
duarte was elected in 1984 on a platform of ending the war and improving the economic situation. but four years later, the war that has taken 65,000 lives grinds on, an estimated 40 percent of salvadorans are unemployed and inflation is running at an annual rate of about 40 percent
arena's campaign slogan was ``change for the better,'' which apparently struck a chord in the electorate
prior to the election, the chistian democrats themselves had conceded they would be set back by the vote, citing the natural erosion of support experienced by a party governing in troubled times
arena national chairman alfredo cristiani told a news conference sunday night his party, if it gained control of the legislature, would work with the christian democrats to resolve the country's pressing problems
we will not present a systematic and capricious opposition. we must look for unity regarding certain crucial points,'' he said
in the san salvador mayor's race, armando calderon sol, the candidate of the rightist alliance, beat alejandro duarte, the christian democratic candidate and son of president jose napoleon duarte
i want to publicly recognize that mr. calderon sol has won,'' duarte said at a news conference sunday night. he congratulated the salvadoran people for voting despite threats of violence from leftist guerrillas
this day was a glorious gesture of the salvadoran people,'' he said. ``we have defeated the terror and violence of the left.''
the third party presenting candidates nationwide was the national conciliation party, another rightist group. leftist parties declined to present candidates, saying the war made fair elections impossible
state-run channel 10 television, citing unofficial preliminary counts, estimated 66 percent of the 1.6 million registered voters had cast ballots. it said that, according to its projections, arena would win an outright majority in the assembly
mario samayoa, president of the electoral council, also hailed the electorate for turning out to vote
he also said there had been no allegations of fraud by any party from any polling station in the country
in a bid to disrupt the election, leftist guerrillas blew up electrical lines, cutting energy to much of the country saturday night. however, little violence was reported during the election sunday, apart from rural skirmishes in the central part of the country. no casualties were immediately reported
power was returning gradually to some regions by today
today was the first day since friday that salvadorans could expect normal transport. the marxist-led farabundo marti national liberation front, an alliance of five guerrilla armies, lifted its 3-day-old road travel ban as of midnight sunday
the rebels had termed the election ``a farce'' and called for a boycott
to vote is a duty, the way we demonstrate we are salvadoran citizens,'' said pablo castellano, a 38-year-old peasant farmer in nejapa, 10 miles north of san salvador. he had walked 10 miles in the blazing sun to cast his ballot
the guerrillas had warned polling places would be considered ``military objectives'' because of the wide deployment of soldiers to provide election security
they had stepped up urban violence in the 10 days prior to the voting. three car bombs exploded in san salvador, wounding three people
voters were electing all 60 members of the national assembly, the unicameral legislature, and mayors and town councils for 262 municipalities nationwide
the guerrillas, who have been fighting since 1979, demand a share of power in exchange for laying down their arms. the government rejects the demand
sam w. reynolds, a businessman who was appointed a u.s. senator and served for seven months, has died. he was 97
he died at home sunday of pneumonia, a family spokesman said
reynolds owned and operated reynolds-updike coal co. for 76 years until retiring in 1984. he also was a partner in updike lumber and coal
gov. bob crosby appointed reynolds, a republican, to the senate in 1954 after the death of sen. hugh butler. reynolds did not seek election to a full term
reynolds was a city councilman in 1956 and 1957 and had been city civil defense coordinator. he won the nebraska amateur golf championship seven times
reynolds' wife, louise, died in 1981. survivors include a brother, three daughters, six grandchildren and three great-grandchildren
a funeral was scheduled wednesday
the supreme court, with four of nine justices on the sidelines, today refused to kill a 13-year-old lawsuit stemming from an armed confrontation between indians and federal agents at wounded knee, s.d
the remaining five justices, citing the lack of a quorum, automatically upheld a federal appeals court ruling that clears the way for a trial on allegations that the government's use of army troops in the 1973 incident violated constitutional rights
the suit names former presidential aide alexander haig, ex-attorney general richard kleindienst and 10 other federal or military officials as defendants
on feb. 27, 1973, an armed group of indians with grievances about the federal government's handling of indian affairs occupied the village of wounded knee on the pine ridge reservation
the fbi, u.s. marshals service and bureau of indian affairs police sealed off the village by setting up roadblocks. before the 71-day standoff ended, two indians were killed and a deputy marshal was wounded
fourteen people, most of them residents of the pine ridge reservation, sued in 1975. their suit contends they were confined unconstitutionally because army troops helped maintain the roadblocks and an armed perimeter around wounded knee
the suit relies heavily on a federal law, the posse comitatus act, that bans use of the army or air force as a civil police force
because the use of army troops violated federal law, it also violated the individuals' constitutional protection against unreasonable government seizures, the lawsuit says
people who allege they were subjected to a constitutionally impermissible search or seizure may sue the offending officials for damages
u.s. district judge donald j. porter in south dakota threw out the suit but the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals reinstated it in 1986
the supreme court last year agreed to review the 8th circuit court's ruling, and today's brief, unsigned opinion upheld that ruling
the 8th circuit court said the involvement of army troops was ``affirmatively forbidden by a criminal law of long standing, itself expressive of an authentically american tradition of even longer standing.''
while acknowledging that a seizure that violates federal law does not necesarily violate the constitution, the appeals court said violations of the posse comitatus act represent ``a special case.''
chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices sandra day o'connor, antonin scalia and anthony m. kennedy disqualified themselves from the case without explanation
the case is haig vs. bissonette, 86-987
the plo defied an eviction deadline today to vacate its u.n. observer mission under a u.s. anti-terrorist law as the general assembly met in emergency session to consider ways to keep the mission open. a court battle appeared likely
the plo observer, labib zehdi terzi, made no move to shut the 13-year-old mission in a townhouse near park avenue and said he was awaiting u.s. legal action against the palestine liberation organization
once we see what they do, then we will respond,'' he said in the u.n. delegates lounge. he said last week that u.s. authorities would have to drag him away
but no confrontation or physical move to shut the mission was expected. the u.s. government said that if the plo does not leave the united states voluntarily, then it would initiate legal action this week to make it move. but u.s. officials say they will allow litigation to run its course
the united states has declared the plo a terrorist organization, but the united nations recognizes it as the only legitimate representative of the palestinian people. it was invited to new york by the united nations
the plo's counsel, former attorney general ramsey clark, said that if the united states files suit against the plo, he will seek to dismiss the complaint
envoy terzi said it is up to the united nations to go to court on behalf of the plo
in the emergency session which started friday, all speakers denounced the u.s. move to close the plo mission and 50 more speakers were scheduled this week
today and tuesday the assembly is scheduled to consider calls by some delegates to take legal action on behalf of the plo and to house the mission on u.n. international territory _ off limits to u.s. police
the plo participates in all debates on the middle east but has no voting rights
some delegates also want to move the next 159-member general assembly to geneva in september or to shift the special session on disarmament in may and june to geneva, but such moves are unlikely
this week the assembly is expected to adopt a resolution calling on secretary-general javier perez de cuellar to take all necessary action, including legal steps, in defense of the headquarters agreement
the justice department was expected to initiate legal action in manhattan federal court probably by wednesday to close the mission, department spokesman patrick korten said in washington on sunday
we're ready to go ahead and file the papers if they don't close the mission voluntarily,'' he said
clark has said the closure order is illegal because it violates the 1947 u.s.-u.n. headquarters treaty under which the united states allows u.n. missions to operate
clark said the anti-terrorism law of 1987 and legal efforts to oust the plo are unconstitutional because they conflict with international law. he said the u.n. headquarters agreement takes precedence over u.s. domestic law
the anti-terrorism law was attached to a state department spending bill and requires closing the plo mission by today
the state department and united nations opposed the legislation on grounds it violates u.s.-u.n. treaty obligations. secretary of state george p. shultz called it ``a very bad piece of legislation'' which unnecessarily glorifies the plo
the supreme court today agreed to decide whether public officials may be sued when their alleged gross negligence permits a child to be abused by a parent
the justices said they will hear an appeal on behalf of a wisconsin boy who at age 4 was seriously and permanently brain damaged from beatings by his father
social workers were accused of violating the child's constitutional rights by failing to come to his rescue after they had repeated evidence he was being beaten
the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals last year threw out the suit against the winnebago county, wis., department of social services and two of its employees
the boy, joshua deshaney, first came to the attention of the welfare agency when he was brought to a hospital in 1983 with cuts and bruises. the girlfriend of joshua's father said the boy was injured in an attack by another child
officials suspected he was being abused by adults. a social worker, ann kemmeter, was assigned to the case
joshua was returned to the custody of his father, randy deshaney, with a recommendation that deshaney's girlfriend move out of the house because deshaney had hinted she might be abusing the boy
deshaney's former wife and joshua's mother, melody deshaney, was living in cheyenne, wyo., where the couple had been divorced
a month after the first hospital visit, joshua again was treated for suspicious injuries
ms. kemmeter visited the deshaney home on several occaisons and noticed bumps on joshua's head. the boy also was treated again at a hosptal for various bruises and injuries. also, deshaney's girlfriend still was living at the home
ms. kemmeter visited the deshaney home on march 7, 1984, and was told that several days earlier joshua had fainted in the bathroom for no apparent reason. but according to court records she did not ask to see the boy
the following day joshua was treated at a hospital for head injuries that destroyed half his brain, leaving him profoundly retarded and institutionalized for the rest of his life
the boy's father was convicted of child abuse and sentenced to two to four years in prison
the county social services department and its employees were sued by joshua's mother on grounds the boy was deprived of liberty without due process
the 7th circuit court said in dismissing the suit, ``if the defendants, though blameworthy, did not cause joshua's injuries, they cannot be said to have deprived him of his liberty. deprivation implies causation.''
the appeals court continued, ``it is unlikely that ann kemmeter's well-intentioned but ineffectual intervention did joshua any good at all. but it is most unlikely that it did him any harm. she merely failed to protect him from his bestial father.''
the appeals court added that ms. kemmeter ``failed to act on mounting and eventually overwhelming evidence that joshua was in great peril from his father.''
but the appeals court said it would place welfare agencies in an unfair predicament to require them to take custody of children who are suspected victims of abuse
to place every state welfare department on the razor's edge, where if it terminates parental rights it is exposed to ... suit by the parent ... and if it fails to terminate those rights it is exposed to ... suit by the child, is unlikely to improve the welfare of american families and is not grounded in constitutional text or principle,'' the appeals court said
in her appeal to the supreme court, mrs. deshaney said the 7th circuit court ruling is in conflict with decisions by other appeals courts
in other action, the court:
_ left unresolved whether public school students enjoy any constitutional protection against paddling or other corporal punishment by teachers and administrators
the justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling in a new mexico case that ``at some degree of excessiveness or cruelty'' such punishment violates constitutional rights. but another appeals court has rejected that view
_ refused to let the dalkon shield's maker set up a $15 million emergency fund to help women who say the contraceptive device left them infertile
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that blocks creation of the fund pending the outcome of bankruptcy proceedings for a.h. robins, which manufactures the device
in a related case, the court refused to review a ruling that at least temporarily barred some dalkon shield users from suing aetna casualty &amp; surety co., which insures a.h. robins for liability claims
_ rejected a constitutional attack on a federal law requiring broadcasters to give equal time to opposing candidates for public office
the justices, without comment, turned down the appeal of a sacramento, calif., television reporter kept off the air while he ran for a non-salaried town council seat
_ agreed to consider killing a key provision of a law designed to promote competitive bidding on government contracts, setting the stage for a new ruling on the boundaries between congressional and presidential powers
the court said it will hear reagan administration arguments challenging the comptroller general's role in administering the 1984 competition in contracting act
_ agreed to decide whether states may impose sales taxes on most books, newspapers and magazines while exempting religious publications
the justices said they will review a texas court ruling that said such a tax neither violates equal-protection rights nor breeches the constitutionally required separation of church and state
_ refused to let states and local governments regulate the prices most of the nation's cable television operators charge for basic service
the court, without comment, rejected arguments that the deregulation effected in 1986 by congress and the federal communications commission left subscribers vulnerable to illegal monopoly pricing
_ agreed to examine the power of labor unions to fire elected officials for disagreeing with union policies
the court said it will consider killing a lawsuit by a los angeles area union business representative who said he was fired illegally by the sheet metal workers' international association
_ agreed to consider shielding states from having to help pay for cleaning up hazardous waste sites when the federal government sues businesses under the so-called superfund law
the court said it will hear arguments by pennsylvania officials that exposing states to such liability could saddle them with $100 billion in clean-up costs
the child-abuse case is deshaney vs. winnebago county, 87-154
lt. col. oliver north's request to retire from the marine corps later this spring has received final approval from the navy, pentagon officials said today
north, the fired national security aide who was indicted last week in connection with the iran-contra affair, also has received permission to start using up his accumulated leave and will no longer have to report for work at marine corps headquarters
lt. col. north began his terminal leave today,'' said lt. col. john shotwell, a marine corps spokesman. ``he had sufficient leave on the books to cover the period from now until his retirement on may 1.''
north announced friday that he had decided to retire from active duty, saying the step was necessary because he would likely have to subpoena ``the highest ranking officials in our government'' to defend himself against the iran-contra charges
that strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my continued service as a marine officer,'' north said at the time
accordingly, with great sadness, i have tendered my request to retire from the marine corps.''
north becomes eligible to retire with a military pension on may 1 _ the point at which he will have spent 20 years on active duty. he automatically had the right to request retirement on that date, but needed a waiver of a requirement that he provide at least four months' advance notice of his plans
that waiver was approved by chase untermeyer, the assistant navy secretary for manpower and reserve affairs
north was reassigned to marine corps headquarters on the planning staff in november 1986 after president reagan fired him as an aide to the national security council
north, former national security advisor rear adm. john poindexter and two others were indicted by a federal grand jury march 16 on charges they conspired to divert iranian arms sales profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
the 23-count indictment, which also named retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and his business partner, albert hakim, said the defendants organized, directed and concealed ``a program to continue funding of and logistical and other support for military and paramilitary operations in nicaragua by the contras'' at a time u.s. law barred such action
the supreme court today refused to let the dalkon shield's maker set up a $15 million emergency fund to help women who say the contraceptive device left them infertile
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that blocks creation of the fund pending the outcome ofbankruptcy proceedings for a.h. robins, which manufactures the device
in a related case, the court refused to review a ruling that at least temporarily barred some dalkon shield users from suing aetna casualty &amp; surety co., which insures a.h. robins for liability claims
robins, facing massive damage claims from hundreds of thousands of women, filed for bankruptcy in 1985 to protect the company's assets. its intrauterine device allegedly caused pelvic inflammation, spontaneous abortions, infertility and, in a few cases, death
robins filed for bankruptcy under what is known as chapter 11, a law that allows debtors to protect assets while repaying debts under a court-devised plan
the company stopped marketing the dalkon shield in 1974 but did not actually recall the product until 1984
robins reported on march 7 that it had a fourth-quarter loss of $1.69 billion in 1987 due to funds set aside for dalkon shield injury claims. the company reported an $81.8 million profit for the year
the case acted on today involving the $15 million fund centered on an attempt by robins to trim some of its losses and to provide immediate money for women who could undergo corrective surgery or become pregnant through in vitro fertilization
that procedure involves fertilizing the woman's egg outside her womb
robins said the surgery, costing approximately $15,000 per woman, or the in vitro procedure would give women approaching the end of their safe child-bearing years a chance to have children
`many claimants who used the dalkon shield when it was introduced in the early 1970s are approaching the biological deadline,'' the company said. it added that the emergency fund serves humanitarian purposes and makes good business sense because it could reduce claims against robins by women whose fertility is restored
lawyers representing women suing the company also supported the idea. the fund was approved last may 21 by u.s. district judge robert r. merhige jr. in richmond, va., who is presiding over nationwide claims against robins
merhige separately has ordered robins to create a $2.48 billion trust fund to pay some 200,000 claims against the company. robins had paid $500 million in damages before filing for bankruptcy
in a related development, american home products corp. is proposing to take over robins for $3 billion
the emergency $15 million fund that is the subject of today's supreme court action was opposed by owners of robins stock. on nov. 3, the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled in the stockholders' favor
the appeals court said the federal bankruptcy code prohibits creation of the emergency fund because it would give preferential treatment to some with claims against robins. the money cannot be spent while reorganization of the company is pending in bankruptcy proceedings, the appeals court said
in the case involving aetna, federal lawsuits were filed in kansas and new hampshire by thousands of women seeking damages from the insurance company
they said aetna was at fault because robins delegated to it responsibility for monitoring the performance of the dalkon shield and deciding whether it should be recalled. the women also accused aetna of covering up evidence that the devices were defective
the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals in september blocked the lawsuits, at least until the bankruptcy proceedings are concluded
the appeals court said, ``inevitably, aetna must involve robins in this litigation. aetna's primary defense logically will be that robins _ not aetna _ is responsible for the injuries suffered.''
the appeals court continued, ``robins will inexorably be drawn into this litigation ... (and) it will detract from the (bankruptcy) process.''
the cases are mabey vs. official committee of equity security holders, 87-1267, and oberg vs. aetna, 87-1208. pvs, ``from there xxxx</note>
