new york (ap) _ four people were arrested today in the beating death of a man who was chased and attacked by an angry mob after he snatched $20 from a woman in a bakery, police said
residents of nearby buildings watching the chase from their windows yelled encouragement as the man was pummeled sunday, reflecting their growing hostility to the street crime and crack dealers in the neighborhood, police said
the crowd of more than a dozen people used sticks and their bare hands to beat the man, identified by police as raymondo carraballo, 41, of manhattan. one man grabbed a garbage can and banged it down on the man's chest as he lay on the sidewalk and then others used the can to hit him again and again, said sgt. ed burns, a police spokesman
police have ruled the death a homicide. sgt. john clifford, a police spokesman, refused to provide the names of the four suspects or any other information
two housing authority police officers rescued carraballo and took him to housing authority headquarters, burns said
from there an ambulance took carraballo to mount sinai hospital, where he lost consciousness and died sunday evening, burns said. an autopsy was scheduled
the beating took place in front of the jefferson houses, a public housing project in the east harlem section around the corner from the capri bakery, where the suspect grabbed $20 from 21-year-old anna beteran, burns said
as carraballo ran out of the store, beteran and her unidentified sister-in-law chased him and yelled at a group of passers-by that he had stolen her money
the crowd chased carraballo and caught him around the corner. between 15 and 20 people joined the pursuit, but it was unclear how many actually took part in the beating, burns said
burns said carraballo had no previous criminal record, but apparently was a drug addict. ``his arms were covered with needle tracks,'' he said
police said several people had been questioned but no arrests had been made and no weapons recovered
at this point we don't have any of the weapons, but we know by the comments on the 911 calls for help that many forms of weapons were used,'' burns said
hester r. mccullough, once a heroine of the political right for her 1940s stand against entertainers associated with communist causes, is dead at 71
mrs. mccullough died at home sunday
in the late 1940s, mrs. mccullough, then living in greenwich, conn., returned a $6 subscription ticket to a performance by dancer paul draper and harmonica player larry adler, whom she accused of being members of communist-front organizations
in a letter to the greenwich community concert association that was published in a local newspaper, mrs. mccullough wrote that the entertainers, ``while fine artists, have been openly denounced in the press as being pro-communist and, as such, i do not believe should appear in any community project in greenwich.''
draper and adler sued mrs. mccullough for libel, but they decided not to pursue the case when it ended in a hung jury in 1950. by then it had become a cause celebre taken up by conservative columnists such as westbrook pegler
in later years, mrs. mccullough said she had no regrets
what i thought then, i still do,'' she told the philadelphia inquirer magazine in a 1987 interview. ``the communists themselves wanted to destroy this country and its government.''
mrs. mccullough was born in philadelphia, graduated from london university when she was 19 and became a secretary at the former pennsylvania military college, now widener university
she married john t. mccullough, a harvard graduate, who worked for time magazine
mrs. mccullough is survived by a son, bruce, of hollywood, calif. update with king announcing that policy about ira funerals will be reviewed. picks up 12th graf, `concerning the ...'</note>
the irish republican army shot dead a policeman today, two days after a mob at an ira funeral killed two british soldiers
police said the policeman was shot in the head in a jeep in the roman catholic creggan district of londonderry, and died at a hospital
the ira claimed responsibility in a clandestine message to belfast media
the officer, whose name was not made public immediately, was the 23rd person and the second policeman to die in the british province this year
police sources said today about 30 suspects were being sought in connection with the mob attack saturday on two british soldiers. the outlawed ira also claimed responsiblity for the killings of the soldiers
irish and british newspapers said a police roundup of suspects in catholic strongholds in belfast was imminent
police made no formal statement, but the sources, requesting anonymity, said suspects were identified by studying videotape of saturday's rampage, in which the two soldiers were beatend and stripped naked by the crowd and shot by ira gunmen
three suspects were arrested immediately after the killings
in the catholic markets district of west belfast, police seized 600 pounds of ``explosive material'' early today and said they arrested a woman
in london, northern ireland secretary tom king announced today an immediate review of its new policy of not policing irish republican army funerals following the killings saturday
in all, five people died during burials or funeral corteges in a four-day period last week
king said a ``massive murder investigation is under way'' in the soldiers deaths
concerning the search for the killers of the soldiers, a statement by the royal ulster constabulary, the northern ireland police force, said only that, ``inquiries are being actively pursued.''
but police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about 30 suspects were identified after officers scrutinized film of the slayings
the british army said sunday the two soldiers had ignored general orders to stay away from the irish republican army funeral procession
the men's commanding officer in belfast, lt. col. martin roberts, said in a radio interview today that the men must have driven into the area by mistake
obviously, the soldiers drove into the funeral cortege by mistake and tried to escape and in the process they were hemmed in by the black taxis,'' said roberts, who is commander of the army's communications in northern ireland
an army helicopter assigned to film the funeral in catholic west belfast hovered overhead as corporals derek wood, 24, and david howes, 23, were killed. king flew to belfast on sunday for briefings from army and police chiefs and was shown the helicopter's film of the attack
ulster unionist leader james molyneaux claimed the two soldiers were ``sacrificed'' to the new policy of not policing ira funerals while 500 members of the security forces were on standby in the city
the rev. ian paisley, leader of the democratic unionist party, also blamed the soldiers' slayings on the new policy. he called on king and the police chief, sir john hermon, to resign
but conservative lawmaker michael mates said scrapping the new policy could mean more violence. ``a return to heavy-handed policing could provoke riots, which is what the ira want so they can say to the world: they won't even let us bury our dead in peace,'' he said
the mainly catholic ira wants to drive the british from northern ireland and unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic
on wednesday, as security forces stayed away from belfast's milltown cemetery for the funerals of three ira members slain by british forces in gibraltar, a protestant gunman killed three mourners and wounded 68 with grenades and bullets
the two soldiers slain saturday interrupted the funeral of kevin brady, 20, one of the three killed in milltown cemetery
a statement from the ira, which said its members shot the soldiers after identifying them, said the mourners thought they were being attacked when the soldiers' car sped toward them
sinn fein, the ira's legal political wing, blamed the british government for the violence and praised those who beat the soldiers for their ``bravery in protecting the cortege from attack.'' grafs, picking up in 6th graf pvs, ``what does; deletes grafs 10-12 pvs, resuming ... primary.</note>
george bush picked up the endorsement of new jersey gov. thomas h. kean today, while democrat albert gore jr. got kind words but no endorsement from new york gov. mario cuomo and richard gephardt got the same from chrysler chairman lee iacocca
the meetings came one day after bush swept to his 23rd primary-season victory in puerto rico and after democrats michael dukakis and jesse jackson recorded good weekend showings in kansas, texas and puerto rico
most of the democrats were campaigning today in michigan, where caucuses saturday offer the next big delegate prize of the season, while bush flew to new jersey for a rally
in meetings today with well-known non-candidates:
_kean endorsed bush in new jersey, saying as bush stood alongside him at a rally, ``we need a president who doesn't apologize for what's wrong with america, but who brags about what's right. we need a president who doesn't have his eyes fastened on the failings of the past, but who gazes steadily at the opportunities of the future.''
_cuomo said in albany, n.y., said he'd had an ``excellent'' and ``interesting'' meeting with gore, but he told reporters he is still not ready to endorse a democratic presidential hopeful. ``the endorsements don't mean a great deal,'' cuomo said
_in michigan, iacocca said, ``dick gephardt's a good friend of mine and he knows what he's talking about on trade.'' but he made no endorsement and said he also was looking forward to meeting with other presidential candidates
gephardt led the democratic parade into michigan, talking with auto executives and steel workers as he works for the victory he must have here to rescue his campaign
what does it profit this nation to conquer grenada if we are losing the auto industries of pontiac, flint and detroit?'' the missouri congressman told michigan democrats over the weekend
wisconsin looks like the next major battleground for the republicans, after bush won his latest victory in the puerto rico primary on sunday. the vice president won with ease over sen. bob dole, who admitted that he has done little to slow down bush's drive for the gop nomination
i still have a lot of supporters out there,'' dole said in milwaukee. ``we want them to know bob dole is a fighter, that we're going to stay in this race. ... i've got a lot of hill to climb before april 5'' and the wisconsin primary where polls give bush a big lead
bush picked up the 14 delegates at stake in puerto rico, boosting his total to 788. that's nearly 70 percent of the 1,139 he needs to win at the national convention in new orleans this summer. dole, who hasn't won an event since feb. 23, has only 178. former television evangelist pat robertson had 17
in puerto rico, jackson won the non-binding preference poll with dukakis running second and simon third. but it was a fight more about local matters than presidential politics
the 51 delegates from puerto rico all ran as uncommitted, and the campaigns promised major efforts to woo them in coming weeks
dukakis won the kansas caucuses on saturday, picking up 16 delegates. but jackson rode strong urban support into a surprising second place and 14 delegates
it's the first farm and agriculture state that i've won and won decisively,'' dukakis said at a dinner in detroit on saturday night. ``i think that's a very good sign for the future. ... now we're on to michigan and here we are.''
in texas, jackson appeared to do better, splitting the delegates there in county conventions that were the next step in allocated at-large delegates for the state. that gave jackson a one-delegate edge over dukakis in the texas national delegate count _ including both the primary and caucus results _ but more complete returns could change that
in south dakota, a saturday caucus followed the results of the feb. 23 primary and gave rep. richard gephardt of missouri the no. 1 spot in state delegates
all that activity left the latest ap delegate count this way: dukakis, 526.5; jackson, 508.55; sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, 362.8; sen. paul simon of illinois, 171.5; and gephardt, 154. of those chosen, 343.65 were uncommitted. to nominate, 2,082 delegates are needed
michigan's saturday caucuses offer 138 to be divided up, and a weekend poll suggested dukakis and jackson were far ahead in that battle as well
a detroit news survey of 38 likely caucus-goers gave the massachusetts governor 33 percent and jackson 30 percent _ a virtual tie. gephardt had 14 percent in the survey conducted march 15-17, with the others trailing
dukakis and gore sounded the traditional party themes in michigan, where auto industry troubles have thrown thousands out of work
we're not going to sit on the sidelines while our neighbors are thrown out of work and america's hometowns are boarded up and left to die,'' dukakis told the party dinner in detroit on saturday
gore emphasized that ``i'm a friend of organized labor and always will be. i believe it is time to put the white house back on the side of working men and women.''
simon, who is looking to wisconsin for victory, admitted that ``i'd be fooling you if i said we expected to win in michigan'' as he campaigned through the state
more than 1 million color televisions, one of china's hottest consumer items, lie unwatched in warehouses partly because suppliers use them for barter and influence, it was reported monday
there were more than 900 cases of illegal trade involving 400,000 color tvs last year, said the china daily, quoting a report in the gongren ribao workers' daily
the nation made 6.7 million color sets last year, 62 percent more than in 1986. however, about one-sixth of them were in warehouses despite heavy consumer demand, the report said
the newspaper blamed part of the problem on poor distribution
it also decried ``unsound tendencies'' among suppliers and distributors who hoard the sets. the newspaper said color sets ``have acquired a kind of bargaining power and can be used to obtain favors.''
the director of one tv factory reportedly obtained steel only after giving sets to suppliers. some supply departments used sets as leverage to gain other best-selling products and unload unpopular ones, the newspaper said
villagers trying to rescue a donkey from a dam dived for cover when they saw what had trapped its hind leg: a wooden box containing a surface-to-air missile
soldiers called to the village near the town of filabusi in southwestern zimbabwe found eight more of the soviet-made missiles after scouring the dam, according to elephant news, a zimbabwe military magazine
the missiles were intact and had never been used,'' the magazine quoted capt. mike mandiringa, commander of the search party, as saying. ``if it were not for the donkey, they would still be in the water.''
the officer said he believed the missiles were stored in villagers' huts by guerrillas during the seven-year war that led to zimbabwe's independence from britain in 1980
the villagers apparently dumped the weapons in the dam when the war ended, he said
guerrillas fighting the white minority government of ian smith in that conflict were supplied with an unknown quantity of heat-seeking missiles
angry poultry farmers threw live chickens and eggs at a u.s. diplomatic office monday during a protest of imported american turkeys
the 3,000 farmers also took their protest to the bureau of foreign trade, where they pelted a senior government official with eggs
during the demonstration outside the american institute in taiwan, farmers shouted ``we don't want u.s. turkeys!''
one protester cried out, ``slogans are useless!'' and the farmers threw 30 live chickens and dozens of eggs into the institute compound. visa applicants, reporters and policemen outside the building also were hit by the eggs
farmers argue that chicken prices have fallen more than 50 percent in five months because the united states has made taiwan a ``dumping ground'' for turkeys
they gave a petition to officials at the institute, which handles diplomatic matters between the united states and taiwan in the absence of formal relations
the protesters then went to the bureau of foreign trade and threw eggs at vincent siew, the bureau's director general, when he spoke with the farmers but failed to promise an immediate ban on turkey imports
siew told demonstrators that allowing u.s. turkey imports was part of a plan to help reduce taiwan's huge trade surplus with the united states, which taipei said reached $16 billion last year
taiwan officials want to lower the surplus to reduce u.s. protectionist sentiment
siew spoke to the farmers in a gynmasium near the bureau office but had to leave under riot police escort as farmers yelled: ``step down, vincent siew!'' the demonstrators dispersed four hours after the protest began
siew is a member of the taiwan-u.s. trade committee, which recommended easing restrictions on u.s. turkey imports. the cabinet still must approve the decision
the american institute in taiwan said u.s. turkeys accounted for less than 1 percent of taiwan's poultry market and did not hurt local farmers. it said the price slump was caused by overproduction and inadequate distribution and marketing
demonstration leader chen tung-fang, president of taiwan's poultry association, argued that chicken farmers have suffered an average monthly loss of $21 million since u.s. turkey imports increased in november
agriculture council officials said taiwan imported 2,261 metric tons of turkeys from the united states last year, up 142 percent from a year earlier
an earlier demonstration was held wednesday, when about 5,000 fruit and poultry farmers marched through taipei streets to protest the government decision to import turkeys and more fruit from the united states
the supreme court today agreed to consider making it easier for people to use a federal anti-racketeering law to sue businesses
the court said it will hear an appeal by phone customers in minnesota who have accused northwestern bell telephone co. of trying to bribe state public utility officials
the phone subcribers sued the company under a law known as the racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act (rico)
they said the company beginning in 1980 tried illegally to win rate increases by offering gifts, employment offers, tickets to sporting and cultural events and other favors to members of the minnesota public utilities commission
the suit was thrown out by a federal judge and that ruling was upheld last september by the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals
the appeals court said the phone users failed to allege a continuing pattern of racketeering activity required to make a case under the rico act
a single fraudulent effort or scheme is insufficient'' grounds for a suit, the appeals court said. it said the phone customers' ``complaint alleges no more than a series of fraudulent acts committed in furtherance of a single scheme to influence'' the public utility commissioners
the supreme court is being asked to pick between various theories of how difficult it should be to maintain such a lawsuit
the most expansive view would permit a rico suit when there are two related acts ``in furtherance of a single episode or a scheme.''
a more restrictive view would be that a pattern of racketeering activity exists only when there are multiple separate criminal schemes or episodes
those suing northwestern bell said there also is a middle road that would permit such suits based on an analysis of various factors, including the number and variety of alleged illegal acts, the number of victims, the length of time of the activity and the number of participants in the alleged scheme
they said the 8th circuit court ruling conflicts with decision by a number of other federal appeals courts
the case is h.j. inc. vs. northwestern bell, 87-1252
sheer elegance at chanel for next winter won designer karl lagerfeld a roar of applause in his monday ready-to-wear show
the great choices in short or long skirts and pants were welcome for chanel fans, sometimes disappointed with lagerfeld's recent creative eccentricities
his sportier looks were based on glen plaid or tweed blazers with lean skirts or pants, often topped with short fencers' capes
with feathered hats, it was vaguely tyrolian, although there were lots of familiar chanel chain belts and buttons used discreetly throughout. gold buttons were de rigueur down the arms and jackets of most suits
as a change from the familiar and much-copied chain and quilt chanel shoulder bag, there's a new model in bright red and green plaids
one of the best jackets here was narrowed at the waist, had curved lounging-jacket lapels, patch pockets with a pleat and came in bright red, green or navy. it topped a swingy, pleated gray skirt or pants
the trouser suits for day were in muted browns, grays or greens, cutest with a nipped plaid bolero. also in the tyrolean vein were the long or short gathered bold plaid skirts, dressiest when topped with a clinging black sweater with lace yoke
there were blouses galore for all the easy pants, most often in white georgette silk crepe with pierrot, double-pleated ruffles and wide flounced necklines
the longer suits _ often in navy or black _ were strictly lean, but moved well. and in black velvet they had lovely touches of double knit rows of ruffles or embroidered flowers, big and small
the fluid evening satin pyjamas with belted tunic tops in searing colors could be sure-fire classic winners
knits were super too, remarkable in ivory cable-knit cardigans over gorgeous draped chiffon dinner dresses. in spite of some peppy, full, bright skirts with lace, ribbons, crinolines and busy tops, the overall statement was totally wearable chic
kenzo's show was a cheery ode to fall. he too showed all lengths with some medieval-renaissance touches. his best red suit with a skirt just above the knee had an interesting sleeve puffed out below the dropped shoulder
kenzo's pants suits were lean and pin-striped for dandies, black ``smokings'' a la george sand or had a medieval look with page-boy knickers, often with capes in rust or olive colors and sometimes with big silk scarves with renaissance portraits
other graceful touches were in the colorful tweed and flowered velvet fitted suits, again skirts mini to long. there was a lovely ``skyline'' inspired group of light challis wool and chiffon dresses printed with puffy clouds
maryll lanvin's versatile approach featured well-cut clothes in good fabrics. they looked young, but could be worn by any age
lots of pants worked fine, especially topped by fitted, checked cropped jackets or tiny boleros in autumn colors
also remarkable were her short suits with very long jackets in windowpane-checked bright yellow or royal blue. other suits came out in more subtle gray, tan or brick shades with full peplums on the jackets
the best coat in hot tones of orange, fuschia and emerald turned up in an egg shape and was worn with a neat piped suit underneath _ in a different sizzling shade
cocktail looks turned elaborate, with drapes and puffs and dazzling colors. they exuded a faint air of ungaro, but were less showy than his exaggerations
a safe but appealing party choice would be the romantic white ruffled victorian blouses over black draped silk sheaths
paisley turned up here as all over the paris shows, in soft, full-skirted day dresses or as big borders on flounced black numbers, or dresses with pointed handkerchief-panel skirts. and the velvet paisley lounging pyjama suit was best of all
sonia rykiel, often best at her own familiar tunes, classic knits, branched out at her winter show into quilted tops and suits that were so puffy they made the wearer look like the michelin man
but she had some excellent suits. an amethyst or flame short knit suit with the jacket bowed in back had the rykiel chic. and her fitted caviar or houndstooth spencer suits were timely and handsome, as were the graceful dark or tan solid-color suits, nearly ankle-length
evenings at rykiel are best in the slinky, long black outfits with sparkly details. striped taffetas with big v-shaped panels in front and full skirts in silvery grays lacked rykiel's light touch and ended up on the too-prim side of heavy victorian
an old print that has adorned a wall in a painter's cottage for decades is a genuine rembrandt etching worth about $53,500, an art expert said monday
the 1626 print, titled ``jesus' circumcision in the temple,'' is the fifth known copy of the etching, said theo lorentzius, who examined the artwork
the print, which measures 8 inches by 5 inches, also was examined by experts of amsterdam's rijksmuseum, a center of rembrandt learning
the owner, painter evert musch, said he bought it about 40 years ago from an art dealer in groningen, a city 16 miles north of this village in the northeastern netherlands. he didn't recall what he paid for it
i've always believed that the print was a genuine rembrandt,'' musch said in an interview with the associated press. the print bears the signature ``rembrandt fecit,'' latin for ``rembrandt made.''
two weeks ago, musch showed his print on a dutch tv show about privately owned art, and the station brought in lorentzius for his opinion
musch said he planned to keep the print. ``it's far too beautiful to sell,'' he added
the supreme court, agreeing to decide an important issue for all lawsuits alleging age bias in employment, said today it will study the case of a laid-off pennsylvania man
the justices agreed to decide whether eugene f. brieck's lawsuit against his former employer, harbison-walker refractories, should proceed to a jury trial
harbison-walker, a division of dresser industries, sells specialized ceramic brick products primarily to steel producers. brieck worked as an installation specialist for harbison-walker from 1965 to 1982
in july 1982, several employees of harbison-walker's iron and steel marketing support group were laid off, including brieck. he then was 55
brieck sued harbison-walker in pittsburgh in 1984, contending that he was laid off and not recalled to work because of his age. his lawsuit pointed to a 39-year-old installation specialist with less seniority who was not laid off until november 1982 and then recalled eight months later
lawyers for harbison-walker contended that the other employee, hugh faust, was retained because of his more diverse work experience
but brieck alleged that such diverse capabilities played a very small role in the job faust performed
u.s. district judge gerald j. weber threw out brieck's suit, ruling that harbison-walker had articulated legitimate, non-discriminatory business reasons for laying off brieck while retaining a younger man with less seniority
but the 3rd u.s. circuit court of appeals reinstated brieck's suit last june 19
the appeals court ruled that an employer charged with violating the federal age discrimination in employment act cannot avoid trial by articulating legitimate business reasons if the suing employee presents ``a reasonable inference that the employer' proffered explanation ... is unworthy of credence.''
the appeals court added: ``the question is not whether the employer's asserted reason is plausible, but whether there is also evidence of record which, if credited, could render the reason implausible.''
in seeking supreme court review, lawyers for harbison-walker argued that the appeals court ruling ``virtually eliminates summary (pretrial) judgment in employment discrimination cases.''
the case is harbison-walker vs. brieck, 87-271. collapse</head>
a bomb exploded in a four-story apartment building in moslem west beirut today, and police said several people were believed buried in the rubble
the blast occurred at 7 p.m. in the tarik jedideh district
civil defense rescue teams and ambulances rushed to the scene, police said. they had no further details
meanwhile, in tripoli, 50 miles north of beirut, an unfinished eight-story building collapsed at daybreak, burying six construction workers, police reported
they said one worker was rescued after six hours. although rescue teams reported hearing moans beneath the wreckage, hopes were fading at nightfall that any of the others would survive
police said the cause of the building collapse in tripoli was not immediately known.  
vice president george bush won puerto rico's republican primary and added 14 more national convention delegates to his tally, while jesse jackson won the democrats' non-binding ``beauty contest'' balloting
with 35 percent of the precincts reporting, bush picked up 98 percent of sunday's vote. gop rival sen. bob dole of kansas had received just 2 percent
bush had an overwhelming 1,935 votes compared to just 48 for dole in ballots that had been tallied. ``bush has the 14 delegates,'' said local gop chairman luis ferre
the vast majority of puerto ricans chose to vote in the democratic primary. with 91 percent of the precincts reporting, jackson led with 87,757 votes, or 32 percent, followed by massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with 70,733 for 26 percent
illinois sen. paul simon was third with 57,639 votes or 21 percent. tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 45,361 for 17 percent, and missouri rep. richard gephardt had received 9,159 or 3 percent of the votes
the democratic primary had no effect on the candidates' delegate totals for the democratic national convention next july in atlanta. the 33 delegates at stake sunday, who will choose another 18 delegates, have said they will go uncommitted to the convention
in all, puerto rico will send 56 delegates to the convention, including gov. raphael hernandez colon and four other party leaders who automatically receive delegate seats. leaders say the delegation intends to vote as a bloc
puerto rico's two main political parties, hernandez colon's popular democratic party and the out-of-power new progressive party, predicted that 1 million voters would cast ballots. new progressives in general favor statehood for puerto rico while popular democrats do not
the turnout was less than half what was expected, possibily because the system approved by the state election commission required voters to register beginning at 9 a.m. but prohibited them from voting until after 2 p.m. the system was set up to prevent double voting
in 1980, the republican presidential primary was held two weeks before the democratic primary. new progressive party voters cast ballots first for george bush, a longtime proponent of statehood for puerto rico, and then for jimmy carter. the popular democratic party supported massachusetts sen. edward m. kennedy eight years ago
gop chairman ferre said many republicans probably did not vote because of the confusion caused by dole backers who tried to call off the primary and choose delegates instead by caucus. the issue was not settled until two days before the primary when a superior court judge ruled it must be held
in preliminary figures released shortly after noon, the commission reported the pdp slate ahead of the npp slate by 373,950 votes to 297,408, with most of the 1,650 polling stations tabulated. a total of 671,358 valid votes were counted
pdp officials claimed they won at least 29 democratic convention delegate seats, and perhaps all 33 that were at stake
what we have seen in these primaries is a prelude of what will happen in november'' when the two parties meet again in gubernatorial elections, said hernandez colon, who is running for re-election
the victory touched off pdp celebrations that included fireworks, speeches and a merengue band at party headquarters, and a caravan that wound its way, horns tooting and loudspeakers blaring, through the old san juan and puerta de tierra sections of the capital at 2 a.m
ex gov. carlos romero barcelo, who headed the npp slate, conceded his delegates lost, but said, ``we are not defeated. the defeated don't continue to fight and we are in a fight (against the pdp) from today on.''
romero barcelo faces a primary on june 12 against san juan mayor baltasar corrada del rio for the npp nomination for governor. losing sunday may have weakened his standing in the party
aside from a test of strength between hernandez colon and romero barcelo, at issue was control of the local democratic party, whose leaders will be chosen by the 33 delegates elected sunday
the npp wants puerto rico to become the 51st u.s. state. the pdp wants things to remain as they are _ with puerto ricans as u.s. citizens with almost every right and obligation except they cannot vote for president in the general election and do not pay federal taxes
anticipating trouble between the rival parties, the police department canceled days off and vacations, and stationed 3,000 officers at or near polling stations and party offices. the sale of alcoholic beverages was prohibited from midnight saturday to sunday night
there were no reports of violence
a woman who put a job-wanted ad in a newspaper was recruited as a communist spy and trained to photograph secret documents with a camera disguised as a cigarette lighter, officials said monday
the woman, arrested friday in bonn, hid film taken for her soviet bloc spymasters in a specially constructed can of hairspray, prosecutors said
she used at least 26 locations in bonn to deliver documents and pick up instructions from other communist agents, they added
prosecutor kurt rebmann said investigators were assessing the damage to national security caused by elke falk, who worked in the west german chancellery from 1974 to 1977 and in other ministries later
the suspect delivered notes, copied documents and photographs from all of her professional duties to her intelligence contacts,'' rebmann said
ms. falk is being held in investigative custody awaiting formal charges, rebmann said. security officials have not identified the soviet bloc intelligence agency for which she allegedly worked
ms. falk was a secretary in the economic coooperation ministry at the time of her arrest friday, hours after officials disclosed the defection of a high east german transport official who apparently led authorities to her
she was the chief secretary to volkmar koehler, no. 2 man in the economic cooperation ministry, until 1987 and later moved to the ministry's european section, officials reported
ministry spokesman manfred oblaender said ms. falk had access to ``very confidential and secret documents'' provided to the ministry by west german intelligence agencies
rebmann told reporters ms. falk was recruited by a man using the name gerhard thieme after she placed an advertisement in a newspaper looking for work. on sunday, the mass-circulation newspaper bild reported that ms. falk began syping after thieme seduced her
in its monday editions, bild said ms. falk had access to top-secret military and defense documents while working at the chancellery
quoting security sources it did not identify, bild said she also had access to transcipts of meetings between former chancellor helmut schmidt and foreign leaders, including former presidents jimmy carter and gerald r. ford
according to rebmann, communist agents warned ms. falk in 1985 that she might be exposed. she told west german authorities she stopped spying at that time and destroyed her equipment, but ignored urgings by communist contacts to flee to the east, he said
he said ms. falk was paid about $11,760 for the information she delivered
bild quoted the security sources as saying ms. falk's activities represented the most serious security breach since the arrest of guenther guillaume, a top aide to former chancellor willy brandt
brandt was forced to resign as chancellor in 1974 after guillaume was exposed as a spy
in the last major west german spy scandal, 15 communist agents were arrested or disappeared between august and december 1985. among them was hans-joachim tiedge, the man in charge of catching east german spies, who fled to east germany
gil evans, a composer, pianist and band leader who made his mark with innovative arrangements with jazz great miles davis, has died in cuernavaca, mexico, at the age of 75
evans died sunday of peritonitis while recuperating from prostate surgery, his widow, anita, said today in new york
evans had been active until recently, playing at a new york club in december and january. he went to cuernavaca to recuperate from his operation, taking his synthesizer to work on new compositions
an upcoming tour will proceed as planned, with evans' son miles leading the gil evans orchestra, mrs. evans said
gil left tones of music to be carried forth,'' mrs. evans said
jazz historian and writer leonard feather said evans made his mark with innovative arranging, particularly in three records by trumpeter miles davis. the albums, ``miles ahead,'' ``porgy and bess'' and ``sketches of spain,'' showcased davis' cool style
they were really among the most brilliant orchestral jazz records made by anybody,'' feather said. ``he made brilliant use of tone colors.''
evans was born ian ernest gilmore green in toronto, ontario, on may 13, 1912. his parents were australian and he grew up in stockton, calif., starting his first jazz band while in high school
he led a band in stockton from 1933 to 1938, and from 1941 to 1948, except for three years of army service, he arranged for the claude thornhill orchestra
he experimented with bebop with davis, gerry mulligan and john lewis, worked as a free-lance arranger in new york and gained recognition for a reunion with davis in 1957 that resulted in ``miles ahead.''
in 1958 he started recording with his own band. his arrangements always had a fuller, more orchestral sound than most jazz and swing bands. in recent years, evans had added electronically amplified instruments for a more commercially acceptable sound
evans had recently had worked on a record album with helen merrill, and davis told mrs. evans last week that he had written a new tune, titled ``gil evans.''
the upcoming tour included appearances at the jvc jazz festival here and appearances in london and at the umbria jazz festival in italy, mrs. evans said
a memorial service will be held in new york, probably on easter sunday, mrs. evans said. evans' sons, noah and miles, were with him in cuernavaca when he died. announcing suspension of military operations. deletes el salvador section.</note>
here is a summary of developments sunday and today involving nicaragua, honduras, the united states and el salvador:
american soldiers engaged in military maneuvers sunday at a honduran airstrip just 20 miles from the nicaraguan border, but u.s. officials said the threat from sandinista troops had subsided and combat appeared unlikely
president reagan sent 3,200 u.s. military personnel to non-combat areas in honduras last week after the central american nation reported that nicaraguan forces had crossed its border to raid bases of u.s.-backed nicaraguan rebels
lt. gen. colin powell, the u.s. national security adviser, said in washington the u.s. military exercises should be completed shortly and the troops will return to the united states
the reagan administration indicated support for a new $48 million proposal for aid to the contras that was advanced by a bipartisan group of senators
contra and nicaraguan leaders met today in sapoa, nicaragua, for the first cease-fire talks held inside nicaragua
nicargua announced that it would suspend military operations for the duration of the talks
on sunday, deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco reiterated a previous sandinista position that the negotiations strictly deal with the mechanics of a cease-fire. rebel leaders said the talks must also focus on ``democratization of nicaragua and free elections.''
earlier, nicaragua formally protested a honduran bombing raid on sandinista positions saturday as an unwarranted act of aggression. it has denied that its troops crossed the jungle-choked border dividing the nations
president jose azcona hoyo on sunday said nicaraguan troops are retreating from honduras and the u.s. soldiers probably won't be needed much longer
honduran officials said saturday's air raid on sandinista positions was carried out because about 600 nicaraguan troops were moving too slowly from a section of the bocay area that honduras considers its territory
congress should order american troops and military installations pulled out of japan unless the japanese do much more to pay for western defense, sen. ted stevens said monday
stevens said that because of the strength of the japanese economy and its favorable trade balance with the unite states, tokyo should be able to foot the bill for its own defense
the yen has conquered a great portion of american,'' the alaska republican told a group of pentagon officials during a hearing of the senate appropriations military construction subcommittee. ``now that the japanese economy is going full tilt,'' japan should pay the full cost of keeping u.s. troops and facilities in that nation, stevens said
stevens said he was ``putting the pentagon on notice'' that he plans to offer a bill next year that would require u.s. military withdrawals from japan
stevens said his proposal would be similar to legislation which was routinely sponsored _ and just as routinely defeated _ by former sen. mike mansfield, d-mont., calling for u.s. troops to be withdrawn from europe. mansfield is now u.s. ambassador to japan
mansfield was right,'' stevens said
the united states has been pressuring japan to increase defense spending and take more responsibility for its defense. those calls have been particularly loud on capitol hill, where japan has come under increasing criticism for its trade policies
in tokyo, prime minister noboru takeshita said monday that japan's military power should match its economic strength
japan last year formally scrapped a decade-old ceiling which limited defense spending to 1 percent of its gross national product. during the current 1986-90 defense buildup plan, the government says japan's defense spending will total $119.87 billion
japan pays about 40 percent of the $5.9 billion cost of maintaining u.s. facilities in the country
richard armitage, assistant secretary of defense for international security affairs, told stevens that congress shouldn't engage in ``japan-bashing.''
japan is increasing its defense budget, armitage said, and the spending total ``is on the verge'' of passing the british, french and west german defense budgets
we should look beyond the popular ally-bashing rhetoric of a campaign year,'' armitage said
stevens responded that he would have offered his proposal this year, but ``it shouldn't be an election-year issue.''
japan is now meeting all its mutually agreed defense goals, armitage said, and is building up its naval fleet
sen. james sasser, d-tenn., chairman of the subcommittee, told armitage that ``this burden-sharing issue is not going to go away.'' the congressional criticism ``is the reflection of a deeply felt concern among the american people'' that u.s. allies should do more
on other matters, sasser said ``there are good signs'' that nato will come up with a new home, probably italy, for the 401st tactical fighter wing in spain. the spanish government earlier this year formally asked that the wing's 72 f-16s be removed from torrejon air base outside madrid
congress has banned the spending of any u.s. money to relocate the wing. instead, the cost will be picked up by nato
five army pershing ii missiles were flight-tested today at the air force space and missile test center range
the missiles were successfully fired by nato troops from west germany under battlefield conditions, said dave harris, a spokesman for the army's redstone arsenal in huntsville, ala
the pershings have been banned from use under an arms treaty signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev, but the treaty has not yet been ratified by the senate
the pershing is a field missile launched by its own erector and can be carried anywhere, towed by a truck. each of the missiles cost $4 million
the missiles were launched separately during the morning from 8:01 a.m until 11:53 a.m., army officials said. pvs, boren said. deletes final 7 grafs pvs to shorten.</note>
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said today the reagan administration is ``very encouraged'' by a new congressional plan to send aid to the contra rebels, but said other suggestions were also welcome
we anticipate signing on to a bill, in the sense that we want a contra aid package, and we are working to get the best one that we can get,'' fitzwater told reporters. ``i think something will be very forthcoming very soon.''
the $48 million plan, which would permit the delivery of as much as $2.5 million worth of previously authorized arms and ammunition, was proposed friday by sen. nancy kassebaum, r-kan., and a bipartisan group of senators. it came in the wake of president reagan's decision to airlift more than 3,100 u.s. troops to honduras
reagan dispatched the troops wednesday after nicaragua's leftist government mounted an offensive against contra rebels along the honduran border. in his saturday radio address, reagan blamed congress' recent rejection of new aid for the contras for the sandinista push against the rebels
asked if the administration objected to anything in the new proposal, fitzwater said, ``i would say overall that we are very encouraged by the kassebaum proposal ... but we want to be open to other suggestions as well.''
he said the administration would hold talks with house speaker jim wright, d-texas, ``when the time is right.'' discussions with other members would continue today, he said, but he refused to name the individuals
asked if the administration believed there was a chance that military aid for the rebels would be approved, the spokesman declined to comment
the spokesman said the sandinista push against the contras had ``improved chances'' for such a package because it had changed minds on capitol hill
events of the last week have left little to the imagination in terms of what president (daniel) ortega and the sandinistas are really up to,'' fitzwater said
secretary of state george shultz, offering the administration's first comment on the contra aid proposal said sunday that it ``should go forward.''
commenting on nbc-tv's ``meet the press,'' he said the package was ``a little low on money'' but under study by the administration
representatives from capitol hill differed today on whether the situation had improved chances for renewed contra aid
senate intelligence committee chairman david boren, d-okla., said on abc-tv's ``good morning america'' that the u.s. show of strength had ``helped the situation.''
boren said he was ``amazed that there hasn't already been more action'' in advancing the plan
however, rep. lee hamilton, d-ind., a senior member of the house foreign affairs committee and an opponent of further military aid to the contras, said today that a favorable vote in the house is much more problematic
the events of last week probably enhanced the possibility of some kind of aid package moving forward,'' hamilton said on the same abc-tv show. ``but there are a lot of obstacles to overcome. it's very had to predict at this point.''
but some in congress say the administration, if it chooses to back a new contra aid request, must confront doubts about the seriousness of the border clash and perhaps even a backlash in congress prompted by the sudden airlift of troops
there is ... a very serious lack of full trust here, which goes back many years,'' said house majority leader thomas foley, appearing on cnn's ``newsmaker sunday.''
reagan's national security adviser, lt. gen. colin powell, denied sunday that he had misled congress when he briefed lawmakers wednesday. he acknowledged, however, that he had failed to mention reagan's decision in principle to send troops to honduras if president jose azcona requested them
we did not go into the specific options because we did not want it all over the newspapers,'' powell said during an appearance on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley.''
the national security adviser said the fighting on the nicaraguan-honduran border was ``pretty much over'' and offered assurances that it was unlikely u.s. troops would become involved
the combat zone is rapidly disappearing as the sandinistas appear to withdraw, and i don't think there is any reasonable likelihood that they would be anywhere near the combat zone,'' powell said of the u.s. troops
want to buy a million-dollar mansion with hardwood floors, chandeliers and a spiral staircase? a firm here will build you one on its assembly line and ship it to you in pieces on flatbed trucks
it's really an evolutionary thing for home building,'' said george oswald, treasurer of techno craft inc., a 3-year-old, privately held company
this business started with mobile homes, went to double-wides and then two-story units. we said that's all well and good but we're going to go ahead of that,'' said greg cunningham, the company's founder and chief executive officer
each two-story luxury home built by techno craft, which began production last august, has hardwood floors, a spiral staircase, chandeliers, a fireplace, jacuzzi, bidet and imported tiles. options include a steam room, sauna and an elevator
cunningham, 35, started the techno craft in 1985 when another company he heads had trouble finding an adequate supply of upscale housing in the new york metropolitan area
this is really the answer to the housing problem in this country, modular housing and done right,'' he said
techno craft produced 100 homes on its assembly line last year and has orders this year for 450, he said
oswald said the company will have to build another plant next year to meet demand. he said they eventually want to make 1,000 homes a year for sale between maine and virginia and increase employment from 125 to 700
nationally, 51,000 modular homes were produced last year, up from 39,000 in 1977, according to the 1988 edition of the red book of housing manufacturers. modular homes accounted for 2.8 percent of the 1.85 million homes built in 1987, according to the book, which based its findings on a survey of more than 500 companies
john j. smolke jr., chief of pennsylvania's division of manufactured housing, a state regulatory agency, said a shortage of skilled labor and greater profit for the builder have helped the growth of the industry
but he said the industry still has to overcome the image that pre-fabricated homes belong in the low-rent district
when people think of something built in a plant, they still envision ... the typical mobile home,'' smolke said
cunningham said building homes in a factory has advantages to building them on the lot
homes built on site can take eight months to a year to build and are subject to vandalism and theft, exposed to the weather and dependent on local labor, he said
techno craft's factory-built mansions take eight weeks from the start of construction to the day the homeowner can move in, and 95 percent of the work takes place in the factory, cunningham said
peter cornell, president of cornell development corp. in albany, n.y., decided to have techno craft build 151 townhouses for a development near albany
they are the only people who can do in the factory what i can with a real quality crew,'' cornell said. he said techno craft will do it at a lower cost
in the 480-foot-long techno craft plant, sections or modules of a house are assembled along an assembly line with 24 work stations
floors and roofs are constructed at separate stations to the side of the assembly line and moved to the line by overhead cranes
the finished sections are shipped from the plant in central pennsylvania on six flatbed trucks and can be assembled in a day
after the sections are lifted onto a foundation with a crane and assembled, siding is added and pre-cut molding and carpeting is installed, cunningham said
oswald said modular homes from other builders require more construction after they are placed on their foundations
it would take anybody else two or three years to get where we are and by that time we'll be way ahead,'' he said
a leukemia patient learned today that his bone marrow does not match that of his brother, a homeless florida man who had declined to undergo testing until he was offered $1,000
you kind of start counting on things and then you have a big letdown,'' said steven j. chapman. ``i've just made up my mind not to count on anything.''
doctors said they were presenting other treatment options to chapman, 31, of oolitic
it's would have been a very rough treatment,'' said dr. richard s. fayssoux, the hematology and oncology specialist who is treating chapman
the patient's brother, randy chapman, 32, who was located last month on the streets of miami, initially refused to submit to tests
if he dies, he dies,'' said randy chapman, who earns his living as the subject of medical experiments
randy chapman eventually accepted an indiana philanthropist's offer of a $1,000 testing incentive. the brother, who left home 16 years ago, would have received an additional $2,000 had there been a match and subsequent transplant operation
steven chapman said doctors were checking into a partial bone marrow match that was located through a national registry
we'll come up with something else,'' said chapman
a woman crossing a street was hit by four vehicles and killed, police said
janell bankhead, 25, was hit by a van as she walked across a street about 12:30 a.m. sunday. she tried to get up, but a pickup truck heading in the opposite direction dragged her a short distance
another van then hit ms. bankhead and the driver did not stop. then a third van ran over her, police said
the drivers who stopped after hitting the woman said they did not see her in the darkness, police said. officers were searching for the driver of the van that did not stop. drivers of the others were not cited
a soviet official today charged that u.s. negotiators are jeopardizing prospects of signing an accord to cut long-range nuclear weapons at the next superpower summit
the remarks came in an interview of alexei a. obukhov, the soviets' top arms negotiator, published today in the communist party newspaper pravda. they coincided with the first day of talks in washington between soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze and u.s. officials
i have the impression that the americans began to hesitate and are not sure now whether it is worthwhile to have an agreement on strategic offensive arms ready by the designated date, that is by the time ronald reagan visits moscow,'' obukhov told pravda. ``today, the americans are slowing down the pace rather than increasing it.''
shevardnadze and u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz have been holding monthly meetings to work out differences in a 200-page treaty to cut long-range missiles by 50 percent
president reagan has been expected to go to moscow later this spring, on a date to be announced, for his fourth meeting with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. both sides have said they would like to sign the treaty on strategic weapons at that time
shultz said in moscow last february that the two sides had agreed to tell treaty negotiators to draft verification and other key elements by the time shevardnadze came to the united states. he also said negotiators should speed up progess in order to ensure a treaty would be ready to sign at a moscow summit
but obukhov said americans were dragging their feet with the idea of turning lack of progress against the soviets. ``our partners think that, with this kind of action, they can spoil the term for working out the agreement and place the blame for this on us,'' he said
obukhov also said the reagan administration's position on the strategic defense initiative, better known as ``star wars,'' still stands in the way of an agreement. the soviets say the program to deploy a space shield against nuclear attack violates the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty between the superpowers
in a separate dispatch, the official tass news agency said the u.s. ``military-industrial complex'' has become wary of star wars because the program's cost may preclude spending on other types of military weapons
the prospect of enormous funds being allocated for sdi at the expense of other military programs has caused obvious concern to individual members of the military-industrial complex, who are beginning to see the star wars project as two birds in the bush that can make them lose the bird in hand,'' tass said
vladimir chernyshov, the agency's military writer, said the fifth anniversary of the strategic defense initiative is being widely celebrated in the united states although ``there is effectively nothing left of the sdi `dream' as conceived five years ago.''
while then they were talking about an `impregnable shield,' now they are talking about a `first phase' of an abm system with very limited capability,'' chernyshov wrote
however, he said it would be a ``dangerous illusion' to believe that because of opposition in congress and elsewhere star wars will soon be abandoned
more than 250,000 refugees of drought and civil war from neighboring sudan need more help to control disease and starvation, the government-owned news agency said monday
the sudanese refugees are aggravating an existing hunger problem in ethiopia, where 7 million people are threatened by starvation. most live in the northern provinces of tigray and eritrea, where ethiopia is fighting its own battle against secessionist rebels
an average of sudanese 15 refugees died each day last month, but the daily death toll recently had dropped to three, ethiopian news agency said, quoting one of the country's red cross officials
the red cross is working among seven national and international agencies providing food, clothing and medicine to the refugees
at least 47,000 of them flooded into ethiopia's western border regions of illubabor and wellega in the past four months. the agency said the influx was increasing daily
many of the refugees were fleeing a war started in 1983 by the southern-based sudan people's liberation army. the rebels are fighting the moslem-dominated government in khartoum for economic reforms and more autonomy in the mainly christian and animist south
that war has also worsened chronic droughts
police arrested 34 taxi drivers monday for violating anti-pollution rules that ban half of the capital's 15,000 taxis from the city center each day
a spokesman for the cabbies said they intentionally entered the district to challenge the ban, which they dismiss as illegal
the ban is part of a set of wide-ranging restrictions limiting traffic in athens. the measures are aimed at dispelling an eye-stinging brown smog that hangs over the city in calm weather
the taxi drivers were arrested because they brought cabs with even license-plate numbers into the 5-square-mile central zone on a day reserved for odd-numbered vehicles, said a spokesmen for the traffic police
nikos stekas, a spokesman for the athens taxi drivers union, said cabbies will defy the ban every day, claiming it cuts their income in half
the taxi drivers face a one-year jail term or a $370 fine, police said. they could also lose their operating permits for a month
state rep. bill english takes along a portable television set and earplug when he goes to the house floor to vote
other lawmakers cluster around a lobby television set or around tvs and radios in their offices, so focused on them that house leaders sometimes need six quorum calls to transact business
the house is virtually at a standstill, with five members working as the board of managers for the senate's impeachment trial of gov. evan mecham and the 55 others fascinated by testimony that has included an alleged death threat, sexual affairs, political paybacks and the governor himself
the trial entered its fourth week monday, and the senate has considered only one of three charges against mecham, a first-term republican who is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona
many house committees canceled meetings last week for lack of bills the chairmen wanted to consider, and the house moved to a three-day week beginning monday, down from four-day work weeks
the 30-member senate, meanwhile, has scheduled night committee meetings in an effort to act on the relatively few key areas lawmakers want to address this session: the budget, taxes, air pollution and indigent health care
regular sessions are supposed to last 100 days, which generally would mean ending in late april. but pressure to close does not begin in earnest until per diem pay is cut in half after 110 days and stops altogether after 120 days
lawmakers say the pace has been especially slow this year, despite promises from the house republican leadership that things would start moving once the house finished pre-impeachment hearings and sent the matter to the senate
it's not been a terribly productive year so far,'' says house minority leader art hamilton, a democrat from phoenix
it's the most difficult session i've seen in 16 years, and it doesn't seem to be getting any better,'' he added, citing ``a lot more emotion than probably action.''
republican leaders acknowledge that impeaching a fellow republican has taken its toll on party unity. hamilton and others note the inaction on major bills and the concentration on issues such as a resolution telling congress that soviet troops should quit angola
other committee chairmen, meanwhile, have continued to limit debate, prompting a series of walkouts by democrats who complain that important bills are not being given a full hearing
republican leaders say they have been trying to keep the session as normal as possible, but hamilton said he thinks lawmakers should take advantage of the spare time to look in-depth at issues such as taxes, arizona's medicaid alternative and pollution, which normally get resolved on a rush basis due to the press of other business
but because most house members are watching the trial, hamilton said, the house is doing little other its ``normal work at a much slower pace.''
it's tough to compete with the soap-opera draw of the impeachment trial
mecham is charged with ordering the department of public safety director not to cooperate with an investigation of the alleged threat by a state official against a former mecham aide. the aide was about to testify before a state grand jury on the governor's unreported $350,000 campaign loan
mecham also is accused in the impeachment trial of concealing the loan and misusing $80,000 in state funds by loaning the money to his auto dealership
mecham has said he will be exonerated
a two-thirds vote of the senate is required to convict mecham, and lawmakers also could bar him from public office. mecham also faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the campaign loan, and a may 17 recall election. last 4 grafs pvs to trim.</note>
the state department today complained of massive soviet arms shipments to nicaragua as the war in the central american country cast a shadow over the visit of foreign minsiter eduard a. shevardnadze even before he opened talks here
charles e. redman, the department spokesman, said the soviets shipped over 3,000 tons of equipment to the sandinista government in january and february alone
for a number of years, the soviets have supplied nicaragua with $500 million to $600 million in assistance annually, he said. ``i certainly don't see it as an issue heating up,'' redman said. but, he said soviet military support is a ``continuing cause for concern.''
in another development before shevardnadze opened talks with secretary of state george p. shultz late in the day, the white house confirmed that there could be two superpower summit meetings this year
signing a treaty to sharply reduce strategic nuclear weapons this spring in moscow ``is our goal,'' presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said
we are hopeful, but there is no guarantee that we'll have a start agreement ready to sign at the summit,'' he said
therefore, fitzwater said, reagan told the international herald tribune last friday in an interview that ``if there was an agreement later sure we'd find some way to sign it.''
while the administration complained about soviet military aid to nicaragua, shevardnadze was bound to register moscow's irritation over the dispatch of 3,200 american troops to honduras
we have quite a few problems,'' the soviet foreign minister said on his arrival sunday for three days of talks with shultz and a session with president reagan at the white house. he singled out the situation in central america as `'rather grave and of some serious concern to us.''
also, an impasse has developed in negotiations, held in geneva under united nations auspices, for the withdrawal of an estimated 120,000 soviet troops from afghanistan
still, the visit may produce a date for the next superpower summit _ speculation centers on late may in moscow _ and some progress toward a treaty to sharply reduce u.s. and soviet long-range nuclear weapons
the treaty is the projected centerpiece for reagan's fourth meeting with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. but negotiations in geneva have proceeded slowly
it's by no means in the bag,'' shultz said sunday of the accord that would reduce by 30 percent to 50 percent the overall arsenals of u.s. and soviet long-range bombers, missiles and submarines
it's possible, but we're not going to try to have one just for the sake of a treaty,'' shultz said on nbc-tv. ``we'll only be willing to go forward; the president will, if it's something we regard as good.''
shevardnadze, in a statement on his arrival at andrews air force base, outside washington, said he was optimistic about arranging reagan's visit
i think we will be able to decide about the date,'' he said, then added, ``we have to work hard; we have to work intently.''
u.s. and soviet negotiators have been working on drafts for the strategic arms reduction treaty. one would deal with how nuclear weapons will be scrapped, another with verifying compliance with the accord
the two sides have exchanged drafts in the past month on how they would inspect each other's missile sites and make sure cutbacks are carried out. shultz and shevardnadze are also due to review the procedures for reducing nuclear arsenals
the procedures are likely to follow the pattern of the treaty to ban intermediate-range nuclear missiles. but verification is considered a more difficult problem since not all the long-range weapons would be scrapped
shultz indicated strongly that reagan would go to moscow to see gorbachev _ with or without a treaty to sign
i think it is important that summit meetings have content,'' he said. ``but it's also true that we are now evolving into a process where, perhaps, they will come to be a little more normal. ... there are plenty of things on our plate right now that could come to fruition other than the strategic arms treaty.''
reagan, in an interview published in the international herald tribune, said he was willing to meet with gorbachev a second time this year if the negotiations for a strategic arms treaty could not be completed by the summit later this spring
shevardnadze, after resting from his long flight from moscow, arranged for a late afternoon meeting with shultz today. they will meet again on tuesday and wednesday. his call on reagan at the white house tentatively is scheduled for wednesday
shultz and shevardnadze have been meeting monthly to plan for the summit. improving the human rights situation in the soviet union and soliciting soviet support for an international arms embargo against iran also are among the u.s. goals
in the meantime, the wars in nicaragua and afghanistan underscore u.s.-soviet rivalries
guerrillas in both countries are fighting with u.s. weapons against marxist governments equipped by the soviet union. the reagan administration last week turned the heat up in central america by sending troops to honduras. injuries</note>
a commuter train bound for chicago hit a truck and derailed today, injuring at least 16 people, one of them seriously, officials said
the train derailed after hitting a truck at a crossroads just west of new lenox, said will county police sgt. belt, who would not provide his first name
nancy talaga, a witness, said the truck was stopped at a red light, and when the light changed, the truck tried to cross the tracks, which have warning signals and crossing gates
the train was right there,'' she said. ``i saw it in my rear-view mirror hit the trailer and derail.''
the truck went into a ditch and the driver came out of the cab, she said. he was trying to walk away, but was unsteady and had blood on his head
new lenox fire chief ken hossack said the injured were taken to silver cross hospital in nearby joliet. he said there were no fatalities
julie grant, a spokeswoman at silver cross, said 16 people had been brought in, with one in serious condition. the others were in good condition and were expected to be released, she said
ms. grant said the man in serious condition, terry lewis, was believed to be the truck driver
the accident occurred shortly after 10:30 a.m., officials said
tracks were blocked in both directions, said joyce macdonald, a spokeswoman for metra, the commuter railroad
we have sent a train out from chicago to pick up passengers who want to continue their trip to chicago,'' ms. macdonald said
two republican congressmen _ dan schaefer of colorado and howard nielson of utah _ announced monday they are running for re-election to their fourth terms in office
schaefer, 52, was first elected to congress from colorado's 6th district to serve out the term of former astronaut jack swigert, who was elected in 1982 but died before he could be seated
he said this might be his toughest contest if former state sen. martha ezzard, a former republican turned democrat, gets in the race. she has expressed interest but has not formally announced
nielson, 63, former utah speaker of the house and one-time statistics professor at brigham young university, won his last election by a 2-1 margin
