a witness at gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial testified today that she was certain she told the governor of an investigation into an alleged death threat two days before he is accused of trying to hinder the probe
peggy griffith, director of the governor's office of women's services, told the senate, ``i believed at the time he understood me.''
mecham is accused of trying to thwart an investigation of the alleged threat, and he testified last week that he did not recall mrs. griffith telling him there was a probe
mrs. grifith also said today that her secretary, terri fields, complained that mecham and his attorney were ``hounding'' her about information on the alleged threat against another official
mrs. griffith quoted ms. fields as saying, ``they just keep asking me about the conversation you had with lee watkins,'' who is accused of making the alleged threat
mecham is charged with ordering department of public safety director ralph milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat by watkins, then head of state prison construction, against former top mecham aide donna carlson
it was mrs. griffith who reported the threat, and ms. fields testified for the defense earlier in the trial in an effort to discredit mrs. griffith's testimony. ms. fields said mrs. griffith was sometimes forgetful and tended to exaggerate things
defense attorney fred craft, who cross-examined mrs. griffith today, asked if she had a ``total recall'' memory
when i hear a death threat i do,'' mrs. griffith said
she also said that during the first several days after the alleged threat occurred, ``i felt very much like nobody believed what i was saying.''
at the time of the alleged nov. 12 threat, ms. carlson was about to testify before a state grand jury on the governor's unreported $350,000 campaign loan
the governor's defense attorney, fred craft, also is expected to be called to the stand before testimony is completed on the count involving the death threat. craft attended a crucial meeting at which mecham was told about the alleged threat
mecham also is accused in the impeachment trial of concealing the loan and misusing $80,000 in state funds by loaning the money to his auto dealership. opening arguments were expected this week on the $80,000 loan
on sunday, with his impeachment trial entering its fourth week and some rocky testimony behind him, mecham said he is still convinced the senate will exonerate him
with the world looking on as they have, i can't see how any of them (senators) who have any claim of judging on the evidence can do anything but exonerate me,'' mecham said
mecham spent part of three days on the stand last week, and contended he was the victim of an attempted mutiny by people in government, including attorney general bob corbin and milstead
but his effort to discredit the former head of his dps security detail, lt. beau johnson, backfired friday when mecham admitted he lacked proof _ as he earlier testified that he had _ that johnson had stolen an unrelated report on the agency from the governor's office
johnson had reported the alleged death threat to mecham, although the governor contends he was not adequately informed of the seriousness of the matter
mecham testified that watkins told him he had been informed by johnson's supervisor, lt. col. james chilcoat, that johnson had taken the report
however, deputy dps director lt. col. gary phelps sparked applause and laughter from the gallery when he testified moments later that watkins in fact had taken the report _ which watkins denied
mecham said sunday he thought he had ``not really'' been hurt by his admission that he lacked the proof he had claimed under oath that he had. and, he said he hadn't intended to make the claim against johnson
i inadvertently used it when they were asking for a lot of things'' during his testimony, mecham said
mecham also said he believed watkins ``was telling the truth when he told me what chilcoat told him.''
the defense also sought last week to discredit milstead with testimony on his sex life by a woman who claimed to be his former lover, christina johnston. she was not allowed to give specifics, but said their relationship was ``intimate and personal'' and that she had been married ``only six'' times
mecham said he had never met mrs. johnston, but that he was told by craft that she was ``a very decent, honest person.''
with the exception of milstead, she marries men instead of just lives with them,'' mecham said. ``women who are vulnerable get taken advantage of by predatory men in this world.''
mecham is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham, and lawmakers also could decide to bar him from future public office
mecham also faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan, and a may 17 recall election
nancy reagan, mostly recovered from a bout of laryngitis, traveled to new york on monday to attend a performance of ``phantom of the opera.''
she's feeling better,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters
the first lady planned to attend the musical on tuesday with her brother, dr. richard davis and his wife patricia, as well as the composer of the show, andrew lloyd webber
mrs. reagan was to meet with the cast after the show and mark the celebration of webber's 40th birthday, said mrs. reagan's spokeswoman, elaine crispen
mrs. crispen said the first lady, who had remained over the weekend at the white house to nurse her throat, has ``90 percent of her voice back.''
she's just fine,'' the spokeswoman said
five army pershing 2 missiles, banned from deployment under a treaty with the soviets, were test-fired monday
the unarmed missiles were successfully fired under battlefield conditions by nato troops, normally based in west germany, an army spokesman said. the tests went off separately from 8:01 a.m. to 11:53 a.m., army officials said
the pershings have been banned from use under an arms treaty signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev, but the treaty has not been ratified by the senate, a move that could come in late spring
the intermediate-range nuclear forces, or inf, treaty, calls for the destruction of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles
six of the pershings were tested feb. 15 at cape canaveral air force station, near the kennedy space center, said capt. ken warren, an air force spokesman
the treaty does not require either side to withdraw or destroy missiles until it has been ratified by both governments
the pershing is a field missile _ each of which costs $4 million _ launched from its own assembly that can be carried by a truck
a supreme court justice monday criticized a denver lawyer over the fees he is charging as the court's ``special master'' in a case
justice harry a. blackmun, dissenting from a court order granting charles j. meyers $69,661.25 in interim fees, complained about the hourly rates many large law firms charge their clients
meyers, a former dean of stanford law school, is a partner in the denver office of the los angeles-based law firm of gibson, dunn &amp; crutcher
meyers in 1984 was appointed as special master in a still-pending dispute between texas and new mexico over use of pecos river water
texas is being allowed to ``sue'' new mexico in the supreme court before the case has been heard by any lower court. in such cases, the justices invoke the court's ``original jurisdiction'' and hire a special master to conduct hearings and make recommendations
the case, in varying forms, has been before the high court since 1975
meyers' submitted bill of over $69,000 represents work he and an associate of his law firm, diana poole, have devoted to the case since late 1986
meyers' bill, to be paid by texas and new mexico, reflects compensation averaging $275.12 an hour for himself and $191.30 for ms. poole
in his dissenting opinion, blackmun notes that many of the 246 hours ms. poole spent working on the case represented getting herself familiar with the legal issues. another associate in meyers' law firm, steven crafton, had been assigned similar duties before leaving the firm's denver office
it seems apparent _ indeed (meyers) so concedes when he describes the nature of the `early months' of her work on the case _ that a substantial amount of ms. poole's time was self-education ... and was duplicative background work already performed by ... crafton,'' blackmun said
the consequences of crafton's departure hardly are to be charged to these litigants,'' blackmun added
he added: ``it also is difficult for me to accept the fact that in denver, colo., this partner's time is now worth $290 an hour, having been increased from $265 on nov. 1, 1987, and that the time of ms. poole is now worth $200 an hour, having been elevated from $170 beginning nov. 1, 1987
it seems to me that `establishment' law firms are doing themselves and the public a disservice by asserting fees of this magnitude so persistently over dissents from the court
public dissatisfaction with lawyers is not unknown; neither is public distrust of lawyers. a fee application of this kind tends to build that dissatisfaction and that distrust,'' blackmun said
the case is texas vs. new mexico, 65 original
president reagan will meet with richard joaquin balaguer, president of the dominican republic, during a white house working visit and lunch on friday, it was announced monday
balaguer, who is scheduled to enter the united states at miami on thursday, also will meet with secretary of state george shultz and members of congress, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said
fitzwater said that balaguer's official activities would be followed by a private u.s. visit
safety experts previewed a series of new designs for child-resistant pill containers monday to highlight this year's national poison prevention week
the special medicine containers have helped reduce the number of children fatally poisoned from nearly 500 in 1962 to 56 in 1985, reported terrence m. scanlon, chairman of the federal consumer product safety commission
marsha millonig of the national poison prevention week said resistant caps are one of the three main factors in reducing poisonings, along with the growth of poison control centers and improved parental awareness of the dangers of poison for children
and dr. toby litovitz of the national capital poison control center at georgetowen university hospital stressed that even with the reduction in poisonings, the danger to toddlers persists and merits continued vigilance
while the special caps on medicine bottles and other products have helped reduce the toll on children, scanlon conceded that many adults also have trouble with them
hugh lockhart of michigan state university described several possible design changes that have been developed
the currently popular design, in which the cap from a pill bottle must be pressed down and turned to get it open, requires some strength and determination, he noted
basically, people are required to ``engage a series of lugs that they cannot see, using a principle that they do not understand. it's no wonder they've had trouble,'' lockhart said
one of the findings of the university researchers is that the physical strength of very old people may be no greater than than of a small child, he said. but the elderly generally retain manual dexterity and can handle problem solving better, so those abilities were considered in designing new closures
among the closures being tested, he said, are:
_placing individual pills in a strong plastic blister, with a peel-off backing
_designing a rigid plastic package with pills in individual blisters. the package would fold in half with a child-resistant latch holding it closed
_bottle caps similar to the current ones, except with a slot that a key could be slid into to allow them to be turned to open
_another bottle cap with a hole in the side into which a pencil or other tool could be inserted to twist it open
_a somewhat easier to open version of the current caps, which is lifted to open rather than being pressed down
_using inks in contrasting colors to make the directions and arrows stand out on caps, expecially those on which arrows have to be lined up to get them open
safety commission vice chairwoman carol dawson said the agency is arranging for test samples of the various designs to be made, and expects to give them tryouts during the next year
designs that are successful would be made available for manufacturers to copy at no charge, she said
some of the designs could be more costly than current child-resistant caps, although lockhard declined to speculate on the amount of the cost
the closure manufacturers association, meanwhile, applauded the research effort and said its members are anxious to participate in the testing of the new designs
a gunman in a black helmet shot dead the driver of a stretch limousine parked on a greenwich village street monday, then roared away on a motorcycle into rush-hour traffic, police said
the indications we see here are symptomatic of a mob hit,'' assistant police chief aaron rosenthal said at the scene
obviously, they knew who they were shooting at. they were very cool about it and very gutsy,'' he said. ``i would characterize it as cool, gutsy and professional and deliberate.''
rosenthal said he had little information on the victim, limousine owner-driver gregory decurtis, 29, who lived across the street from the shooting scene
his cream-colored cadillac was parked outside a cafe when two men, both wearing black helmets, sped up on a red and white motorcycle at 8:20 a.m., police said
one man dismounted and fired five shots into the closed driver's window, striking decurtis three times in the arm and once in the back, police said. the man then got back on the bike and fled
a passenger in the front seat, a man in his late 20s, was unhurt; his name was not released, said officer hugh barry
police moved in on a crowd of more than 500 people demonstrating today against u.s. military presence in central america, arresting an estimated 225 protesters who tried to block the entrance to the federal building
baton-wielding officers began rounding up demonstrators after police capt. william welch warned the crowd they were gathered illegally and ordered them to disperse
demonstrators hurled newspaper vending boxes and other debris into the street, trying to disrupt traffic and stay one step ahead of helmeted police
shouts of ``no contra aid'' and ``u.s., cia, out of nicaragua,'' filled the air as the demonstrators circled in front of the closed main entrance while early arrivals for work got in through another door
but the crowd quickly moved to that entrance, holding aloft a 6-foot-long sign reading, ``this building closed for renovation of morals.''
some demonstrators tried disrupting traffic, wandering in the path of cars and forcing them to swerve or stop. in one instance, a demonstrator fled, leaving behind a small yellow scooter, which an officer picked up and hurled into the gutter
most of those arrested were cited for taking part in an illegal assembly
we're not going to stop these protests because we want people to know we are seriously committed to stopping u.s. intervention in central america,'' said bill nygren, a spokesman for pledge of resistance, one of several groups sponsoring the demonstrations
on friday, about 250 people were arrested when they encircled the building and tried to stop 5,000 federal workers from entering
today's effort follows a protest through city streets saturday night by at least 5,000 people, where _ at one point _ several hundred protesters battled police for 25 minutes after a fire was lighted in the street
since thursday, 278 people have been arrested during troop deployment protests in san francisco. most of those arrested were cited for failure to disperse at an unlawful assembly, said sgt. dave ambrose
last wednesday, reagan ordered 3,200 troops, 1,100 of them fort ord near monterey, into honduras to counter the reported presence of nicaraguan soldiers in that country
an explosion ripped through a four-story apartment building in moslem west beirut on monday night, killing one man and injuring four others, police said
investigators were trying to determine the cause of the 7 p.m. blast in the low-income, predominantly sunni moslem district of tarik jedideh
some surviving tenants claim it was a gas cylinder explosion and others say it was a small bomb that went off on the staircase,'' a police captain said
the explosion wrecked the northern front of the building, but all four apartments remained intact
the dead man was identified as mohammed kurdi, 85, the landlord's father
his grandson, also named mohammed kurdi, shouted: ``it's him! it's my grandfather!'' when civil defense rescuers found the body in the debris
rescuers rushed to the scene after the explosion. all the tenants had been accounted for
in tripoli, 50 miles north of beirut, an unfinished eight-story building collapsed at daybreak, burying six construction workers, police said
one man was rescued after six hours. although rescue teams reported hearing moans beneath the wreckage, hopes were fading at nightfall that any of the other five would be found alive
it was not known why the building collapsed
the senate finance committee, flooded by complaints from farmers, fishermen and mining companies, voted monday to allow some sales of diesel fuel without the payment of tax
the relief would be financed by doubling the tax on gas-guzzling cars and closing a loophole that has allowed a handful of distilleries to dodge part of the liquor tax by watering down some of their booze
because of the drive to reduce the budget deficit, farmers and others who buy diesel for off-road use may not get their relief until oct. 1. unless some bookkeeping trick can be found quickly, they will have to pay the 15.1-cent-a-gallon tax and then apply for a refund when they file their income tax returns next year
but the prospect of delivering that message to farmers is not a happy one for lawmakers
when we go back for recess (easter week), it will be about (tax-return) filing time and it would be like us walking through a field of scorpions barefooted'' to have to tell farmers they face all that paperwork for another six months, said sen. david pryor, d-ark
with the creativity of the minds around here, perhaps we can come up with'' a solution that will make the relief available on april 1, said sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, the committee chairman
the committee is restrained by an agreement between congress and the reagan administration which requires that each dollar of tax relief be offset by a dollar of tax increase
as part of the deficit-reduction law passed last december, farmers and other off-the-road diesel users are required to pay the tax, beginning april 1, and then apply for a refund. congress found there had been a considerable amount of evasion because of the difficulty in policing so many retail outlets. the new law requires the tax be collected by wholesalers or producers
farmers accused the government of trying to balance the budget on their backs, contending there is no reason that washington should have interest-free use of their money _ an average of about $320 per farmer per year _ for as much as 12 months. similar complaints have come from timber companies, mine operators, fishermen and oil drillers
the finance committee put together this package, which is subject to approval in the senate and house:
_to allow all diesel bought for any off-road use from wholesalers to escape the tax altogether. tax-exempt buyers of off-road diesel from retailers would have to pay the tax and get a refund next year. this would cost the government $543 million through 1993
_to approve a ``taxpayer bill of rights,'' which would clamp down on what are perceived to be abuses of taxpayers by the internal revenue service. this would lose $517 million over five years, due chiefly to a drop in compliance
_to extend through june 30, 1989, the expiring authority for the irs to withhold tax refunds from people who owe student loans, farm loans and other federal debts. this would raise about $400 million
_to double the tax on new cars whose fuel efficiency does not meet federal standards, raising $375 million through 1993. in the current model year, the tax hits only expensive foreign cars, such as the $138,850 lamborghini countach, which gets 8.8 miles per gallon and is subject to a $3,850 levy, and the bmw 750, which gets 16.4 mpg and faces a $1,500 gas-guzzler tax. those taxes would rise to $7,700 and $3,000 respectively
_to limit use of a ``wine flavors credit'' under which some manufacturers of distilled spirits avoid a significant share of the $12.50-a-gallon liquor tax by mixing some products with a grape-based alcohol. this is expected to raise $360 million over five years
the committee's bill does nothing about a 1986 law, also aimed at tax evaders, that requires about 82,000 state, city and county government units to pay taxes of 9.1 cents a gallon on their gasoline and apply later for a refund. that provision took effect jan. 1
