sandinista government and contra rebel leaders today announced a suspension of military operations during the first cease-fire talks ever held inside the country
gen. humberto ortega, the nation's defense minister and brother of president daniel ortega, made the announcement that government troops were halting military operations and urged the contras to ``act in kind.''
he called the three days of peace talks that began today in this small town on the border with costa rica ``an historic encounter.''
bosco matamoros, spokesman for the contra delegation, later announced a suspension of offensive military operations in nicaragua as an ``expression of our good will.'' he also said the conversations were ``frank and of mutual respect.''
the talks began at 11:10 a.m. (12:10 p.m. est), more than an hour late. both delegations started meeting behind closed doors in the custom house on the border just outside sapoa, the only building large enough here for the event
humberto ortega is heading the nicaraguan delegation to the peace talks. alfredo cesar is the leader of the contra delegation
the sandinista delegation includes brian wilson _ an american pacifist whose legs were severed when he was hit by a train during a protest last year _ and singer kris kristofferson. wilson and kristofferson are longtime sandinista supporters
cheering sandinista supporters lined both sides of the 90-mile-long road from managua to sapoa as ortega drove by. many carried red-and-black sandinista flags, and school children waved nicaraguan blue-and-white paper banners
mariachi bands played music along the route. the crowds shouted: ``we insist on the surrender of the mercenaries,'' as the contras are called by the sandinistas
the contra delegation arrived a few minutes after the sandinistas in a bus escorted by a group of cars and jeeps. the entire town was closely guarded by sandinista troops and security agents in plainclothes
adolfo calero, another contra leader, said the contras came ``here with an open agenda, and that it includes democratization, includes amnesty. we insisted on speaking about all the problems facing nicaragua.''
the peace talks were held despite an earlier sandinista offensive along the honduran border
in a break with the past, both sides agreed that the talks would have an open agenda
but on sunday, deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco reiterated a previous sandinista position that the negotiations strictly deal with the mechanics of a cease-fire
and the contras indicated that they wanted to talk about other matters, such as democratization and free elections
the contras replaced calero, the top-ranking leader of the nicaraguan resistance, with cesar as head of their delegation in the hope that his familiarity with the sandinistas might pressure the nicaraguan government into serious negotiations
cesar was a former high-ranking sandinista official before he broke with the sandinistas in 1982
also scheduled to attend was aristides sanchez, a third member of the directorate of the resistance, the contra umbrella organization
entering today's sessions, contra leaders indicated they were not optimistic
the sandinistas don't object to making tactical concessions, but they will never enact reforms that risk their grip on power in nicaragua,'' said contra adviser gonzalo facio
cesar asserted the contras had recently suffered military setbacks, but that the sandinista offensive had helped their cause politically
rebel fighters ``are going to be militarily weakened by the suspension of united states aid and the growth in soviet aid to the sandinistas,'' cesar said
but he added that ``politically we are going to be stronger and the sandinistas weaker because the international community condemned them for their bombardments last week of our positions.''
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, the mediator in previous talks and an observer to today's discussions, also seemed pessimistic about their outcome
i see the situation as quite complicated,'' he said during his sunday homily in managua. ``it is very difficult to reconcile two things that are completely opposite.''
the cease-fire talks are called for under a central american peace plan signed by the region's five presidents last aug. 7
the sandinistas have already complied with some stipulations in the peace accord by lifting a nearly 6-year-old state of emergency and allowing more press freedom
the rebels have been fighting the government since 1981 in a conflict that has killed more than 40,000 people
howard benedict, veteran aerospace writer for the associated press, was awarded the 1987 lauren d. lyman award for distinguished achievement monday by the aviation-space writers association
benedict, who has covered the nation's space program for nearly three decades starting with the earliest space and missile shots, expressed concern at the awards luncheon about the future of america's space program
we need a space program that transcends political boundaries. it cannot be a political football or a partisan event,'' he said. ``... sadly i don't see that commitment on the horizon.''
benedict, who is the ap's correspondent at cape canaveral, fla., was cited for his lifetime of distinguished achievement as the news service's senior aerospace writer. his career included coverage of man's first steps into space, his first walk on the moon and the challenger shuttle disaster
the aviation-space writers association established the lyman award in 1972 in memory of lauren ``deac'' lyman, a pulitzer prize-winning aviation writer for the new york times. the award is sponsored by united technologies corp., for which lyman also once worked
a u.s. army transport helicopter participating in a military exercise in honduras crashed on monday, and a number of soldiers were reported injured, pentagon officials said
the officials, who requested anonymity, said the accident occurred monday afternoon near the honduran town of juticalpa and involved an american uh-1 huey transport copter
while the initial reports were fragmentary, it appeared that the copter was carrying nine soldiers and that all of them survived, the sources said
we have no reports of any fatalities,'' said one official. ``but we do have reports of some injuries and medical evacuations under way.''
the sources said the accident did not occur in or near a combat zone and did not involve hostile fire
it looks like it was mechanical,'' said one official
the accident scene was said to be located about six miles south of juticalpa. that would place it 35 miles north of the honduras-nicaragua border and about 60 miles west of the border region where nicaraguan troops were fighting contra guerrillas last week
the pentagon sources, who stressed they were awaiting more information from u.s. authorities in honduras, said it was unclear whether the nine aboard the huey were all american or whether some of the passengers might have included honduran troops
the united states airlifted more than 3,100 army troops to honduras last week in a warning to the leftist sandinista government, after nicaraguan troops moved into honduras to attack base camps of the u.s.-backed contra guerrillas
after arriving in honduras, the american soldiers dispersed around the country for joint exercises with honduran forces. one of those exercise areas is near juticalpa, and a battalion from the 82nd airborne division was sent to that site
the reagan administration has made it clear it does not intend to send the u.s. troops into combat with the sandinistas. administration sources said monday it appeared the fighting was ending in any event and that nicaragua was withdrawing its troops from honduran soil
according to the pentagon sources, the uh-1 that crashed monday was apparently assigned to u.s. forces in panama and was not airlifted to the country by the 82nd airborne
the pentagon maintains a force of about 1,100 military personnel in honduras as part of what is known as joint task force bravo to oversee training exercises in the central american country
rising to what one called a ``once-in-a-lifetime chance,'' engineers from around the world unveiled designs monday for a new williamsburg bridge from brooklyn to manhattan _ even though the old bridge may not have to be replaced
the 85-year-old span over the east river is slowly disintegrating, although officials have not decided whether to rebuild or replace it
one of the 25 designs submitted calls for a bridge with two 48-story towers topped by v-shaped structures, one holding a restaurant and one a museum
another, designed by an international consortium that includes the architect i.m. pei, feature a roadway held by two metal wishbones slightly twisted like a ribbon pulled taut and given a half turn
but the designs may never span anything but the imagination
since announcing the competition for a new bridge last year, local officials have discovered that the bridge may not be as close to collapse as was feared. although a 1985 study showed that the bridge would have to be replaced by 1995, later inspections have indicated that it might last longer
preliminary estimates indicate that the bridge could be renovated for about $250 million. estimates for a new bridge range from $200 million to $600 million
still, bridge engineers attending monday's unveiling said they could not resist the opportunity to design a major new bridge for one of the world's largest cities
such a location you'll never find again,'' said swiss engineer bruno thurlimann of zurich, who collaborated on a swiss-american proposal with i.m. pei &amp; partners and three other companies. ``it's a once-in-a-lifetime chance.''
asking why an engineer submitted a design is ``like asking sir edmund hillary, `why did you climb (mount everest)?''' said nils d. olsson of drc consultants inc
structural engineers are always looking for fresh challenges, and this is one of the most important projects since the verrazano,'' he said
olsson, whose new york firm proposed the restaurant-topped bridge, was referring to the verrazano-narrows bridge, a link completed in 1964 between brooklyn and staten island. with 4,260 feet between supports, it is one of the world's longest suspension bridge
most of the designs for the williamsburg call for a 1,600-foot cable-stayed bridge that would be the longest of its type in the world
a cable-stayed bridge has cables stretching from its towers to the roadway, while a suspension bridge has a roadway hung from cables stretching from one side to the other
the united states has sold mexico 30,000 metric tons of surplus non-fat dry milk for $1,260 per ton, about a third less than it cost american taxpayers, the agriculture department said monday
acting undersecretary richard w. goldberg said the surplus powdered milk was sold by the department's commodity credit corp. to conasupo, the mexican government's food purchasing authority
goldberg said the sale ``reflects the world market price for non-fat dry milk at the time the sale was negotiated'' with mexico. deliveries are scheduled through march 1989. in addition, the ccc provided mexico with a three-year credit arrangement at commercial rates of interest, he said
according to a recent ccc report, about 454 million pounds of non-fat dry milk were held in storage, with a value of more than $385 million, or about 85 cents per pound
there are approximately 2,205 pounds in a metric ton, which translates to a u.s. value of $1,874 per ton
the surplus was acquired by ccc through purchases of cheese, butter and non-fat dry milk to support the price of milk paid to dairy farmers
congress in 1985 farm law mandated the export sale of 150,000 tons of dairy products annually for the three fiscal years ending sept. 30, 1988. the latest deal with mexico boosted sales this year to 77,520 tons, goldberg said. court</head>
the latest squabble between prosecutors and defense attornyes isn't about cases, tactics or money. it's about being able to bypass new security procedures at the dirksen federal building, and it's headed for _ where else? _ the bench
complaints from the public have been few, but the security system brought the entire u.s. district court system here to a screeching halt one afternoon and prompted 39 attorneys _ including several of chicago's best-known defenders _ to petition the district's 21 judges for the same exemptions granted to prosecutors and building employees. a decision is expected thursday
things are bad enough when the lines stretch all the way around the (elevator) bank,'' attorney judith halprin, who is spear-heading the defenders' effort, said monday
but when they decided to give exemptions to prosecutors,'' she added, ``that was the last straw.''
replied u.s. attorney anton valukas: ``we're being given exemptions because we're employees of the building, no more, no less. ... this seems to be a means by which certain people can keep their names in the paper.''
the u.s. marshal's office said the procedures were in response to a growing number of threats against the federal judiciary nationwide and an increase in terrorism trials. they follow recent trials of members of the el rukn street gang and the puerto rican independence group, faln, on terrorism-related charges
ms. halprin's first act of defiance came march 8, the day the airport-type screening began with federal marshals using metal detectors for all people heading to courtroom floors and x-ray machines for briefcases
ms. halprin, invoking her constitutional rights against unreasonable search and seizure, refused to step through the metal detector on her way to u.s. district judge brian duff's courtroom
that was 10 a.m. ms. halprin waited in the lobby for more than two hours while her client, charged with selling phony immigration papers to an undercover agent, stood before duff
the judge issued an order exempting ms. halprin, but she remained there for another two hours because a marshal refused to disobey chief u.s. district judge john grady's original directive
duff responded by ordering chief u.s. marshal john adams to appear before him and explain why he should not be held in contempt of court
duff himself was then called to an emergency meeting of the district's judges and a new order resulted: attorneys working trials that began prior to march 8 could be exempted for the duration of that trial
but that hasn't satisfied ms. halprin and her colleagues
they're exempting whole classes of people, chicago policemen for example,'' she said. ``well one of us was representing a cop subpoenaed by a grand jury
so, the target of the investigation gets to go through untouched,'' she added, ``and the lawyer is the one subjected to a search of his person and papers
now is that silly or not?''
efforts to place deaf students in regular public schools have backfired, leaving many deaf students with an inadequate education, a government commission told a senate panel monday
the state of the art in deafness education today at all levels is unsatisfactory,'' frank r. bowe, who chaired the commission on education of the deaf, told the senate labor and human resources subcommittee on the handicapped. ``we still have high school graduates reading below a third-grade level.''
the 13-member commission, established by congress in 1986, concluded that the education department should consider placing deaf students in special schools or centers for the deaf, instead of forcing them to compete with their hearing counterparts
those of us who are deaf have had access to some form of education, but it's not been a good one, and it's not getting better,'' said bowe, a regional commissioner of the rehabilitation services administration, who also is deaf
two-thirds of the panel themselves are deaf. the commission, made up of government officials and educators of the deaf, also included actress nanette fabray macdougall
the report also recommended that a majority of the board of trustees of gallaudet university be hearing impaired, which was a demand made by students at the school for the deaf during protests earlier this month
the commission concluded that significant improvements have been made in techniques for educating the deaf since 1965, when a federal panel last suggested changes
the report also determined, however, that ``the actual implementation of these changes has been inadequate and sometimes misguided, and that progress has been at best spotty and sporadic.''
the commission found that 95 percent of america's deaf students are ``prelingually deaf'' _ left without hearing at birth or deprived of it in infancy _ and recommended improvements in identifying these children and teaching them english
early intervention programs are very important,'' said gertrude galloway, a commission member. ``right now, many children come to school at 4 or 5 with no language.''
the commission also called for expansion of post-secondary education programs, including vocational and technical training, junior college and college programs. currently, there are two colleges in the nation for deaf students, and four regional post-secondary programs housed at hearing colleges
the commission also recommended that the department of education include american sign language _ the native language to most of those born deaf _ under the bilingual education act, which would treat asl like any other foreign language. this would give deaf students access to special training programs other foreign-language students now receive
establishment of a national institute on deafness as part of the federal national insititutes of health is another priority of the commission, along with the creation of a national technical insititute for the deaf at gallaudet
the commission also instructed congress to pass legislation requiring the federal communications commission to issue rules making new televisions capable of decoding closed-caption broadcasts. until those sets are common, decoders should be distributed free, the commission said
the commission took 20 months to interview deaf education specialists, students and school administrators before coming up with the 52 recommendations included in the 144-page report
a house panel will hold hearings on the commission's study next week, and senate and house committees then will work with the department of education to establish some of the proposed changes
members of the deaf community lauded the report
the commission is on target,'' said philip bravin, an ibm executive named last week to chair gallaudet's board of trustees. ``the education of the deaf in america needs to be improved. i'm doing ok, but many of my friends and peers aren't.''
a bottle containing a note from a high school class probably languished for two years in the gulf stream before a hurricane swept it to the coast of france, a marine biology teacher said
the bottle was found by pierre maupin the day after the storm hit the brittany village of carnac in northwest france last october, said john gregory, a teacher at john i. leonard high school
it was ironic _ the guy who found it didn't show excitement,'' gregory said friday. ``he just filled out the information sheet, sent it back, and that was it.''
but students at the school, who received maupin's reply in late december, are enthusiastic about the bottle-releasing project, which is aimed at helping them learn more about ocean currents
(when) he told us what we would be doing, at first it didn't seem as exciting. but when we started getting the letters back, it seemed interesting,'' said 16-year-old anthony izzarone
since 1976, gregory's classes have released about 900 silicone-sealed bottles 30 miles off florida's gold coast into the gulf stream. so far, 104 bottles have been found in locations ranging from cape canaveral and melbourne, just up the florida coast, to the azores islands in the mid-atlantic
the high school's experiments have a return rate of 11 percent. that's much better than the national oceanic and atmospheric administration, which gets back only about 2 percent of the bottles it puts in the ocean to test currents, gregory said
environmentalists still nagged by the demise of the last known dusky seaside sparrow plan a final search of the bird's one-time habitat before writing an epitaph
a search of the area near kennedy space center had been planned for this spring, even though regional officials of the u.s. fish and wildlife service are convinced there are no more duskies
a final search will be conducted in about a year before the dusky is declared extinct, said john christian, deputy assistant regional director of the wildlife service in atlanta
state and federal officials sponsor the bird-watching expedition in which volunteers will go through area with binoculars. if no duskies are spotted, the species will be considered extinct
the last tiny dusky died of old age in june in a specially designed environment on discovery island, a walt disney world zoological park primarily for birds. the last five survivors, all males, were taken there from their only known wildlife habitat on cape canaveral several years ago
they were bred with close cousins, seeking to preserve their genes, but they died one by one
the bird's decline began in the 1940s when mosquito fighters began spraying ddt over the st. johns river refuge marshlands, ruining the duskies' eggs and insect food supply
although they were protected by law, conservationists say the birds did not have much chance against diking, drainage, land-clearing, highway construction, housing developments, mosquito-control projects and fires
we have laws protecting the species, but not the habitat,'' said john wood, a federal official. ``you can protect the species all you want, but if you don't have the habitat, they have no place to go and won't make it.''
but christian pointed out that the 5,000-acre st. johns refuge was purchased for $3 million to protect the dusky
we thought we had enough habitat to sustain them, and then the population just crashed,'' christian said. ``we will never know what biological mechanism was responsible. nobody really knows.''
charles cook, curator of discovery island and a leader in the fight to preserve the dusky genes, said he hoped that someday some of the part-duskies will be released on an experimental basis in the protected area
cook believes there is a chance one or more of the birds may exist in a remote section of the refuge
scientists always keep the option open,'' he said. ``i definitely feel it is worth looking into, particularly in a peripheral habitat not frequently visited by people.''
a commuter train on monday slammed into a truck that crashed through the railroad crossing gates, injuring at least 16 people, authorities said
the semi tractor-trailer, carrying medium-duty trucks, burst into flames upon impact, and the driver was seriously injured, authorities said
the force of the crash sent two passenger cars off the train tracks and broke the engineer's leg, authorities said
the metra commuter train, headed from joliet to chicago, was carrying 16 passengers and five crew members, and likely was traveling at about 50 mph when it hit the truck a mile west of new lenox, said metra spokesman chris knapton
as the crossing signals became activated, the driver of the tractor-trailer combination continued southbound and attempted to beat the train,'' said will county sheriff's lt. jim srygler
the truck driver smashed through railroad crossing gates. the gate came down on his hood,'' knapton said
sixteen people, including the engineer and the truck driver, were taken to silver cross hospital in joliet, a spokeswoman said. most were treated and released
the truck driver, terry lewis, 34, of drayton plains, mich., was in serious condition, said the spokeswoman
police would not immediately talk about any charges that could be filed
vice president george bush is the overwhelming favorite going into new york's april 19 primary among likely republican voters questioned for a statewide poll released monday
the marist county institute for public opinion reported that of the 292 likely republican voters sampled, 68 percent favored bush, 22 percent opted for kansas sen. bob dole nd 3 percent went for pat robertson. six percent said they were undecided and less than 1 percent picked another candidate. the margin of error was plus or minus 6 percent
the institute also reported that in theoretical matchups between bush and the major democratic candidates, the vice president came out ahead of every democrat except massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
