the former republican congressman from texas said it is not the job of the federal government to run central america like a colony
i don't want my sons murdered in another vicious and unconstitutional war. and i don't want any other american boys harmed either,'' paul said in a statement
the political damage ohio and other urban states may be doing to themselves by holding late-season presidential primaries could go beyond having fewer candidate choices, an elections researcher says
linda l.m. bennett, a political science professor at wittenberg university, says the problems of ohio's cities and others in the northeast and midwest may be ignored as candidates look past ohio's may 3 primary and toward the clincher _ california, which holds its primary june 7
the problem begins with the emphasis placed on the february iowa caucuses, ms. bennett says
it emphasizes all the old classic themes of american politics,'' such as the romanticized notion of farming, she said. but urban problems are getting lost in the shuffle
it would be nice if they addressed the issues of the 90 percent of us who live in urban areas,'' ms. bennett said
here are some of the recommendations made monday by the commission on education of the deaf in a congressionally ordered report:
_the u.s. department of education should put less emphasis on placing deaf students in the ``least restrictive environment'' and more on providing an appropriate education. for many, that means special schools and centers for the deaf
_the department should specify that removing a deaf child from a regular classroom does not require ``compelling evidence.''
_congress should grant full recognition to american sign language as a ``native'' language, just like spanish, under the bilingual education act and programs
_more help and services for low-achieving deaf students, not just the college bound
_congress should require the federal communications commission to force broadcasters to caption their programming, and consider the same requirement for film producers
_congress ``should caption its own televised proceedings.''
_congress should require the fcc to issue rules making new tv sets capable of decoding closed captions. until such sets become widely available, decoders should be distributed free to the deaf
_earlier identification of deaf infants. it isn't necessary to test the hearing of every newborn, just those at high risk of hearing impairments
_the u.s. department of health and human services should issue guidelines to help states improve screening procedures
_parents should have the option to choose what type of school their child attends, and must ``believe in whichever communication method is chosen for their child's educational program.''
_congress should pass a ``quality in deaf education'' bill
_changes should be made in the management of gallaudet university, including appointment of a majority of deaf people to its board of trustees
_congress should bar hearing undergraduates from gallaudet, which in 1985 began to admit a handful interested in careers in education of the deaf
_the model secondary school for the deaf at gallaudet should admit more low-achieving deaf students so that it ``more closely mirrors the national demographics of secondary school-age deaf children.''
_the government should expand its regional postsecondary education program to the southwest. it now has programs in other regions
_congress should establish a national center on deafness research at gallaudet
_congress should create a national institute on deafness and other communication disorders at the national institutes of health
_gallaudet and the national technical institute for the deaf in rochester, n.y., should limit enrollment of foreign students to 10 percent, and charge them 75 percent of the actual costs, or about $18,250 a year
_both gallaudet and ntid should do a better job of hiring the deaf. only 12 percent of the staff at ntid and 25 percent at gallaudet are deaf
the state department expressed regret monday at south africa's denial of a visa to u.s. civil rights leader joseph lowery
we believe that greater, not lesser contact between our two societies is needed,'' said state department spokesman charles redman
the south african embassy in washington gave no reason for the denial it issued over the weekend, said evelyn lowery, whose husband is president of the southern christian leadership conference
we ... have our suspicions. you know the situation in south africa, the persecution of black leaders there, and they certainly know we're in sympathy (with south africa's blacks),'' she said
kevin brennan, an embassy spokesman, confirmed lowery's application for a visa was denied. he declined to give a reason
lowery, who was in massachusetts monday lecturing at holy cross college, had planned to deliver a sermon at martin luther king jr. memorial services scheduled in south africa friday through sunday. value</head>
eligible stockholders in six financially troubled production credit associations in the omaha, neb., and spokane, wash., districts will receive par value cash or credit for their stock, the farm credit system assistance board said monday
eric p. thor, head of the board, said the compensation will go to those whose stock was either frozen or not retired at par when the associations went into liquidation
acting under the new agricultural credit act of 1987, the board ``initiated a series of agreements resulting in the issuance of preferred stock on behalf of the associations in liquidation'' to a related entity, the farm credit system financial assistance corp
the corporation will provide more than $20.5 million to retire the frozen stock, thor said. as a result, association borrowers whose stock was frozen or retired at less than par value will be able to collect par value for their stock
stockholders should receive checks or notification of credit within a few weeks, he said
the associations in liquidation in the omaha district are the o'neill and valentine production credit associations. in the spokane district, the pcas are glendive, milk river, western montana and western washington
the associations, which are cooperatively owned by the borrowers, extend loans to farmers to meet production expenses
state attorney general robert abrams said monday he will prevent representatives of tawana brawley from disrupting the grand jury hearing evidence into the black teen-ager's allegations that she was sexually attacked by six white men
the rev. al sharpton, a new york city minister advising the 16-year-old girl, has threatened to stop anyone from testifying tuesday at the grand jury hearing. sharpton said he'd risk arrest to stop the proceedings
i don't think there is a need or necessity to move the grand jury, but we would take any and all steps that are necessary to protect the integrity of the grand jury process,'' abrams said at a news conference
representatives of miss brawley have refused to cooperate with state prosecutors investigating the alleged racial and sexual attack. they have criticized suggestions that witnesses might be granted immunity in exchange for their testimony
the teen-ager's lawyers want a special prosecutor named to investigate race-related crimes, for abrams to be removed from the case and for a new grand jury to be convened outside of dutchess county
abrams also said he was appalled at the telecast of photos of miss brawley shortly after her alleged november attack by a group of white men and is investigating how a television station got the pictures
he said no one in his office authorized the release of the photos, which were shown thursday night on wnbc in new york city and nationally on the nbc's network news
i was indeed quite upset,'' abrams said, adding ``it's a serious invasion of the privacy of the victim.''
one of the photos shows the word ``nigger'' scrawled on miss brawley's stomach and another shows her lying in her hospital bed with monitoring devices attached to her upper torso
mary lou o'callaghan, director of news information for nbc, said the network would not reveal the source of the photos. ``we covered what has become a significant news story,'' she said in defense of the telecast
abrams said he was confident that no one in the attorney general's task force released the photos. other law enforcement agencies that investigated the case might have given the photos away, he said
the pentagon has quietly increased the number of security personnel in panama, dispatching more than 300 soldiers to the strife-torn country in the past three days, officials said monday
two-thirds of those dispatched during the latest troop movement were members of the 503rd military police battalion, which is headquartered at fort bragg, n.c., the pentagon said
the remainder were dispatched from fort eustis, va., and fort hood, texas
capt. nancy laluntas, a pentagon spokeswoman, said in response to a query that ``212 members of the 503rd military police battalion have deployed to panama to augment u.s. security forces in that country.''
this deployment of military police is not in response to any incident, but simply good planning in view of the current unrest in panama,'' she continued
the deployment began last friday ``and is a prudent measure, consistent with the panama canal treaty, to further safeguard the canal and u.s. lives, property and interests in the area,'' she said
in addition to the mps, about 100 soldiers from forts eustis and hood were dispatched ``to assist in the movement of these additional security force personnel and to augment u.s. southern command security forces,'' she added
those soldiers are ``army airfield movements control personnel,'' the spokeswoman said
the latest dispatch of troops comes less than a week after the pentagon ordered slightly more than 100 marine and air force security personnel to panama to bolster security around the panama canal and nearby military bases
all told, about 420 security personnel have now been sent to panama to join the roughly 600 servicemen who already were assigned to security duties with the u.s. southern command, which is headquartered there
the southern command, which oversees all u.s. military operations in the region, has about 10,000 servicemen assigned to it
the pentagon's security concerns stem from the administration's efforts to unseat panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
although no moves have been reported against american servicemen or their dependents, defense officials are said to be concerned that noriega might lash back at the united states by attacking or sabotaging facilities there
backers of a drive to oust mayor federico pena say they expect to collect 50,000 signatures, 10,000 more than necessary to force a new election, by the april 13 deadline
i think we're going to be in real good shape,'' said marge doty, whose metropolitan action committee is heading the recall effort. she said the names would be counted wednesday
just because marge says it, doesn't mean it's true,'' said former denver election commissioner susan duncan, leader of a group fighting the recall
recall organizers must prove at least 39,091 signatures are of registered voters in order to force a new election. the ballot would include pena and all candidates who collected 300 valid nominating signatures
the recall drive against pena, now in his second term, is rooted in the public works department, where employees began gathering after last summer's mayoral election to air their grievances
by fall, the workers, who complained pena is a poor manager, had hired doty, retired director of admissions at denver general hospital
basically, we're guiding ourselves by intuition,'' doty said in an interview last week. ``the political expertise is coming from the seat of my pants.''
the petition drive was launched jan. 15 amid criticism of pena's snow-removal efforts after a christmas weekend snowstorm left unplowed, impassable streets. the effort was fueled by television reports last month that street crews, who were followed and secretly filmed, were loafing on duty
but even if enough valid signatures are collected, it could be months before an election is held
after april 13, pena will have 10 days to challenge signatures, and the election commission will have 50 days to conduct hearings on the mayor's appeal
if there are enough valid signatures, the city council will have to schedule an election within 60 to 90 days
pena would be reimbursed by the city for any legal challenge to the petitions. if he won the recall election, the state would reimburse him for campaign expenses
exporters have sold china an additional 200,000 metric tons of u.s. wheat at subsidized prices, the agriculture department said monday
the sale, equal to 7.34 million bushels, was handled by continental grain co. and will be shipped in the 1988-89 wheat marketing year that begins on june 1
melvin e. sims, general sales manager for the department's foreign agricultural service, said the sales were part of an authorized 1.2 million tons of wheat announced feb. 5 under the export enhancement program, or eep
although no selling prices or other details were announced, recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $2.67 per bushel, indicating a u.s. farm value of about $20 million
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat
china bought more than 4 million tons of wheat under previous eep arrangements, which allow exporters to sell commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies
sims said the bonus averaged $24.45 per ton, or about 67 cents per bushel of wheat. the bonuses will be paid in the form of surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp
china has 260,000 tons remaining for use under the eep initiative announced on feb. 5, he said
actor ed flanders, making a sentimental return for the last episode of nbc's ``st. elsewhere,'' surprised fellow actors and angered producers by delivering an unscripted soliloquy on death, it was reported monday
flanders, who earlier this season left his role as dr. donald westphall, was back for a farewell to the series, which is leaving the air at the end of the season
the script taped friday called for flanders, as westphall, to make a touching statement about beginnings and endings at st. eligius hospital, otherwise known as ``st. elsewhere.'' instead, usa today reported, he talked about death as his fellow actors looked on bewildered
he spoiled the moment for everybody,'' producer tom fontana told the newspaper
executive producer bruce paltrow called flanders' speech ``a tragedy.''
fontana and paltrow declined to talk about the incident monday, but larry bloustein, a spokesman for mtm enterprises, which produces the show, said they confirmed the accuracy of the report
there was no immediate word on what the producers would do, although there was talk of refilming it with dr. mark craig, played by william daniels, reading the lines
aids has meant isolation and poverty for a family of four, two with aids and two exposed to the fatal disease, said the father
the parents, who agreed to be interviewed by the tampa tribune if their identities were protected, lost their jobs and were forced to seek government assistance. their two cars were repossessed and furniture sold to pay debts and buy food, said the couple, who are in their 30s
the woman said she confided in a friend at work, who told the boss. she and her husband, who worked in the entertainment field, were fired, she said
we were rejected by almost everyone we knew, everyone we worked with,'' he said
the couple said they filed a discrimination complaint with the florida commission on human relations but dropped the case after an investigator told them that fighting their ex-employer would expose the family to a traumatic public argument, possibily involving their children
the father said he was infected with the aids virus through a sexual encounter with another man years ago, the tribune reported monday
unknowingly carrying the virus, he married in 1980 and two years later fathered a son. he was healthy, he said, except for a nagging cough and a shortness of breath one doctor attributed to asthma
then, early last year, while his wife was pregnant with their second child, he learned he had acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the newspaper reported
worse, he learned his 6-year-old son has aids. his wife is being treated for aids-related complex, a less-severe condition associated with the aids virus
and their 7-month-old son has tested positive for aids antibodies, but doctors don't know if he will develop the disease
a couple of months ago, the father said, ``i was ready to die.'' but his outlook changed, he said, mainly because of an aids support group and the realization that his family needed him
before you die of aids,'' he said, ``you have to live with it.''
today, the family primarily lives on social security disability payments. medical costs average more than $1,100 a month, and they must pay $251 before medicaid's catastrophic health-care plan picks up the rest
when you look at it from the financial point of view, it looks pretty bleak,'' he said. ``so we don't look at it that way.''
a man who held his ex-wife and two sons hostage in a deadly burst of violence at his trailer home had been jailed recently for a similar, less violent episode, authorities said monday
police said jerry staggs, 40, shot one man to death outside the trailer sunday morning and, after holding his children and ex-wife hostage for eight hours, shot himself in the head sunday night. staggs died monday morning
sheriff joe patterson said staggs, who worked for the city's maintenance department, had been taken into custody earlier this month and accused of abducting sherry staggs, 27, who had been married to him for 11 years
the sheriff said officers ``tried to get the mental health center to talk with him when we had him in jail for kidnapping his ex-wife ... but they wouldn't talk to him.''
gary porier, county mental health center director, said he had ``no direct knowledge'' of the sheriff's request. ``we always go to any law enforcement emergency call if they ask us,'' he said
there were no reports of any injuries in the earlier incident
but on sunday morning staggs killed don pressnell, 41, as he drove up with mrs. staggs and her brother, eddie hamilton, 28
hamilton said the staggs' marriage legally ended march 16 with mrs. staggs getting custody of their 9-year-old son, michael. hamilton said she was going to take the boy on an outing when staggs became irritated at seeing pressnell and pulled a gun
he shot him (pressnell) once in the head and then started shooting at me,'' said hamilton. ``he emptied that gun but he missed me. i threw a cup of coffee on him and he pulled another gun out of his pocket and pointed it at sherry's head and made her and michael go back inside.''
scotty staggs, his 15-year-old son from an earlier marriage, also was at the home and held hostage
about 25 law enforcement officers surrounded the trailer and evacuated residents of other mobile homes in the trailer park. staggs used his 15-year-old son to communicate with police. the boy told officers ``we'll all be dead'' if authorities tried to enter the trailer. ``my daddy's word is worth gold.''
about 6 p.m., the 9-year-old was released and about a half-hour later, the 15-year-old was freed. then a shot rang out and mrs. staggs fled the trailer. she said staggs had shot himself in the head
