about 50 people gathered outside the headquarters of the department of health and human services on monday to protest the use of animals in medical research
the hour-long peaceful protest featured speeches by several participants and the arrest of about a dozen demonstrators when they attempted to block the entrance to the building
the demonstration was organized by a california-based group, ``in defense of animals.'' `department spokesman ... rightist victory' with 2 to update with lugar comment, details; corrects spelling to d'aubuisson, lower-case d', throughout</note>
rightists stunned the ruling christian democrats on monday with a landslide victory in legislative and municipal elections, weakening president jose napoleon duarte in his last year in office
voters ignored a leftist guerrilla call to boycott the elections and threats of violence and turned out in great numbers sunday to elect legislators and municipal officials from 262 towns and cities nationwide
mario samayoa, president of the central elections council, said more than 50 percent of the votes cast went to the republican nationalist alliance, known as arena
the rout included the election of arena candidate armando calderon sol, a 39-year-old lawyer, as mayor of san salvador in a race against alejandro duarte, son of duarte
the defeat in the capital, home to 1.5 million of the country's 5 million people, was especially bitter because the christian democrats had held the post since 1964
final results of the nationwide races were not expected before tuesday night
the guerrillas rejected the elections as illegitimate, contending they could not be free and fair in wartime
samayoa said monday that more than 70 percent of the 1.6 million registered voters cast ballots
we knew they (the guerrillas) would not be able to daunt the people, to intimidate them,'' he said
samayoa's announcement of a majority for arena meant the triumph was even greater than the rightists had originally predicted, increasing their membership in 60-seat national assembly from 13 to at least 30
such a tally would guarantee arena control of the legislature because two small rightist parties supportive of arena are assured of at least one seat apiece
local media projections gave arena between 33 and 35 seats. the christian democrats entered the race with 33 seats
the upset by arena drastically altered prospects for duarte, one of the staunchest u.s. allies in central america, in his final year as president. it raised big questions about el salvador will proceed in its fight against an 8-year-old guerrilla insurgency and how it will deal with staggering problems of underdevelopment aggravated by the conflict
arena, formed in 1981, is fiercely nationalistic. its founder, retired army maj. roberto d'aubuisson, has blasted the united states and is considered the boss of early 1980s death-squads
former u.s. ambassador to el salvador robert white once described d'aubuisson _ who retained his legislative seat in sunday's vote _ as ``a pathological killer.''
d'aubuisson has rejected such charges, as well as the term ``death squads.'' he says citizens were obliged to defend themselves against leftist ``terrorists.''
the party's president, alfredo cristiani, a coffee-grower and businessman who was educated at georgetown university, has been trying to project an image of moderation for the past two years. cristiani also retained his seat in the legislature
el salvador needs support and would probably be in difficult problems if the u.s. would not provide support,'' he told the associated press in an interview sunday
washington sent el salvador almost $600 million in military and economic aid last year, tops in the western hemisphere
in washington, the state department hailed el salvador's national elections and called them a strong victory for the democratic process
sen. richard lugar, an indiana repblican who led an observer team named by president reagan, called the election honest and important ``because power transferred peacefully'' and ``the rebels didn't win.''
state department spokesman charles redman was asked whether the united states had reservations about the rightist victory
our basic policy is that we don't choose sides in these kinds of elections,'' redman said
arena benefited from a huge groundswell of popular discontent with the christian democrats. duarte defeated d'aubuisson for the presidency in 1984 on a platform that promised to end the war and improve the average salvadoran's lot
but the war continues, unemployment is estimated at 40 percent and inflation is about 40 percent annually
cristiani said sunday night his party would not present what he termed ``a systematic and capricious opposition'' to duarte in the new assembly
we are not going to make war on duarte,'' he added, apparently trying to dispel speculation that arena would do everything possible to make the christian democrats' life impossible with an eye to winning the 1989 presidential election
cristiani said he and his party would try to reach agreement on fundamental points, including how to wage the war, with all parties represented in the legislature
if the guerrillas do not accept the proposal we will make them, which will be the result of a national consensus, they do not leave any other way out but a military solution,'' he said. new grafs 2-3</note>
republican presidential contender bob dole, trailing george bush in wisconsin as well as nationally, challenged bush anew to a debate on monday and won applause from a farm crowd for his proposal to freeze most federal spending
later, in eau claire, dole called for stiffer penalties for drug dealers, including capital punishment
if that person is tried and convicted and found guilty, i can't think of any penalty that's severe enough _ including the death penalty,'' dole said. ``we've got to set an example. we've got to stop it. we're not going to do it by just a slap on the wrist.''
vern peterson, acting mayor of amery, a farm community in northwestwern wisconsin, said during dole's appearance that he would send a debate invitation to bush this week ``and of course you, mr. dole, are invited.''
i'll be here. in fact, maybe i'll just stay here,'' said dole, who has unsuccessfully pressed bush for a one-on-one debate for weeks
bush is far ahead of dole in the race for the republican nomination. and a poll published sunday in the milwaukee journal showed the vice president leading dole by nearly 3-to-1 among wisconsin voters likely to vote in wisconsin's april 5 primary
dole's remarks about his proposed spending freeze drew cheers from more than 900 farmers who packed a small barn to hear him speak during farm city days
dole said his deficit-reduction plan would allow ``no exceptions, except some things for low-income americans.''
that one-year freeze will save $150 billion over three years, no taxes, no gimmicks, no phony accounting, just $150 billion in real savings,'' dole said
he said the freeze would give him time to negotiate a budget deficit reduction plan that would provide a lasting solution to the problem of rising federal red ink
on another topic, in an interview after he toured the festival grounds, dole said he thought a newly proposed aid plan for nicaragua's contra rebels could pass the senate if brought to a vote, ``but the big question is whether it can be brought to a vote in the senate.''
dole said that although wisconsin gov. tommy g. thompson has endorsed bush, the republican governor is a good example of a lawmaker who makes a good executive
my opponent says bob dole is a good opponent but he doesn't have any executive experience. governor thompson had 20 years of experience in the legislature and now he's governor and he's doing a good job of saving you money because he can go back and deal with the legislators he knows,'' dole said. ``i can do the same.''
the palestine liberation organization on monday defied a u.s. order to shut down its u.n. observer mission and washington prepared to take legal action to close it
the general assembly, meeting in its second emergency session on the dispute, was expected to urge washington to desist from its efforts to close the mission
diplomats said the assembly also would request u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar to take legal action if necessary to protect the plo mission and provide alternative accommodations to its members on u.n. international territory
the 1987 anti-terrorist act passed by congress went into effect monday. it requires the government to close the plo mission, whose offices are in a townhouse in new york city
zehdi labib terzi, the plo's permanent representative to the u.n., said he would not voluntarily close the 13-year-old mission near park avenue as ordered by attorney general edwin meese iii
once we see what the u.s. government does, then we will respond,'' terzi said
in washington, justice department spokesman mark sheehan said in a telephone interview that the government probably would file suit tuesday in u.s. district court in new york city seeking a court order to close the mission
we will lay out our belief that continued operation of the plo u.n. observer mission is in violation of the law passed by congress and ask the court to agree and issue an order directing him (terzi) to close down,'' sheehan said
he said he did not expect an immediate ruling by the court, and the plo probably would have at least 20 days to file a response to the civil suit
in a message to terzi on march 11, meese said if the mission was not closed voluntarily by march 21, the plo would be in violation of the law and a suit would be filed
a source at the united states' u.n. mission, speaking on condition of anonymity, said if a court rules against the plo, the government might try to render the plo mission ineffective by turning off electricity and water
plo officials have said repeatedly the dispute is between the united states and the united nations, not between washington and the plo
the united nations and the plo say the 1987 anti-terrorist act violates the 1947 u.n. headquarters treaty, by which the united states agreed to allow all u.n. missions to operate
the plo was granted observer status by the 159-member world body, which considers the organization the only legitimate representative of the palestinian people. the plo participates in u.n. debates on the middle east but does not have the right to vote
former u.s. attorney general ramsey clark, the plo's legal counsel, has said that if the united states sues to close the plo mission, he would seek to have the complaint dismissed on grounds the united states lacks jurisdiction
an 11-year-old boy played with a loaded anti-tank weapon for a day and a half, thinking it was a toy bazooka, but never figured out how to fire the rocket, authorities said monday
weapons experts detonated the 66mm armor-piercing rocket round on sunday at a local gun club after the boy's father alerted police
the vietnam war-era weapon has a range of more than 1,000 yards and the projectile can pierce more than 6 inches of steel, officials said
had dennis grigg, fired the weapon, it could have exploded in his face because the propellant in the projectile had leaked out, said chief deputy chris kratzer of the sangamon county sheriff's department
but the boy never figured out how to operate the weapon
investigators tried to unravel conflicting accounts about how the boy obtained the weapon, while the army attempted to find out where the device came from by tracing the control numbers on the launcher and projectile, kratzer said
the boy's father, david grigg, said he was working on a car sunday afternoon when he saw his son pointing the weapon at him. grigg looked down the barrel, saw something inside and called the sheriff's office
the boy told police that he got the weapon from a friend who found it in his father's pickup truck, but the man mentioned by the boy denied involvement, kratzer said. confusion</head>
party officials and even jesse jackson's campaign staff were at a loss monday to explain why he beat michael dukakis, albert gore, jr. and other rivals in a primary-day democratic straw poll
among the republicans, vice president george bush prevailed in his party's primary sunday in an atmosphere of confusion in which most polling stations did not have ballots and few republicans voted. bush garnered all 14 national convention delegates
you all stood in there and got the job done,'' bush told supporters in a telephone call monday from air force two as he traveled between campaign stops in the northeast
i have no idea'' why jackson won, said miguel hernandez agosto, a leader of the popular democratic party slate of delegates who will travel to the july presidential nominating convention in atlanta
jackson never visited this island 1,000 miles southeast of florida, and never allowed himself to be pinned down on its main political interest _ should puerto rico remain a u.s. commonwealth or become the 51st state
asked why he thought jackson won, press aide tom schade said in a telephone interview from jackson's headquarters in chicago, ``i don't have an answer for that.''
jackson's victory may or may not help him at the democratic national convention. puerto rico's 56-member delegation is going uncommitted, as hernandez agosto and gov. raphael henandez colon stressed after sunday's balloting
the straw poll was ``merely an expression of affection and good wishes for the candidates,'' hernandez agosto said monday. ``it does not commit the delegates in any way. each member of the delegation is aware of that.''
gov. hernandez colon said, ``at this time, we have not made a decision on which u.s. presidential candidate we are going to support.''
the latest unofficial results showed that with 1,494 of 1,650 precincts reporting, or 91 percent, jackson had 87,757 votes, or 32 percent, to 70,733 votes, or 26 percent, for dukakis, and 57,639 votes, or 21 percent, for illinois sen. paul simon
simon made one campaign trip here, as did dukakis. the massachusetts governor also sent a videotaped speech to pdp delegates, in spanish, noting he honeymooned in puerto rico
among other democrats, tennessee sen. gore finished fourth with 45,361 votes, or 17 percent, missouri rep. richard gephardt, fifth with 9,159 votes, or 3 percent, and lyndon larouche last with 3,753 votes, or 1 percent
bush swamped kansas sen. bob dole, 1,935 votes to 48, or 98 percent to 2 percent, according to the latest unofficial results with 582 of 1,650 stations reporting, apparently just 35 percent
dole backers tried up to the last to call off the primary and allocate the 14 gop delegates by caucus
on sunday, gop ballots and election material sat unused in trucks because no one came to distribute them to precinct stations. local party chairman luis ferre, expecting a very low turnout, approved a plan sunday morning whereby 1,650 polling stations were consolidated to 104
the state election commission, which conducted the election, was not consulted about the maneuver and on monday was unsure how to tally republican votes. the consolidation might mean that bush's 1,935 votes represent much more than 35 percent of all gop votes cast
dole had no following here,'' ferre said. ``his supporters tried to stop the primary'' because they knew that otherwise, dole had no chance of defeating bush
on the democratic side, 33 delegates were selected. those 33 will choose 18 more. the remaining five seats in the delegation automatically go to party officials such as gov. hernandez colon
the main issue was not simon's advocacy of statehood for this caribbean island of 3.5 million, or gore's defense of tax breaks that generate jobs here, or dukakis' position that federal minimum wage laws be applied here. the main issue was control of the local democratic party
the party currently is split exactly in half _ the popular democratic party of gov. hernandez colon and the rival new progressive party of ex-gov. carlos romero barcelo each has its own chairman, vice chairman and national committeeman and committeewoman
the entire 33-member pdp delegate slate won sunday, 373,950 to 297,408, giving hernandez colon an island-wide base to press for federal patronage, legislation and the political status quo whereby puerto ricans are u.s. citizens with almost every right and obligation except they cannot vote for president and pay no federal taxes
the npp favors statehood for puerto rico
democratic presidential contender jesse jackson pledged monday to bring an end to apartheid in south africa if elected
jackson, speaking at a denver high school, was asked whether he supported a protest by university of colorado students against the university's investment with a company that has south africa holdings
i support the ambition of those students,'' said jackson. ``a university must maintain a moral integrity and should not invest'' in south africa
broadening his statements to include u.s. policy toward south africa, jackson said, ``it doesn't make much sense to mine harbors in nicaragua and send troops to honduras in the name of open and free elections and then say nothing when south africa locks up labor leaders and kills innocent men, women and children.''
the integrity of our nation is at stake,'' he said
jackson said pressure and sanctions by the united states and its allies could end apartheid
the sure way to end apartheid in south africa is to elect jesse jackson president,'' he said
jackson, who has made anti-drug comments a part of most campaign appearances, exhorted the students at george washington high school to stay away from drugs
he also urged the students to participate in colorado's precinct caucuses april 4, noting that they coincide with the 20th anniversary of martin luther king jr.'s assassination
since gary hart is not in the race, let me be colorado's favorite son,'' said jackson, who later met briefly with hart at stapleton international airport. hart withdrew from the presidential race for the second time march 11
i have appealed to him (hart) for help in our campaign to give assistance in the direction of policy development, and he will help do so,'' jackson told reporters after meeting with hart
hart said this did not mean he was endorsing jackson. ``direct endorsements are old-fashioned,'' he said. ``i can't deliver any votes to jesse.''
but he said he was willing to work with jackson _ or any democratic candidate _ on policy matters
i think the best assistance i can give him or any other candidate for president is in the area of policies,'' said hart. ``i want to work very closely with jesse and his people to help him develop a policy to govern this country.'' background, that actress undecided about presidential candidate, convention focused on local races.</head>
former ``falcon crest'' siren morgan fairchild is making another name for herself in the muddy waters of democratic politics
not content to just raise funds for democratic causes and candidates, ms. fairchild took on a new role as a delegate at the state party convention over the weekend
if you're an actor who has made up your mind about a presidential candidate, you're asked to go to iowa, go on national television and tell everybody why you support the candidate,'' she said. ``so if you are seriously involved, you have to be willing to make that commitment and know what you're talking about.''
but the blond, blue-eyed femme fatale is hardly ready to run for office herself
it's the last thing i would think of,'' she said. ``my contribution right now is in trying to raise funds. people don't need me to give a speech.''
miss fairchild is undecided on which presidential candidate to support, said one of her publicists, rachel vizcarra. ``she just hasn't made up her mind yet.''
