a u.s. military helicopter crashed monday during a training exercise near the honduran town of juticalpa and all 10 american soldiers aboard were injured, u.s. officials reported
maj. gary hovatter, spokesman for the american forces sent to honduras last week, said the uh-1 huey helicopter went down at about 1 p.m. est and he called the crash an accident
in washington, pentagon spokesman lt. cmdr. mel sundin said there were 10 people aboard the helicopter, not nine as previously thought. their injuries did not appear to be serious
all are in good to excellent condition,'' sundin said. he added that those aboard the chopper were american soldiers, but did not have further details
capt. nancy laluntas, a pentagon spokeswoman, said earlier that there were no reports of fatalities. she said other helicopters evacuated the victims for medical treatment but it was not clear where they were taken
one pentagon official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the cause of the crash appeared to be mechanical
hovatter said the helicopter was taking part in an exercise called ``golden pheasant,'' which was launched after 3,200 u.s. soldiers arrived in honduras last week
president reagan sent the troops as a warning to nicaragua after u.s. and honduran officials said nicaraguan soldiers crossed into honduras to attack base camps of u.s.-backed nicaraguan rebels
neither hovatter nor laluntas gave further information on the injured soldiers because the victims' relatives had not yet been notified
the officers said the helicopter crashed about six miles south of juticalpa. the area is 35 miles north of the honduras-nicaragua border and about 60 miles west of the region where nicaraguan troops battled the rebels last week
the troops sent to honduras were from the 82d airborne division based at fort bragg, n.c., and the 7th light infantry from fort ord, calif
all aboard the helicopter were from the 82nd airborne, chip barkley, a spokesman with the american embassy in tegucigalpa, told raleigh radio station wptf-am
but pentagon sources said the helicopter that crashed apparently was assigned to u.s. forces in panama and was not airlifted to honduras by the airborne division
the reagan administration has said the troops were not sent to combat against nicaragua's sandinista army. administration sources said monday it appeared the fighting was ending and the sandinistas were withdrawing from honduran territory
the pentagon maintains a force of about 1,100 military personnel in honduras as part of joint task force bravo to oversee training exercises in the central american country
the uh-1 helicopter is a single-engine transport craft
deceptive marketing by bell of pennsylvania results in many customers paying for optional telephone services they don't want or need, state officials charged monday
in a joint announcement, attorney general leroy zimmerman and consumer advocate david barasch said bell has been engaged in a longstanding sales practice that misleads customers about service options. in some cases, they said, lower-income residents were saddled with costly extras
the attorney general and consumer advocate filed separate but related legal actions to restrain bell from using the allegedly illegal marketing practices, to make refunds to customers and to pay civil penalties
in many cases, bell representatives assign services such as call waiting and wire maintenance plans without ever telling the consumer that the services are optional,'' zimmerman said during a news conference
bell, the state's largest telephone company, said the allegations were unjustified and ``an affront'' to its employees
regis f. filtz, bell vice president and chief operating officer, said company representatives often spend a half-hour or an hour with customers to ensure they make informed choices
certainly we sell. but we have no interest in overselling, or selling services by misleading customers as to the cost, value or benefits of our services,'' filtz said
bell serves about 3.7 million customers, representing about 80 percent of the state's telephone lines
barasch said consumers have spent about $176 million on bell's optional services since 1984. but he was unable to determine how many customers may have been mislead about the charges. optional services include touch-tone service, call forwarding, call waiting, three-way calling and speed calling
the allegations were based on 32 test calls made to bell representatives by agents posing as customers
in one test call, an agent identifying herself as a single mother living on welfare was assigned a package of services costing $28.55 monthly, when basic phone service could be obtained for $6.65 per month, officials said
of the callers, more than 70 percent were assigned up to three optional services they had not requested or were not told were optional, officials said. three-quarters of the callers were assigned touch-tone service without requesting it or without being told it was optional, they said
in a complaint filed with the public utility commission, barasch labeled the sales practices ``unlawful, unfair and deceptive.'' besides the penalties and refunds, barasch also asks the commission to force the company to set up new procedures for initiating and re-establishing service
zimmerman, in a suit filed in commonwealth court, asks that the company be assessed civil penalties for violating consumer-protection laws
barasch estimated the company would have to pay ``many millions of dollars'' in refunds and fines. wide-ranging talks</head> meeting. picks up 4th graf pvs bgng: a treaty ...; should stand for ams</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz opened wide-ranging talks monday in which he intends to confront visiting soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze about massive soviet arms shipments to central america
they met for 90 minutes to set their agenda for the next two days. also, shevardnadze told reporters, he had ``a very general review of the international situation'' with shultz
the dispute over central america appeared unlikely to spoil progress in efforts to reduce u.s. and soviet nuclear arms or preparations for the next superpower summit meeting in moscow
shevardnadze was expected to offer a late-may summit date and to have it accepted by president reagan after they meet wednesday at the white house
the soviet foreign minister called his first session with shultz ``organizational.'' asked if a date for the summit would be set during his visit, shevardnadze said, ``i think so.''
a treaty to slash u.s. and soviet armories of long-range nuclear arms by 30 percent to 50 percent is the projected centerpiece of reagan's fourth meeting with general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev
while shultz said sunday the agreement was not yet ``in the bag,'' u.s. and soviet experts will try to square drafts of their treaty proposals during shevardnadze's three-day visit
but the wars in nicaragua and afghanistan cast a cloud on the pre-summit preprarations
assistant secretary of state rozanne l. ridgway and state department spokesman charles e. redman accused moscow of an unceasing supply of weapons to the leftist government in nicaragua
apparently referring also to the reported supply of soviet rifles and other arms to embattled panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega from cuba, ms. ridgway said: ``what we need now is an end to the continued soviet provision of these high levels of military equipment.''
redman, meanwhile, accused the soviets of shipping more than 3,000 tons of equipment to nicaragua in january and february alone
for a number of years, the soviets have supplied nicaragua with $500 million to $600 million in assistance annually, he said. ``i certainly don't see it as an issue heating up,'' redman said, but soviet military support is a ``continuing cause for concern.''
in afghanistan, meanwhile, the united states has been arming rebels fighting a marxist government backed by an estimated 120,000 soviet troops and weapons
the united states is demanding the soviets withdraw the troops and also end the aid. negotiations between afghanistan and pakistan reached an impasse last week, but shultz evidently was not prepared to seek a compromise solution with shevardnadze
they're the ones who got into afghanistan and the ones who have to figure out how they are going to get out,'' ms. ridgway said
reagan, at a white house ceremony to sign an afghanistan day proclamation approved by congress, said:
we may be approaching an historic moment. we all hope that what we hear from moscow means there will be a complete and irreversible withdrawal of all the soviet forces from afghanistan, that the afghan people will be able to freely determine their own future, and that the millions of refugees can return to their homes with dignity.''
shultz's first session with shevardnadze dealt primarily with setting an agenda for their talks on tuesday and wednesday. they will take up four main issues: arms control, human rights, regional disputes and u.s.-soviet relations generally
that is the traditional lineup for what has become monthly meetings between shultz and shevardnadze, alternating between washington and moscow
but in a novel break with tradition, instead of scheduling a formal dinner tuesday night, shultz arranged a buffet at the state department _ simultaneously with the showing in the ben franklin reception room of the movie, ``that's entertainment.''
and tuesday morning, a new ``risk-reduction'' center will be opened at the state department to provide quicker communication between the two capitals in order to avoid accidental nuclear war
a formal agreement was signed here last september. a center is being established in moscow, as well
satellite links will transmit information between the two capitals, augmenting an existing telecommunications hotline
guerrillas in south lebanon made one of their biggest assaults of the year before dawn monday, attacking six positions manned by israeli-backed militiamen, a u.n. spokesman said
there was no immediate report on casualties and it was not clear which faction was involved. it was the second battle between anti-israel guerrillas and the south lebanon army reported in three days
security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the attackers fired machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades into militia positions in the central sector of israel's self-proclaimed ``security zone'' just north of the border
the mainly christian militia, which is financed by israel and acts as its surrogate, retaliated with mortars and tank cannon
timur goksel, the u.n. spokesman, said several positions manned by irish troops of the u.n. peacekeeping force were caught in the crossfire but reported no casualties
there was very heavy shooting in the area,'' he said. ``seven irish battalion posts were caught in the crossfire.''
sources said israeli soldiers rushed to the militia's aid in qantara, shoumariyeh, rashaf, haddata, beit yahoun and braachit, a string of villages 13 miles southeast of tyre, and opened up on the raiders with tank cannons
the fighting lasted for two hours and the attackers withdrew, the sources said, speaking privately
militiamen and israeli gunners later shelled the shiite moslem market town of nabatiyek. two lebanese women were reported wounded
monday's hostilities came two days after israeli troops and south lebanon army militiamen, led by tanks, raided guerrilla bases four miles northeast of the security zone
israeli fighter-bombers raided a palestinian guerrilla camp in the chouf mountains southeast of beirut last thursday, killing one guerrilla
a canadian-soviet research team has completed nearly a fifth of its 1,100-mile trek across the arctic with only the anticipated problems like frostbite and blisters, its spokeswoman said monday
the 13 soviet and canadian team members skied 13 miles monday, shirley smyth said by telephone from ottawa. she said the team covered 16 miles sunday, its greatest single-day distance, in minus 33 cold
using an angle-measuring device called a theodolite, which resembles a surveyor's transit, scientists are trying to find a second magnetic pole on their journey over untrodden territory
she said a canadian and soviet doctor on the 3-week-old expedition are treating team members for frostbite and blisters
team members took a two-day break last week to begin scientific tests and repair broken equipment. they also varied their steady diet of dried-meat known as pemmican with fruit, eggs and steak
they could have a bit of a picnic,'' said smyth. ``it was a break from pemmican.''
she said relations between canadians and soviets were warm and spirits high
the expedition left the severnaya zemlya archipelago, the northernmost point in the soviet union, to ski and walk to the north pole. the three-month journey will end in canada at cape columbia on ellesmere island
lawmen along the texas coast braced for another wave of tourists monday after a wild weekend that included a riot, four stabbings and two drownings
hundreds of sailors will flood the coast near galveston this week when their ships dock, navy officials said as law officers in the surrounding areas made plans to bolster their forces
we're going to have to have more law enforcement,'' said j.p. luby, a county commissioner whose district includes nearly 20 miles of public beaches
we want the spring breakers to have a good time, but things should be worked out so that we have a better understanding of the problems,'' he said
over the weekend, eight spring break revelers were arrested following a late-night riot, four stabbings and several drunken driving incidents. two san antonio men were killed when their car crashed through a flashing barrier and plunged off a ferry dock, sinking in 20 to 25 feet of water
we had 35 units patrolling the area of port aransas and the padre island national seashore. but at night, there are not as many to go around,'' luby said. ``the department of public safety had 18 officers out and that wasn't enough.''
luby said he and constables, police and emergency workers met two weeks ago to prepare for the onslaught of college students converging on corpus christi-area beaches
but no one was prepared for the fracas that erupted saturday night on nearby mustang island, he said
the melee erupted shortly before midnight when a motorist struck a 16-year-old girl on the beach and then attempted to leave, said police chief don perkins. angry youths began to attack the driver, but he was pulled away by police
the mob tipped over his car, smashed in the windows and set it and a nearby portable toilet afire, police said
police estimated there were 3,000 rioters and about 100 officers on hand. officials used tear gas and helicopters with search lights to quell the uproar
two law enforcement officers were injured in the melee. four people were stabbed in unrelated attacks, police said
the real problem is we have 21{ miles of beach in nueces county and port aransas has 3 miles and everyone congregates in an area of about 1{ to 2 miles of beach,'' luby said. ``you've got too many people in a small area.''
authorities said it was calm along the beach monday
still, there is one more weekend of large crowds expected for spring break before the easter weekend, when more tourists are expected
in galveston, 230 miles to the northeast of here, officials say 1,650 sailors from the uss lexington and two other navy ships will be mixing with the students
navy spokesman lt. jim fallon in dallas said the training vessel uss lexington, the submarine rescue platform ship uss petrel and a research submarine will be berthed at galveston on tuesday through friday
many of the sailors who serve aboard the ships will get shore leave during the visit, he said. he estimated about 1,000 sailors will be off the ships at one time
the world bank is asking its 151 member governments for an additional $2.24 billion in cash, including $420 million from the united states, in order to raise lending to poor countries, the bank's president said monday
the bank now lends about $14 billion a year at current rates of interest, though for much longer periods than commercial banks usually do. it lends an additional $3 billion annually on even easier terms to the poorest countries
the new cash represents 3 percent of the bank's recently announced $74.8 billion increase in capital, which has been approved by the member governments. the rest of the money would be on call in case the bank fell short of funds. but it has never had to use any of its ``on call'' money in more than 40 years of operations
the united states is being asked for the biggest single share of the new capital increase: $14 billion, of which $420 million would be in cash and the rest on call. because the cash would be spread out over five or six years, the administration is now asking congress for a first $70 million
but as a former congressman who well remembers senator everett dirksen`s description of the appropriations process as `a billion dollars here, a billion dollars there, and pretty soon you're talking about real money,' i do not expect or want automatic approval of this capital increase,'' said bank president, barber b. conable, a former republican congressman from new york
conable said that as needs have grown in the third world, resources to meet them have not kept pace
he noted that in the previous five years there had been a flow of $65 billion from the industrial countries to the poor ones
the reversal amounts to a crisis for development, one that puts a duty on the world bank to be even more vigorous as an honest broker between rich and poor...,'' he said
conable's speech was prepared for delivery in san francisco to the world affairs council of northern california. copies were distributed to reporters by the bank's headquarters in washington. publicist says</head>
