the 84-year-old comedian ``does not have cancer,'' said spokesman jim mahoney after the surgery
hope was operated on at the usc kenneth norris jr. cancer hospital, but mahoney explained that hope was at the facility because he had been referred to dr. donald g. skinner, chief of urology at usc who performs his operations at the cancer hospital
skinner said hope was in ``excellent'' condition after the operation
mahoney said the comedian is expected to be hospitalized for three or four days. the operation was scheduled in advance, not emergency surgery, he said
last week, the comedian was one of the presenters at the writers guild of america awards at the beverly hilton hotel. he chatted with reporters and photographers there, but didn't mention the surgery
mahoney said the operation, common for older men, was similar to a procedure performed on president reagan in january 1987. the surgeon removed fibrous tissue filling the prostate, using small instruments and working through a catheter
the 3,200 u.s. troops rushed here after an alleged incursion by nicaraguan troops will begin a set of joint maneuvers with the honduran army tuesday, a u.s. military spokesman said
maj. gary hovatter, spokesman for the american forces in honduras, made the announcement monday but refused to disclose details
the announcement came as nicaragua's sandinista government and contra rebels agreed to halt all offensive military operations during three days of talks that began monday. the negotiations are to achieve a permanent cease-fire
u.s. troops arrived in honduras last week at the request of president jose azcona hoyo and are stationed at five bases throughout honduras. the soldiers are from the 82nd airborne division based in fort bragg, n.c. and the 7th light infantry division from fort ord, calif
in an exercise monday, a u.s. helicopter crashed near a base in the southern town of juticalpa with 10 people aboard. hovatter said there were injuries but would not give further information until relatives are notified. pentagon spokesmen in washington said there were no fatalities and that the injuries did not appear serious
some of the u.s. soldiers are based at jamastran, about 20 miles from the nicaraguan border, but 80 miles from the site of the alleged nicaraguan incursion at the bocay region in the honduran province of olancho. the bocay area straddles the nicaraguan-honduran border
others are at tamara and at san lorenzo in southern honduras, and a corps of about 200 soldiers remained at american military headquarters at the honduran air force base of palmerola, about 45 miles northwest of tegucigalpa
president reagan dispatched the troops both as a show of support for honduras and as a warning to nicaragua against further action in the area
president daniel ortega of nicaragua repeatedly has denied his country's troops were inside honduras. the contras maintain supply and staging camps in bocay region
honduran presidential spokesman lisandro quesada said monday the estimated 2,000 sandinista troops who entered this country last week in pursuit of contra rebels have dwindled
col. manuel suarez benavides, the honduran armed forces public relations director, said it will be ``days only'' before the u.s. troops return home
neither suarez nor quesada would say the threat from the sandinistas has ended
when the last sandinista crosses the segovia river into nicaragua then this subject will be forgotten,'' quesada said. arrests at similar minneapolis protest, picking up 3rd graf ``shouts of'' and adds 6 grafs with details from minneapolis.</note>
riot-ready police moved in quickly monday, arresting 225 demonstrators among a yelling crowd of more than 500 people protesting u.s. military presence in central america
at a similar protest in minneapolis, police arrested about 50 of several hundred protesters after rocks and paint and paint were thrown at the federal building there and a window was broken
in san francisco, arrests for blocking entrances to the federal building and the streets around it began within minutes of the start of the protest at 7 a.m. the main entrance was closed, and for about a half-hour the protesters blocked the rear entrance. more than 5,000 people work in the 20-story building
shouts of ``no contra aid'' and ``u.s., cia, out of nicaragua,'' filled the air. some demonstrators, surging from one intersection to another, hurled newspaper vending boxes and debris into the street, disrupting traffic
on friday, about 250 people were arrested when they encircled the federal building
and on saturday, at least 5,000 people rallied in the streets. bottles, wooden crosses and bags of garbage were thrown at police. one person was arrested for felony assault on an officer, and four others were arrested on assorted charges
demonstrations have been held in several u.s. cities since president reagan sent 3,200 u.s. troops to honduras last week after honduras said 2,000 sandinistas had crossed the border from nicaragua
on monday, officers with visored helmets and batons marched on the double from one street to another as protesters harassed them with quick moves. some protesters went limp and were dragged screaming to police vans. a young man was hit in the mouth with a baton and bloodied
at times, as many as six police vans and a sheriff's bus lined up to receive those arrested. they were photographed and booked on the street before being taken to the hall of justice for citations
we're not going to stop these protests because we want people to know we are seriously committed to stopping u.s. intervention in central america,'' said bill nygren, a spokesman for pledge of resistance, one of several groups sponsoring the demonstration
the minneapolis protesters, carrying signs reading, ``human rights, not reagan might'' and ``stop the killing, ronnie. work for peace now,'' were met by dozens of police carrying night sticks and wearing protective head gear
officers ripped some banners down and tore them up and used dogs to keep the streets clear. none of the protesters got inside the federal building
the demonstration began at late afternoon when protesters blocked a busy intersection with their bodies, chanting ``u.s. out of honduras.''
scores of them faced off against about 30 counter-protesters who chanted ``more contra aid,'' but no violence was reported
a brief scuffle began when a man who said he was an undercover police officer grabbed an american flag from a protester and took it away, saying it was government property
demonstrators burned a flag in a protest friday
a u.n. fact-finding team will leave for nicaragua tuesday to investigate the border violence between nicaragua and honduras, the united nations announced
it said in a statement monday that the delegation of two diplomats and two military observers was being sent at the request of the leftist sandinista government
the statement said the team will visit only nicaragua since no permission was received from the honduran government to observe the situation on the honduran side of the border
border violence flared in the mountainous, jungle-covered bocay region last week when about 4,500 nicaraguan troops mounted a major assault to drive u.s.-backed contra rebels from nicaraguan territory and destroy contra supply bases on the honduran side
president reagan sent about 3,200 u.s. troops to honduras on a training exercise as a show of support for that government
the u.n. observers are gilberto schlittler-silva, director-designate of the u.n. division of security council affairs; aleksandr martinovic, political affairs officer in the office of secretary-general javier perez de cuellar; and two ecuadorean military officers, maj. jose viggiano and maj. eduardo gorgitano
they are to report to perez de cuellar upon their return
records for low temperatures were set in alpena, mich., 5 degrees below zero; binghamton, n.y., 3 degrees; marquette, mich., 15 below; and youngstown, ohio, 7 degrees. records were tied in sault ste. marie, mich., 9 degrees, and el paso, texas, 28
tuesday's forecast called for rain along the northern pacific coast; widely scattered rain showers and mountain snow in the northern plateau and the northern and central rockies; scattered showers from southern montana and northern wyoming into southern minnesota, with scattered snow in northern minnesota; and sunny skies over eastern and southern sections of the nation
high temperatures were expected to reach only into the 20s in northern new england, in the 30s and 40s over the rest of new england and from north dakota to the mid-atlantic states; in the 40s from washington into northwest montana; and in the 70s and 80s from southern california across the desert southwest, the southern rockies, the southern plains, the upper and middle mississippi valley and the southeast; and in the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of the nation
three former du pont co. employees suffering from exposure to asbestos pledged monday to give 90 percent of a $75 million award in punitive damages to six institutions
william kapp jr. of elkton, md., one of the victims and spokesman for the group, said the $67.5 million _ if the damage award is upheld on appeal _ will be donated ``to try to help our fellow asbestos victims, as well as to help assure that this kind of corporate abuse of public trust will never happen again.''
this is just our way of putting the punitive damages award to its highest purposes,'' kapp said
in november, a superior court jury awarded kapp, 55; james webb, 74, of newport; and joseph kaster, 71, of the newport area and their wives what has been called the second-largest personal injury award in u.s. history, against raymark industries inc. of trumbull, conn
the jury supported claims that raymark, formerly raybestos manhattan inc., conspired with the former johns manville corp., now manville corp., to suppress information relating to the health hazards of asbestos and failing to place warnings on their products
raymark manufactured asbestos that the men worked around for more than 25 years at du pont's newport plant. previous state court rulings had barred liability of employers in such cases
in addition to the punitive damage award, the men were awarded more than $1 million in actual damages for personal injury. they said they had contracted lung disorders linked to breathing asbestos fibers. six co-defendants settled the case
there are 350 similar cases pending against raymark in delaware
the inhalation of asbestos, once commonly used in building insulation and other products, has been linked to cancer and other diseases
the national campaign against toxic hazards, a toxic victims advocacy group, was earmarked to receive $13 million of the $67.5 million
the boston-based group's organizing director peter obstler said the money would be used ``to continue to provide staff and technical assistance to victims'' of toxic chemicals
but kapp stressed that the money may never be awarded
both sides are awaiting a decision from judge clarence w. taylor on whether to uphold the award. if it is upheld, raymark will appeal, according to legrande l. young, raymark general counsel
kapp, who employed by du pont for 33 years before he became too ill to work, said he was hoping the move to donate the money to charity would persuade taylor to uphold the $75 million award
young said he did not think the judge could be swayed. ``either it's an appropriate judgment or it's not,'' he said
the other institutions targeted for part of the award at $13 million each are the mount sinai school of environmental medicine in new york; the university of delaware school of business to establish a chair to advance the study of business ethics; the medical center of delaware's carpenter clinic for cancer research; and the white lung association, a baltimore-based organization of asbestos victims
an additional $2.5 million was pledged to the emily p. bissell hospital for the critically ill in newport
the largest jury award is believed to be $127.8 million to an orange county, calif., teen-ager who sued ford motor co. over burns he received when the gasoline tank of his 1972 pinto exploded. with demonstration in sidon. picks up 10th pvs, `at rafah...' subs 17th pvs, `time and newsweek...' with 1 graf to include reuters joined suit.</note>
israeli troopers on monday shot a palestinian teen-ager dead and a plo leaflet exhorted arabs to ``shower soldiers and herds of cowardly settlers'' with stones, firebombs and iron bars
troops expanded their search for weapons in the occupied west bank and gaza strip the day after an arab shot and killed a soldier in bethlehem
at least 106 palestinians and the israeli soldier have been killed since riots began in the occupied lands dec. 8, according to u.n. figures
israeli police arrested a prominent arab-american attorney monday and assailants attacked the homes of two moderate palestinians _ a newspaper editor and a member of jordan's parliament
the army announced a new military law permitting any security prisoner to be held up to six months with less judicial review than before. it said the law eliminated the requirement that a military judge review a case within 96 hours
israeli officials said the measure would apply for six months and would ease an overload on the military court system, which has handled nearly 3,000 cases since december. arab lawyers said they feared detention without trial could become more common
arabs mounted a general strike monday in the west bank and gaza to mark the anniversary of a 1968 battle resulting from an israeli raid on palestinian guerrillas inside jordan
graffiti scrawled on walls overnight urged arabs to attack israeli troops and civilians in memory of the battle at karameh, jordan
protests were reported at more than a dozen sites in the west bank and gaza. palestinian flags, outlawed by israel, flew from utility poles and were raised on mosques
an estimated 12,000 palestinians demonstrated at the ein el-hilweh refugee camp in the southern lebanese port city of sidon to show support for the uprisings in the occupied territories
ein el-hillweh is the largest refugee camp in lebanon with about 60,000 inhabitants
at rafah, a seaside town in the gaza strip, israeli troops tried to restrain protesters by dropping tear gas from helicopters, and then used live ammunition, arab witnesses said
soldiers shot abdel ahmed jaber al mudalal, 17, in the chest and he died of his wounds, according to the palestine press service and other arab reports
army spokesmen confirmed the death but said the family took the body from nasser hospital at khan yunis and the cause of death could not be determined
israeli gunfire wounded 16 palestinians on monday, according to hospital officials and the arab-run press service, which provided names and ages. the army said 11 arabs were wounded
leaflet no. 11, the latest distributed by the palestine liberation organization, told arabs to prepare for a long struggle against the israelis by developing ``home economy, raising chickens, rabbits and planting vegetables.''
it urged palestinians to ``shower soldiers and herds of cowardly settlers with stones, firebombs and iron bars'' and designated march 26 as a day of struggle against israeli-appointed arab municipal officials in the west bank and gaza
the people of the uprising will be severe with anyone who remains outside the national consensus and refuses to resign immediately,'' it said
time and newsweek magazines and the reuters news agency filed a suit with the supreme court in an effort to recover film confiscated after sunday's fatal shooting of israeli sgt. moshe katz in bethlehem. photographers took pictures moments after katz was shot in the head
demands for the return of the film made repeatedly to israeli authorities have been unavailing, and as a result legal action is being pursued,'' the magazines said in a statement
military officials said soldiers had widened the search for illegal weapons since the katz shooting. the jerusalem post quoted one as saying ``substantial amounts of weaponry'' were in the gaza strip but many caches were in mosques, ``beyond the grasp'' of israeli soldiers
army policy prohibits soldiers from entering mosques
jonathan kuttab, the arab-american lawyer, was charged with supporting an illegal organization _ a reference to an art exhibit at the hakawati theater that he said included palestinian nationalist work
kuttab, who is the theater's attorney and on its board, called the charge ``ridiculous and an infringement of the freedom of artists.'' he was released on bail of 1,000 shekels, or about $750
attackers fired shots at the home and car of jack khazmo, a moderate palestinian editor who lives in ram, a village just north of jerusalem, and threw three firebombs at the home of mousa abu ghosh, a member of jordan's parliament, in the west bank city of ramallah
israel captured the west bank and gaza strip from jordan and egypt in 1967. comment from miles davis. picks up 6th graf, `trumpeter dizzy...'.</note>
gil evans, a composer, pianist and band leader considered one of the greatest orchestrators in jazz, has died in mexico, his widow said here monday. he was 75
evans died sunday in cuernavaca of peritonitis while recuperating from prostate surgery, anita evans said in new york
evans, who had led his band in a new york city club in december and january, decided not to return to the club in march but to go to mexico to recuperate. mrs. evans said that he felt energetic when he left on the trip and he took his synthesizer and their two sons, noah and miles
evans made his mark in the 1950s and 1960s with innovative arrangements for trumpeter miles davis, particularly three recordings that showcased davis' cool style: ``miles ahead,'' ``porgy and bess'' and ``sketches of spain.''
they were really among the most brilliant orchestral jazz records made by anybody,'' said jazz historian and writer leonard feather. ``he made brilliant use of tone colors.''
through his spokeswoman, terry williams, davis said: ``whenever i had a question about the music, composing or which way to go, i would think about what gil would do. i'll really miss him.''
trumpeter dizzy gillespie, reached in los angeles, said evans would be missed ``for keeping time with the age that he's in.''
whatever new thing, new ideas come up, gil evans was right on top them,'' said gillespie, who knew evans well but did not perform with him. ``he will be missed for having a very strong feeling for the soloist. he was tender. one of a kind.''
evans was born in toronto may 13, 1912, and grew up in stockton, calif., where he organized a jazz band in high school. his first professional band, in stockton, was taken over by skinnay ennis, but evans stayed on as arranger
he was beginning the style that deployed instruments to bring out richness of tone and textures. he never left jazz as his base, and his arrangements never conflicted with the sense of spontaneity vital to jazz
after he worked as arranger for the claude thornhill orchestra during the 1940s, evans' reputation grew with his work for davis' nine-piece band in 1949. he blended french horn and tuba on davis' ``boplicity'' and ``birth of the cool,'' which proved influential
his first recording with his own band, ``the arranger's touch,'' used french horn, muted trumpet and bassoon in arrangements marked by originality. evans arranged for davis again in 1959, with davis playing flugelhorn over a 19-piece orchestra, on the album ``miles ahead.''
evans orchestrated two more davis albums, ``porgy and bess'' and ``sketches of spain,'' tailoring them to davis' artistic temperament. he worked as a free-lance arranger, doing works like cannonball adderley's ``pacific standard time'' album and his own ``out of the cool.''
a project to arrange for rock guitarist jimi hendrix was canceled by hendrix's death in 1970. later, evans recorded ``gil evans plays hendrix.'' he scored the film ``absolute beginners'' at age 74
an upcoming tour of northern europe by the gil evans orchestra, plus appearances at jazz festivals in umbria, italy, and new york will go on, mrs. evans said, with son miles evans conducting
she said that a memorial service will be held, probably on easter. both sides propose cease-fires. picks up 10th graf pvs, `cheering sandinista...</note>
the sandinista government and u.s.-backed rebels on monday opened three days of talks in this border town by exchanging cease-fire proposals and agreeing to a truce during the negotiations
neither side seeks a military victory over the other,'' said alfredo cesar, head of the rebel delegation, after the completion of the first day of talks _ the first face-to-face negotiations on nicaraguan soil
he said the contra rebels proposed a 30-day cease-fire and continuous talks to reach a permanent truce
cesar told reporters the contras also proposed total amnesty and guarantees of free expression to lead toward reconciliation. he called monday's talks, which were behind closed doors, ``a step ahead.''
defense minister humberto ortega, leader of the government delegation, said he proposed an ``immediate and definitive cease-fire.'' he did not elaborate
the rebels, battered by a two-week-old sandinista offensive, agreed to accept a truce for the duration of the negotiations in what contra spokesman bosco matamoros called ``a gesture of good will.''
frank arana, another contra spokesman, said the two sides discussed military and political issues including ``concepts of democracy.''
if so, it would be the first time the sandinistas consented to discuss political issues with the rebels
in two rounds of indirect talks in the dominican republic and costa rica, the sandinistas demanded the negotiations deal exclusively on the mechanics of a cease-fire
negotiations opened after ortega, brother of president daniel ortega, said the sandinistas were suspending military operations for the duration of the talks and called on the contras to do the same
sandinista spokesman manuel espinoza said the ``reciprocation of the contras'' in agreeing to suspend hostilities and ``the fact that this meeting is taking place are the first positive steps'' toward a permanent cease-fire. he spoke to reporters during the lunch break
the rebels entered the talks in this small town on the border with costa rica without high expectations of sandinista concessions
cesar told reporters earlier that he feared the rebels were being weakened ``by the suspension of united states aid and the growth in soviet aid to the sandinistas.''
unlike the two previous rounds of negotiations, the sapoa agenda was supposed to be open. on sunday, however, sandinista officials said they would focus on a cease-fire in the civil war, which began in 1981 and has cost an estimated 40,000 lives
cheering sandinista supporters calling for a contra ``surrender'' lined both sides of the 90-mile road the government delegation traveled from managua to sapoa. the contras arrived from costa rica
soldiers and security agents in plainclothes guarded sapoa. security was especially tight at the customs house, where the talks were being held
with the sandinista were brian wilson, an american pacifist whose legs were severed by a train in califoria during a protest last year, and singer-actor kris kristofferson. both are sandinista supporters of long standing
the contras made cesar, once a high sandinista official, head of their delegation in hopes of gaining benefit from his familiarity with the sandinistas
cesar said he last visited sapoa as a sandinista revolutionary fighting the late president anastasio somoza, who was overthrown in july 1979
it has been nine years since i was last in sapoa and i am still struggling for the freedom of nicaragua,'' he said. cesar broke with the sandinistas in 1982
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, nicaragua's roman catholic prelate who mediated earlier talks, and joao baena soares, general secretary of the organization of american states, attended the meeting as observers
cease-fire talks are required under the peace plan signed by the presidents of nicaragua, honduras, costa rica, el salvador and guatemala last august. among other provisions are amnesties, greater democracy and an end to the use of one nation's territory for attacks on another. saying only political option offered mecham was ``going down with ship,'' moving up background, picking up 4th graf ``craft testified...'. deletes 13th graf pvs, `the obstruction...', now redundant.</note>
gov. evan mecham's lawyer, in an abrupt role change, became a witness in his client's impeachment trial monday, saying the only political option advisers offered the governor was ``to go down with the ship.''
fred craft, who was subpoenaed by the senate on a motion by democratic minority leader sen. alan stephens, made the comment during cross-examination by prosecutor paul eckstein
craft and his co-counsel, jerris leonard, objected to the cross-examination, saying that only senators were supposed to question a lawyer called as a witness under such unusual circumstances. the presiding officer disagreed
eckstein asked whether craft ever advised mecham to resign
i've talked to the governoer a lot,'' said craft. ``sometimes i've said, `governor, why are you doiing this to yourself?'''
without answering directly, he recalled mecham advisers brainstorming about the governor's political options
we had these meetings and no one could see a political escape route for the governor,'' craft said. ``no one was offering the governor any other political option than to go down with the ship.''
craft, now one of mecham's lawyers in the impeachment case, was a washington lobbyist for mecham and an adviser to the first-term republican
the senate, which began its fourth week of inquiry into the governor's actions monday, has been hearing testimony on an allegation that mecham tried to obstruct justice by thwarting an attorney general's probe of the alleged death threat against former mecham aide donna carlson
the obstruction of justice charge is one of three broad allegations against mecham at the trial. he also is charged with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and with misusing $80,000 from a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
earlier, craft corroborated mecham's assertions that he was not informed that a death threat had been made against a former aide
craft testified he stood next to mecham when a state police officer first reported the alleged threat. craft said it was reported as ``an altercation between two employees.''
i never heard `felony.' i never heard `death threat' and i certainly never heard `tampering with a grand jury witness,''' craft said in an almost exact duplicate of mecham's own testimony last week
at the time of the alleged threat last november, ms. carlson was preparing to testify before a grand jury investigating mecham's campaign finances
like mecham, craft accused lt. beau johnson of the department of public safety of testifying falsely when he said he alerted mecham to a possible felony _ tampering with a grand jury witness
craft swore johnson never gave that warning
i don't remember so much what he said as what he did not say because i'm a trained lawyer ...,'' said craft. ``if he had said those words, my antennae would have gone up
johnson has said he went to mecham and told him that a mecham aide, lee watkins, had threatened mrs. carlson and that a possible felony was involved. mecham has denied this version, saying he understood two employees had a disagreement and that he referred it to watkins' superior, max hawkins
senators supported stephens' motion to have craft testify because he was mentioned by other witnesses as participating in key conversations. craft said he did not give the governor legal advice during that period and acknowledged he could not claim an attorney-client privilege of confidentiality
craft took the stand after peggy griffith, he official who reported hearing the alleged threat against ms. carlson, said she was told mecham blamed her for getting him ``in hot water.''
mrs. griffith, returning to testify as a prosecution rebuttal witness, said she was told by her secretary, terri fields, that the governor and his then-lawyer, murray miller, were mad at mrs. griffith
she came in and was very tearful and agitated,'' mrs. griffith said of ms. fields. ``she said,`i can't stand it anymore. i'm going to quit. they're hounding me. the governor and murray miller ... they said it's all your fault, peggy. they said if you had not told, the governor would not be in hot water and it's all your fault.'''
mrs. griffith, a strong mecham supporter, said that was ``a gut blow.''
it would take a two-thirds vote of the 30 senators to convict mecham. they could then take another vote and forbid mecham to ever hold state office again
mecham, the first u.s. governor to be impeached in 60 years, also faces an april 21 criminal trial on felony charges of concealing the $350,000 loan and a recall election may 17
mecham, who friday completed three days of testimony, was absent from the trial monday. to death</head> zone description was applied to section of spanish harlem, sted the entire neighborhood. picks up 6th graf pvs, `this is...'.</note>
three men and a teen-ager who ``thought they had done the right thing'' were charged monday with manslaughter in the beating death of a man who allegedly stole $20 and was chased by a mob in a drug-ravaged neighborhood
the four were surprised when told they were being charged in the death of raymondo caraballo, 41, said detective capt. william quigley
they thought they had done the right thing, chasing and capturing this guy,'' quigley said. ``well, somebody's dead. somebody's got to be responsible for it.''
three others were being sought and arrests were expected, he said
the killing took place in a section of spanish harlem that residents and area workers described as a drug war zone
this is vietnam here. it's bad, it's bad,'' said a city worker cleaning out a room on the ground floor of the building outside which caraballo was beaten. he insisted on anonymity
the suspect entered a bakery shortly after noon sunday and grabbed $20 from 21-year-old anna beteran, witnesses told police
i heard the people screaming,'' bakery co-owner orlando testa said monday. ``the guy stole the money from the girl and ran away.''
as caraballo ran out, beteran and her unidentified sister-in-law chased him, police said. the women lost sight of him when he ducked into the jefferson houses project about a block away, quigley said
as the women asked members of a crowd on the corner if they had seen the man, caraballo appeared and the group gave chase
they started to beat him (with) fists and feet,'' quigley said at an afternoon news conference. a garbage can cover was thrown at caraballo, but it was deflected and did not hit him, as reported earlier, quigley said
he was getting beaten all over, the legs, the ribs,'' said al rivera, 27, who was visiting a friend in the area of the beating sunday
he was yelling, `please stop. no more, no more,''' rivera said, pointing to the blue scaffolding under which the beating took place
housing police who were called in broke up the crowd. the man stood up and was handcuffed, but the officers radioed for an ambulance as they took him away
the man died about five hours later at mount sinai hospital. hospital personnel said, according to quigley, that caraballo had irreversible brain trauma and internal injuries. an autopsy was scheduled
quigley identified the four charged with first- and second-degree manslaughter as david andino, 22, charles mimms, 20, jesus negron, 23, and isidore cuadrado, 14. none knew the man who was killed or the others arrested, quigley said
negron was arrested about 10 p.m. sunday and the other three surrendered overnight because ``the word was out in the street,'' quigley said
in the neighborhood bodegas, in the housing project and on the street, the talk monday was about drugs and robberies and an exasperating way of life that causes people to live by looking over their shoulders
it's frightening. ... it's crazy,'' julia white, a 16-year resident and supervisor with the jefferson houses tenants association, said about the presence of drug users
there's no answer to it. and there's no end to it,'' she said, shaking her head
last year, a girl was found killed ...'' she said, hesitating as he suddenly remembered where: ``in here. oh, my goodness.'' would accept help in ending war; iraq's u.n. ambassador accusing iran of using chemical weapons. picks up 4th graf pvs, `the king ...' adds 6 grafs at bottom with details of iranian allegations.</note>
king hussein on monday urged the moslem world to support the revolt in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip, where more than 100 palestinians and an israeli soldier have been killed since dec. 8
opening a meeting of foreign ministers of the 46-member organization of islamic conference, the jordanian monarch also expressed hope that iran would agree to a cease-fire in its war with iraq
the iranian envoy to the conference, mohammed ali tashkiri, told reporters that his nation would accept the help of any ``truthful hand'' that tried to end the devastating iran-iraq missile duel on each other's cities
at the united nations monday, iraq's u.n. ambassador accused iraq of using chemical weapons which he said killed 5,000 people and wounded 5,000 in kurdish border cities inside iran
king hussein told the conference in his opening address: ``the palestinian people have a rightful claim on us to support their uprising both on the national and international level so that the uprising (in the occupied territories) may bear fruit.''
the king did not elaborate on what forms aid should take, but asked the ministers to support an international conference on middle east peace
sharifuddin pir zadeh, secretary-general of the islamic conference, said earlier that protesters in the israeli-occupied territories should be supported ``financially and morally.''
hussein said the palestinian were ``heroically fighting for their freedom and national rights and defying in their uprising the arrogance of the forces of occupation.''
he said there should be a seat for the palestine liberation organization at an international peace conference, which would involve the parties to the conflict and the five permanent members of the u.n. security council: the united states, soviet union, britain, france and china
by calling for a plo seat at the conference, hussein set himself apart from u.s. peace proposals, which he discussed in amman on sunday with u.s. envoy philip habib. the u.s. plan does not call for a plo seat at the conference
the uprising of the palestinian people is not an end in itself nor is it a transient coincidental event that will soon wither away,'' hussein said. ``it is rather an expression of the will of an entire nation to fight for its freedom and right of self-determination in its own land.''
the rebellion in the occupied territories, which palestinians call ``the uprising,'' and the iran-iraq war dominate the agenda of the meeting, at which all members of the conference except chad are represented
king hussein, who supports iraq in the war, called the conflict a ``deep wound in the body'' of the moslem world that is ``bleeding and draining our resources and energies.''
our hope is that iran ... will accept security council resolution 598, which represents the will of the international community,'' he said
the resolution, passed last july, provides for a cease-fire and return to pre-war borders
iraq has said it will stop shooting if iran does but the iranians demand that iraq be named the aggressor before a truce takes effect. iraq invaded iran in september 1980 after several border skirmishes
tashkiri, who heads the foreign relations department in iran's ministry of information and religious guidance, told journalists that he would attempt to get the conference to discuss the missile duel
we support a halt in the war of the cities and we will back any truthful hand that tries to stop it,'' he said
the relatively low-ranking level of the iranian delegation in amman appeared to make it unlikely such negotiations would start at the conference
iran's u.n. ambassador, mohammad ja'afar mahallati, accused iraq of sending planes to bombard border cities with nerve gas on a scale ``unprecedented'' in the persian gulf war, and also of employing mustard gas and cyanide gas in a campaign that began march 17
iraq's ambassador, ismat taha kittani, refused comment
mahallatti asked the u.n. security council to denounce iraq, to send a fact-finding team to verify his claims and to mobilize the world health organization and similar agencies to aid victims
an explosion monday near the imperial palace and another blast close to the israeli embassy shattered windows but caused no injuries and apparently were the work of radicals, said police
a motorcycle rigged as a bomb burst into flames and exploded at 7:17 p.m. near hibiya park, about 900 yards southeast of the imperial palace, breaking windows in the saudi arabian airlines office, said a police official who spoke on condition of anonymity
about 15 minutes later, explosives in the trunk of a parked car went off 3{ miles away, near the israeli embassy, breaking windows in buildings nearby, he said. there were no reports of damage at the embassy
the police official said japanese radicals, who sometimes fire homemade missiles from cars parked in streets, may have been responsible for the explosions in downtown tokyo. no more details were immediately available
in february, four shuttle buses used to transport passengers to and from airports were burned in tokyo in apparent attacks by radicals opposed to expanding the new tokyo international airport at narita. there were no reports of injuries
narita area farmers and their supporters, including anti-government radical groups, have resisted plans to expropriate farmland for a second runway at the $2.5 billion airport at narita
in 1986, radicals fired homemade missiles at the state guest house, u.s. embassy, imperial palace, crown prince's residence and osaka police headquarters before the seven-nation summit meeeting held in tokyo in may
one attack occurred during japan's welcoming ceremonies for the heads of government of the united states, canada, britain, france, west germany and italy. separate toll lists kept and figure unaltered</note>
ira gunmen killed a policeman monday at a checkpoint in londonderry, the 12th victim in two weeks of heightening tension and sectarian violence
britain announced a massive manhunt in west belfast's roman catholic ghettos for the killers of two british soldiers caught in an ira funeral procession
northern ireland secretary tom king said in london that the royal ulster constabulary has launched an immediate review of its new policy of keeping a low profile at irish republican army funerals. the policy was aimed at avoiding clashes between police and supporters of the outlawed ira
the policeman who was killed monday, clive graham, 25, was shot in the head in a jeep while at a checkpoint in the roman catholic creggan district of londonderry, northern ireland's second-largest city. he died later in the hospital
the ira claimed responsibility for graham's killing in a clandestine message to belfast media
he was the 12th person to die since march 6, when british commandos shot dead three ira guerrillas who allegedly were plotting a car bombing in gibraltar
the funeral policy was started wednesday at services for the guerrillas killed in gibraltar. a protestant gunman opened fire and hurled grenades at the catholic milltown cemetery, killing three people and wounding 68
king's announcement of a review of the policy stopped well short of demands by leaders of northern ireland protestant parties to return to a heavy presence at ira funerals
as expectations grew of an imminent wave of arrests in west belfast, there was also speculation that dozens of ira supporters who were filmed surrounding and beating the soldiers' unmarked car with iron bars and dragging them out had gone into hiding
a massive murder investigation is under way in which all possible resources are involved to identify all those responsible,'' king said of the manhunt in west belfast
three people were arrested saturday and police sources said monday that up to 30 others were being sought after hours of scrutiny of film taken by an army helicopter which hovered over the scene and by tv networks. gruesome scenes of the attack also were shown on television
cpls. derek wood and david howes, in plainclothes, were surrounded when they drove up to the cortege, dragged from their car, stripped, beaten and shot dead
king said an emergency meeting of senior government ministers from britain and the republic of ireland will be held this week to consider stepped up security
king denied charges by northern ireland protestant politicians that police and troops failed to come to the soldiers' aid because of political orders to stay away from ira funerals
he said it was not immediately clear to police watching film relayed from the helicopter that soldiers were under attack because police ``were certain there were no security forces in the area whatsoever.''
he said the soldiers were under general orders to keep out of catholic districts unless on operational duty and had ``no reason to be in the vicinity of the funerals.'' he said he did not know why they were there
as the commons listened in silence, king praised the corporals, identified as signals corpsmen heading back to barracks after doing maintenance work at a base in belfast, for their restraint in firing only one shot into the mob that surrounded them
the truth is that there will be new depths (of horror) again as long as this awful and evil campaign of terrorism and revenge continues,'' king said
it has got to stop in the name of humanity and if there is to be any decent future for the people of northern ireland and for all those living in the island of ireland, and if the evil shroud of terrorism is to be lifted from the united kingdom as whole.''
since 1969, 2,638 people have been killed in the sectarian violence in this protestant-dominated province. the ira is fighting to end british rule and unite northern ireland with the catholic republic of ireland under a leftist administration. 03-21 0781</first> cut budget, raises possibility of tax increases later, and with some bills introduced by legislators. no pickup. should stand for ams.</note>
warning that louisiana is in a ``terrifying financial crisis,'' gov. buddy roemer on monday told the legislature that he must have unprecedented authority to make budget cuts in order to keep the state afloat
we must build on the foundation of a balanced budget,'' roemer said in his address before lawmakers called into special session
although the governor said the first step would be to cut spending, he said tax increases would be necessary later
roemer said the state faces a more than $2 billion problem, including a $210 million cash-flow shortage that could shut down government within 50 days, a projected $756 million deficit for the 1988-89 fiscal year and an accumulated debt of $1.3 billion
we inherited a mess, a real, unbelievable mess,'' the governor said
roemer asked lawmakers to give him the authority to cut up to 20 percent from each department and eliminate entire state programs through the rest of the fiscal year ending june 30
i must have the power to make decisions and accelerate the decision-making process,'' he said
the governor said that if then-gov. edwin edwards had accepted $100 million in budget cuts that roemer proposed during the transition, the cash-flow problem would have been averted
time is eating us alive,'' he said
roemer said the legislature could reverse any budget decisions he makes when lawmakers convene for their regular session in april, adding, ``i am not requesting that you abdicate your responsibility in the budget process.''
the special session would center around solving the short-term cash problem and laying the groundwork for paying off the accumulated debt. budget cuts made now will translate into savings in the next fiscal year, he said
as part of a government reorganization plan to save money, roemer asked lawmakers to divide the department of health and human resources into two agencies, eliminate the department of urban and community affairs, and forgive loans taken from ``dedicated,'' or special-use, funds to keep the state operating
besides eliminating the entire urban affairs department, which would require separate legislative action, roemer did not cite specifically what state programs he wanted to eliminate, but he said some state institutions may have to be closed
tax increases and borrowing alone, without budget cuts, will not solve the financial problem and will hamper efforts to attract new business and industry to louisiana, roemer warned
more borrowing or new taxes are not now the answer,'' he said. ``we will need to do both eventually. but each action must be carefully thought out and precisely planned.''
roemer said his administration already had taken steps to save $214 million through such steps as better utilization of state office space, reducing the number of state vehicles by a third, limiting bond issues for major construction projects and the elimination of positions held by political appointees
the regular legislative session will concern itself with plans to pay off the long-term debt, an overhaul of the state's tax system, a balanced budget for 1987-88, education and environmental changes and a plan to diversify the state's economy, roemer said
the ability to attract new business to louisiana will depend upon ``our willingness to make tough decisions,'' the governor said
i did not expect nor did i ask for this perilous economic situation. but i am prepared to lead us through these tough times in such a way that we protect essential services and we avoid having to make these choices over and over and over again. it will not be easy,'' he said
after the house and senate convened shortly after 5 p.m., administration-backed bills aimed at slashing state spending and reorganizing government were introduced in both chambers
in the house, legislation was put forth to give roemer the temporary authority he wants to cut spending
there was also a proposal for a statewide lottery to pay off bonds that would be used to finance the state's accumulated budget deficit. once the deficit was paid off, further proceeds would go to education, health care and local governments, according to the bill. roemer has voiced opposition to a lottery
also referred to a senate committee were bills to transfer the functions of some agencies to other departments, reduce the interest rate on some refunds and payments being delayed by the governor in order to save cash, and abolish most special funds in the state treasury
officials of the inter american press association praised the united states on monday for progress in press freedom, but criticized pentagon restrictions on coverage of some events
a panamanian publisher attending iapa's mid-year meeting said drug traffickers have ``hijacked'' his country and there will be no press freedom there until gen. manuel antonio noriega leaves power
gilberto arias of the newspaper extra said the army closed the three independent daily newspapers and major radio and television stations ``when they refused to be muzzled.'' the newspapers are extra, la prensa and el siglo
iapa represents more than 1,300 newspapers in the united states and latin america. a special report on press freedom in the hemisphere is scheduled for release thursday
anthony day of the los angeles times reported advances in congress and the supreme court for the cause of free expression in the united states
but day criticized pentagon restrictions on news coverage of u.s. military operations in the persian gulf and honduras. he is vice president for the united states of the iapa freedom of the press committee
day told the press freedom committee that news coverage has been limited in the gulf and last week, when the united states sent 3,200 soldiers to honduras, the pentagon sent its national media pool of 10 correspondents with them
such pool coverage, though on occasion necessary for swift and sudden operations, is most unsatisfactory for long-term coverage, as in the persian gulf,'' he said
he described as a step in the right direction a new law that restricts the government's right to refuse entry to foreigners ``because of any past, current or expected beliefs or associations, which, if engaged in by a u.s. citizen in the united states, would be protected under the constitution of the united states.''
according to day, iapa sought the congressional action after the immigration and naturalization service refused entry to patricia lara, a reporter for el tiempo in bogota. the government contended she was a member of the leftist m-19 guerrillas, which she denied
day said the new law represents progress but the government still may use reasons of foreign policy or national security to deny entry to people linked to terrorist actions or activities
i myself fear that the government might use these exceptions to keep people arbitrarily out of the country,'' he said. ``it seems to me that patricia lara could still be denied admission under the law.''
another problem with the law is that it applies only for the remainder of the reagan administration, he said. day said iapa, mainly through the efforts of edward seaton of seaton newspapers in manhattan, kan., took the lead in pressing for legislation and should try to strengthen and extend it
day applauded a supreme court ruling in february guaranteeing ``parodists, caricaturists and other amusing rascals'' the same first amendment protections ``as the more sober-sided members of the press have,'' in its ruling on the rev. jerry falwell's damage suit against hustler magazine
the magazine published a phony advertisement depicting falwell, leader of the moral majority, in what the court described as a ``drunken incestuous rendezvous with his mother.'' it said public figures have many ways of protecting themselves against vitriolic criticism and tasteless parodies without suing their critics
so we in the united states are in debt to hustler magazine,'' day said. ``as a matter of fact, the supreme court decision is welcome financially as well as morally. its decision greatly inhibits the filing of libel suits.''
arias told the committee ``journalists work under constant threats'' in panama, where ``there is no freedom of the press and there won't be until the dicatorship of gen. noriega ends.''
several foreign journalists have been detained or refused entry to panama, where noriega is the power behind the civilian government as chief of the 15,000 defense forces
noriega has been indicted on drug charges in florida, the united states has cut off the flow of cash to his country and the reagan administration is trying to force him into exile
panama has been hijacked by drug traffickers'' who are capable of ``shutting down the canal at any moment,'' arias said
for a dictatorship accused of drug trafficking, hostile to humanity, hostile to all democratic and civilized forces, it is not difficult to sink a ship at the entrance of the panama canal.''
he and other speakers said much of the threat to the press in latin america is linked to the region's drug traffic
a state board delayed a decision monday on whether to parole former black panther johnny spain, who earlier this month was freed after 21 years in prison for murder
the full state board of prison terms voted unanimously to have one of its smaller, three-member panels reconsider parole of the ``san quentin six'' member, even though he was released from vacaville state prison march 10 on court orders that required $350,000 bail
spain, who lives in san francisco and is preparing to go to work as an electrician, a trade he learned behind bars, had been in prison since december 1966 on a conviction of murdering a man he was trying to rob in los angeles
in 1976, he became the only prisoner convicted of murder in an august 1971 bloodbath at san quentin prison _ the worst in state prison history _ that took the lives of militant leader george jackson, two other prisoners and three guards
the san quentin conviction was overturned in 1986, and a new trial ordered, a ruling the state is appealing
in february, a three-member panel voted 2-1 to grant parole in 1989 on the 1966 murder charge. the dissenting member, however, asked the full board to review the decision
earlier this month, however, a superior court judge in los angeles, citing technical irregularities in earlier parole hearings, ordered spain released on parole immediately
that ruling cleared the way for spain's release on bail pending the state's appeal of the order for a new trial in the san quentin case
the parole board's chief legal counsel, william cashdollar, said the new hearing would take place within 45 days, in effect canceling the february ruling to grant parole in 1989
cashdollar refused to provide any further details of their reasoning during monday's closed board hearing and said the board was ``complying fully with court orders but also continuing to comply with the statutes that establish our responsibilities'' regarding parole of inmates
it's a unique situation,'' cashdollar said. ``most of the individuals are in custody when we are making our determinations.''
spain's attorney, dennis riordan, criticized what he called the board's decision ``to reconsider whether he should have any parole date at all.''
riordan said the board would have to obtain a court order to enforce any move to return spain to prison between now and the time his parole is reconsidered, a move that riordan said he would fight
they've never been confronted by this situation before and they are confused by it,'' he said
board of prison terms spokeswoman phyllis scott said all options regarding spain's immediate future would be discussed with the state attorney general's office, including the possibility that it would seek to return him to prison
assistant attorney general alan ashby refused to comment on the case
vice president george bush indicated monday he supported president reagan's veto of a major civil rights bill, even as the house and senate were poised to override the president's action
the legislation ... is imperfect and the imperfections should be corrected,'' the vice president, who is seeking the republican presidential nomination, said in remarks to a group of black supporters in washington
until now, the vice president had avoided direct comment on whether he supported reagan's veto. but, as he campaigned in hartford, conn., he told reporters who asked him about it: ``i'm not going to start differing with the president now.''
i'm not going to start doing now what i haven't been doing for seven years, finding differences with the president, for whom i have great respect,'' he told the group in washington, which applauded enthusiastically his remarks about the bill
the civil rights restoration act passed both chambers earlier this year by large margins. both supporters and opponents of the measure said there was little chance the veto would be sustained
the measure would forbid the distribution of federal funds to entire institutions, state and local government agencies and many corporations if any part of them practices discrimination
it was prompted by a 1984 supreme court ruling that civil rights laws applied only to a specific program or activity receiving federal aid. under the decision, for example, the government could not cut off money to a college if the discrimination occurred in a department that did not receive such aid
supporters of the measure say it restores civil rights laws to the way they were interpreted before the court challenge mounted by tiny grove city college in pennsylvania
bush criticized the measure, but added: ``having said that, however, the federal government must require that organizations that get tax dollars comply with our civil rights laws.''
he said in hartford that he believed the president should have line-item veto powers so he could ``take some of the extremes'' out of a piece of legislation
the reagan administration has called for an alternative bill similar to an earlier republican plan voted down in congress, which would grant religious schools and organizations as well as corporations more exemptions from civil rights laws
earlier monday, bush picked up endorsements from gov. thomas h. kean and new jersey's county republican chairmen, a gain that one chairman said was ``like winning the state's presidential primary.''
we republicans have had a spirited campaign. we've heard good ideas, from jack kemp, from bob dole, from pete du pont, from al haig and from pat robertson. now it's time for our party to come together,'' said kean with bush by his side
george bush is our leader, and with the republican vision of a stronger america that offers opportunity to all regardless of color or creed, we can not only retain the presidency, but send (house speaker) jim wright to the back benches for the rest of this century,'' kean said
the popular governor abandoned his neutrality one week after bush won the illinois primary, taking a commanding lead for the republican nomination
new jersey's 21 county republican chairmen, who had been waiting for kean to act, followed the governor's lead and voted to endorse bush at a breakfast meeting monday
kean also campaigned monday with the vice president in connecticut, which holds its presidential primary next tuesday
in bloomfield, conn., the vice president, whose father was a u.s. senator from conecticut and whose brother and mother still live in greenwich, said: ``i don't want to be beaten in this state.''
we're taking nothing for granted. there's no arrogance factor, no overconfidence certainly,'' bush said
bush was also asked about a possible pardon for former national security adviser john poindexter and former white house aide oliver north, who have been indicted in connection with the iran-contra affair
pardon imputes guilt, it seems to me, a pardon for something. that has not been established,'' the vice president said. ``the system has to work; it will work.''
in new jersey, assemblyman richard kamin, the morris county gop chairman, said the endorsements were ``like winning the state's presidential primary,'' almost assuring that bush will win new jersey's 64 republican delegates. the state's primary is june 7
it is significant to have them at this point, when you have your opponent still vowing to go on,'' kamin said
in his endorsement speech, kean cited two themes he has embraced as governor: the need to improve education and the need for republicans to practice the ``politics of inclusion'' by reaching out to blacks and others not usually in the party's fold
the governor said bush ``wants to be the education president.'' and he said bush ``doesn't just talk about expanding the republican party; he has been doing it for more than 20 years.''
a grand jury has added drug and weapons charges to the indictment against an attorney charged with murder in the beating death of a 6-year-old girl he had illegally adopted, a prosecutor said monday
officers found heroin, cocaine and marijuana in joel steinberg's greenwich village apartment on nov. 2 when they discovered lisa steinberg comatose and brain dead, manhattan district attorney robert morgenthau said
the apartment also contained scales, crack pipes and drug recipe cards for cocaine and heroin derivatives along with a .45-caliber revolver and bullets for another weapon, morgenthau said
the child's death touched off a nationwide debate on child abuse and the role of school and welfare officials in trying to prevent it
a nine-count indictment, which supersedes a november indictment, also charges that steinberg abused the girl during the two months before her death, the prosecutor said. the original indictment charged him with endangering the welfare of a child on nov. 2
the new abuse charge is a felony. the weapons, drug and drug-paraphernalia possession charges are misdemeanors
steinberg has been held without bail in protective custody at rikers island. his longtime companion, hedda nussbaum, remains at columbia-presbyterian hospital, where she has been undergoing psychiatric treatment
after the girl's death, ms. nussbaum, an author and former children's book editor, was treated for a broken nose, injured eye and other injuries apparently stemming from a beating
she was charged by police in connection with lisa's death but has not been indicted. prosecutors said they would let her receive treatment before she decides whether to testify before a grand jury
lisa's biological mother, an unwed teen-ager, has testified she gave her newborn daughter to steinberg to arrange an adoption. the lawyer has admitted during a family court hearing that he kept the child without legally adopting her. name of village to sand lake, sted nelson village, in 2nd graf, add background in 6th graf</note>
ralph boerman is the lucky winner of an election in which candidates and voters stayed away in droves
boerman, bob vandenberg and earl thomas got exactly one write-in vote apiece in the coolly contested march 14 election in sand lake, a northern kent county village of about 200 people
on monday, three kent county employees gathered around a box to see if boerman, vandenberg or thomas would be the next village trustee
vandenberg's and thomas' proxies drew slips marked ``not elected.'' boerman's proxy drew the slip marked ``elected'' and boerman, who like the other candidates didn't attend the draw-off, became the new trustee of the village north of grand rapids
the 22-year-old winner, who has never held elective office, confessed monday he's got a lot to learn about his new job. he isn't sure how many people are on the board of trustees, what it does or how much he gets paid
i guess it just helps run (nelson) township and decides what happens,'' boerman said, referring to the township in which sand lake is contained. ``i really don't know but i will find out, the hard way.''
election law requires tie votes to be resolved by a drawing
vandenberg, 51, just resigned as the village president, a post he held for six years. thomas, 40, is a former village clerk. bill</note>
democrats albert gore jr. and richard gephardt campaigned in the glow of popular non-candidates monday _ gore with mario cuomo and gephardt with lee iacocca _ but came away without endorsements. republican george bush touted his endorsement by new jersey gov. thomas h. kean
bush, meanwhile, gave out another kind of endorsement _ lending his support to president reagan's veto of a major civil rights bill. congress was poised to override the veto on tuesday
the legislation ... is imperfect and the imperfections should be corrected,'' he told a group of black supporters in washington. ``i'm not going to start doing now what i haven't been doing for seven years, finding differences with the president, for whom i have great respect.''
bush said, however, that he supported the idea that the federal government should require that organizations that get tax dollars comply with civil rights laws
