britain announced a massive manhunt in west belfast's roman catholic ghettos for the killers of two british soldiers caught in an ira funeral procession
northern ireland secretary tom king said in london that the royal ulster constabulary has launched an immediate review of its new policy of keeping a low profile at irish republican army funerals. the policy was aimed at avoiding clashes between police and supporters of the outlawed ira
iranian gunboats attacked and set ablaze a spanish freighter and a liberian tanker in the persian gulf on monday, two days after an iraqi attack on a norweigan vessel left 54 seamen missing and presumed dead
there have been six maritime attacks since friday when iran, in apparent reprisal for the resumption of iraqi strikes against its oil lifeline, ended a five-week hiatus in assaults on commercial shipping in the oil-rich waterway
there was no word on casualties aboard the 10,168-ton spanish refrigerator ship iberian reefer, which was ``burning fiercely'' at dusk, hours after it was attacked in the strait of hormuz, maritime salvage experts said
scientists have redesigned a potent natural poison so that it seeks out and kills cancer cells in the test tube, signaling a possible new route for fighting some tumors, a scientist said monday
the poison, so strong that a dose the size of a salt grain can kill a person, may be harnessed for fighting breast cancers that have spread elsewhere in the body, and some lung and brain tumors, said ira pastan of the national cancer institute
the strategy takes advantage of the fact that some cancer cells display on their surface certain kinds of protein structures called receptors. specific substances bind to each kind of receptor before they enter the cell
the supreme court agreed monday to decide whether abused children may sue public officials for failing to protect them from their parents
the justices said they will hear an appeal on behalf of a wisconsin boy who suffered serious and permanent brain damage from beatings by his father. social workers and officials are accused of gross negligence in ignoring evidence the boy was being brutally victimized
the court's study of the case, expected to yield a ruling sometime in 1989, comes amid growing concern nationwide over child abuse
an old generation is remembering the vietnam war and a new generation is curious, stirring a revival of the controversial era in books and movies. now comes a new publication, a slick magazine simply named vietnam, whose premiere issue goes on sale tuesday
our timing could not have been better because right now, look at all the vietnam movies that have come out,'' said publisher gregg r. oehler in a telephone interview from leesburg, va., where the magazine is published by empire press. ``look at all the major emphasis now on video, on books. it's vietnam. everyone now is talking about vietnam.''
oehler said 150,000 copies of the first issue were printed, including 50,000 for subscribers and 100,000 for newsstand sales across the united states and in 16 other countries. the magazine, a quarterly, sells for $2.95 a copy on newsstands and for $9.95 for the four issues by subscription
the latest squabble between prosecutors and defense attornyes isn't about cases, tactics or money. it's about being able to bypass new security procedures at the dirksen federal building, and it's headed for _ where else? _ the bench
complaints from the public have been few, but the security system brought the entire u.s. district court system here to a screeching halt one afternoon and prompted 39 attorneys _ including several of chicago's best-known defenders _ to petition the district's 21 judges for the same exemptions granted to prosecutors and building employees. a decision is expected thursday
the u.s. marshal's office said the procedures were in response to a growing number of threats against the federal judiciary nationwide and an increase in terrorism trials. they follow recent trials of members of the el rukn street gang and the puerto rican independence group, faln, on terrorism-related charges
want to buy a million-dollar mansion with hardwood floors, chandeliers and a spiral staircase? a firm here will build you one on its assembly line and ship it to you in pieces on flatbed trucks
it's really an evolutionary thing for home building,'' said george oswald, treasurer of techno craft inc., a 3-year-old, privately held company
each two-story luxury home built by techno craft, which began production last august, has hardwood floors, a spiral staircase, chandeliers, a fireplace, jacuzzi, bidet and imported tiles. options include a steam room, sauna and an elevator
cunningham, 35, started the techno craft in 1985 when another company he heads had trouble finding an adequate supply of upscale housing in the new york metropolitan area
a dozen french archaeologists are racing against a swarm of bulldozers in this coastal village, trying to save precious history before it is churned to pieces by construction of the tunnel under the english channel
in reality, the race already is lost. according to the building schedule, only six months remain for the historians to save what they can from sites containing vestiges of paleolithic, neolithic, bronze age, iron age, gallo-roman, merovingian and medieval cultures
sites that normally would take years to excavate are being dug and studied in two months. the meticulous preparation through library and archives research is being put off until later. the focus is entirely on the ground, soon to be churned and destroyed
we know what we can't do,'' said jean-claude routier, chief of one crew working at a site on a chalk hill containing the remains of an 11th century church and an earlier burial ground. ``we select. we are starting to get used to the pressure.''
a colleague, jean-pierre jorrand, uncovering a nearby gallo-roman site, said ``we stress recovering knowledge over artifacts.''
president francois mitterrand of france and prime minister margaret thatcher of britain signed an accord in january 1986 for the construction of a rail tunnel for trains to carry freight, motor vehicles and passengers in both directions. it is scheduled for completion by 1993 at an estimated cost of about $8 billion, making it the largest privately financed building project ever attempted
though completion is still five years away, by september the earthmovers will have torn into the entire 2,200-acre area that will be the train terminal on the french side
the $442,000 budget for the archaeological excavations is provided jointly by the french culture ministry, the anglo-french eurotunnel building consortium, the state-run french railroad and local and regional governments
it's difficult for an archaeologist to work so fast,'' says luc vallin, conservator of antiquities and prehistory in the nord-pas de calais region of northern france as well as field director here. ``it's really rescue archaeology.''
the historians started working on an archaeological report in the autumn of 1985, before the tunnel accord was signed. the report was completed in march 1986, but archaeological work was delayed while a financing agreement was worked out
prospecting for potential digging sites began, with money advanced by eurotunnel, in september 1986, even before the budget agreement was reached. aerial surveys were made. mechanical shovels dug swaths across the ground in areas of potential archaeological value
twenty sites were selected
some excavation began in june 1987, but work really didn't get moving strongly until december
at one site, if we could have excavated it completely, we could have reconstructed entire gaullish houses,'' said vallin. ``as it was, we had to content ourselves with what could be saved.''
archaeologists know very little about the gallo-roman era in this region, roughly from boulogne to the belgian border. rural life in the medieval period also is a subject of great interest
perhaps it's in the medieval period that we are finding the most exciting material, and in protohistory,'' the bronze and iron ages, vallin said
the biggest problem, apart from time, is personnel
at some sites, we could have used 20 people for a year instead of three for two months,'' vallin said
relations with the tunnel builders have been fairly good, even if they sometimes push a little hard. the archaeologists and the construction men meet once a week to discuss schedules
the vast range of history covered by the digs requires a wide range of talent. most of the archaeologists are contract workers hired for a limited time, usually according to their speciality
from an educational point of view, i am a prehistorian,'' vallin said. ``but i have learned a lot about the roman and medieval periods.''
sitting on the chalk hill surveying the remains of a medieval church and nearby structures, crew chief routier was preparing to move on after 2{ months at the site
it would be interesting to dig up all the graves to study the methods of the period,'' he said. ``it's all going to disappear with the bulldozers.''
even so, vallin and the others said, without the tunnel project, it's likely the sites would not have been tapped at all because of lack of funding
it is the very picture of adventure, the climber planting a flag in triumph atop an icy himalayan peak. what isn't generally known, however, is that a mountain of paperwork has to be scaled first
mountain climbing in nepal, for all its risk and romance, also means conquering an array of permits, payments, insurance forms, and wills for sherpa guides. and then comes patience, for it can take years to get it all done
anyone who wants to climb the famed mount everest, for example, may have to wait six or seven years to get a nepalese government permit because the world's highest peak also is nepal's most desired challenge. then there are the expenses and 58 pages of rules set down by nepal's government
probably 80 percent of the effort is getting to the bottom of the mountain (to start the climb),'' says steve langley, a canadian leading a six-week expedition up 22,479-foot mount ama dablam, 10 miles southwest of everest
langley, a 40-year-old computer consultant from calgary, alberta, first applied to climb the mountain in 1982
we arrived here without the permit,'' he said. ``it was finally granted officially three weeks ago.''
murari p. khatiwada of nepal's mountaineering division says the long wait is due to the growing number of people who want to ascend 122 of the 1,310 peaks nepal grants permits for
ten years ago we had 20 expeditions throughout the year. now we have more than 100,'' said khatiwada
he explained that amounted to 800 to 1,000 climbers, not including the guides and porters, usually from the nimble sherpa tribe, who accompany foreign mountaineers
for this reason, khatiwada said, nearly all nepal's mountains are booked through 1990 and applications for some peaks are being accepted for the year 2000
he said it was vital to limit the number of climbers to protect nepal's environment
a mountain is fragile,'' he explained. ``it cannot bear the burden of too many people.''
just as frustrating as the wait for climbers are the government regulations, which get down to such details as how many socks, shoes and umbrellas must be supplied to guides and porters. they also list fees for the peaks. all that is just the beginning of an expedition's expenses
the permit to climb everest's 29,028 feet costs $2,547. for any other peak above 26,400 feet, the fee is $2,038. for mount ama dablam, it costs $1,528
langley's team of himself, four other canadians and an american has budgeted $24,000 for the climb, and he said ``we're doing it on the cheap.''
all his people are experienced and already have most of the needed equipment. the american climber, tom dickey, 31, of boulder, colo., has worked as a trekking guide in nepal
but the team is taking along a liaison officer, required by the government but paid by the expedition; a chief sherpa; an assistant, and 12 porters. salaries for all are specified in the government rules, along with the equipment to be provided them
langley said the actual gear is rarely given the sherpas, most of whom have equipment from earlier climbs, and a cash payment is usually negotiated in lieu of equipment
the daily salary, in the scheme of things, is peanuts,'' said langley
he said the pay to the government liaison officer, for example, is $2 a day. his equipment allowance comes to the equivalent of $800
other expenses include $1,000 for an agency to help ease the way through the nepalese bureaucracy, $350 for required insurance for climbers and sherpas, and the cost of getting climbers and their equipment to nepal
each man on langley's team is putting up $4,000 to make the climb, although expeditions often seek funds from mountaineering societies, philanthropists or companies wanting publicity for their products
peter hill, an englishman also leading an expedition up ama dablam, said he wrote 400 letters seeking backing without success
to get money these days for a peak, it's got to be unclimbed or it's got to be everest,'' he complained
but hill, 26, ran into a stroke of luck. his father happened upon a newspaper ad for a bank, perpetual unit trust, picturing its symbol _ the peak of ama dablam
dickey, the colorado climber, noted that mountaineers can avoid all the preliminary trouble by climbing europe's alps or the andes in south america, where no permits are needed
nevertheless, he said, ``i'm in on an everest expedition in 1990.''
although communist rebels threaten to attack u.s. businesses in the philippines, one american company is growing pineapples on a substantial chunk of mindanao island and showing little fear in doing it
it's a very open company and a very open society,'' said brian carew, field operations manager of the philippine packing corp., local subsidiary of rjr reynolds, which now owns the del monte brand of products. ``i feel safer here than in new york.''
communist rebels, who operate near this giant plantation some 500 miles southeast of manila, have threatened to attack american interests in retaliation for u.s. support of philippines governments that have been fighting the insurgents for 19 years
this past november the rival dole-philippines inc., considered abandoning its fruit plantation in mindanao's south cotabato province after raids by communist rebels resulted in more than $250,000 worth of property and equipment damage
the del monte plantation, in bukidnon province, has no fencing and only a small security force
in december, communist new people's army guerrillas raided a military camp in the bukidnon town of don carlos and made off with a machine gun, more than 20 automatic assault rifles, grenades and thousands of rounds of ammunition
carew, a native of dorchester, mass., said communist bands occasionally pass through the western side of the plantation but have not attacked. he said del monte does not pay the rebels protection money
since del monte began operations in the philippines in 1926, its holdings have grown from about 9,880 acres to more than 61,750 acres around the towns of impasugong, sumilao, libona and manolo fortich
one-third of the land is leased from the government's national development corp. for about $16 an acre a year. the rest is leased from local farmers
company officials said in interviews with the associated press that del monte employs about 10,600 workers, including about 100 at company headquarters in manila. most workers come from bukidnon and neighboring misamis oriental province
the subsidiary had gross sales of $110 million last year and net income of $20.7 million. it earned $78.8 million in hard currency for the philippines and paid the philippines peso equivalent of $21 million in taxes
company officials estimate that about 60,000 people in the area depend on the plantation
at camp philipps, the largest of the subsidiary's seven camps, workers's quarters are simple but adequate. a large social hall dominates the main road, next to a cooperative store where workers buy most of their daily needs
speak english'' signs are posted on the walls of the camp's vocational school for boys
children of management officials, including carew's 12-year-old daughter, jessica, attend the del monte school up to seventh grade. the school teaches 20 to 25 children, about three-fourths of them filipino
private secondary schools and colleges are subsidized by the comany and tuition fees are comparatively low
officials said the average daily salary is 105 pesos ($5.25), nearly double the mandated minimum wage. medical treatment is free. housing, including electricity and water, is free for some 2,000 senior employees while others get housing allowances
brian haycox, the philippines company president, said del monte believes in above average worker benefits because ``we can't run our business, manage it and address all the issues facing us today unless we have good human resource development.''
the company does not allow visiting journalists to interview workers unless accompanied by an official
i don't apologize to anybody about what we do because we do it well,'' carew told a group of visiting reporters
the company came in for criticism this past october in report by a swiss mission that visited in february 1987. the mission, made up of the migros cooperative society, swiss aid, helbetas, swiss lenten fund and bread for brethren, said many workers complained of harassment and intimidation by lower- and middle-grade supervisors and of unjustified promotions
the overriding feeling is one of fear of losing the job,'' the report said. ``mistrust of the company is widespread.''
it added that workers showed ``little confidence'' in their unions, the associated labor union and the workers alliance of trade unions, which it said are perceived as pro-management
but worker activity against the company has been limited
some workers have been picketing the company's cannery in nearby gugo, and a company bus was set afire early this year
the swiss mission report also criticized the company's policy of leasing land from local farmers, charging the leases are couched in language the farmers can't understand
adrian pabayo, the company's public relations manager, defended the policy
there is enough land available here not being used,'' he said
three years after he was swept to office in a landslide, prime minister rajiv gandhi has become the target of a vociferous opposition campaign for his ouster
anti-government rallies have been drawing thousands of slogan-shouting demonstrators to new delhi. parliament has been disrupted by angry walk-outs. general strikes have closed businesses and schools
we think he is vulnerable,'' said prakash karat of the marxist communist party of india, which has helped organize some of the agitation. ``if he dares to call a mid-term poll (snap election), the opposition has a good chance of winning.''
in karat's eyes, the 43-year-old prime minister has brought the problems on himself. he cited charges of corruption, rising sikh separatist violence in punjab state and mounting economic problems
gandhi has so far rejected calls for a snap election, and aides and some independent analysts say the opposition parties are too much in disarray to beat him anyway
the handful of factions are united only in their anti-gandhi fervor and often tend to compete more with each other. no overall leader has emerged from among the dissidents
the indian press, alive to rumors that gandhi may indeed call an election, has begun talking about his ``tina factor,'' an acronym for ``there is no alternative.'' supporters and detractors alike say tina may ensure that gandhi not only weathers the political storm but emerges with a second, five-year term
a poll of more than 10,000 voters conducted in february for india today, a biweekly news magazine, indicated that if parliament elections were held now, gandhi's congress party would win 64 percent of the seats
that would be down from the 77 percent congress won in december 1984, when gandhi came to power on a wave of sympathy two months after his mother and predecessor, indira gandhi, was assassinated by two sikh bodyguards. but it's more than enough to form a government in india's multiparty system
rajiv gandhi's congress benefits from the tina factor precisely because the opposition parties show no signs of coming together,'' india today concluded
ashis nandy, a political analyst at the center for the study of developing societies, doesn't agree. regardless of what opinion polls show, he said, the opposition could defeat gandhi
the indian electorate traditionally either rewards a regime for ruling well or punishes it for ruling badly,'' nandy added. ``although rajiv gandhi may still be personally honest, he looks tainted, looks inefficient. the voters do not feel good about him.''
just who would lead an opposition charge nationally remains in question. the strongest contender is v.p. singh, who was gandhi's finance minister and then defense minister before being ousted from the congress party on grounds of anti-party activity
singh now assails gandhi as ``a total failure.'' he and a dozen other congress dissidents have been trying to forge alliances with other opposition groups. no common front has emerged, in part because leftist groups like the communist party refuse to ally themselves with right-wing, hindu-dominated parties like the bharatiya janata party
gandhi enjoyed a honeymoon, of sorts, during his first two years in office. an airline pilot before moving into politics, he promised to modernize india and was nicknamed ``mr. clean'' for his pledge to bring honest government to the 800 million indians
with the congress-dominated parliament behind him, gandhi liberalized industrial policy, modified the tax system to encourage private investment and increased funding for education and health
last year, the honeymoon ended. first came the disclosure that gandhi's finance ministry had hired an american detective agency to investigate the illegal overseas bank accounts of indians, a controversial move in a nation wary of foreign influence
next came the announcement that the government was investigating alleged kickbacks paid on contracts for swedish artillery and west german submarines
opposition leaders and several powerful newspapers seized the corruption issue and hammered away with allegations that some of the bribes went to gandhi or his allies in the congress party
none of the charges were proved, but gandhi was forced to go to parliament and deny personal involvement
at the same time, domestic problems mounted
_the annual monsoon rains failed, plunging two-thirds of the nation into drought
_attacks by sikh extremists in punjab rose dramatically, leaving more than 1,000 people dead by the end of 1987
_an indian-sponsored peace accord in nearby sri lanka was signed but shortly collapsed. although gandhi has sent more than 50,000 troops to the island to put down a tamil separatist rebellion, the opposition has not focused on the issue
last year there was a tremendous amount of uncertainty,'' said a gandhi aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``we weathered it. since then, a lot of high temperatures have come down.''
today is monday, march 28, the 88th day of 1988. there are 278 days left in the year
   today's highlight in history:
on march 28th, 1979, the worst u.s. commercial nuclear accident occurred inside the no. 2 reactor at pennsylvania's three mile island power plant. a cooling system malfunctioned, damaging the reactor's core and leaking radioactivity
on this date:
in 1797, nathaniel briggs of new hampshire patented a washing machine
in 1834, the u.s. senate voted to censure president andrew jackson for the removal of federal deposits from the bank of the united states
in 1930, the names of the turkish cities of constantinople and angora were changed to istanbul and ankara
in 1939, the spanish civil war ended as madrid fell to the forces of francisco franco
in 1941, novelist and critic virginia woolf died in lewes, england
in 1942, during world war ii, british naval forces raided the nazi-occupied french port of st. nazaire
in 1943, composer sergei rachmaninoff died in beverly hills, calif
in 1953, athlete jim thorpe died in lomita, calif
in 1969, the 34th president of the united states, dwight d. eisenhower, died in washington at the age of 78
in 1977, ``rocky'' won the academy award for best picture of 1976. awards for best actor and best actress went to the late peter finch and to faye dunaway, for ``network.''
