today's birthdays: former british prime minister james callaghan is 76. singer snooky lanson is 74. former secretary of state cyrus r. vance is 71. singer sarah vaughan is 64. newspaper columnist anthony lewis is 61. dance company director arthur mitchell is 54. actor michael york is 46
thought for today: ``an optimist is a man who starts a crossword puzzle with a fountain pen.'' -- anonymous
police have restored order in tibetan streets following the second bloody pro-independence protest in five months, but china's policy toward the rugged area remains in disorder with signs of backstage wrangling
on the one side are officials who argue for leniency, noting that the chinese earned the hatred of tibetans during the 1960s and 1970s by virtually outlawing buddhism, the center of most tibetans' lives
the panchen lama, the highest-ranking tibetan religious leader in china, is among these. an official news report after a protest march 5 quoted him as saying china must ``further improve regional autonomy ... and heal the wounds caused by the ultra-leftist line.''
he promised ``even more lenient and flexible policies'' from beijing, whose rule he supports
on the other side are those who believe beijing's relative leniency since 1980 is to blame for the unrest and that only a tough crackdown will ensure it is not repeated
it is necessary to exercise dictatorship over such separatists,'' the director of united front's tibet department, zheng ying, was quoted as saying. the united front is an organization that seeks to coordinate relations between the governing communist party and other parties, which are few
other reports have quoted unidentified officials as declaring that the government ``has exercised too much restraint.''
so far, neither side appears to have won out. sketchy reports from foreign travelers to tibet's capital, lhasa, indicate widespread arrests but the monasteries do not appear to be under direct police control, as they were after demonstratons last year
no foreign journalists have been allowed in lhasa since march 5
piecing together official accounts and those of foreign witnesses, this picture emerges of what happened that day:
hundreds of monks had gathered outside the 1,300-year-old jokhang temple in tibet's capital, lhasa, for the conclusion of a 10-day prayer festival. one monk stood up suddenly and called for tibetan independence
as police dragged him away, other monks took up the chant and stoned the officers. more than 12 hours of violence followed, during which thousands of tibetans stoned police from behind makeshift barricades and burned chinese restaurants. police set off tear gas and stormed the jokhang
according to official accounts, one policeman was killed and more than 30 hospitalized. western travelers in lhasa said tibetans reported 21 tibetans and three policemen killed
in its duration and scope, the protest appeared much larger than the attack by thousands of tibetans oct. 1 on a police station in lhasa. foreign witnesses reported at least 14 people killed then
the new violence makes it clear the violence oct. 1 was not an isolated incident, the result of momentarily high emotions, but rather an expression of tibetan determination to shake off 37 years of chinese communist rule
it thus makes more difficult beijing's task of charting a policy most likely to keep the peace
those who favor conciliation and greater autonomy and development aid for tibetans hope to gain time for a gradual cultural assimilation under the gentle pressure of chinese schools, television and other influences
but those opposed to liberal policies argue that relaxation has fostered rebellion by allowing tibet's buddhist monasteries to reopen and enroll new candidates
the monasteries have become hotbeds of religious-inspired nationalism, with most monks praying for the return of the dalai lama, tibet's former temporal and spiritual leader now in exile in india
the dalai lama, regarded as a reincarnation of tibet's protector god, fled in 1959 during a failed uprising against chinese rule. the dalai lama is central to tibetan buddhism, which in turn is central to tibetans' cultural identity
the clashes oct. 1 and march 5 began when monks shouted independence slogans, and the youngest monks generally led the violence
a harsh crackdown on the monasteries might crush this source of nationalism _ or encourage more martyrdom
it also could trigger concern in china's other minority areas about the depth of beijing's commitment to their own local autonomy. most of china's strategic border regions are populated by minorities
notable in the aftermath of the protest was the lack of any significant u.s. response. after the oct. 1 clash, the u.s. senate adopted a resolution urging greater respect for human rights in tibet. the resolution prompted angry protests from china of what it called interference in its internal affairs
this time, foreign minister wu xueqian of china was in the united states but u.s. officials did not mention tibet in public
u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz raised the issue in private talks with wu but it was not allowed to disturb the visit's overall atmosphere of friendliness. instead, the reagan administration lifted a freeze on expanding sales of high-technology goods to china. the freeze was imposed last year to protest chinese missile sales to iran
china's liberal policies in tibet created the conditions that sparked bloody riots in lhasa in october and early march, according to american tibet scholars and u.s. officials
in an ironic twist, the observers say, beijing's attempts to improve the lot of the tibetan people have caused a crisis of higher expectations, prompting tibetans to seek faster change from a recalcitrant beijing
these observers predict that rioting in the province's capital, lhasa, on march 5 will prompt an iron-fisted crackdown and the return of hardline chinese rule to the ``roof of the world.''
such a crackdown will postpone again any possibility of resolving china's main minority problem, ensuring renewed suffering for tibetans
tibetans are grabbing for a mile when the chinese are offering them an inch,'' said a state department official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``we see little possibility for resolution.''
after (the disturbances march 5) a military response is the only way,'' said tom grunfeld, a tibetan expert and professor at the state university of new york's empire state college in manhattan. ``it's part of the sad equation in tibet.''
china has claimed sovereignty over the himalayan region since the 13th century. but many tibetans view the chinese as an occupying force and yearn for independence
in 1950 the chinese red army entered tibet and beijing promised tibetan leaders a measure of autonomy. it failed to deliver
nine years later, tibetans rebelled. the chinese army cracked down and the dalai lama, tibet's temporal and spiritual leader, fled to india
in 1966, conditions further deteriorated with the onset of china's ultra-leftist cultural revolution
atheist chinese red guards, charging that tibet was backward and feudalistic, attempted to destroy its buddhist culture. of tibet's 3,000 temples only a handful survived. thousands of monks and religious pilgrims were slaughtered
grunfeld said his interviews with refugees gave no indications of sustained unrest among the tibetan people from 1959 to 1976
the chinese clamped a very tight lid on tibet. any protest was crushed immediately.''
conditions in tibet began to improve after the end of the cultural revolution with the death of chairman mao tse-tung in 1976
hu yaobang, the former communist party boss, went to lhasa and issued a public apology for the excesses of the cultural revolution
for the first time since 1959, tibetans were allowed to travel from one county to the next without government permission
hospitals were built, the tibetan language was allowed back in the schools and taxes were cut or eliminated. china opened its border with nepal, allowing renewed contact with the tibetan exile community
with an eye to a profitable tourist trade, the chinese also began repairing some of the monasteries destroyed by the red guards. a prohibition on buddhist proselytzing was lifted and young monks appeared again in the temples
in 1980, representatives of the dalai lama began negotiations with the chinese to set conditions for his return to china. negotiations broke off two years later because the chinese insisted that he live in beijing and he wanted to live in lhasa
the chinese are pumping millions of dollars into the region and there are only 3 million people there,'' grunfeld said. ``things are looking up, especially in the cities.''
emboldened by reforms, tibetans staged pro-independence demonstrations in september and october last year and again march 5 and 6
the demonstrations were led by monks, tibet's traditional soldiers, who grunfeld said, don't fit the western idea of ``a contemplative individual making cheese and wine.''
the observers said china's reforms prompted the riots because they allowed tibetans to congregate more freely without fear of instant repression. the reforms also allowed contact with tibetans abroad. and by opening tibet to western tourists, the chinese provided the monks with an international stage for their protests
the success of the reforms also played a hand
the reforms have created among some tibetan refugees a sense of desperation,'' said the state department official. ``it's like they said, `we've got to act now or we'll never be able to do it again.'''
many tibetans claim the reforms are insidious, aimed at turning tibet into a living museum to boost china's tourism industry
they also claim their land is being overrun by hordes of chinese, sent in from beijing to sinicize the remote region
grunfeld says the truth of that allegation depends on how one defines tibet
tibet's current boundaries correspond to its traditional political influence. but tibetan activists define tibet as the area of its traditional cultural influence which includes large tracts of qinghai, sichuan and yunnan provinces
grunfeld said thousands of chinese settlers are moving to those three provinces but few are going to tibet
but he added that the region cannot lure enough competent chinese officials to manage it
it's a dumping ground for incompetents. the chinese can't get anyone to go there.''
blacks' most obvious gains in the two decades since martin luther king's assassination have come in politics. from an era in which people had to march, and sometimes die, to win blacks the right to vote, the united states today is listening seriously to a black presidential candidate and counts thousands of black elected officials, including the mayors of 17 of its largest cities. but as the second story of three assessing black progress in america reports, it is one of its smallest towns, bolton, miss., that is considered a model of political advancement
the final major area of untapped power for the negro is in the political arena.''
_ martin luther king jr
its decaying store fronts, tar-paper roofs and rusty railroad tracks suggest bolton is just another town time forgot
but each day, a sign of how much times have changed appears when a tall, slender black man drives up to city hall. the street is named after martin luther king jr., and the man is the mayor
lawrence butler, a man once barred from the ballot box, now presides over this ragged rural hamlet some call a model of black political progress in america
no blacks were allowed to vote in bolton municipal elections until 1969. today, its mayor and four of five council members are black. change, indeed, but butler says blacks still haven't reached the mountaintop
i know we ain't where we used to be,'' he said. ``lord, we ain't where we ought to be. sometimes, i question myself, where are we?''
in the 15 years since it elected its first black mayor, bolton, population 650, has built a new city hall and community center, paved streets, built houses, bought land for an industrial park and acquired an ambulance and fire and garbage trucks
what bolton represents since it got black leadership is certainly progress, for blacks, even for whites,'' said linda williams, senior political analyst at the joint center for political studies in washington
bolton is a prime example of ``how blacks deprived in a segregated system ... can take political power, turn a town around and make it more responsive to the needs of black citizens,'' said attorney frank parker
parker spearheaded many legal fights on behalf of elected blacks seeking to take office in bolton. courts and judges intervened, federal pollwatchers came to town and death threats were made before it all came about
hundreds of other communities in all corners of the united states have made white-to-black political transitions in the 20 years since king's assassination. some of the biggest change has come in the south, home to more than half of the u.s. black population
blacks are running towns they marched through in the '60s, fighting for the right to vote. the number of southern black elected officials has increased by 55 times since 1965, williams said
mississippi, where civil rights leader medgar evers was slain in front of his house, where riots erupted when james meredith tried to enter college and the late gov. ross barnett, surrounded by a cadre of state troopers, turned him away, has 548 black elected officials _ tops in the nation
mississippi has changed in many ways. bolton is part of the metamorphosis
the no. 1 progress is getting rid of the fear,'' said butler, who picked cotton as a child and once picketed a whites-only pool with a sign that urged, ``don't blow your cool. let us in the pool.''
used to be you had a fear of somebody coming up to you and ... accusing you of anything,'' he said. ``you might have a confrontation with a white and there was no such thing as winning.''
butler never doubted blacks could manage bolton. he just didn't think it would happen
i figured whites would have died before they let us have the right to vote,'' he said. ``some did. and blacks did, too.''
black officeholders here, he said, have given folks ``a certain sense of pride and understanding. blacks know there's somebody here on a day-to-day basis fighting for them.''
still, black leadership has not made poor people richer, or two societies one
butler estimates blacks' annual income in bolton at about $4,500 _ about a third that of whites. he said about 25 percent of blacks are jobless
although blacks and whites live together, they attend separate churches and social functions, and white children attend private schools
i would love to paint you a peaches-and-cream story,'' said bennie thompson, the town's first black mayor, now a member of the hinds county board of supervisors
i want to tell you i stand by my fence and drink coffee (with my white) neighbor. i can't tell you that. it's not reality.''
everybody gets along,'' said doug beard, the sole white council member. ``(but) i think both feel better with their own peers.''
in bolton, politics brings neither power nor prestige. the mayor and council are part-time posts. there are no big salaries, no high-profile jobs
and there's little to lure outsiders, particularly with jackson 16 miles away. a cotton gin is virtually the only industry, and the main drag is a row of crumbling, century-old stores
still, bolton was important enough to cause a lot of kicking and screaming when blacks, about 60 percent of the population, wanted a say in government
it was a long, tough fight _ harder and tougher than any i've ever seen in mississippi,'' said parker, now at the lawyers' committee for civil rights under law in washington, d.c
the whites perceived their town as their plantation. it was theirs to run.''
the fight began in the late '60s. thompson, a local college graduate who marched in mississippi with king, felt blacks had been ignored long enough
it wasn't an attempt to take over,'' he said. ``all we wanted to do is help develop the community.'' blacks, including thompson, sought three of five aldermanic seats
after fights over registration procedures, and complaints filed with federal authorities, the blacks won. the losers sued, alleging voter irregularities. the blacks prevailed in appeals court
but after the mayor repeatedly vetoed the black aldermen's proposals, thompson ran for mayor in 1973 on an all-black slate. that winning slate also was sued _ unsuccessfully
this town has generated more voting litigation than any i know of in mississippi to keep blacks from taking office,'' parker said
that was just the beginning. when thompson took office, the police department quit, the county repossessed the garbage truck and the lease on the garbage dump was revoked. thompson said he found that town records were kept on a school notepad, water bill monies were stored in a lard can and town employees were paid from the general store, which was then reimbursed
being black, we couldn't afford to operate the system like our counterparts,'' he explained, because it would make them vulnerable to corruption charges. ``the system would have destroyed us. what kinds of checks and balances do you have putting money in a lard can?''
to make matters worse, bolton lacked the basics. fires, for example, were fought with a pickup truck with a loose wheel and a pump on the back
so thompson launched a letter-writing campaign, asking foundations and cities for help. it came: a fire truck, donated for one dollar, from new york city; a garbage truck from southfield, mich.; an ambulance from marshalltown, iowa, and a planner from the national council of churches who developed a town hall, fire station, park and day-care center
gravel streets in the black neighborhoods were paved, sewer and water improvements were made. a $1.1 million, 40-unit, subsidized housing development was built for low-income and elderly residents in the middle of the white part of town, drawing angry opposition
we have shown that black elected officials can bring a community from virtual obscurity into the 20th century _ from the standpoint of municipal services, human and social needs,'' said thompson, who says he has received death threats over the years. ``but we also created hope that things can be better. there was no hope. there was nothing.''
some disagree. while beard concedes some improvements have been made, ``the overall appearance of the city is much worse,'' he said. ``business is worse because people don't like coming to an area (that looks) deplorable.''
thompson stepped down in 1979 to become a board member in the county _ one of the first two blacks. butler, who moved to bolton as a teen-ager, has been mayor since, running unopposed in 1985
parker says whites ``have basically deserted the political process.''
beard says they don't seek office for ``the same reason blacks are not runnning in bolton. people just don't care, to be honest.''
thompson says they do, and black leadership has changed bolton
there are young people in our community who've never seen anybody in authority except somebody who's black. they're good role models,'' he said. ``black elected officials clearly represent a new awakening. ..
we can't run this community like our white predecessors. we want things to be accessible to everybody.''
sharon cohen is the ap midwest regional reporter, based in chicago. ^with laserphoto</head>
they are a new breed of leaders, protesters turned politicians, outsiders turned insiders, the powerless become powerful
blacks are reshaping politics across america, calling the shots today in towns where they risked beatings, cattle prods, jail and even death a generation ago as they fought for the right to vote
nationwide, almost 6,700 blacks held elected office last year, more than four times that of 1970, according to the joint center for political studies, a black-oriented think tank in washiks now lead four of the nation's six largest cities _ tom bradley in los angeles, eugene sawyer in chicago, wilson goode in philadelphia and coleman young in ngton
blacdetroit. thirteen other big cities have black mayors, including marion barry of washington, d.c., and andrew young of atlanta
blacks have more than doubled their ranks in congress in 20 years. and jesse jackson, a one-time lieutenant of martin luther king jr., is making surprising inroads among white voters in his second white house bid
twenty years ago, it would have been unthinkable,'' said u.s. rep. john lewis of georgia, a veteran civil rights activist.ch some manufacturers of distilled spirits avoid a significant share of the $12.50-a-gallon liquor tax by mixing some products with a grape-based alcohol. this is expected to raise $360 million over five years
the committee's bill does nothing about a 1986 law, also aimed at tax evaders, that requires about 82,000 state, city and county government units to pay taxes of 9.1 cents a gallon on their gasoline and apply later for a refund. that provision took effect jan. 1
black power was to me a black version of ethnic american politics,'' said charles hamilton, a columbia university political science professor and co-author with carmichael of ``black power _ the politics of liberation in america.''
we're talking about no more than what italians have done, what the irish have done,'' he said. ``before we almost had to assimilate in order to achieve. i saw that as wrong. it denied one's heritage.''
black power gave birth to a new sense of self-worth
what the black power movement was all about was you've got to shed the negative image,'' morris said. ``that's why you got (the phrase) `black is beautiful.' there was a profound evaluation of black people, of who they are.''
it was a repudiation of the notion blacks had to judge their own beauty and importance by white standards,'' he added
new styles and customs emerged, emphasizing black roots: afro-american names, mushrooming afro hairdos and loose-fitting, boldly patterned dashikis
one symbol _ the clenched fist _ stirred anger, and sometimes fear. at the 1968 mexico city olympics, just six months after king's assassination, sprinters tommie smith and john carlos, the gold and bronze medal winners in the 200-meter dash, raised black-gloved fists high overhead as the national anthem was played. for what they termed a display of black unity and protest of black poverty, the two athletes were suspended by the u.s. olympic committee
the symbols and words of black power shocked many whites, even some who marched in civil rights demonstrations
some ``found it extremely threatening,'' said douglas mcadam, associate sociology professor at the university of arizona. to them, ``it smacked of reverse racism _ no longer equality, but black power, black domination.''
mcadam has written a book chronicling how financial contributions dropped when groups such as the student non-violent coordinating committee, a civil rights organization, shifted focus from the fight for equality to more incendiary urgings
the movement also divided blacks. king, who preached non-violent tactics, said the slogan carried the wrong connotations and was potentially destructive
separatism wasn't the answer, he argued, because blacks and whites needed each other. ``there is no salvation for the negro through isolation,'' king wrote in his book, ``where do we go from here: chaos or community?''
he thought it was too divisive, too difficult to explain,'' hamilton said. ``he was right.''
other black leaders and groups, including the naacp, also opposed the black power term, creating friction as two movements competed for center stage
the civil rights movement was overrun,'' walters said. ``many of its leaders would not join black power. ... more fundamentally, it took away the allegiance of the people.''
but academics also note that black leaders eventually supported many of the movement's goals. king, in particular, embraced the psychological need for black power and the importance of black economic strength
after his assassination, the movement took new forms as some of its causes became mainstream
once blacks got the vote and began to elect more (blacks), people began to believe they at least had channels,'' said linda williams, senior political analyst at the joint center for political studies
the black power movement also weakened as radicals were jailed and the government cracked down; the fbi conducted a secret campaign of ``dirty tricks'' involving faked panther documents and letters, informants and infiltrators
it was surprising to me the movement was destroyed so completely,'' said newton, panther co-founder. newton today believes any gains made by the black power movement have been wiped out
black unemployment is very high,'' he said. ``police actions are as belligerent as ever. overt racism is on the rampage as if there never was a movement.''
with the hindsight of 20 years, some criticize black power as merely words without a program. others say it left a strong legacy
academics point to the growth of black-owned businesses, newspapers and radio stations, as well as greater numbers of black journalists and literature and arts programs
others cite the thousands of black officeholders and jesse jackson's strong presidential bid. ``black power today is being carried out in the electoral arena,'' jennings sai
universities offer hundreds of black studies programs, and hamilton credits the movement for the formation of such groups as the congressional black caucus
still, the movement has not given all blacks power
in economics, there have been a lot of gains, but they've been concentrated in the black middle class,'' said clayborne carson, a stanford university history professor and editor of the martin luther king papers project
the group left out is the poor,'' he said. ``the irony is that's who black power was supposed to help the most.''
sharon cohen is the ap midwest regional reporter, based in chicago
here is a rundown of some 1960s black activists and where they are today:
_ h. rap brown, who said ``violence is as american as apple pie,'' is now a devout muslim known as jamil abdullah al-amin. he runs a convenience store in atlanta
_ huey p. newton, who helped found the black panthers, lives in oakland, calif., and says he lectures around the country about ``political philosophies'' and ``the realities of the 1960s.'' he also said he is writing his memoirs
_ eldridge cleaver, one-time panther information minister and author of the acclaimed ``soul on ice,'' lives in berkeley, calif. a mormon and conservative republican, cleaver recently told ebony magazine he lectures to conservative groups and makes and sells ceramic objects
in 1986, cleaver unsuccessfully sought the republican nomination for the u.s. senate in california
cleaver fled the country for several years in the late 1960s after a shootout between the panthers and the police. he told ebony that after spending time in china, algeria and north vietnam he ended his advocacy of communism and ``developed an understanding and respect for free enterprise and the democratic political system.''
_ stokely carmichael, a former chairman of the student non-violent coordinating committee, whose chant of ``black power'' became a slogan for a movement, is now known as kwame toure and travels between guinea and the united states, said charles hamilton, a political science professor at columbia university. hamilton and carmichael wrote a book together
toure is a full-time organizer for the all-african peoples revolutionary party, working toward pan-african socialist principles, hamilton said. pan-africanism is the unity of all people of african descent
_ bobby seale, who also helped organize the panthers, is working for temple university in philadelphia as a community liaison for the department of african american studies and a recruiter for students for the college of arts and sciences
_ marion barry, first chairman of sncc, is mayor of washington, d.c
barry once dressed in dashikis and urged blacks not to celebrate the apollo moon landing because ``white america's money and technology'' had not reached the inner city
a former chemistry teacher, barry went to washington for sncc and worked as a fund-raiser. he later ran a job-training program, pride inc., and served on the washington school board and city council
_ john lewis, also a one-time sncc chairman, is a georgia congressman. a former member of the atlanta city council, lewis was among those leading a line of 600 marchers to the edmund pettus bridge in selma, ala., where officers clubbed, tear-gassed and bull-whipped blacks trying to march to montgomery in march 1965. ^agencies and radio out</note> ^from ap newsfeatures</note> photo and 1 illustration

editor's note _ to be or not to be metric is perhaps our longest national debate. a 1975 attempt to speed things along missed by a mile. but 62 percent of fortune 1,000 companies now make something that's metric. if the meter has wedged a foot in the back door of the nation, can the kilogram be far behind?
___ ^by sid moody</note>
whatever became of the indy 804.5 and the rest of the metric system?
the whole thing went away and died,'' says ray lloyd of the scale manufacturers association
he meant the 1975 act of congress which was to have consigned pounds, inches, rods, furlongs, picas, acres, gills, gallons, miles per hour and their myriad cousins to the trash bin for a brave new world of metrics. officially, three bureaucrats, a secretary and a $250,000 budget inside the huge department of commerce in washington are what remain of that vision of a metric america
but inch by inch the meter has wedged a foot in the back door of the nation
oh, a miss is still as good as a mile. lovers still love, a bushel and a peck, not a liter and a stere
but almost all american cars are built to metric measure. booze and wine come by the liter. skis, film, pharmaceuticals are in millimeters and grams. edwin moses runs the 400-meter hurdles. almost all grade-schoolers learn some metrics. ``star wars,'' when and if, will be metric, as the pentagon honorably discharges the old measurements inherited from great britain where a yard was the distance from henry i's nose to the tip of his middle finger
sixty-two percent of the fortune 1,000 companies make something that's metric. thirty-four percent of their new products are. in five or six years probably all packaged goods on supermarket shelves will be labeled gram-liters as well as pound-ounces. most significantly, an omnibus trade bill to be voted on this spring by congress contains a provision requiring 42 agencies of the federal government to basically go metric by september 30, 1993. that includes the department of defense, the biggest buyer of them all. in hearings last summer, no organized constituency opposed the metric portion of the bill
ask anyone who knows a hand (four inches) from a hectare: will america ever be metric? the invariable answer: inevitably. when? nobody can say. congress is charged by the constitution with regulating weights and measures. congress is congress. and old habits are old habits
in the metric conversion act of 1975, congress declared it the policy of the united states to ``coordinate and plan ... the voluntary (stress added) conversion to the metric system.''
this bold pronouncement, toothless as a professional hockey player, was akin to telling the nation's 4-year-olds: ``eat your broccoli because it's good for you, but you can stick to ice cream if you want.'' americans, by and large, preferred vanilla
to be or not to be metric is called america's longest debate. congress almost adopted the meter in 1896. but the nation's largest trading partner, britain and its empire, were pound-inches. the united states went along
inch-pounds led and lead the world because of the standards and technology that support them,'' says charles wilson, director of engineering for the industrial fastener institute
by the 1960s, however, american industry was expanding overseas into a largely metric world. in 1969 the united states exported $14 billion in measure-sensitive products and imported only $6 billion. but by 1975 it was estimated the nation would suffer a $600 million loss in foreign business because it was not metric
in 1971 the national bureau of standards, whose official yard and pound are based on metric measure, completed a three-year study of metrication. two years later general motors announced it would make metric cars. the 1975 act originally set a 10-year schedule for conversion. heavy lobbying, particularly by trade unions and small businesses, struck this out. while the act set up a 17-member metric board, it was only empowered to ``publicize,'' ``encourage,'' ``consult,'' ``assist.''
how can you do something if it's not mandated?'' asks metric hard-liner louis sokol, past president of the private u.s. metric association. ``we don't make speed limits or the income tax voluntary. the metric board just became a debating society.''
we missed an opportunity 13 years ago,'' gerald underwood concedes. his office of metric programs _ that four-person operation at the commerce department _ is what survives of the metric board that once had 100 employees and a $3 million annual budget. ronald reagan cut off its funds in 1982
metrication should have been presented in terms of trade instead of conformance,'' says underwood. ``focused on the pocketbook instead of the agony of converting the housewife's recipe book. but i believe in free enterprise rather than government dictate.''
we felt the enormity of the problem of conversion was completely underestimated,'' says bob woods, research director for the international brotherhood of electrical workers
machinists and carpenters would have to buy new tools. they'd be fired for mismeasuring. above all, foreign metric goods would pour in
of course, that's what happened anyway,'' says sokol
just what metric conversion nationally might cost seems impossible to calculate. one unattributed estimate was $25 billion over 30 years. the pentagon has said it would cost the defense industry $18 billion, three-fourths of that in the first 10 years. the steel industry had a figure of $2 billion in 1973 but said actuality was ``nothing close'' to the original estimate
the ford motor company started with a metrication department which became a section, then a group and then me,'' says george baumgartner, whose job as metric planner was done away with last year. ``the cost was negligible. everything is now metric except the speedometer and tire rims. our biggest problem is how to spell liter. l-i-t-r-e?''
gm found the accounting costs for conversion cost more than conversion itself,'' says sokol. the pharmaceutical industry, which converted in the 1950s, said the cost was lower than expected and produced savings through fewer mistakes, easier employee training and improved records
small businesses, on the other hand, don't have the economies of scale
machine tools can cost $2 million,'' says wilson of the fastener institute. ``changing dies is very expensive, so you want to make as many items as you can without having to tear the machine up to make another size. the u.s. uses 200 billion fasteners a year. it would cost billions to stock dual sizes.''
john deere, where underwood was head of standards, spent one-third the value of its shelf parts on annual inventory. ``part of that cost is insurance, space, heat, light. standardization reduces these costs. we used to have about 70 screw sizes. metrication reduced that to 12 or 15, which meant economies in buying in bulk, number of bins and errors
for the nation it's almost impossible to figure a cost. but we figure each $1 billion in manufacturing means 30,000 jobs. anything that metrication does to improve our international trade is then part of that equation.''
to purists, the late 1970s were the ``golden years'' of metrication. interstate highway signs announced distances in miles-kilometers. schools blossomed with colorful conversion posters. shell oil spent $2 million converting 16,000 gas stations. sunrise, fla., said it would go entirely metric to celebrate the bicentennial
motorists immediately began ``screaming their heads off,'' says the federal highway administration. in 1978 congress took the signs down. shell soon found metric gas pumps confused drivers and converted back to gallons. when the national geographic society started using metrics on maps and stories, some 70 readers said the magazine had gone pinko and canceled their subscriptions
metric zealots ``just kind of gave up and went looking for other crusades,'' says valerie antoine, executive director of the u.s. metric association
metericians hoped the schools would incubate a metric america. ``but when the rest of society didn't keep pace, teachers said `hey, we got left out on a limb,''' says leroy negus, associate in mathematics at the n.y. state department of education
california said all its textbooks would be metric by 1985. they aren't. but almost all schools in the country include some metric instruction. october 10 _ get it? 10-10 _ still kicks off national metric week
the effort is to get children to think metric as well as know it, to know right off that 28 degrees celsius is hot outside without multiplying nine-fifths plus 32 to get fahrenheit
kent ashworth of educational testing service, the princeton, n.j., organization that gives scholastic aptitude tests, says a survey of 13-year-olds showed those who use metrics ``often'' outside class more than doubled _ 16 percent to 34 percent _ between 1978 and 1982
but in a 1981 test given internationally, american students finished near the bottom in measurement skills
children are taught both systems,'' says sokol. ``they are knowledgeable in both and proficient in neither.''
as a ninth-grader wrote the late commerce secretary malcolm baldridge: ``if you ask me it's confusing using both (systems) when our nation could choose one ... please keep this letter in consideration and remember all of the confused kids in this country.''
sokol worries, too, about adult education. why did some newspapers convert the 70- and 80-meter ski jump results at the recent calgary winter olympics to feet? why, when president reagan clunked 14-pound congressional bills on the dais in his recent state of the union address, didn't he call them 6.2-kilogram bills? ``what a wasted opportunity,'' bemoans sokol
the united states stands alone with burma as the only non-metric holdouts in a kilogram world. canada said in 1970 it would go metric and did. its metric commission disbanded in 1985. ``no problems,'' says francois broeur of the ministry of consumer and corporate affairs
he probably didn't talk to larae willson, an american housewife in thunder bay, ont. ``liters schmeeters. i just tell the man to fill up the tank. i follow my butcher from safeway to safeway because he'll sell me meat in pounds.''
she admits to carrying a pound-kilo pocket converter. ``you gotta eat.''
britain decided to go metric in 1972. highway signs are still in miles _ too costly to change _ and a pint of bitter mild is a pint of bitter mild
australia set a 10-year timetable and converted in eight. japan started metrication in 1921 and made it compulsory in 1951, saying sayonara to the 11.93-inch shaku and 8.267-pound kan
in the united states, the meter's foreign birth is ``undoubtedly a factor'' in resistance to it, underwood acknowledged. ``but there is an enormous explosion of technology in the world. it's taking place everywhere, not just america. the upshot is international collaboration, and the language of that collaboration is metric.''
measurement uncertainties can have immediate effects. there was confusion at first over just what radiation units the russians were using to assess radiation levels at chernobyl. a canadian plane crashed when it ran out of fuel after a refill mix-up. more critical at a time of america's huge trade deficit is the fact that 10 percent of the nation's gross national product derives from foreign commerce, two-thirds of that being measure-sensitive products
if the 1975 metric act had no incisors and the university of michigan survey research center says only 40 percent of americans can name even one metric unit, there is nonetheless a considerable metric component in u.s. life
sixty-five to 68 percent of supermarket goods are prepackaged and 70 percent of that has metric labels,'' says george carlton, chairman of the food and grocery coordinating committee on metrication. ``the no. 2 can is standard worldwide. the consumer knows how many kids a no. 2 can will feed. the rubber hits the road when the housewife meets the retailer at the meat counter and pays 2.205 times as much for a kilo of hamburger than she paid for a pound.''
but wine went metric in 1978 and hard liquor in 1980. soft drinks have gone to two-liter bottles with no reading on the richter scale
if a commodity is desired, it doesn't matter if it's packaged in swahili,'' says al navas, president of the national metric council in washington. ``metric transition is going to come about product by product.''
cars are easy because new models are always being introduced. machine-like drill presses are adjustable by definition. many small businesses will make whatever their customers want
some think american industry will be predominantly metric by the turn of the century. wilson thinks it will take 75 years
market forces will probably be more determining than the government
metrics never elected a senator,'' says navas. ``it isn't liberal-conservative or republican-democrat. it's apolitical. i was on a radio talk show in detroit recently, and they cut me off after 25 minutes. no one was calling in to protest metrics.''
probably the bell cow in metric transition will be the pentagon with its 300,000 suppliers in the defense industry and 15 million contracts a year. the army's multibillion-dollar lhx helicopter will be metric. so will ``star wars.''
last september the defense department said its policy was to use metric ``in all of its activities consistent with security . . . technical, logistical and safety requirements.'' any deviation has to be cleared by senior officials. fourteen percent of defense standards are already metric
partially this is the result of the u.s. alliance in an otherwise metric nato. ``but we're talking about the equipment we'll be fighting with into the 21st century,'' says air force col. thomas mansperger, pentagon metric coordinating officer. ``we base it on what we see our future needs will be and what kind of world we're going to work in.''
a metric world. ^agencies and radio out</note>
the metric system was born in the french revolution, which also tried _ and failed _ to create the 10-day week
the intent was to give the citizen a fairer shake with weights and measures than the honesty of a merchant's thumb on the scale. the paris academy of sciences decided to base the system on a constant physical dimension, in this case, one ten-millionth of the arc from the north pole to the equator on a meridian passing through paris. that unit was to be called a meter, from the greek word metron for ``measure.''
the liter was to be the volume of a cube one-tenth meter on a side. the gram: the weight of pure water at a certain temperature in a cube one-hundredth of a meter on a side. all variations of these basic measurements were to be to the base 10 to simplify their use in arithmetic
almost at once the meter was in hot water. surveyors measuring the distance on the meridian from dunkirk to barcelona used white flags as markers. white was the color of the monarchists who were soon to see their king beheaded. the surveyors kept having to talk their way out of jail, explaining they were just inventing the metric system, not showing support for louis xvi
the paris assembly adopted their work in 1791. thomas jefferson proposed a similar decimal system a few years later when he was secretary of state
the french made metrics mandatory in 1840. the u.s. congress declared the system legal in 1866. in 1875 the treaty of the meter was signed by the united states and 16 other nations creating an international bureau of weights and measures near paris
since 1893 the american yard and pound have been based on the meter and kilogram. but the united states has yet to officially convert to metrics. it and burma are the only nations in the world not to have done so. ^agencies and radio out</note> ^from ap newsfeatures</note> photos. colorfoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</note>

editor's note _ some of the old color is returning to miami beach, the art deco treasure-trove that had fallen on hard times. now, affluent young people are rediscovering the district, lured by refurbished buildings with their pastel-painted accents and distinctive, geometric designs
a painstaking facelift of the historic but seedy southern tip of miami beach appears to be more than skin deep
city officials are working to ensure the project's success and younger, more affluent tenants keep moving in
not long ago, investors remained leery of the run-down area, uncertain whether it could be turned around by refurbishing historic buildings that were crumbling around the edges and cloaked in layers 
when the city began spurring renovation, inspectors forced landlords to upgrade apartments and limit the number of residents per dwelling, according to jud kurlancheek, director of planning. that, along with new interest by young professionals, drove up prices
while the city doesn't keep track of the ethnicity of its residents, kurlancheek says the post-world war ii eastern european immigrants who retired to miami beach from new york and chicago weren't replaced. generally, he says, the advent of condominiums and planned retirement communities elsewhere in south florida curtailed miami beach's image as a retirement haven
the reaction among those who have stayed has been mixed. some complain that they've been priced out of their homes, while others welcome the revitalization
for saul gross, a new yorker who began investing in the area three years ago, when many were still unconvinced of the district's potential, the payoff has been big
everybody told me i was crazy at the time,'' says gross, president of the beach-based streamline development co. ``it turns out i have 175 apartments and 165 of those leased in the past year at higher rents than anybody ever thought.''
gross' holdings now include 11 apartment buildings and 25,000 square feet of commercial property being renovated on washington avenue, which cuts through the heart of the district with an area of about a square mile
out-of-town investors in particular have taken more of an interest in the district, acquiring a number of the 800 or so art deco structures. local investors have not been as quick to jump in
some say that could soon be changing
chuck lennon, executive director of the builders association of south florida, says local builders are geared more to large, planned developments on virgin tracts of land. as less land becomes available, builders are likely to turn more readily to refurbishing projects, he says
city officials are doing their part to lure local investors. recently, they staged a two-day seminar for members of the powerful latin builders association to promote investment possibilities on the beach
to protect and promote one of its most popular sections, the city recently passed an amendment to its historic preservation ordinance that gives officials the option of imposing a permanent moratorium on demolition of significant buildings
the initial 1982 ordinance only provided for a six-month delay in demolition, little more than ``a delaying factor, or cooling-off'' period to try and convince buyers of historic buildings not to raze them, singer says
a 10-month project will begin in march to enhance pedestrian traffic on ocean drive, where deco hotels fronting the ocean have become a symbol of the rebirth. sidewalks will be widened to 15 feet, three times their current width, and ocean-side lummus park will be spruced up
stuart rogel, director of economic and community development, says he recognizes the art deco district as ``a source of pride and reason for attracting people to our city, whether they come to visit or live in the buildings. ... it's an important area for the city.''
although only about 10 percent of the deco-style buildings have been renovated, progress has picked up in recent years, says richard hoberman, president of the miami design preservation league
in the past two years, more than half the properties on ocean (drive) and collins (avenue) have changed hands,'' hoberman says
the direction of things six years ago was that everything was on the decline,'' says denis russ, executive director of the miami beach development corp., a private, non-profit group. ``now there is occurring here the development of a neighborhood fabric.''
younger, more affluent tenants are moving into the refurbished apartments, which now rent for up to $850 for a two-bedroom unit, ms. meyers says. the average vacancy rate of redone buildings is about 10 percent, a significant drop from a high of 30 percent among buildings not yet renovated
meanwhile, apartment buildings in need of upgrading, which five years ago sold for about $12,000 a unit, now command up to $20,000, ms. meyers says. hotels that used to sell for about $6,000 a room, are going for up to $20,000, especially along the ocean
we are experiencing a change, a revitalization, a recycling and this will be a continuing phenomenom,'' russ says. ``i think it's not measured in weeks or seasons, but years. it won't reach the peak of its happening for another 10 years.''
ms. meyers says the increased activity is snowballing
we're not yet out of the woods,'' she says, ``but if the pattern continues, we'll see tremendous change in three years.'' ^agencies and radio out</note> ^with bc-apn--art deco</note>
a new generation has discovered ``america's riviera,'' replacing the glitz and glamour that faded decades ago with rock music clubs, quaint restaurants and neighborhood bars
instead of frank sinatra, sammy davis jr., jerry lewis or others who frequented miami beach in the '50s and '60s, recent visitors saw mick taylor and ron wood, rolling stones past and present, at woody's on the beach. others heard stephen stills and savoy brown at the china club, where doobie brothers jammed with steely dan, and where rocker david bowie, tennis star vitas gerulaitis and former beatles' producer george martin were among the crowd
the night life plays a great role in the revitalization of the entire community,'' says mayor alex daoud, 44, a miami beach native who can recall passing clark gable, gary cooper and kirk douglas on the streets of his youth
one of the largest concerns people have is: `where can i go at night?' when i was growing up here, entertainment was very expensive. now we have more affordable entertainment, and also family-oriented entertainment.''
in less than five years, nearly 20 music clubs and restaurants have sprung up in formerly rundown hotels, some deserted, others occupied by the elderly poor or mariel cuban refugees
the first time david giles, a british-born investment consultant, walked into the future site of woody's, ``there were six guys on the floor doing crack cocaine. it was absolutely derelict.''
months later, giles, 37, welcomed 600 people who paid $100 to $150 each to attend a new year's eve opening featuring the music of wood, a minority investor in a european ownership group assembled by giles
i still don't know if it will sustain itself, but the area appears to have turned a corner,'' says giles, who plans to expand his club into a beach club with sauna, exercise facilities and a gallery showcasing wood's artwork
jud kurlancheek, city director of planning and zoning, says the night life is ``a magnet for things that happen. it gets people to come here, and they look around and decide they'd like to live here.''
unlike in suburbia, where entertainment follows residential development, the reverse appears true in urban areas, kurlancheek says
in the art deco district undergoing restoration as a national historic area, the first wave brought upscale restaurants such as the european-style cafe the strand, and trendy music clubs such as china club, woody's, club nu and the tropics international. now, the neighborhood is adding the trappings of a settled-in professional community: a sushi restaurant, chummy neighborhood bars, an art deco-style burger king and, soon, domino's pizza, mcdonald's and wendy's fast-food restaurants
the average age of miami beach's 100,000 people dropped from 66 in 1980 to 54 in 1985 and is projected to be under 50 by 1980, says kurlancheek
young people are happy to live blocks from the beach,'' says jeffrey cohen, a partner in the china club. ``the weather has always been the finest on the continent and now, with the resurgence of the young people, it's like a rediscovery.''
the shift in entertainment tastes and the onset of jet travel to the caribbean and other competing resorts spelled the end to miami beach's heyday in the '60s, beach veterans say. the south beach area was hitting bottom by the time thousands of jobless cubans from the 1980 mariel boatlift crowded in with the elderly eastern european immigrants who couldn't afford the condominium retirement communities springing up in south florida
two efforts to gain legalization of casino gambling failed. finally, developers stopped looking for the ``quick fix'' and instead concentrated on more lasting solutions such as widening the eroded beach from 15 feet in places to 300, adding a boardwalk and reviving interest in preserving art deco styles. at the same time, tougher zoning ordinances forced landlords to make costly improvements. the higher rents that resulted helped chase away many of those responsible for raising the crime rates
many involved in the night life comeback are people in their 30s and 40s who have been interested in miami beach redevelopment for years. woody graber, a buffalo-born publicist who's been working for redevelopment and art deco preservation since 1979, says he's finally confident
people are finally realizing the potential. it's sort of like helping people find a buried treasure,'' graber says. ``this isn't going to die; there's too much going on for it to die now.'' photo.)</note>

editor's note _ cruise ships are notorious for their food. not the quality, the quantity. elaborate meals are served several times a day, right up to the midnight buffet. the head chef of one such ship, who's in charge of getting all that food to the table, shows what goes on in the galley
the problem of the latter-day galley slaves in a storm at sea was posed by the poet-passenger rudyard kipling, who often hung over the rail in a heaving sea:
when the cabin portholes are dark and green
because of the seas outside,
when the ship goes wop (with a wiggle between)
and the steward falls into the soup tureen,
and the trunks begin to slide..
why, then you will know (if you haven't guessed)
you're 50 north and 40 west.''
that would be well off newfoundland. gerd tschampel has survived several howling storms in even more northern latitudes, like off spitzbergen and norway's north cape, without falling into the soup tureen
as head chef on the 10,000-ton west german liner mv berlin, now sailing off brazil, gerd knows that in a really big blow, more accidents happen in the kitchen than anywhere else on board
we have a saying about storms at sea,'' he says. ``if something is falling, don't stop it. don't try to catch it. get out of the way. better to lose the soup or the sauce than suffer a scald.''
on the relatively calm equator it was near time for the first dinner seating. gerd was moving down the line, as they call the row of hissing pots and pans, sampling the various dishes with a large serving spoon
this is usually the only meal i have time to take,'' he said between slurps that occasionally provoked a sprinkle of salt or paprika from the palm of his hand. ``a taste of this and a sip of that, which means i am really eating all the time. thank god, from the beginning i have been a good sailor with no worries about rough weather.''
for gerd, just turned 35, the beginning was when his cousin came to their home in windsbach, northern bavaria, with armloads of exotic souvenirs from all over the world
junk mostly, i suppose, like i collect now,'' gerd laughed, ``but i was l6 years old then and he was a chef on the kungsholm, traveling everywhere. i made up my mind to someday roam the globe like him behind a stove.''
he apprenticed at a small hotel in ansbach, near nuremberg, with a gourmet dining room frequented by american air force personnel from a nearby base. going to catering school three weeks a year and passing certification tests, as is required in west germany, gerd rose to the rank of sous-chef
his dream became a reality via a classified ad in a restaurant trade paper. the german liner berlin was looking for qualified kitchen help
i applied for third cook, the lowest rank. a month later i was looking out a porthole at jakarta,'' gerd recalls. ``my cousin meanwhile was chef on the ferry from kiel to goteborg. his wife said, `enough.'''
three years later, gerd, now head chef, has learned to cope with the biggest difference between cooking on land and at sea. ``at the hotel, if you forget something, you pick up the telephone. out here, you forget something, forget it. you have nothing.''
fresh fruit and vegetables are always a problem for the growing number of cruise ships of many flags that spend the winter in the tropics
the other day we were in martinique,'' gerd says, shaking his head over his menu-planning clipboard. ``you think caribbean ports could supply all the melons, fish and shrimp you need. then you telex ahead for 900 kilos of something and they can only come up with 200 kilos. right now we have too many tomatoes and not enough cucumbers. you learn to be versatile.''
the following morning, the berlin would dock at belem, 90 miles up the amazon, where gerd expected five tons of food to be winched aboard, ``if the agent can locate it.'' some supplies would be flown out from west germany where weeks before christmas the ship had left its home port of neustadt, near hamburg, with enough food in its freezers to last three months
the other big difference about cooking at sea,'' says gerd, dipping his spoon into an enormous tray of red snapper simmering in almond butter, ``is that everything is served all at once, not like in a restaurant where orders may come hours apart. ''
to feed 450 passengers and 200 crew members, gerd supervises a staff of 26 that includes a sous-chef, a bread baker, four butchers, two pastry chefs and assorted specialists at meat, fish, soups, sauces, salads and ice cream-making
eating is a round-the-clock pastime for passengers. breakfast starts at 7 a.m. in the dining salon or at poolside. hot bouillon at 10. lunch is at noon in the dining room or on the lido deck. afternoon tea with rich pastry is at 4. there are two dinner sittings, at 6 and 8, then an elaborate midnight buffet
when people, sometimes even the captain and the doctor, complain to me about getting too thick, too fat, i tell them, look, i only do the cooking. you must do the eating,'' says the lean and lanky chef
gerd's day is divided into two shifts. he shows up in the gleaming tile and steel galley at 6 a.m., takes a break at noon for a few hours, then is back on the line at 5 or so. ``in this job, '' he says, sampling the just-made kiwi fruit ice cream with hazelnut sauce, ``you know when you start but you never know when you finish. sometimes it is midnight.''
menus are planned two days ahead, after a nervous look at the larder
on a cruise ship, the chef learns to pace himself, so that each day is better than the last,'' gerd says. the progression is from venison and filet mignon to boeuf wellington and lobster, from pate de foie gras to smoked salmon to caviar. it all builds to the captain's farewell banquet, when the lamps are dimmed and the waiters come marching in behind the ship's orchestra with flaming baked alaska held proudly on high
then in ritual rich as king neptune's court at the crossing of the equator, the captain gives his little speech and introduces his officers and the cruise staff. but the loudest applause always rings out for the chef
since the berlin flies the west german flag, the menu at lunch usually features a regional specialty like gefuellte kalbsbrust heidelberg, stuffed breast of veal, or kaiserschmarren, luscious tyrolean pancakes. the six-course dinner, from pate and soup to cheese board and exotic pastry, invariably offers a choice of three entrees
the cuisine is continental, but menu choices do not seem to vary regardless of whether german, french or americans predominate the passenger list. with some 400 guests studying his daily delectations, gerd can predict ``within 20 or 30 portions'' which of the three entrees will be the most in demand
that way, we don't waste much food,'' he says. ``also, the weather is a factor. people eat less here in the tropics. on the chilly north cape run, they never stop eating.''
in the pecking order at sea, gerd is entitled to wear an officer's uniform with three stripes on the sleeve, the equivalent rank of first mate or first engineer. but he prefers a white apron and the toque blanche, the tall chef's hat that crowns his profession and always brings down the house
in germany,'' he mused over a steaming cauldron of crab and spinach soup, ``cooking is still a respected profession, but young people don't want it. the hours are too long, the work too hard, and you're never off on weekends, christmas or easter. every cruise i am breaking in four or five new cooks. they stay for two or three years, and then the wife or the girlfriend says enough. well, you can't blame them. the sea is for dreamers.'' photo. colorfoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</note>

editor's note _ camel caravans still wend across the sahara desert in northern niger as they have done for centuries, but droughts in this decade have wiped out most livestock herds, putting an end to the wandering of the nomadic tuaregs. in villages such as agadez, many have been reduced to hawking jewelry to tourists or scratching a meager garden out of the sand
the evening call to prayer from a medieval minaret echoes through the sand streets to a market stall next to the sultan's palace where abdou amadou sells nomad souvenirs and dreams of hondas
the souvenirs are mere remnants of a fabulous desert culture that once flourished in agadez, then a bustling crossroad of the great trans-saharan trade
the village is now an impoverished outpost in the landlocked west african nation of niger, one of the poorest and most anonymous countries on earth. but agadez manages to survive, living off the legacy of the sahara's golden age
abdou, 16, is watching the shop while his grandfather prays on a straw mat outside in the street. two tourists browse through the sabers, jewelry and camel saddles hanging on the wall
it's nomad,'' abdou says, pointing to a bracelet. ``it's silver. i'll make you a good price.''
as the tourists walk away, abdou says in french, ``i want to sell enough to buy a honda someday and do a motorcross. it would be marvelous.'' his grandfather returns and, speaking quietly in tamanjek, tells abdou to get back to work
tamanjek is the language of the tuareg nomads, who for a thousand years lived and wandered in the once-borderless sahara desert that is now northern niger
crafts and caravans, as well as tourism, are essential structural supports for the economy of northern niger, a country with a population of about 7 million and an average per capita income of $270 a year
the caravan route to timbuktu originated in agadez and was followed by arabs, turks and egyptians. the wealthy traders of the medieval world, including a few europeans, kept agents in agadez to expedite the flow of goods south to black africa and north to the mediterranean ports
the gateway to the sahara, agadez linked europe and africa, white world and black; the route came to symbolize the mystery of africa
throughout the middle ages and continuing until two centuries ago, huge caravans crisscrossed the desert waste. sometimes lines of up to 40,000 camels stretched to the shimmering horizon. tuareg nomads, proud and independent, served as escorts, camel handlers and guides across the unmarked sand. nomad craftsmen made saddles, sabers and other gear for the trail while other tuaregs bred camels to replace those lost to exhaustion and thirst
crossing the desert was a complicated and dangerous business. tens of thousands of human and animal skeletons lie buried beneath the sand. whole convoys died from lack of water or heat or fell victim to bandits. black africans perished on the forced march north to slavery or were worked to death more slowly in the desert salt pits
the pits not far from agadez, near the libyan border, are still being worked, although not by slaves, and the transport still is handled in the cool winter months by camel caravans. scores of caravans carry salt to feed the livestock of farmers in the more fertile south. to the north they return with millet, dates and wheat
caravans appear suddenly from behind dunes like an illustration from arabian nights or frames from a hollywood foreign legion film. the camels glide across the top of dunes, tied in a line, their hooves trailing plumes of sand. beside them walk the nomads in robes that billow like sails in the wind. from their belts swing curved, carved sabers, symbols of the tuaregs' warrior past
the caravan trade still feeds some families, but many tuaregs in agadez have been reduced to hawking jewelry to tourists or scratching a meager garden out of the sand. droughts in this decade have wiped out most herds, putting an end to the nomad's wandering and livelihood. government policies that encourage the nomads to settle down have accelerated the change to a sedentary life
the descendant of a line that dates at least to the 10th century, sultan ibrahim spent one recent morning negotiating movie rights to film a caravan
the sultan reclined on a carpet by an open fire in the dark palace, slowly spinning a silver cylinder of snuff in his hand. across from him on lawn chairs sat a reporter and producer from the british broadcasting co., nervously negotiating
they explained their plan to an old, white-robed interpreter who translated it from french for the sultan and his retinue. the sultan's black eyes, the only part of his head not concealed by an abundant turban, revealed nothing but inscrutable reserve
after a while he raised his hand and discussion of details ceased between the bbc and a barefoot caravaner. he approved 30 camels and agreed to outfit the caravan for a reasonable price _ and agreed to be interviewed on camera for the trade route film
thirty camels can go now without danger,'' the sultan says. ``it is no longer necessary to travel in large groups for protection.''
the danger facing agadez these days, he says, is not other men, but nature
it is getting drier, the water table is falling and we have not had a good rain in two years,'' he says. ``it is difficult to say exactly what is happening
we have enough water for the moment for our 30,000 people and there is enough fodder, but any further loss of pasture and there will be no livestock left. i don't know about will happen to the people.''
the spread of the sahara is the biggest problem in agadez, in the region, in all of niger. desertification and the environment was the top priority listed by the new government when it took over in november. the new chief of state is ali seibou, the third man to lead niger since it gained independence from france three decades ago
col. seibou, leader of the nigerien military, took over nov. 17 from president seyna kountche, who died in a paris hospital of a brain tumor. seibou immediately was chosen to head the seven-man ruling supreme military council
already known for his leadership in efficiently distributing food throughout niger during the 1984 famine, seibou increased his popularity by releasing about 200 political prisoners and reducing police presence in niamey, the capital. articles mildly critical of the government began appearing in the press. the atmosphere seemed looser, people said
the transition of power was especially smooth when compared to other west african nations, where violent coups d'etat often mark the change in government. niger's reputation for stability has been strengthened in international circles, including the united states
international affairs, even national ones, receive little attention in agadez, where there are only a couple of television sets and one plane a week lands on the sand-swept airstrip near town. tradition is what matters
even the way of saying hello on the street is rooted in the sahara's golden age. the tuareg have a complicated and courteous way of greeting each other, exchanging several phrases before conversation begins. softly spoken, ritualistic phrases, which everyone knows by heart, sometimes go on for a minute or more
salum alaikum,'' they begin. peace to you
alaikum wa salam.'' peace to you too
yak lo bas.'' no evil to you
lo bas.'' no evil
lo bas. hamdullah.'' no evil, thanks to god
as the phrases continue, the men look each other over. the ritual was useful for sizing up a stranger on the desert, identifying his tribe
abdou, sporting a georgia historical society t-shirt given to him by a foreign friend, thinks the greeting is old-fashioned. but he respects the ancient traditions, knowing that this is what brings the tourists to his grandfather's shop
you want to go see the camel market outside town?'' he asks a visitor. ``i can borrow my brother's motorcycle and take you there.''
here are some facts and figures on niger:
the land: located on the southern edge of the sahara, between libya and nigeria, niger is a landlocked nation of 490,000 square miles (the size of texas and california combined), most of it uninhabited desert
more than a century of french colonial rule ended peacefully on aug. 8, 1960. the nigeriens adopted a constitution three months later that was suspended following a military coup in 1974
the people: the population, estimated at 7 million, is largely made up of three ethnic groups. the hausa, who also constitute the major ethnic group of northern nigeria, represent half the total population and the djerma-songhai, a quarter. most are concentrated in the southern, more fertile, part of the country. the rest of the nigeriens are nomadic or seminomadic peoples wandering the deserts of the north, including the tuareg, fulani, kanouri and toubou. each ethnic group has its own language and customs but the hausa language is the one most widely spoken. ninety-eight percent of the population is moslem. the birthrate is one of the world's highest, increasing at 3.4 percent per year. the average life expectancy is 45
the economy: despite the development of uranium mining in recent years, niger remains a very poor country, 97 percent covered in sand. uranium output peaked in 1981 and declined after prices fell owing to worldwide cuts in nuclear power programs. the falling uranium prices caused the rate of economic growth to plummet from 12 percent in 1979 to 4.2 percent in 1985
niger's gross national product per head declined, in real terms, by an average of 1.6 percent annually between 1960 and 1981. per capita income in 1987 was estimated at $270 a year. the decline in the economy combined with an exploding population and recurring drought. niger is thought to be the country that was most severely affected by the 1984 drought and resulting food shortages
about 90 percent of niger's work force is employed in some form of agriculture or herding. the principal food crops are millet and sorghum. the main cash crops are peanuts, cotton and cowpeas
history: the british were the first to explore the upper reaches of the niger river, beginning with the scotsman mungo park, who disappeared there in 1806. but it was the french who colonized it between 1891 and 1911. the country was not fully ``pacified'' until much later and there were a number of resistance movements which challenged colonial power, the most serious being the siege of agadez by tuareg nomad warriors in 1916-17
its colonial history and development paralleled that of other french west african territories, administered from paris through the governor general at dakar, senegal, and governors in the individual territories. the country gained independence in 1960, but remained staunchly pro-french
the constitution adopted in 1960 was suspended in april 1974 following a coup in which seyni kountche ousted hamani diori, who had served since independence but was accused of corruption, particularly with regard to the distribution of food aid
in november 1987, kountche died in a paris hospital following a long illness and was immediately replaced by his chief aide and the head of the 4,000-man nigerien military, ali seibou
the country has been ruled since 1974 by a supreme military council and all basic powers have been vested in it. political parties are banned. a cabinet, composed of both civilians and military personnel, administers the country. the government has promised to reinstate a constitution and parliament
niger pursues a neutral, moderate foreign policy and maintains friendly relations with both east and west. photo.)</note>
british actress jane seymour says she found much to admire in wallis simpson, the american divorcee who became the duchess of windsor, the woman the english loved to hate
she was the woman who stole their king,'' says seymour, who portrays simpson in the cbs movie, ``the woman he loved.''
they hated her. she was a naive american who didn't understand the monarchy or how it worked or what it stood for. she thought david could make her his queen.''
instead, david, already king edward viii but not yet crowned, was forced to abdicate in 1936 to marry wallis. they became the duke and duchess of windsor and lived the rest of their lives in exile
the two-hour movie, which cbs will televise on sunday, also stars anthony andrews as david, olivia de havilland as wallis' aunt bessie, julie harris as her mother, lucy gutteridge as another woman who saw herself as david's queen, robert hardy as winston churchill and phyllis calvert as queen mary
i've never heard anyone say a good word about her,'' seymour says. ``other than that, she gave great dinner parties. but i liked her. she had a sense of humor, a straightforwardness. she was definitely attentive to her husband and, although she was no beauty, she had style and elegance. i certainly wouldn't trust her with my husband
it's boring to play a perfect person. but to play a woman who was not liked and to find something about her that is likeable is fascinating.''
seymour says she saw david as a weak man who never really wanted to be king. wallis simpson fulfilled some of his needs
rumor has it that wallis learned to do sexual tricks when she lived in china,'' she says. ``the king had a few problems in that area and she fixed them.''
when wallis first met david, he was the prince of wales and she was married to american businessman ernest simpson. the flirtation turned to romance, and simpson's marriage to divorce. her plan was to marry david and become queen, but the british prime minister and royal family forbade his marriage as king to a twice-divorced woman
the woman he loved'' takes a different and less political approach than the british-made miniseries ``edward and mrs. simpson,'' which ran on pbs several years ago
english newspapers became heavily involved with the making of ``the woman he loved'' and seymour says one paper seemed to give royal status to her role-playing. the times published seymour's picture as the duchess at david's funeral. it went on the court circular page, a serious chronicle of royal events
i tried to play her in various shades of gray,'' seymour says. ``i play her the way i believe she was thinking at the time. she was manipulating things. she had a great plan and it didn't work. i purposely don't play her sympathetically.''
parts of the movie were filmed in western england, where seymour owns a 15th-century estate outside the old roman spa city of bath. she stayed at her home, st. catherine's court, during that time
seymour divides her time between england, where she is still a citizen, and this country, where she has lived for the past 10 years. she and her husband, american businessman david flynn, have two children, katie, 5, born here, and sean, 2, born in england
she works mostly in american television and films, having shed her english accent in order to play american roles
seymour was on her way to spain to play opera star maria callas in the abc miniseries ``onassis: the richest man in the world.'' the four-hour miniseries, which tells of the romance between callas and greek magnate aristotle onassis (raul julia), will be televised in early may
she has already completed her role as natalie jastrow henry in ``war and remembrance,'' the 30-hour miniseries being readied for abc next season. so far she has starred in 10 american miniseries
this seems to be my `duchess and diva' period,'' she says with a laugh. ``i seem to be getting some great roles now. it's very exciting. i'm like a chameleon, changing the way i look, the way i sound, the kind of roles i play.''
she took over the role played by ali macgraw in ``the winds of war,'' the first of author herman wouk's two massive novels on world war ii
for her role as maria callas she had to learn to sing several arias. she also worked with dialect coach robert easton for her roles as wallis simpson and maria callas
next, she goes to london for a role in the cbs miniseries ``jack the ripper.'' she plays the romantic interest to michael caine, who stars as scotland yard inspector frederick abberline. armand assante also stars as an american actor playing ``dr. jekyll and mr. hyde'' on the london stage at the time of jack the ripper's reign of terror. photo.)</note>
liliane montevecchi is a french singer-dancer whose cabaret show, ``on the boulevard,'' opened in february and keeps getting extended at the tiny off-broadway kaufman theater
whether she will let it extend into the summer, she can't say. ``i don't make plans. i do whatever pleases me
i'm like a cork on the ocean and just let it ride,'' she says in french- accented english, her words punctuated by a hearty laugh
her father was italian, her mother french. she grew up in paris. she was the star of the folies bergere for 10 years. minus the feathers of the folies, she's doing her first one-woman show
in ``on the boulevard,'' she wears a black long-sleeved, mini-skirted dress, accenting her gamine face, svelte figure and shapely legs. after intermission, for a ``boulevard stroll,'' she belts on a very french-looking trench coat. she bought it for $25 in a salvation army store near the manhattan apartment where she's staying. this ``cork on the ocean'' doesn't keep a permanent apartment in paris or new york
the songs in the show, sung mostly in english, aren't all french. but the singer, whose name is pronounced montevekky, makes ``it might as well be spring'' sound as french as ``autumn leaves.''
critic clive barnes called her ``an american-styled, but never americanized, impression of a reality that is itself so brilliant, so telling and so touching that it becomes a new and lovely reality in its own right.''
tommy tune, who chose miss montevecchi for ``nine'' on broadway, planned ``on the boulevard'' with her, but his name isn't in the program. she says, ``he did it for me as a friend. the critics were so good he should have the recognition he deserves. i asked him and he said, `now that you're well on your way, do what you want.' it is so brilliantly pulled together in that little theater, not an easy theater to work with
the first time we came to the theater and sat there, he said, `i see you higher.' we didn't know how yet. a boulevard was not even thought of.'' they eventually decided on a raised, diagonal walkway across the tiny stage
we were there, moved around, thought aloud, did boo-boos. it was being unafraid to do things that are not good, then clean it up. i always rehearse in a black leotard; i can see where the body goes. we started with a leotard covered with diamonds i had from a long time ago, for the show. it was too much.''
they didn't try for a single mood, like nostalgia. ``we should have variety,'' she says. ``alive, alive, alive. and true. you cannot cheat the public. they don't know why but they feel when it is true. the public is very intelligent, you see.''
miss montevecchi thinks her singing has improved. ``life makes you different, the sorrow, joy, people you lose. the songs are closer to my heart and i'm not afraid any more. tommy and i say we are finished to be afraid. now we attack!
tommy decided no more hats or glittering gowns. i attack with pleasure. i feel very comfortable with that. i took a risk, i guess. if one doesn't take a risk, one stays in a rut.''
tune first saw and heard the 5-foot-6-inch dancer-singer during auditions for broadway's ``nine,'' which he directed
she had played in atlantic city for 18 months, on contracts renewed in three-month increments. from atlantic city, she went to hollywood, where she once had a seven-year mgm contract, to try to re-enter films
i didn't get a thing, not even a radio spot. i can't wait. i try and if it doesn't work, i disappear. i decided to go back to paris. i stopped here, to visit a friend, and called my agent. he said, `it's funny you called. tomorrow there's an audition for a play which requires accents
i went there. i was not prepared at all. i didn't have a pianist. i sang `la vie en rose.' tommy liked me. he didn't have a part for me but he wanted me in the show. why not have me play the part of a producer originally written for a man? because of me, the cast, except for raul julia, became all women
the timing of things is incredible.''
in paris, at age 9, miss montevecchi started ballet lessons, sent by a mother who had wanted to be a ballerina. ``she didn't push me too hard. i loved it. i still love it today. i go to ballet class every day. it is my drug, my equilibrium, my love, what makes me breathe.''
roland petit saw miss montevecchi dance as a teen-ager, hired her for his ballet company and three months later, when she was 18, named her prima ballerina. she stayed three years before a screen test took her to hollywood, where she attended school with kindergarteners to learn english
after hollywood came ``la plume de ma tante,'' on broadway and on tour; a play in europe, and 10 years of starring in the folies bergere, in new york, where it flopped, las vegas and paris. she wasn't topless, miss montevecchi says. ``ballet is a very proper thing and i always kept this. and i was the star of it, in 17 enormous costumes a night, with huge, huge feathers, from catherine of russia to a tango queen.''
her mother died last year in paris. miss montevecchi says, ``i spent five months in paris; i had to do things. i came back here with her little dog that i bought her 12 years ago. i do this show for her. she made me do it, in my heart and mind.''
as an angry young man in the 1960s, jackie ntuane spent more than three years in prison for his political activism
as a prosperous insurance executive today, he says his focus is on economic independence
ntuane is part of a growing black south african middle class, which has found opportunities in the business world even while locked out of national politics
this emerging business class, though still small, sees black economic development as the neglected partner of black political advancement. both are viewed as necessary ingredients in dismantling apartheid, the government's policies of racial segregation
economics and politics are part of the same struggle for blacks,'' said ntuane, who manages a 50-member branch office for the old mutual insurance company
blacks must succeed in both areas if they are to take control of their own lives,'' added ntuane, who was imprisoned for belonging to the outlawed pan africanist congress
the south african economy, by far the largest and most advanced in africa, requires an ever increasing number of middle-class professionals. blacks have begun to fill that demand, and some clear signs of black economic progress are emerging:
_black households earned an average of 406 rand ($203) a month in 1986, more than double the figure in 1981 and nearly six times higher than in 1975, according to market research africa, a private firm. however, black households still earn less than 20 percent of the average white family income
_the new lesedi city shopping mall, east of johannesburg, has more than 50 black-run businesses and is the largest shopping complex yet built in a black area
_black taxi drivers, banding together in a nationwide association, over the past decade have taken away a huge portion of black commuter ridership from white-owned bus companies
_shareworld, a disneyland-style amusement park in soweto, opened several months ago and is believed the largest enterprise in the country controlled by black shareholders. a total of 880 black investors hold 60 percent of the stock
there are success stories, but they remain the exception,'' said gabriel mokgoko, spokesman for the national african federated chamber of commerce. ``blacks still are not part of the economic mainstream.''
the middle class remains a small fraction of the country's 26 million blacks. blacks make up about 75 percent of the population, but only 5 percent of the executives and managers. black businesses account for only 1 percent of south africa's gross national product, according to black enterprise magazine
black businesses face obstacles on several fronts, including hostility from their own community, where many younger blacks see the business world as an extension of apartheid and white domination
capitalism has become a discredited system to hundreds of thousands of (black) south africans,'' the editors of black enterprise wrote recently. ``to many of our younger students and graduates, even its name is an anathema (and) earns thinly disguised ridicule and contempt.''
dr. nthato motlana, a prominent anti-apartheid activist, said blacks have become increasingly hostile to business and have failed to perceive black buying power as a political weapon
the attitude of young black activists and the unions is most unfortunate,'' he said recently. ``this message must go out to the political activists _ blacks need to make money too. blacks have no political power, but they should translate their consumer power into economic power.''
a long-held theory in the white business establishment is that apartheid will wither as the economy develops and blacks are drawn into the middle class
business has proved less resistent to blacks than most other fields, and the workplace is the most frequent point of multiracial interaction in a country where neighborhoods and public schools remain segregated
but black leaders say white business has done far less than it could to assist blacks
white business climbed on the back of the apartheid political system years ago and that's where it remains today,'' said mokgoko. ``business pays lip service to racial reform, but they have never exercised their power to help dismantle apartheid or assist blacks economically.''
blacks are the largest consumers of most basic necessities, such as food and clothing, yet most black businesses are relatively small operations limited to black townships
south africa has no nationwide black-owned chains, and only one of the more than 500 companies listed on the johannesburg stock exchange (a group of six bakeries) is run by blacks
blacks have no credible representation in any of the major economic sectors such as mining, agriculture, manufacturing, the financial institutions, even retailing,'' reuel khoza, the black managing director of shareworld, wrote recently in leadership magazine
by whatever index we use, black economic activity is so insignificant as to be almost non-existent,'' khoza wrote
economic life in soweto, the huge township outside johannesburg, is typical of many black areas. most shops are mom-and-pop operations and a substantial informal business sector of street vendors exists
but the township of an estimated 2.5 million people has no large, central business district or shopping area. soweto residents are more likely to shop at white-owned businesses in johannesburg than in their neighborhoods
by far the largest industry in soweto is shebeens, illegal bars _ an estimated 4,000 of them, outnumbering all other businesses combined
black businessmen say the townships will remain underdeveloped until bankers become willing to invest in black areas. south africa has more than 50 banks, but only one, the african bank, is black-run and makes most of its loans to the black community
regulation and statute have reduced us to a nation of small-time merchants running essentially one-man operations,'' khoza wrote
our political spirit has never been crushed, but our assault on the economic edifice of apartheid has been lamentable,'' he added. ``in the economic field, we must create a mythology of competence, of high motivation and high ideals in pursuit of economic liberation.''
every workday morning and evening, the road between johannesburg and soweto is lined with vans taking blacks to and from their jobs
known as ``combis,'' the vans are privately owned taxis that have contributed to one of the country's leading black business success stories
an estimated 100,000 combis operate nationwide, and almost all are run by blacks for blacks
the black taxi industry is a clear example of the black entrepreneurial flair that exists in south africa when it is allowed to flourish,'' said james chapman, a white who is spokesman for the southern african bus and taxi association (sabta)
for decades, most urban blacks were at the mercy of inefficient and inconvenient train and bus systems for their daily trips from the outlying townships into the cities where they worked
when black taxi drivers began appearing in the late 1970s, they faced a range of restrictions, including limits on the number of passengers and the requirement that those in each ride be of the same race
but sabta, a co-operative with 45,000 members, successfully fought regulatory curbs and has become an increasingly powerful force in the transport industry since its formation in 1979
sabta has an annual budget of more than 60 million rand ($30 million), runs 16 gas and service stations for members, and arranges discounts on parts and repairs. the organization also has persuaded the toyota and nissan automotive plants in south africa to modify their vans to better accommodate the needs of taxi drivers
seventy percent of the association's members own only one or two taxi vans, but most are doing well financially, sabta says
successful black taxi drivers in urban areas earn as much as 1,000 rand ($500) a month, making them among the highest-earning black group in the country, said godfrey ntlatleng, the association's vice president. the average monthly income for a black household in south africa is 406 rand ($203)
i had to work a lot of 16-hour days, but i always wanted to be my own boss,'' said ntlatleng, who started with one taxi and now oversees a fleet of several combis
to join sabta, members pay an annual 100-rand ($50) fee, and become part of the local association that sets rates and handles administrative functions. the current fare for the trip between johannesburg and soweto costs the equivalent of 60 cents and most vans carry 10 or 15 passengers
sabta's membership and resources have been expanding rapidly, although the organization failed last year in an attempt to takeover the nation's largest bus system, putco, for 150 million rand ($75 million)
it was a temporary setback,'' said chapman. ``but we've proven we're a force to be reckoned with.''
the sweeping capitalist revolution in britain is prime minister margaret thatcher's
but her top treasury official, chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson, is the architect of the astounding turnaround in britain's economy _ the world's fifth largest
once an economic laughing stock, plagued by strikes, high interest rates and inflation that coined the phrase ``the british disease,'' britain is in its seventh consecutive year of economic growth and expanding faster than most of its major trading partners
at a projected 3 percent in 1988, britain's growth will outstrip the united states' 2.3 percent and west germany's 1.7 percent, and stand second only to japan's 4.2 percent
the base lending rate is down from a peak of 16 percent in 1981 to 8.5 percent. the annual inflation rate has been reined in from 18 percent in 1980 to 4 percent last year
now, with a budget unveiled march 15 that will radically reform the tax structure, lawson's accomplishments as the main architect of mrs. thatcher's economic policies rank him as one of britain's boldest and most respected chancellors
i think you can certainly say that, certainly in the postwar period,'' said ian harwood, a chief economist at the london investment firm warburg securities
he compares well with other chancellors,'' said diane coyoe, a british economist with the private forecasting firm dri europe. ``he's been a very hands-on chancellor so he has to get a lot of the credit for it.''
she added: ``he will certainly be well remembered.''
lawson's opponents in the socialistic labor party disagree. they shouted down his budget speech when he announced big tax cuts for high earners, and one was expelled from the house of commons for calling his strategy ``an utter obscenity.''
lawson's fifth budget marked his zenith with the nine-year-old conservative government's biggest tax reform
reducing the income tax categories from six to two, he slashed the rate for britain's highest income earners from 60 percent to 40, and set a basic rate of 25 percent, the lowest since 1938
in a testament to the government's tight fiscal spending policies, 1987-88 produced the first budget surplus in almost 20 years
rich man's budget,'' stormed the opposition laborites, but a large conservative majority in the house of commons assures its passage
lawson proudly predicted another year of healthy and non-inflationary economic growth, despite the october stock markets' crash, and repeated his common boast:
the british economy is stronger than at any time since the war. we have followed the right policies and stuck to them.''
the government's critics say that if this is a success story, the price is too high
they say the poor, the unemployed and the sick have been abandoned by fiscal spending policies short on social conscience. mrs. thatcher argues that only a strong economy can protect the weak
the critics also maintain that unemployment, at a rate of 9.1 percent, is too high. lawson notes it was above 11 percent 18 months ago
economists also worry about the trade deficit, which is expected to triple to $7.4 billion in 1988
britain's surplus in oil trade, which was $7.4 billion in 1987, equal to the expected trade deficit, disguises the real extent of the country's trade imbalance, the critics say
they also contend that falling oil prices played a significant part in slowing the growth rate from 4.5 percent last year to the projected 3 percent
lawson's critics also say manufacturing output hasn't fully recovered from the recession of the early 1980s. it will grow by 5.5 percent in 1988, lawson said. but the government's most recent manufacturing output index stood at 113.5 in january, still below its record 116.8 in june 1974
in addition, the labor unrest that mrs. thatcher had curbed with laws limiting union power has picked up with a variety of strikes in recent months
but the government says 3.39 million work days were lost to strikes last year, up from a 34-year low of 1.92 million in 1986, but much lower than the 1970s average
lawson, like mrs. thatcher, doesn't waver from his agenda, which has the prime minister's almost unqualified endorsement
he has held his own opinions and followed them,'' ms. coyoe said
his relationship with mrs. thatcher is not always harmonious, however. just before budget day, they disagreed over how much the government should intervene to stem the increase in the value of the british pound against other major currencies
mrs. thatcher stood by her free-market convictions, while lawson feared that without intervention, a strong pound would hurt britain's exports and corporate profits
short, boyish-faced, chubby, with a shock of black hair and a tart sense of humor, lawson is the son of a jewish latvian immigrant who became a london tea merchant
lawson graduated from oxford university in economics, politics and philosophy, and was a journalist before being elected to parliament in 1974. in 1979 he became a junior treasury minister in mrs. thatcher's first government
he became chancellor in 1983, the first trained economist to hold the post since 1951, and began as a monetarist, vowing to extinguish inflation by controlling the growth in britain's money supply and government borrowing
today he is a supply-sider who advocates tax cuts and restrained fiscal spending. supply-side economists believe increasing the money available for investment will boost productivity
lawson lives with his second wife and two young children at 11 downing st., next door to the thatchers at no. 10
despite being credited with a large part in winning mrs. thatcher her third consecutive term of office, lawson's political future is uncertain. critics say the chancellor is not sociable enough to garner support to lead the party in the unlikely event that the unflagging mrs. thatcher would step down
i think he would make a very good prime minister,'' harwood said. ``whether he would have a chance is another question.''
the british press has speculated that after five years in the thatcher cabinet, lawson is tired and frustrated, and might take a lucrative job in the city, london's financial district
lawson says that while his tax reform is complete, it is too soon to say whether he will be presenting next year's budget
the shabby 64-room motel where martin luther king jr. died is closed, emptied of its last stubborn resident, surrounded by a chain-link fence 8 feet high and awaiting renovation. the slums are as full as ever
dr. king was about the business of poor people at the time of his death, and today there are more poor black people in memphis than there were then,'' said maxine smith, executive secretary of the local naacp
king was shot to death at the lorraine motel on april 4, 1968, and civil rights leaders say the 20th anniversary of his assassination should remind the nation that the battles he fought remain unwon
the attention of the country should be on memphis,'' said james e. smith, director of local 1733 of the american federation of state, county and municipal employees
king was in memphis to support striking city garbage men when he was slain. on april 3, the union will sponsor a memorial service at the mason temple, where he delivered one of his most famous speeches
i've been to the mountain top,'' king told his followers the night before his death. ``i may not get there with you, but i want you to know tonight that we as a people will get to the promised land.''
a ``poor-people's pilgrimage'' through mississippi, alabama and georgia will begin april 4 in memphis with a wreath-laying ceremony at the lorraine
a program of speeches and music to be staged at a downtown theater april 4 will be the first event the city has ever sponsored in king's honor
i think anybody who is familiar with memphis politics, memphis society, would have thought you were crazy if you said five or 10 years ago that memphis was going to sponsor an official city tribute to dr. king,'' said the rev. kenneth whalum jr., chairman of a commission appointed by mayor richard hackett to coordinate the city program
it speaks volumes about the progress we have made,'' whalum said
the city and county governments have put up $2.2 million each to match $4.4 million from the state for a civil rights museum at the lorraine, and museum supporters say it indicates memphis is less worried about being identified as the city where king was killed
there had to be time for people to realize that the impact of the movement and dr. king was not a passing moment,'' said d'army bailey, a prime mover behind the project. ``the lorraine didn't become less important over the years. it became more important.''
the city must recognize it has a special place in history because king was killed here, he said
it is a remarkable challenge that we have to continually answer to show we are making some progress toward racial and economic justice,'' bailey said. ``there is essentially a white memphis and a black memphis, but i don't see that most other american cities are any different. i think we are trying here.''
despite progress, however, other community leaders say racial and economic divisions in memphis are still sharp
we have a long way to go in healing the wounds of king's assassination and in addressing racial polarization,'' said willie herenton, superintendent of memphis schools. he said conditions for the hard-core poor had changed little in two decades
there's a lot of hopelessness and despair,'' he said
jacqueline smith, 37, who was forcibly evicted from the lorraine on march 2 after living there nine years, remains camped out on the sidewalk in protest. the former lorraine chambermaid and waitress thinks the motel should be converted to a shelter for the homeless
i'm trying to help the people who live in this area,'' she said as she was being evicted. ``we're being forced out'' of the neighborhood
the u.s. census bureau says memphis' population of 558,000 in 1968 was about 40 percent black. in 1987 the population was estimated at 652,000 and 50 percent black
in 1970, the median income for blacks in memphis was about half that of whites, and a 1987 report on local poverty by the shelby county mayor's office says that margin has not lessened
almost half of the black families in memphis live in poverty, the report says, and 79 percent of the children in city schools live near or below the poverty level. seventy-eight percent of the 107,000 students in the schools are black
if you look at the percentage of property ownership and things like that, where the money is, blacks are still mainly on the outside,'' said charles crawford, a history professor at memphis state university
but king's assassination in this city permanently changed the city's racial attitudes
there was a feeling of real shock that it had happened and, maybe like (president john) kennedy's assassination in dallas, that it had happened here,'' crawford said. ``it brought about a much more sudden acceptance of the necessity of integration.''
after king's death, blacks greatly increased their involvement in city politics, crawford said, and white politicians began taking them more seriously
in 1967, the city's registered voters broke down to 152,562 whites and 78,655 blacks. now, 181,539 whites, 175,395 blacks and 14,180 others are registered
three of the 13 city council members are black, the same as 20 years ago, and four members of the 11-member shelby county commission are black. photos. colorfoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</note>

editor's note _ like thomas chippendale, 18th century cabinetmaker and woodworking artist before him, wendell castle is both a sculptor who makes furniture and a furniture craftsman who makes sculpture. experts say he's currently acknowledged to be the only major artist working in furniture
wendell castle, the kingpin of art furniture in the united states, takes delight in creating pieces that sometimes defy definition
his work, whether it's a chair with a wooden suit coat draped over it or a cabinet that appears destined to topple over, always seems to have a ``fooled you again'' quality
the 55-year-old artist has found an interesting niche between the art and furniture worlds
for example, a ladder-like, impractical sculpture contains a tiny, working cabinet. a beautifully crafted table has an open book and eyeglasses carved out of wood sitting atop the delicate inlay
he can turn wood into wrinkled sheets and cabinets into spectacular sculpture
castle, trying to explain his career recently to an acquaintance who is an attorney, told him, ``i make art furniture.''
in this case, that statement didn't help matters,'' castle recalls. ``so i said, `it's sort of halfway between being furniture and sculpture
that is exactly what i do, but whether that description means anything to a lawyer, i don't know.''
castle is a sculptor who makes furniture, a furniture craftsman who makes sculpture
his creations sell for anywhere from $8,000 to $130,000. they have been shown in art galleries and on the pages of woodworking magazines
his two most important commissions recently have been designing the 500,000th steinway piano and a 19-foot tall clock sculpture in downtown toronto
castle, a slender, bearded man who wears half-glasses when he delicately trims blocks of wood on a band saw, doesn't mind being a man without a label. in fact, he prefers it
i sort of bounce back and forth,'' he says. ``whenever i get real close to one or stay close to one for very long, it bothers me. staying in the middle is more difficult, but there's where i really want to be.''
in the art world, castle is well known as the only major artist working in furniture, a field that has a rich history dating back to the renaissance, says art historian penelope hunter-stiebel
probably the ``most recognizable artist of this type'' is thomas chippendale, the 18th century english cabinetmaker, says hunter-steibel, a former curator at metropolitan museum of art in new york, who acquired a castle loveseat for the museum. ``there's been lots of cabinetmakers, but only a few artists. wendell castle is one of the few.''
in the furniture world, castle's name is a ``household word'' among woodworkers and furniture designers, says paul bertorelli, a senior editor at taunton press, publisher of ``fine woodworking'' magazine
castle graduated from the university of kansas with an undergraduate degree in industrial design and a master's degree in sculpture
he painted abstract expressionist art before coming to the rochester institute of technology in 1962 and starting his innovative career that took him to brockport state college in 1970 and then to his own furniture design school in 1980
during that time he's created some of the world's strangest-looking chairs, desks, clocks and book shelves. he's tackling a musical instrument for the first time
i've never even made a guitar. i've been interested in building a piano for maybe 10 years,'' he says. castle was approached by the smithsonian institution about building a piano in the 1970s, but the project fell through
castle was given the prestigious commission of designing the 500,000th steinway model d grand piano last summer and submitted 10 designs to steinway &amp; sons
all of the designs were somewhat conservative, at least by castle's standards
there wouldn't be any point in reinventing the piano,'' he says. ``and since the steinway model d is the standard concert instrument in the world i didn't think it would be smart to deviate from it too much.''
the 100,000th steinway is in the smithsonian and the 200,000th, presented to president franklin d. roosevelt in 1938, is in the east room of the white house
castle's design uses dark ebony and striped indian ebony wood to create an elegant, angular shape with large boxy legs
the names of the more than 1,000 steinway artists, such as vladimir horowitz and van cliburn, who chose to play steinways professionally, will be etched into the dark ebony
in his workshop, castle gently brushes the sawdust from the dark, unfinished wood as he explains how moving the rear leg on his design dramatically changed the piano's sound
the rear leg, he says, is always found on the edge of the piano so it won't affect the vibrations that produce the instrument's sounds
but i don't like the look of that, so we're going to do a little bit of extra work so we can put the leg here,'' castle said pointing to an area in the middle of the piano
the change will require the construction of a bridge-like device that will keep the leg from actually touching the underside of the center of the piano
the piano will be unveiled june 2 at a gala celebration in carnegie hall in new york and will then begin a tour of the world's great concert halls, says steinway spokesman leo spellman
a day earlier, castle's huge clock, made out of bronze and stainless steel, will be unveiled at the corner of bloor and yonge streets, one of downtown toronto's busiest intersections
both works will mark a milestone of sorts for castle
i've wanted to make a stronger statement publicly. i've wanted to make big pieces,'' castle says. ``that's one of the problems with furniture. a sculptor can make a monument _ an important public piece. well, what's an important piece of furniture. i don't know what that is.''
a federal judge dealt a severe blow to campeau corp. in the battle for control of federated department stores inc., ruling that federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense could remain in effect
at the same time on friday, u.s. district judge leonard sand delayed a decision on when campeau's $6.2 billion cash tender offer for federated should be allowed to expire
sand denied a request from r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. to force campeau's offer to remain open until march 30, but he ruled the bid must remain in effect at least until next friday
president reagan named treasury secretary james a. baker iii to head a working group to coordinate recommendations for altering the government's regulation of financial markets
the group was appointed friday under a presidential order after nicholas f. brady, head of reagan's task force on the oct. 19 stock market crash, told congress a repeat of that event could occur unless the government's regulatory authorities are put under one roof
the sec has blamed trading in stock index futures for worsening the october crash, which saw the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fall more than 500 points in one day
a white house commission said the government should turn over to private businesses the operation of prisons, air traffic control facilities, mail delivery and scores of other services
agencies now providing those services ``have become muscle-bound to the point of paralysis,'' the panel's chairman, david f. linowes, told reporters friday after presenting president reagan with what he called the first ``independent, exhaustive analysis'' of the privatization issue
international paper co. said it planned to begin discussions with union representatives aimed at resolving bitter labor disputes at several plants around the country
officials for the company and the international paperworkers international union said friday they had agreed to meet with intermediaries within the next several weeks
the meetings are intended to defuse the hostility between management and labor and set up a framework for pursuing the company's labor problems on a local level, the company said
roper corp. accepted a sweetened $470 million buyout offer from whirlpool corp., which filed suit charging that general electric corp. tried to ``sabotage'' the deal with a competing bid
roper said its board reviewed both offers before recommending whirlpool's $50-a-share cash tender offer to shareholders on friday
the bid tops the $37.50-a-share whirlpool offer made last month, which prompted a bidding war for the augusta, ga.-based maker of garden equipment and cooking ranges
illegal aliens are driving down wages and job conditions for low-income native americans and legal immigrants but also are indirectly enhancing job opportunities for some higher-skilled workers, congressional investigators say in a new report
hurt most by the tide of illegal workers sweeping border, farm and some metropolitan areas are native and legally documented immigrant crop pickers, janitors and food processing workers, the general accounting office said friday
pillsbury co.'s report of a larger-than-expected quarterly loss ended a two-day run-up in its stock price that was spurred by takeover speculation, but analysts said the company remained vulnerable
i don't think anything has really changed,'' craig carver of dain bosworth inc. said friday. ``i think this company is still a very strong takeover possibility even though the stock has traded down somewhat.''
in active trading on the new york stock exchange, pillsbury closed down $2.50 a share at $42.87{
the senate finance committee approved a ``taxpayer bill of rights'' that would require the internal revenue service to waive any penalty resulting from erroneous written advice from the irs
the watered-down bill approved friday is designed to respond to what sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, called ``a bully mentality'' among some irs officials. the future of the legislation, sponsored chiefly by sen. david pryor, d-ark., is uncertain. the reagan administration opposes several parts of it, as do some members of the house ways and means committee
bridgestone corp. of japan plans to create the most-technologically advanced tire company in the world when it purchases firestone tire &amp; rubber co., bridgestone president akira yeiri said
firestone's board of directors recommended that shareholders accept bridgestone's offer to purchase firestone's 32 million outstanding shares for $80 a share. bridgestone was spurred to make the $2.6 billion offer thursday because of an unsolicited offer from italian tiremaker pirelli spa
less than a week before insider trader ivan f. boesky was to start serving a federal prison term, officials declined to discuss his whereabouts and there were indications he might already be in custody
the mystery friday of the ex-financier's location came against a background of death threats made against him, raising the possibility that he might have sought federal protection prior to his scheduled surrender date of march 24
boesky, the central figure in wall street's biggest insider trading scandal, was sentenced to a three-year prison term for securities fraud
a federal judge has set a january court date in polaroid corp.'s $5.7 billion patent infringement claim against eastman kodak co
judge rya zobel on friday set a jan. 9, 1989, trial date in the 12-year-old case and ordered pre-trial evidence be presented to the court on july 27
in 1985, zobel ruled that kodak had infringed on seven of about 150 polaroid patents on instant cameras and film
polaroid claims $3.2 billion in lost camera and film sales and seeks an additional $2.5 billion for lost opportunities to develop and market new products
the stock market managed a meager advance friday. the dow jones average of 30 industrials edged up 1.33 points to 2,087.37, stretching its gain for the week to 52.39 points
bond prices dropped in active trading, pressured by resurgent anxiety about inflation
the dollar held its ground against other foreign currencies, while gold moved higher
on other markets, oil futures moved higher for the fourth consecutive day, wheat was higher while corn and soybeans declined
koppers co.'s board of directors will consider a sweetened buyout offer totaling about $1.5 billion from a group led by british investor brian beazer and the firm shearson lehman hutton inc., the company says
the new offer disclosed sunday of $56 for each of koppers' roughly 27.2 million common shares outstanding tops the group's initial $45 a share offer that koppers rejected as inadequate last week
koppers stock rose 12{ cents to $53.75 a share friday in new york stock exchange composite trading
charles r. pullin, koppers chairman, said that in addition to considering the sweetened offer the construction materials and chemical company would continue exploring ways to enhance shareholder values
in rejecting the investor group's initial offer, koppers' board authorized management to examine defensive alterantives that might include a recapitalization plan under which shareholders would receive a substantial dividend payment while retaining equity in the company
pullin also reiterated a disclosure made last week in a securities and exchange commission filing that koppers was engaged in discussions with third parties regarding the possible sale of the company's construction materials and services businesses
the dollar fell in light trading in europe today in the absence of any market-moving news. gold prices rose
foreign exchange dealers said they expected the trading session to remain lackluster throughout much of the european day because of a lack of input from tokyo, where markets are closed for a holiday
traders said that in absence of news, some dealers were taking minor short-dollar positions _ or agreeing to sell dollars they don't yet own _ in expectations of a further slide in the dollar in the short term
we see the dollar coming down a bit, especially since it failed to take out 1.70 (west german marks) after the (u.s.) trade figures came out,'' said a senior dealer at a major u.s. bank in frankfurt
the commerce department reported thursday the u.s. merchandise trade deficit widened to $12.4 billion in january from $12.2 billion in december. the markets had been expecting a deficit of $12.8 billion
the dollar was quoted at 127.35 yen in london, compared with 128.35 yen in tokyo on friday
other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late friday's rates, included: 1.6898 west german marks, down from 1.6950; 1.3970 swiss francs, down from 1.4010; 5.7440 french francs, down from 5.7480; 1.8983 dutch guilders, down from 1.9010; 1,250.75 italian lire, down from 1,252.50; and 1.2470 canadian dollars, down from 1.2495
in london, the british pound was quoted at $1.8300, compared with $1.8235 late friday
gold opened in london at a bid price of $445.80 dollars a troy ounce, compared with late friday's $443.25. at mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $446.50
in zurich, the noon bid price was $446.35, up from $445 late friday
earlier, in hong kong, gold closed at $448.26 bid, up 36 cents from saturday
silver was quoted in london today at a bid price of $6.37 a troy ounce, up from late friday's $6.31
alexander m. lewyt, an inventor who developed a vacuum cleaner designed to operate without interfering with tv or radio reception, has died at age 79
lewyt died on friday
born in new york, lewyt was the son of an austrian immigrant who ran a gadget shop
he held patents on scores of inventions
when he learned of undertakers' difficulty in fastening neckties on corpses, the teen-age lewyt devised a new kind of bow tie that clipped on. he sold 50,000 of them. it was unclear whether he ever patented the concept
he was best known for the compact lewyt vacuum cleaner, which had no dust bag and was designed not to cause interference
in the first eight years after his vacuum cleaner was introduced after world war ii, lewyt corp. sold 2 million of them. during the war, lewyt corp. did a multi-million dollar business making such things as radar antennas and popcorn poppers
lewyt sold his interest in the company to the budd corp. in the 1950s
stocks fell in early active trading today, eroding gains of the previous week
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 19.23 points to 2,068.14 as of 10 a.m. est
among broader market barometers, the new york stock exchange composite index of all listed issues fell 1.16 to 151.49. the american stock exchange market value index fell 1.07 to 298.04
losing issues outnumbered gainers by more than a 5-to-3 margin on the nyse, with 558 down, 300 up and 386 unchanged. volume totaled 21.48 million after the first half hour
on friday, the dow jones industrials managed a 1.33-point advance to 2,087.37, its second straight post-crash high, but the broader market was mixed
losers outpaced gainers by 8-to-7 on the nyse, with 807 down, 716 up and 461 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 245.75 million shares, against 211.92 million the previous session
nestle sa, the giant swiss food products group, plans to appoint paul volcker, former chairman of the u.s. federal reserve, to its board of directors, the company has announced
shareholders will be asked to elect volcker and swiss industrialist stephan schmidheiny to nestle's board at the company's general meeting on may 19, the company said friday
volcker, who last year elected not to accept another term at the u.s. central bank, earlier this month was named chairman of the new york investment banking firm james d. wolfensohn inc. and as a professor at princeton university
during his eight years as chairman of the fed, volcker gained an international reputation, which combined with the widespread connections made during from his tenure as fed chairman has made him much sought-after by private business
west germany said monday it will sell its remaining shares in volkswagen ag, returning to its twice-delayed plans to privatize the government's stake in the giant car company
the government will sell its 16 percent volkswagen stake at 238 marks, or $140, a share beginning thursday, according to a statement by the finance ministry. the price set by the finance ministry is a slight discount from volkswagen's current cost of 240 marks a share
the government owns 4.8 million shares in the company, and expects to make some 1.14 billion marks on the deal, the ministry said
the shares will be sold through a consortium of 75 west german and foreign banks led by dresdner bank, deutsche bank, commerzbank and others
west germany announced plans to sell its volkswagen stake more than a year ago, but the move has been delayed twice in recent months
the sale was delayed last summer after volkswagen was hit by a scandal in the company's foreign exchange division that cost millions of marks
plans to reschedule the sale for late in the year were shelved shortly after the oct. 19 stock market crash that sent share prices plummeting around the world
analysts say the government is going ahead with the transaction now because it is faced with a wider-than-expected federal budget deficit in 1988
stocks fell broadly this morning, pressured by another dose of post-crash anxiety and declining bond prices
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which hit the highest level since the oct. 19 collapse twice last week and flirted with the 2,100-point barrier, fell 20.89 points to 2,066.48 by 11 a.m. on wall street
there are very nervous people out there,'' said hank striefler, vice president on the trading floor at shearson lehman hutton inc. ``everybody is concerned. by reaching 2,100, that's sort of a top for the dow at the moment.''
among broader market indicators, the new york stock exchange composite index of all listed issues fell 1.34 to 151.31. on the american stock exchange, the market value index fell 1.39 to 297.72
declining issues outnumbered gainers by nearly 3-to-1 on the nyse, with 954 down, 344 up and 440 unchanged. volume totaled 46.6 million shares after the first 90 minutes of trading
brokers said some of the selling pressure came from slumping prices in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of inflation and interest rates. evidence of economic strength that emerged from government reports last week suggested that inflation could intensify, eroding the value of fixed-income investments
