on friday, the dow jones industrials managed a 1.33-point advance to 2,087.37, its second straight post-crash high, but the broader market was mixed
losers outpaced gainers by 8-to-7 on the nyse, with 807 down, 716 up and 461 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 245.75 million shares, against 211.92 million the previous session
the supreme court agreed today to hear a reagan administration appeal aimed at allowing some creditors to collect more money from debtors who declare bankruptcy
the court said it will review a decision denying the government's claim for some interest payments on taxes owed by a bankrupt company
the case stems from a reorganization petition filed by ron pair enterprises before a bankruptcy judge in detroit in 1984
the government said the company owed it $53,278 in taxes, penalties and interest accrued prior to the filing of the bankruptcy petition
the company agreed to pay the amount, but refused to pay additional interest accrued after the bankruptcy filing
the government said the company should pay the post-filing interest because the collateral _ tax liens on company property _ securing the debt owed the government exceeded the amount of the original debt
the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled against the government in september. the appeals court said the bankruptcy code, revised by congress in 1978, does not clearly provide for such payments. they previously had been disallowed by courts
justice department lawyers said the appeals court ruling could prove costly to the government
they said the internal revenue service filed secured claims in bankruptcy proceedings totaling more than $730 million from 1982 through 1986, including $186 million in 1986 alone
the government lawyers said state and local governments and private creditors also are affected by the appeals court ruling
the case is u.s. vs. ron pair, 87-1043. pickup.</note>
general electric co. today boosted its bid for roper corp. to $507 million and filed lawsuits seeking to block roper from merging with whirlpool corp
ge, which sweetened its bid by $9 a share, announced the new $54-a-share tender offer today
the offer betters whirlpool's second tender bid for roper, made last week, which amounts to $50 a share, or about $470 million. ge's latest bid expires april 1, unless extended
whirlpool's initial $37.50-a-share offer prompted the bidding war for augusta, ga.-based roper. on march 6, ge entered the fray by offering to pay $45 a share for roper's 9.4 million outstanding shares
after jumping $5.75 a share on friday, roper stock had risen another $2.625 a share on the new york stock exchange by midday
ge's lawsuit, filed in delaware state court, is the second wave of legal action in the battle for the augusta, ga.-based appliance and lawn equipment maker
on friday, whirlpool filed suit charging that ge tried to ``sabotage the definitive merger agreement whirlpool reached with roper's board of directors last month
moving aggressively, ge today alleged that the roper board made no effort to ``test the price'' before agreeing to merge with whirlpool on feb. 29. ge charged that roper concealed ge's interest in the company when it advised shareholders to tender to whirlpool
ge contends that it had expressed ``prior interest in acquiring roper and had asked to be informed if roper became available for acquisition.''
the suit was filed against the roper board and names whirlpool as a defendant
in a separate lawsuit filed in u.s. district court in delaware, ge charged that both whirlpool and roper failed to adequately disclose terms of their merger agreement under securities and exchange commission laws
ge said in a statement earlier that it would ``vigorously defend itself'' against whirlpool's charges that ge tried to ``sabotage'' the whirlpool-roper merger agreement. ge seeks to transfer that suit from u.s. district court in grand rapids, mich., to federal court in delaware
in its lawsuit, whirlpool charged that ge intentionally sought to block whirlpool's merger with roper
whirlpool alleged that the head of ge's appliance business personally tried to persuade roper to break its contract with whirlpool. the suit said ge ``intentionally, maliciously and unjustifiedly engaged in a continuing course of conduct to sabotage'' the deal
ge said in a statement today the suit ``grossly misstated the facts and was totally without legal merit.'' ge noted that its offer was made directly to shareholders who ``are not bound by the acquisition agreement between whirlpool and the roper board.''
whirlpool said its suit is ``similar in theory'' to pennzoil co.'s billion-dollar legal battle with texaco inc. over texaco's acquisition of getty oil co. texaco agreed to settle the suit for $3 billion after pennzoil won a $10.3 billion judgment against the oil giant on charges that texaco prompted getty to back out of an agreement with pennzoil
roper has been supportive of whirlpool's efforts. last week roper chief executive officer robert cook said the company ``has a strong desire to see this combination successfully completed.''
analysts say a roper-whirlpool merger will move whirlpool ahead of ge as the nation's leading appliance maker. whirlpool has said it would expand roper from a maker of cooking ranges into a producer and marketer of a full line of appliances
roper reported net income of $24 million on sales of $703 million in fiscal 1987
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that makes it easier for investors to sue their brokers over the collapse in 1984 of a $3 billion oil and natural gas investment fund
the court, without comment, rejected appeals by three brokerage firms seeking to force investors who lost money in the fund to sue individually rather than as a group
the case stems from the collapse of the petro-lewis fund, in which some 180,000 people purchased securities and limited partnerships from 1970 to 1984. the average initial investment by a limited partner was $8,600
petro-lewis' financial problems began when a supply glut caused oil and gas prices to plummet in the early 1980s
the fund revealed in february 1984 that its condition was critical, cutting partnership distribution by as much as 50 percent and selling up to one-third of its reserves
that prompted numerous lawsuits against petro-lewis, and also against brokers who helped market the fund
some investors settled with petro-lewis, which set up a $23.5 million fund to handle the claims. but that agreement did not preclude investors from suing their brokers
the investors said the brokerage houses and individual brokers ``knowingly or recklessly participated with petro-lewis in disseminating misleading information'' about the financial condition of the funds
at issue in the case acted on today is whether the investors can maintain ``class action'' suits that permit them to apportion the costs of fighting the case and divide up any court award
robinson-humphrey co., shearson lehman hutton inc. and painewebber inc. appealed a ruling by the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals in atlanta favoring the investors
the appeals court said investors who claimed they were defrauded are arguing a common theory
they allege ``that the petro-lewis shares, which were not traded on the open market, could not have been marketed but for the defendants' fraud,'' the appeals court said
the appeals court rejected the brokers' argument that because investors relied on information given them orally by different brokers their claims should be tried separately
the complaints alleged that the defendant brokerage firms and individual officers engaged in a common course of conduct to misrepresent ... the financial condition of petro-lewis,'' the appeals court said. ``these claims involve common issues that clearly overwhelm the individual issues that may be present.''
it would be repetitive, wasteful and an unnecessary burden on the courts to require separate trials, the appeals court added
the cases are robinson humphrey vs. sanders, 87-835, and painewebber vs. parker, 87-836
grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly higher today on the chicago board of trade in reaction to reports of real and rumored grain purchases by the soviet union
on friday, the agriculture department targeted the soviet union for 1 million metric tons of u.s. wheat under the export enhancement program
the usda also announced late friday that the soviets had bought 500,000 metric tons of u.s. corn
rumors early today that the soviet union had purchased some south american soybean meal helped boost soybean futures, said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc
that's not as friendly as if they'd bought u.s. meal but if the rumors are correct, it shows that russia is in the market for meal again,'' lespinasse said
in early trading, wheat was } cent to 2 cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.01 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1} cents higher with march at $1.99 a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to 1} cents higher with march at $1.95} a bushel; soybeans were 5{ cents to 7\ cents higher with march at $6.27 a bushel
livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the chicago mercantile exchange
live cattle were .27 cent lower to .37 cent higher with april at 73.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .27 cent lower with march at 81.85 cents a pound; hogs were .50 cent lower to .10 cent higher with april at 45.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .15 cent lower to .55 cent higher with march at 55.65 cents a pound
livestock and meat futures closed mostly higher on friday
