takeover action buoyed some notable issues. koppers rose 3 to 56} following another takeover offer of $56 a share from beazer plc. american standard rose { to 76| after kelso said it would consider an increase in its $78-a-share offer to thwart counter-offers from rival black &amp; decker
claire molloy sits in her wheelchair mulling the possible purchase of a knit jogging suit that just happens to be in lilac, currently her favorite color
what i really need are lilac sneakers,'' said the 65-year-old resident of the bartley manor nursing home before tossing the jogging suit back on the rack
she and other residents were choosing their spring wardrobes over coffee and doughnuts in the nursing home's sunny recreation room
the at-home shopping service is made available by silverthreads inc., an audubon, n.j.-based company that specializes in health-care apparel
silverthreads actually is a traveling store that sets up shop in nursing homes in delaware, maryland, new jersey, pennsylvania, virginia and west virginia. its mail-order catalog serves other customers, many of whom are cared for at home by their families
silverthreads president martin misiaszek, who started the firm 10 years ago, said the company tries to provide its elderly customers with everyday apparel such as nightgowns and dresses as well as specialized apparel such as washable shoes for patients who may be incontinent
what we try to do is bring a clothing store to a nursing home,'' said misiaszek, who has a degree in health-care management
silverthreads treats its customers, most of whom are over 85 years old, with respect and understanding, he said
we all like to see what we're going to purchase, whether it has two pockets or a belt. these people are no different,'' he said
while on the road, silverthreads packs its inventory, racks, bins and mirrors in a 20-foot truck. it's driven by misiaszek's younger brother, bob, the company's vice president
silverthreads' most popular lines are shirts, dresses and night clothes that close in the back, and mens' pants with snaps on the sides, he said
these are for people who can't dress themselves so nurses can dress them,'' bob misiaszek said. ``it's a big help for nurses aides.''
other speciality items include terry-cloth bibs with velcro snaps, flannel and corduroy lap wraps that tie around a wheelchair patient's waist and cushy non-skid slippers for patients with foot disorders
we try to have clothes that allow people to retain their self-esteem,'' bob misiaszek said while straightening a bin filled with dainty women's underwear and frilly nightgowns
prices are range from $24 for cotton dresses with front zippers to $16 for a two-piece jumpsuit
the prices are reasonable. we've been looking around and the prices here are better than a department store,'' said jerry schultz of pine beach, n.j
he and his wife, jean, were shopping for new clothes for his 91-year-old mother, amelia schultz
this is ideal,'' he said. ``we can't take mother out to the store and she should like what she's wearing.''
silverthreads also will put on fashion shows at the request of nursing homes. the shows are a boost for patients and staff alike, said betty maxwell, the recreation director at bartley manor
it's great. they can try them on right afterwards,'' she said as some residents and their families clustered around racks of dresses, slacks and other items
the misiaszeks say annual sales are a family secret. they also say silverthreads provides more than a shopping service
it's really rewarding to see i'm making a difference. it really has a lot of painful moments,'' martin misiaszek said. ``but i love it. i wouldn't do anything else except win the lottery.''
mrs. molloy never found her lilac sneakers, although there were plenty in other colors
nooooo,'' she said. ``gotta be lilac.''
she settled for a pair of pale yellow slacks, then decided to browse a bit longer because ``i might find something else that strikes my fancy. they have things here that we can really use.''
unionists at the beijing no. 1 machine tool plant recently decided the factory manager had not been duly rewarded for his hard work, and voted to increase his annual bonus
that was one example, boasted zheng lanjun, head of the 7,200-member union, of how unions in socialist china strive to serve, rather than confront, the system
but that cozy relationship, under the firm guidance of the communist party, is changing
china's bold economic reforms, including giving factory bosses the authority to hire and fire workers, have forced unions to redefine their role, and even infused them with a touch of militancy
with party approval, unions are becoming more democratic, less subservient to the party and more vocal on such issues as wages and worker safety
the reforms have brought prosperity to the country and benefits to workers,'' shen zuying, spokesman for the all-china federation of trade unions, said in an interview. ``but they have also created new tasks for the unions as protectors of workers' interests.''
shen related how a union in wuhan, central china, recently fought back when the manager fired six workers for breaking factory rules. it managed to get five reinstated, he said
in the northeast city of tianjin, workers at a factory exercised their new-found power to oversee company operations by casting a no-confidence vote against the factory manager. he was reassigned to the plant's library
the government has sanctioned a more assertive union movement to balance the growing power of factory managers under reforms that make industry more competitive and end lifetime employment guarantees
beijing is giving factory heads greater freedom and responsibility over profits and losses, and promoting job contracts that tie wages to performance. few workers ever get fired, but for the first time, employees face discipline and possible dismissal for loafing on the job
communist party chief zhao ziyang has called on unions to wake up to the new realities, and play a greater ``supervisory role'' over the activities of their now powerful bosses
for a long time, trade unions were only involved in trifles, distributing film tickets or relief aid to needy workers,'' the official xinhua news agency said. ``they played a small role in political issues.''
that wasn't all the unions' fault. the all-china federation of trade unions, made up of 15 union groupings with a membership of 90 million, or 90 percent of chinese factory workers, dates back to 1926. but since the communists came to power in 1949 and proclaimed the dictatorship of the proletariat, the unions have been relegated to carrying out the party line on the factory floor
in the 1950s, unions were accused of ``syndicalism,'' or trying to dominate the government, and unions were disbanded during the ultra-leftist 1966-76 cultural revolution
the right of workers to strike was deleted from the 1982 constitution
the leaders didn't think it was necessary,'' said the acftu's shen. ``we are socialists, and the country's interests and those of workers are the same.''
he added, however, that strikes are not illegal, and that if a strike is found to be justified, ``we should support it.'' such cases, he said, have been very rare
instead, unions are focusing on gaining a greater say in factory decisions
workers in many plants nominate and elect their union representatives, called workers' congresses. the congresses, or their leaders, must in turn be consulted by the factory manager before major decisions are made, particularly on personnel matters
party officials are supposed to let the unions run their own day-to-day affairs, although they still hold seats on union committees and are expected to guide the ideological thinking of workers
in the past, the party interfered too much in our activities,'' shen said
the union at the beijing no. 1 machine tool plant, besides organizing badminton tournaments and calligraphy classes, is increasingly called on to mediate worker disputes, zheng said
he related how the union was the arbiter when a woman caught stealing was fired, and when a man who lost both legs in an accident was unhappy with management's compensation of a new apartment, television and refrigerator. in both cases, the union came down on the side of management
but the union also has demanded that the factory do something about its unsanitary dining hall, and is pushing for the factory to provide physical examinations more frequently than the current once every four years
the trade union should support the director in exercising his rights, and at the same time protect the rights of workers,'' zheng said
the acftu's monopoly over organized labor is not likely to change. in 1981, some young people tried to establish independent unions modeled after poland's solidarity, but they were quickly suppressed
although union membership is technically voluntary, almost everybody joins. zheng said the 100 non-union workers in the 7,300-worker plant are new employees who haven't put their applications in yet
but the acftu's shen noted that the reforms also have created 20 million private businessmen and 80 million workers in small rural factories who are largely unorganized. these groups, he said, may be the union movement's next big challenge
bell resources ltd. on monday withdrew its takeover offer for bell group ltd. following a bid for bell resources by two investors
the investors, sir ronald brierley's industrial equity ltd. and kerry packer's consolidated press holdings ltd., are jointly offering 900 million australian dollars, the equivalent of $665 million, for bell resources
their offer, made last thursday, was conditioned on bell resources ending its offer for bell group. the companies are the main listed concerns operated by australian financier robert holmes a court
bell resources said the takeover offer was ``a material change in circumstances'' that should be considered by the company and its shareholders although bell resources considered the price inadequate
brierley and packer were offering 1.50 australian dollars a share for bell resources. the company's stock closed at 1.57 australian dollars in trading in sydney monday, indicating the market expects the bid to be raised
on feb. 29, bell resources offered one of its own shares plus 1 australian dollar cash for each bell group share
the bid was seen by many analysts as a move to simplify holmes a court's corporate structure after the october stock market crash, to put togther bell resource's cash and investments with bell group's industrial operations, and therefore to reduce bell group's heavy borrowings
the move would give holmes a court cash. he owns 45 percent of bell group, which in owns about 40 percent of bell resources
the takeover bid was criticized as too generous for bell group shares and so to the disadvantage of bell resources shareholders
investment in plant and equipment by u.s. business is likely to increase about 8.8 percent this year but only 0.5 percent in 1989, according to a survey released monday
manufacturers are likely to lead the way this year with a 12.5 percent increase in investment, but trail in 1989 with a 2.9 percent decrease, data resources inc. of lexington, mass., said
the larger non-manufacturing sector is expected to be more stable, with a 6.6 percent increase this year and a 2.7 percent increase in 1989, the survey said, based on answers from 457 companies
companies were more optimistic about 1988 than in a previous survey conducted just before the october stock market crash, when they predicted overall investment in plant and equipment would rise 6.2 percent, according to data resources, a unit of mcgraw-hill inc
many economists say the stock market crash cooled off the economy at a time when it was in danger of overheating and falling into recession. some are now pushing back the date of an expected recession to 1989
here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken monday by the supreme court in some business-related cases:

dalkon shield

the court refused to let the dalkon shield's maker set up a $15 million emergency fund to help women who say the contraceptive device left them infertile
the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that blocks creation of the fund pending the outcome of bankruptcy proceedings for a.h. robins, which manufactures the device
in a related case, the court refused to review a ruling that at least temporarily barred some dalkon shield users from suing aetna casualty &amp; surety co., which insures a.h. robins for liability claims
the cases are mabey vs. official committee of equity security holders, 87-1267, and oberg vs. aetna, 87-1208

equal time

the court rejected a constitutional attack on a federal law requiring broadcasters to give equal time to opposing candidates for public office
the justices, without comment, turned down the appeal of a sacramento, calif., television reporter kept off the air while he ran for a non-salaried town council seat
the case is branch vs. fcc, 87-628

age bias

the court, agreeing to decide an important issue for all lawsuits alleging age bias in employment, said it will study the case of a laid-off pennsylvania man
the justices agreed to decide whether eugene f. brieck's lawsuit against his former employer, harbison-walker refractories, should proceed to a jury trial
the case is harbison-walker vs. brieck, 87-271

government contracts

the court agreed to consider killing a key provision of a law designed to promote competitive bidding on government contracts, setting the stage for a new ruling on the boundaries between congressional and presidential powers
the court said it will hear reagan administration arguments challenging the comptroller general's role in administering the 1984 competition in contracting act
the case is army corps of engineers vs. ameron, 87-163

sales tax

the court agreed to decide whether states may impose sales taxes on most books, newspapers and magazines while exempting religious publications
the justices said they will review a texas court ruling that said such a tax neither violates equal-protection rights nor breeches the constitutionally required separation of church and state
the case is texas monthly vs. bullock, 87-1245

cable rates

the court refused to let states and local governments regulate the prices most of the nation's cable television operators charge for basic service
the court, without comment, rejected arguments that the deregulation effected in 1986 by congress and the federal communications commission left subscribers vulnerable to illegal monopoly pricing

the case is connecticut vs. fcc, 87-671

the court agreed to examine the power of labor unions to fire elected officials for disagreeing with union policies
the court said it will consider killing a lawsuit by a los angeles area union business representative who said he was fired illegally by the sheet metal workers' international association
the case is sheet metal workers vs. lynn, 86-1940

superfund

the court agreed to consider shielding states from having to help pay for cleaning up hazardous waste sites when the federal government sues businesses under the so-called superfund law
the court said it will hear arguments by pennsylvania officials that exposing states to such liability could saddle them with $100 billion in clean-up costs
the case is pennsylvania vs. union gas, 87-1241

rico

the court agreed to consider making it easier for people to use a federal anti-racketeering law to sue businesses
the court said it will hear an appeal by phone customers in minnesota who have accused northwestern bell telephone co. of trying to bribe state public utility officials
the phone subscribers sued the company under a law known as the racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act (rico)
the case is h.j. inc. vs. northwestern bell, 87-1252
kelso &amp; co. expects to decide by the end of this month whether to sweeten its $2.5 billion tender offer for american standard inc. to fend off rival bidder black &amp; decker corp., according to a report published monday
american standard, a new york-based plumbing and air conditioning company, on thursday accepted kelso's $78-a-share offer. but the following day, black &amp; decker raised its bid for american standard to $77 a share from $73
the kelso offer began monday and was scheduled to expire at 12:01 a.m. est april 1. black &amp; decker extended its offer to expire on the same day
despite the fact that kelso's bid is about $30 million higher, black &amp; decker has maintained that its proposal is better ``in light of the timing and probability of payment.''
black &amp; decker, a towson, md.-based tool and appliance maker, is hoping to benefit from nervous arbitrageurs who hold a majority of american standard's stock and worry that kelso might not be able to come up with the financing to complete the transaction
tendering their shares to black &amp; decker still would ensure a premium price for american standard's stock, which by late afternoon monday traded at $76.50 a share, up 87.5 cents, on the new york stock exchange
kelso, however, said it was willing to raise its bid to win over shareholders, according to monday's editions of the wall street journal
we didn't come this far to be deterred by this kind of response,'' joseph schuchert, kelso's managing partner, told the newspaper. ``we'll tender at $78 and see what they do. if it's necessary to bump our tender offer, that's what we'll do.''
he said kelso was unlikely to act until march 31
kelso officials did not return numerous telephone calls from the associated press on monday
kelso specializes in leveraged buyouts involving employee stock ownership plans, or esops, a concept it pioneered about 30 years ago
in a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely through borrowed money repaid from the target company's profits or sale of assets. esops also are financed mostly with borrowed funds, but equity is divided among all of the company's workers, not just a few investors
kelso said it planned to finance the american standard acquisition through a $250 million investment and several bank loans
stocks fell today in a spate of selling that reflected another dose of post-crash anxiety and falling prices in the bond market, a warning signal of higher interest rates
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which hit the highest level since the oct. 19 collapse twice last week and flirted with the 2,100-point barrier, fell 21.89 points to 2,065.48 by 3 p.m. on wall street
there are very nervous people out there,'' said hank striefler, vice president on the trading floor at shearson lehman hutton inc. ``everybody is concerned. by reaching 2,100, that's sort of a top for the dow at the moment.''
among broader market indicators, the new york stock exchange composite index of all listed issues fell 1.39 to 151.26. on the american stock exchange, the market value index fell 1.61 to 297.50
losing issues outnumbered gainers by more than 2-to-1 on the nyse, with 1,106 down, 427 up and 419 unchanged. volume totaled 107.07 million shares with an hour left, a considerably slower pace than in the two previous sessions
brokers said some of the selling pressure came from slumping prices in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of inflation and interest rates
evidence of economic strength that emerged from government reports last week suggested that inflation could intensify, eroding the value of fixed-income investments and dampening hope of an easier monetary policy by the federal reserve
among the most prominent losing blue-chips, ibm fell } to 113{, dupont fell 1 to 87}, philip morris fell 1] to 92} and merck fell 1| to 158{
takeover action buoyed some notable issues. koppers rose 3} to 57{ following another offer of $56 a share from beazer plc. pillsbury rose | to 43| on persistent speculation about unannounced offers for the company. federated department stores, target of rival takeover offers from r.h. macy and campeau, rose | to 66~
the supreme court agreed monday, in a case brought by phone customers in minnesota, to consider making it easier for people to use a federal anti-racketeering law to sue businesses
the court also agreed to hear a reagan administration appeal aimed at allowing some creditors to collect more money from debtors who declare bankruptcy
the justices also agreed to study the case of a laid-off pennsylvania man in a matter that could decide an important issue for lawsuits alleging age bias in employment
in another case, the court refused to let states and local governments regulate the prices which most of the nation's cable television operators charge for basic service
in the anti-racketeering case, the court said it will hear an appeal by phone customers in minnesota who have accused northwestern bell telephone co. of trying to bribe state public utility officials
the phone subcribers sued the company under a law known as the racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act (rico)
they said the company beginning in 1980 tried illegally to win rate increases by offering gifts, employment offers, tickets to sporting and cultural events and other favors to members of the minnesota public utilities commission
the suit was thrown out by a federal judge and that ruling was upheld last september by the 8th u.s. circuit court of appeals
the appeals court said the phone users failed to allege a continuing pattern of racketeering activity required to make a case under the rico act
the supreme court is being asked to choose among various theories of how difficult it should be to maintain such a lawsuit
in the bankruptcy case, the court said it will review a decision denying the government's claim for some interest payments on taxes owed by a bankrupt company
the case stems from a reorganization petition filed by ron pair enterprises before a bankruptcy judge in detroit in 1984
the government said the company owed $53,278 in taxes, penalties and interest accrued prior to the filing of the bankruptcy petition
the company agreed to pay the amount, but refused to pay additional interest accrued after the bankruptcy filing
the 6th u.s. circuit court of appeals ruled against the government in september. justice department lawyers said the appeals court ruling could prove costly to the government
in the age discrimination case, the justices agreed to decide whether eugene f. brieck's lawsuit against his former employer, harbison-walker refractories, should proceed to a jury trial
in july 1982, several employees of harbison-walker's iron and steel marketing support group were laid off, including brieck. he then was 55
brieck sued harbison-walker in pittsburgh in 1984, contending that he was laid off and not recalled to work because of his age
u.s. district judge gerald j. weber threw out brieck's suit, but the 3rd u.s. circuit court of appeals reinstated brieck's suit last june 19
in the cable tv case, the court, without comment, rejected arguments that the deregulation effected in 1986 by congress and the federal communications commission left subscribers vulnerable to illegal monopoly pricing
most of the nation's 7,800 cable tv operators provide both basic and ``premium'' services. for an extra monthly fee, subscribers receive channels offering exclusive sports and movie programming
prior to 1984, the fcc allowed local communities to regulate the rates charged for basic cable service but not for premium service rates
congress in 1984 enacted the cable communications policy act, which lets local authorities regulate basic cable rates only in the absence of ``effective competition.''
defining ``effective competition'' was left up to the fcc, and the commission's definition paved the way for the deregulation of basic-service rates charged by more than 90 percent of all cable operators
the appeal acted on monday was filed by lawyers for connecticut, new york city, the national league of cities and the american civil liberties union
lawyers for the commission and the cable operators association urged the justices to reject the appeal
in other cases, the court:
_agreed to consider killing a key provision of a law designed to promote competitive bidding on government contracts. at issue is the proper boundary between presidential and congressional power
_refused to let the dalkon shield's maker set up a $15 million emergency fund to help women who say the contraceptive device left them infertile. the court, without comment, let stand a ruling that blocks creation of the fund pending the outcome of bankruptcy proceedings for a.h. robins co. inc., which manufactures the device
_agreed to decide whether an airline may be forced to reinstate workers when their strike ends, making necessary the layoffs of trainees and employees who crossed the picket lines. the court said it will study an appeal by trans world airlines in a dispute stemming from a 1986 strike by flight attendants
_let stand a ruling that makes it easier for investors to sue their brokers over the collapse in 1984 of a $3 billion oil and natural gas investment fund
_agreed to decide in a case from texas whether states may impose sales taxes on most books, newspapers and magazines while exempting religious publications
steel production rose to 1.991 million tons in the week ended march 19, an increase of 1.2 percent from the previous week's 1.967 million tons, the american iron and steel institute reported monday
the industry's production amounted to 92.7 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 91.6 percent in the previous week
estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 21.726 million net tons, an increase of 34.8 percent from the 16.115 million net tons in the previous year. the steel operations of usx corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a strike during the first month of 1987
production so far this year used 89.7 percent of capacity, compared with 67.0 percent a year earlier
net tonnage by district for the week ended march 19: northeast coast, 277,000; pittsburgh, 203,000; youngstown, 131,000; lake erie, 164,000; detroit, 159,000; chicago, 553,000; midwest, 176,000; southern, 225,000; and western, 103,000
a new york real estate firm on monday announced plans to erect europe's tallest building _ a 53-story, 838-foot office tower _ on sprawling fairgrounds in this west german city
tishman speyer properties said the project, which it valued at $375 million, will be financed by citibank
the skyscraper, with its 920,000 square feet of office space, will surpass the palac kultury of warsaw, poland, as europe's tallest building. the palac kultury, has 42 stories and is 790 feet tall
frankfurt mayor wolfram brueck said the building is expected to be completed by 1991
tishman speyer president jerry speyer, appearing at a press conference with the mayor, said his company already has received rental inquiries about the building
frankfurt, west germany's flourishing banking and finance center, has been expanding in recent years. new office buildings have sprouted up in the city's center, and decaying downtown neighborhoods have been renovated
the fairgrounds are not far from the city's downtown shopping area, its main train station and banking district
tishman speyer manages a portfolio of properties valued at $4 billion, the company said in a statement. the company currently has $1 billion worth of projects under development, including the beijing american express center, an office and apartment complex in china
corn and soybean futures prices closed higher monday on the chicago board of trade, while wheat prices fell
soybean futures gained as much as 7\ cents a bushel. prices rose early on rumors of new soviet buying and got a boost later in the day when the south american agricultural newsletter safras y mercado dropped its brazilian soybean crop estimate by 400,000 metric tons due to dry weather in an important soybean region
wheat futures retreated on profit-taking by traders who had purchased contracts after the agriculture department's announcement late friday that it had targeted the soviet union for 1 million metric tons of wheat under the export enhancement program
at the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to { cent higher with the contract for delivery in march at $2.97\ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents to 3{ cents higher with march at $2.01\ a bushel; oats were 5 cents lower to { cent higher with march at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 7\ cents higher with march at $6.27 a bushel
the number of working oil and gas rigs in the united states declined by three this week to total 943, baker hughes inc. announced
this week's decrease was much smaller from the previous week, when the count lost 32 rigs to total 946. a year ago, the count totaled 784, baker hughes said monday
the rig count reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil as of last friday, not the number of rigs producing oil
houston-based baker hughes, an oil toolmaker company, tallies the number of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index of drilling activity
hughes tool co., which merged this year with baker international corp. of orange, calif., has kept track of the number of working rigs since 1940
the rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in december 1981, which was the height of the oil boom. but oil prices plunged to less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986 and the rig count went with it, dropping to 663 _ the lowest since hughes began compiling figures
among the major oil producing states, wyoming lost six rigs and texas was down by five this week. ohio's count was down by three, while north dakota and and pennsylvania each lost two rigs
states posting increases included new mexico and kansas, each of which gained four rigs. colorado's and california's counts were each up by two. oklahoma gained one rig, while louisiana lost one rig
british petroleum co. plc has been ordered to pay $1.36 million in fines for violating health and safety laws in connection with two refinery blasts that killed three men and seriously injured two others, the government said monday
the fine was the highest ever levied under the health and safety at work act enacted in 1974, officials said
high court judge lord allanbridge said he imposed ``substanial'' fines because ``there were obvious hazards to the safety and lives of employees and others'' at the refinery near falkirk in central scotland where the explosions occurred nine days apart in march 1987
the company pleaded guilty to two charges of breaking the health and safety act
after the ruling, the government's chief inspector for factories, david eves, said the explosions showed ``the ever present potential for serious incidents must not be underestimated.''
he said in a statement that ``these incidents .... cost the lives of three men, as well as a great deal of human suffering and the loss to the management of the company of millions of pounds in lost production and plant repairs.''
company officials were not available for comment monday evening
the judge fined the company 250,000 pounds ($455,000) for the first explosion, which was heard 20 miles away and hurled a three-ton steel plate more than half a mile
the first blast occurred when workers from two subcontractors began taking apart a section of machinery that had not been drained of flammable gases and liquids
liquid began leaking out and then exploded, killing james bruce, 40, and philip mellon, 35, and seriously injuring ian taylor and allan bissett. the fire took two days to put out
in the second incident, bp was fined 500,000 pounds ($910,000) for disconnecting a safety alarm at another unit where an explosion and fire killed george spiers, 52
the west german and french finance ministers praised the first meeting of their bilateral economic council monday and pledged to boost cooperation on monetary issues
the ministers said they did not talk about proposals for a european central bank during their landmark meeting, but agreed to meet again before the summer, in paris
gerhard stoltenberg, the west german finance minister, said monday's meeting reviewed economic developments in the two nations, analyzed budget and tax plans and began examining ways of boosting cooperation in monetary policy
french finance minister edouard balladur also praised the session, and said he was pleased with franco-german economic cooperation, particularly the close contact between the two nations' central banks
i am especially happy about the excellent cooperation that has existed between the bundesbank and the banque de france,'' he told reporters after the three-hour session
the franco-german economic council was established in january as a way of better coordinating policy between the two neighboring nations
the council is to meet four times a year, and comprise the nations' finance and economics ministers and the heads of the two central banks
west germany's central bank president, karl otto poehl, is known to have been skeptical about the council because of fears that it may infringe upon his bundesbank's independence
but poehl praised monday's session, and said the council would help europe achieve its goal of a barrier-free internal market by 1992
both stoltenberg and balladur said the council would work to better coordinate 1988 budgets in both nations, and concentrate on seeking ways of achieving economic growth. agreement in court</head> bid and closing stock price; picks up 5th graf pvs: ge's two ...</note>
general electric co. launched a double-pronged attack monday in its bid for roper corp. by boosting its tender offer to $507 million and filing lawsuits challenging roper's agreement to merge with whirlpool corp
ge's latest bid, up $9 a share to $54 for roper's outstanding stock, surpasses the $50-a-share sweetened bid whirlpool made last week for the appliance and lawn equipment maker
in the second wave of lawsuits filed in the hotly contested bid for augusta, ga.-based roper, ge charged that roper's board failed to act in the best interest of shareholders and, together with whirlpool, violated federal disclosure laws
in a statement issued after the stock market closed, roper said it is reviewing ge's new tender offer and plans to hold a board meeting later in the week to determine the company's position on the sweetened bid
roper rose $2.50 a share in composite new york stock exchange trading to close at $55.50 a share. roper jumped $5.75 a share on friday
ge's two lawsuits, filed in separate courts in delaware, counter a suit filed friday in which whirlpool accused ge of trying to ``sabotage'' the definitive merger agreement whirlpool reached with roper's board of directors on feb. 29
ge said in court papers it contacted robert cook, roper's president and chief executive officer, about a possible acquisition in november but was turned down
three months later, roper's board authorized a $37.50-a-share merger with whirlpool after whirlpool threatened to mount a hostile takeover bid, papers filed in delaware state court showed
ge, which entered into the fray march 6 with a $45-a-share offer, charged that roper failed to ``test the price'' before agreeing to merge with whirlpool. ge also charged that roper concealed ge's interest in the company when it advised shareholders to tender to whirlpool
in an attempt to ``lock up'' its agreement with whirlpool, roper gave the benton harbor, mich.-based company an option to purchase 1.6 million newly issued shares for $37.50 if the deal fell through, a move ge charged would make any subsequent roper acquisition more expensive. ge is seeking to block the issue and transfer of those shares
in a separate suit filed in u.s. district court in delaware, ge charged that both whirlpool and roper failed to adequately disclose terms of their merger agreement under securities and exchange commission laws and neglected to mention ge's interest in roper
whirlpool, which threw the battle into the courtroom on friday, alleged in its suit that a ge executive personally tried to persuade roper to break its contract with whirlpool. the suit said ge ``intentionally, maliciously and unjustifiedly engaged in a continuing course of conduct to sabotage'' the deal
part of whirlpool's lawsuit seeks $117 million in damages, or the difference between its $50-a-share offer and original offer
ge vowed to ``vigorously defend itself'' against the charges and seeks to transfer the suit from u.s. district court in grand rapids, mich., to federal court in delaware
whirlpool said its suit is ``similar in theory'' to pennzoil co.'s legal battle with texaco inc. over texaco's acquisition of getty oil co
texaco agreed to settle the suit for $3 billion after pennzoil won a $10.3 billion judgment against the oil giant on charges that texaco prompted getty to back out of an agreement with pennzoil
roper has been supportive of whirlpool's efforts. in endorsing whirlpool's sweetened bid last week, roper's cook said the company ``has a strong desire to see this combination successfully completed.'' he had no further comment when contacted monday
analysts say a roper-whirlpool merger would move whirlpool ahead of ge as the nation's leading appliance maker. whirlpool has said it would expand roper from a maker of cooking ranges into a producer and marketer of a full line of appliances
but the acquisition of roper would help ge secure its position in the gas stove market and enhance its supplier relationship with sears, roebuck &amp; co
long limited to electric ranges, ge decided a year ago to widen its market share by selling gas stoves. since then ge has purchased gas stoves from four companies, including roper, said ge spokesman jack batty from the company's headquarters in fairfield, conn
in addition, analysts estimate that roughly two-thirds of roper's sales come from its agreement to supply sears with its kitchen appliance and lawn equipment products
roper reported net income of $24 million on sales of $703 million in fiscal 1987
stocks stumbled monday over inflation fears and lingering post-crash anxiety among large institutional investors, resulting in the slowest trading volume this year
the buying interest in the equity market disappeared here today,'' said ronald b. doran, manager of institutional trading at the first albany corp. brokerage. ``the institutional investors are doing little of anything.''
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which hit the highest level since the oct. 19 collapse twice last week, dropped sharply at the opening and never recovered, closing at 2,067.14, down 20.23. broader market indices also fell
volume on the new york stock exchange fell to 128.83 million shares, slightly more than half the friday volume of 245.75 million shares and the lowest level since a 111.58 million-share day dec. 29
much of the trading was confined to stocks of companies targeted in rumored or actual acquisitions
beyond takeover deals, nothing is happening,'' said lawrence wachtel, a wall street analyst at prudential bache securities co. ``to a degree, the market is absent of ideas.''
brokers said falling prices in the bond market contributed to the selling mood by signaling higher inflation and interest rates. this provided many investors with an excuse to cash in stocks that had gained recently
the reluctance of market participants to commit themselves to stocks for more than a short time reflected an underlying anxiety that has persisted since the october collapse
there are very nervous people out there,'' said hank striefler, vice president on the trading floor at shearson lehman hutton inc
losing issues outnumbered gainers by more than a 2-to-1 margin in composite new york stock exchange trading, with 1,042 down, 502 up and 444 unchanged
among the most notable blue-chip losers, goodyear fell 1~ to 63~, dupont fell 1[ to 87{, woolworth fell 1[ to 47, alcoa fell 1[ to 45| and philip morris fell 1[ to 93
takeover activity boosted several prominent stocks. roper gained 2{ to 55{, reflecting a heightened battle for the appliance maker by general electric and whirlpool. koppers jumped 3} to 57{ after a group led by beazer plc sweetened its offer for the construction company from $45 per share to $56
kansas city southern jumped 8} to 55 after an investor group offered $60 a share for the railroad and financial services concern
conflicting news about oil prices reverberated through petroleum stocks, which ended mixed. kerr mcgee fell 1[ to 37], chevron droped { to 46~, and occidental petroleum rose 2 to 29
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 150.02 million shares
as measured by the wilshire 5000 equity index, the value of all u.s. stocks fell by $20.25 billion monday to $2.661 trillion, off 0.76 percent from friday
the nyse index of all listed issues fell 1.18 to 151.47
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials fell 2.60 to 312.04, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index fell 2.38 to 268.74
at the american stock exchange, the market value index fell 0.93 to 298.18. the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market fell 3.01 to 378.57
the dollar fell against all major currencies except the canadian dollar in quiet trading monday, mirroring a selloff in both the stock and bond markets
gold prices jumped as much as $5 a troy ounce in active trading, spurred by a rally in oil prices. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $449.45 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from $444 an ounce late friday
gold prices moved in concert with crude oil futures prices, which pierced the $17-a-barrel level before sliding back late in the trading session on the new york mercantile exchange
currency dealers said the dollar moved in a narrow trading range throughout the day. trading was quieter than usual because a national holiday in japan kept financial institutions closed
the dollar continued to give back ground after gaining last week on a better-than-expected government report that put the u.s. trade deficit for january at $12.4 billion
a selloff in the stock market, which saw the dow jones average of 30 industrials drop 20.23 points to 2,067.14, and lower bond prices ``took a little momentum away from the upside of the dollar,'' said ronald holzer, chief currency dealer at harris trust and savings bank in chicago
traders also said the strengthening japanese yen took its toll on the dollar. ``people are talking a lot about strong economic growth in japan,'' said james mcgroarty, vice president at discount corp. he said the speculation about japanese growth has heated up interest in buying the yen
in london, the dollar was quoted at 126.85 yen late monday compared with 128.35 yen in tokyo late friday. later in new york, the dollar closed at 126.92 yen, down from 128.00 yen on friday
one british pound cost $1.8285 late monday in london, slightly more expensive than late friday's $1.8235. in new york, it cost $1.8297 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.8240 late friday
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late friday, included: 1.6894 west german marks, down from 1.69575; 1.3986 swiss francs, down from 1.4040; 5.7545 french francs, down from 5.7590; 1,249.00 italian lire, down from 1.255.50, and 1.24905 canadian dollars, up from $1.24885
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late friday, included: 1.6880 west german marks, down from 1.6950; 1.3970 swiss francs, down from 1.4010; 5.7380 french francs, down from 5.7480; 1.8970 dutch guilders, down from 1.9010; 1,249.25 italian lire, down from 1,252.50, and 1.2494 canadian dollars, down from 1.2495
on the new york commodity exchange, gold closed at $450.20 a troy ounce, up from $445.20 on friday, in reaction to higher oil prices and the specter of inflation. but as sentiment in the oil market became bearish later in the session, gold prices began to recede
in london, gold jumped $6.25 an ounce to a late bid price of $449.50. in zurich, switzerland, the metal was up $5.50 an ounce to a late bid of $450.50. earlier, in hong kong, gold closed at $448.26 bid, up 36 cents from saturday's late bid
silver bullion prices rose in london to a late bid price of $6.47 a troy ounce from friday's $6.31. on new york's comex, silver closed at $6.447 a troy ounce, up from $6.365 an ounce on friday
bank of new york co. said monday it was beginning a $1.08 billion tender offer for irving bank corp. after having received approval to make the bid from the securities and exchange commission
the sec approved the registration statement on friday, allowing bank of new york to issue its prospectus, bank of new york spokesman owen brady said
irving spokesman david santos dismissed the development as ``pretty much a non-event.''
bank of new york began its hostile attempt to acquire irving last september, a struggle that has been widely followed by bankers because unfriendly takeovers are unusual in the banking industry. its tender offer expires at midnight on april 15
irving's board last week amended its anti-takeover plan to make it harder for a slate of new irving directors to scuttle rights if they win a proxy fight at irving's annual meeting april 21
bank of new york already has nominated a 16-director slate to compete with irving's slate at the meeting. the bank said it would fight irving's amended anti-takeover plan in the courts
platinum futures prices surged above $500 a troy ounce monday, helped by early gains in oil prices and a generally positive economic outlook
oil prices settled mixed, however. on other markets, gold and silver futures advanced; soybean futures were sharply higher while the grains were mixed; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated
the contract for april delivery of platinum settled $6.90 higher at $504.20 on the new york mercantile exchange. the move marked only the second time since jan. 20 that the april platinum contract has finished above the psychologically important $500 barrier
analysts said gains monday in all the precious metals _ platinum, gold, silver and palladium _ were driven primarily by a sharp increase in crude oil futures prices early in the day
but when oil prices later fell steeply, the metals gave up only some of their gains, indicating other supportive factors were at work
the weak dollar, increased u.s. auto sales and the generally positive tone of recent economic data are all bullish for metals prices, said jacques luben, executive director of investments for the platinum guild international
it seems as though the consensus is that interest rates will remain relatively low for the remainder of the year, we may see higher inflation and we probably won't see a recession this year,'' luben said
monday's performance was ``a reassuring vote of confidence for the metals'' but the next few sessions will show just how deep that confidence runs, said jack barbanel, director of futures trading for gruntal &amp; co. in new york
we're either at the early stage of some new buying momentum or we're seeing an upside correction in a downside metals market,'' he said
on new york's commodity exchange, gold settled $4.90 to $7.20 higher with april at $449.20 a troy ounce; silver was 8 cents to 10.3 cents higher with march at $6.447 a troy ounce
crude oil's early jump above $17 a barrel on the new york mercantile exchange was triggered partly by speculation that opec president rilwanu lukman would announce a meeting of opec's pricing committee at a tuesday news conference, said nauman barakat, an analyst with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
but prices came tumbling down later in the session when saudi arabia's king fahd confirmed the country was ``offering discounts, quite indiscriminately, to almost everybody,'' barakat said
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 9 cents lower to 8 cents higher with april at $16.49 a barrel; heating oil was .12 cent lower to .35 cent higher with april at 45.40 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was unchanged to .12 cent higher with april at 46.11 cents a gallon
soybean and corn futures settled sharply higher on the chicago board of trade while wheat prices fell
soybean futures rose early in the session on rumors of new soviet buying and got a boost later in the day when the agricultural newsletter safras y mercado dropped its brazilian soybean crop estimate by 400,000 metric tons due to dry weather, said victor lespinasse, a trader for dean witter reynolds inc
wheat settled 2} cents lower to { cent higher with march at $2.96\ a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 4} cents higher with march at $2.01{ a bushel; oats were 5{ cents lower to { cent higher with march at $1.90{ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 10 cents higher with march at $6.30 a bushel
frozen pork belly futures settled sharply lower on the chicago mercantile exchange while livestock futures were mixed
the drop in pork belly futures was largely due to expectations, later confirmed, of a sharp increase in bellies in cold storage. the usda announced after the close that nearly 67 million pounds of pork bellies were stored in the nation's freezers on feb. 29, compared to 34.7 million pounds a year ago
sharply lower cash hog prices weighed on the livestock futures, said walter kowalski, an analyst in chicago with lind-waldock &amp; co
live cattle settled .12 cent lower to .50 cent higher with april at 73.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .10 cent higher with march at 82.70 cents a pound; hogs were .65 cent lower to .10 cent higher with april at 45.55 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to 1.70 cents lower with march at 54.10 cents a pound
stock-index futures retreated on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for june delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 1.7 points lower at 270.60
batus inc. took its campaign for farmers group inc. to the company's shareholders monday, soliciting proxies to support reconsideration of its bid for one of the nation's largest insurers
batus said the non-binding resolution will be introduced at farmers' annual stockholders' meeting may 20 at the company's los angeles headquarters
on march 10, farmers' board unanimously rejected a hostile takeover offer of $63 a share, or $4.4 billion, and called upon its shareholders to do the same. the offer was described as being substantially less than the company is worth
the board, which has refused to enter into negotiations, also announced it was exploring a variety of alternatives to the batus bid, including restructuring or consolidating with another company
farmers said it has had discussions with an unidentified third party about a possible leveraged buyout to counter the offer from batus, the u.s. subsidiary of british bat industries plc
farmers group shares fell to $62.50, down $1.12{, in active over-the-counter trading monday
in seeking the proxies, batus said its resolution would give stockholders an opportunity to express their support for the merger, at no less than $63 a share, and would encourage the directors to pursue such a sale
in case a higher bidder emerged, the resolution recommends that farmers' directors ``consider in good faith whether to negotiate with such a bidder.''
batus' latest maneuver ``was no surprise,'' said tom welch, director of corporate investments for farmers. ``we have been expecting it.'' he declined further comment
batus spokesman wilson wyatt jr. said the solicitation was being handled by the carter organization in new york
wyatt also said batus does not intend to oppose or take any position with respect to the election of farmers' nominees to the board
wyatt said that batus, based in louisville, owns 696,000 shares of farmers' stock, of which there were 68,916,614 shares outstanding as of oct. 31, 1987
earlier this month, a federal judge in nevada ordered farmers to place batus' negotiation proposal in the proxy cards being sent to shareholders for the meeting
the case was heard in nevada because farmers is incorporated there
batus, which owns a diversified group of businesses including retailers saks fifth avenue and marshall field's, began the bidding in january with a $60 per share offer for farmers
farmers is the nation's third-largest home and auto insurer after state farm and allstate and the seventh-largest property and casualty insurer
some analysts have said batus needs to raise its offer by $5 to $20 a share if it expects to acquire farmers, which has about $11 billion in assets, mostly in insurance
the wall street journal reported monday that state insurance regulators and legislators had raised questions that could hinder the batus bid
officials of the texas state board of insurance have questioned the company's ability to service the debt required to accomplish the deal
in ohio, the state house of representatives has approved a resolution expressing its concern about how the takeover might affect farmers' policyholders and employees in that state
a spokesman for batus' british parent told the journal that it was responding to the questions from the texas authorities and believes it meets all the legal requirements to control insurance companies in texas and ohio
before its purchase of farmers can be completed, batus must get approval from insurance regulators in nine states. regulators in several states, including idaho, illinois and kansas, have asked the company for more information, the journal said. industries</head>
an investment group that owns an 11 percent stake in kansas city southern industries inc. said monday it was offering $60 a share, or about $594 million, for the rest of the railroad concern's common stock
kansas city southern, which also has interests in financial services, said its board would consider the all-cash proposal soon at a special meeting
the company has nearly 11.1 million shares outstanding, and the investment group led by howard kaskel claims it controls about 1.2 million shares
in trading on the new york stock exchange, kansas city southern jumped $8.75 a share to $55
kaskel outlined the merger proposal in a letter to landon h. rowland, president and chief executive of kansas city southern, and requested an opportunity to negotiate ``all aspects of the offer, including price.''
he said completing the proposal was subject to reaching a definitive agreement, approval by the requisite number of directors and stockholders and satisfaction of all regulatory requirements
but he warned that if the company's board rejected or failed to act on the offer by april 4, ``we will be forced to commence a proxy contest to elect directors who will actively pursue and encourage the maximization of stockholder values.,''
kaskel said he had made various proposals to company management over the past eight months on ways to maximize shareholder values
unfortunately, you have rejected each of my suggestions,'' kaskel wrote
in addition, he said he found it ``dismaying'' that the board erected obstacles ``designed to entrench itself and to prevent stockholders from realizing a full return on their investment.''
among these steps, kaskel cited the recent issuance of about 1.4 million shares, or almost 15 percent of the company's then-outstanding common stock, to employee stock ownership plans at $49 a share
this could only have been motivated by the board's desire to place substantial voting power in its hands as a means of opposing'' proposals that may be brought before its shareholders, the letter said
kaskel also cited kansas city southern's continued efforts to acquire the southern pacific railroad despite southern pacific's ``binding agreement for its sale to the denver rio grande.''
responding to the offer, rowland said in a statement from company headquarters in kansas city that the company had received a merger proposal from kaskel and that it would be considered by the company's board ``at a special meeting to be held shortly.''
he said the company would have no further comment until the board of directors had an opportunity to study the proposal
kansas city southern owns the kansas city southern railroad which operates on about 1,500 miles of track in missouri, arkansas, oklahoma, kansas, louisiana and texas
it also owns 87 percent of dst systems inc., a kansas city-based concern that provides data systems and record-keeping services for mutual funds, insurance companies and other financial services providers
the company also owns 80 percent of janus capital corp., a denver-based concern that provides investment advice and had about $915 million in funds under management at the end of february, according to kansas city southern's vice president and secretary, albert mauro
for the fiscal year ended dec. 31, kansas city southern reported a profit of $17.7 million, or $1.82 a share, on revenue of $507.6 million
trw inc. said monday it has reached an agreement to buy chilton corp. from borg-warner corp. for about $360 million
chilton operates consumer credit reporting, accounts receivable management and related businesses. chilton, headquartered in dallas, is a wholly owned subsidiary of borg-warner, based in chicago
chilton will become a part of trw information systems group, which provides information and information processing services to the financial services industry. trw information systems is located in long beach, calif
chilton has an excellent reputation. combining its resources with those of trw will provide consumers and the consumer information market with better and more efficient service,'' said richard d.c. whilden, trw executive vice president and general manager of trw information systems group
chilton president van smith said the combination enhances the companies ability to provide new products and services
borg-warner's products and services include automotive components, chemicals and plastics and protective services. the cleveland-based trw provides high technology products and services for the space and defense, automotive, and information systems markets
u.s. bankruptcy judge howard c. buschman iii heard testimony monday in a court battle over three missing zeros on a financial document that could cost prudential insurance co. of america millions of dollars
prudential is trying to establish that a mortgage lien it holds is for $92,885,000, even though a document records its value as only $92,885 because of a clerical error
the lien is on eight ships once owned by united states lines, a shipping company whose assets are being sold off to satisfy creditors under bankruptcy court supervision
the hearing before buschman lasted past the normal close of business hours monday and lawyers for the various parties could not be reached by telephone for comment. february</head>
the federal government chalked up a $23.9 billion deficit in its february spending after posting a rare budget surplus in january, the treasury department reported monday
meanwhile, stock prices fell in the slowest trading of the year, while the dollar followed suit and oil prices were mixed
the treasury's latest monthly report on the government's spending and revenues followed a $16.1 billion surplus in january which had occurred because social security checks that month were mailed early and counted in the december spending figures
so far this fiscal year, the government has run up a five-month deficit of $89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the red ink incurred in the same period a year earlier
the reagan administration is projecting a deficit of $146.7 billion for the fiscal year ending sept. 30, down 2.4 percent from the $150.4 billion deficit in 1987
but many forecasters believe the small improvement will not be realized because they think the administration has used overly optimistic projections about the economy
on wall street, inflation fears and lingering post-crash anxiety sent stocks tumbling across the board, with the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropping sharply at the opening and remaining down throughout the trading session
the closely watched indicator closed at 2,067.14, down 20.23 points. broader market indices also fell
trading was also quiet on world currency markets. the dollar fell against all major currencies except the canadian dollar, mirroring the stock market selloff and a decline in bond prices
gold prices jumped as much as $5 a troy ounce in active trading, spurred by a rally in oil prices. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $449.45 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from $444 an ounce late friday
gold prices moved in concert with crude oil futures prices, which pierced the $17-a-barrel level before sliding back in late trading, following a statement by saudi king fahd on prices and production
in remarks carried by the official saudi press agency, fahd suggested that cheating on production quotas and prices by some members of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries encouraged further weakness in prices
that punctured a rally on the new york mercantile exchange, where contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, closed at $16.49 per 42-gallon barrel, down 9 cents from friday. they had been up as much as 45 cents during the day
among refined products for april, wholesale heating oil closed 0.35 cent higher at 45.40 cents a gallon, after having touched 46.70 cents a gallon earlier. unleaded gasoline gave up a 1.41-cent gain to close 0.12 cent higher at 46.11 cents a gallon
campbell soup co. is replacing the red-and-white labels on ``cooking soups'' used primarily as recipe ingredients, but plans to keep the familiar 90-year-old design on its eating soups, the company said monday
the new labels will feature color photographs of meals that can be made from recipes using campbell's 16 varieties of cooking soups, according to company spokesman kevin lowery
the recipe for the pictured meal will be printed on the underside of the label along with another recipe and a cookbook offer
the traditional red-and-white label was born in 1898, when a campbell executive was so inspired by the colors in cornell university's new football team uniforms that he ordered the change from the previous orange-and-black label, lowery said
the red-and-white label went on to win the gold medallion for excellence at the 1900 paris exposition and was immortalized in pop art by the late andy warhol
cooking soups, such as chicken broth, cream of mushroom and tomato, constitute one-third of campbell's market
campbell initially will use the new labels on cans produced and sold in nine western states, where the company will judge consumer reaction
the company indicated the change, the product of one year's research, could help consumers by saving shopping time and aiding menu planning
borg-warner corp. has sold its credit-reporting subsidiary, chilton corp., to trw inc. for about $360 million in cash, the companies announced monday
borg-warner said it sold dallas-based chilton, which it acquired in march 1986 for $252 million, to help pay off debt incurred in its 1987 leveraged buyout
borg-warner went private last year in the buyout led by a merrill lynch &amp; co. unit and must pay off $1.7 billion in debts by the end of 1988. the buyout, which was engineered to avert a hostile takeover by gaf corp., left borg-warner with total debt of more than $4 billion
trw chairman ruben f. mettler said in a statement issued in cleveland that the acquisition fits into trw's previously announced strategy of increasing its presence in the commercial information systems business
the sale of chilton leaves borg-warner with interests in chemicals and plastics, automotive parts and security and armored guard services. borg-warner already has divested itself of other assets, including its bwac inc. finance unit and its industrial products group, to pay off debt incurred in the buyout
